TITLE: Concerto for Piano and Strings

AUTHOR: Carroll, Charles

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Ugay, Liliya

MEMBER (university representative): Williams, Heidi Louise

MEMBER (committee member): Callender, Clifton

MEMBER (committee member): Gümrükçüoğlu, Osman Eren

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (80 pages)

ABSTRACT: Concerto for Piano and Strings presented herein is a single-movement opus for piano and string orchestra that delves deep into the labyrinth of human emotion. Drawing inspiration from a diverse array of sources, with a particular nod to Alfred Schnittke's evocative Concerto for Piano and String Orchestra, this composition embarks on a visceral journey through the complexities of the human psyche. At its core, this concerto is a study in contrasts—an exploration of the tension between Romantic lyricism and uncompromising dissonance, between the ethereal beauty of soaring melodies and the haunting stillness of static textures. Much like the human experience itself, the music traverses the heights of passion and the depths of despair, weaving together a tapestry of emotions that resonate with raw intensity. The influence of Schnittke's masterwork is present throughout, infusing the composition with a sense of urgency and existential weight. A language of dense, tortuous harmonies and angular melodies is employed to evoke a world teetering on the brink of chaos—a world where beauty and brutality intertwine in a delicate balance. Yet, the concerto is not beholden solely to Schnittke's aesthetic vision; rather, it draws from a rich tapestry of musical influences, including Christopher Rouse's visceral piano concerto "Seeing," Rachmaninoff's iconic Second Piano Concerto, the bold, angular compositions of Sergei Prokofiev, and the wildly expressive piano works of Michael Finnissy. These influences manifest in the concerto's multifaceted approach to orchestration, its juxtaposition of contrasting themes and textures, and its relentless pursuit of emotional authenticity. Concerto for Piano and Strings is, at its heart, a meditation on the human experience—a testament to the complexity of our inner worlds and the myriad emotions that course through our veins. It is a journey through the darkest recesses of the soul and the soaring heights of transcendence—a symphony of joy and sorrow, hope and despair, love and loss.

TITLE: The Effects of Regulatory and Statutory Reliefs on CECL Adopting Banks' Lending to Low-Income and Minority Borrowers

AUTHOR: Chappell, Moniquca

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Keskek, Sami

MEMBER (university representative): Cheng, Yingmei

MEMBER (committee member): Ehinger, Anne C.

MEMBER (committee member): Mauler, Landon M.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Business

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Accounting

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (77 pages)

ABSTRACT: I examine the effect of the change from incurred loss model to the current expected credit loss (CECL) model on mortgage lending. I find that the extent that the CECL model under ASC 326 exacerbates the lending disparities for low-income and minority (LIM) borrowers is dependent on banks' choice of relief. I find banks who opted for regulatory relief that defers CECL's effect on regulatory capital, but not net income, decreased lending to LIM borrowers in preparation for and after enactment of ASC 326. In contrast, banks who opted for statutory relief that defers CECL's effect on both regulatory capital and net income did not reduce lending to LIM borrowers. Banks who opted for no relief decreased lending to LIM borrowers after enactment of ASC 326. This study highlights how the choice of relief (regulatory, statutory or no relief), which is heavily influenced by investor pressure, can have real consequences for LIM borrowers.

ABSTRACT: This research delves into the lived experiences of individuals with mixed/multicultural backgrounds in the United States, spurred by the researcher's introspection during the COVID-19 pandemic and a personal journey navigating systemic oppression. Employing a hermeneutic phenomenological methodology, the study aims to not only elucidate the experiences of mixed/multicultural individuals through the medium of art-making but also to probe the researcher's own identity. Furthermore, this study invites fellow therapist-researchers to incorporate art as a tool for cultural humility practice and to explore shared intersections, not solely with participants but also with clients.

ABSTRACT: This treatise explores selected compositions by the contemporary Russian composers Mikhail Kollontay and Valery Arzoumanov. TITLE: Engineering Cell-Matrix Interaction in 3D Human Central Nervous System Models: Utilizing Human Pluripotent Stem Cell-Derived Organoids

AUTHOR: Chen, Xingchi

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Li, Yan

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Zeng, Changchun (Chad)

MEMBER (university representative): Shanbhag, Sachin

MEMBER (committee member): Ricarte, Ralm

MEMBER (committee member): Guan, Jingjiao

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemical and Biomedical Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (172 pages)

ABSTRACT: Human induced pluripotent stem cells (hiPSCs) are recognized as an excellent alternative to embryonic stem cells in the fields of regenerative medicine, in vitro model construction, and drug discovery. Given the challenge of limited passages to primary cells from patients, the use of hiPSCs has greatly facilitated diverse studies aiming to recapitulate physiological and pathological mechanisms. This approach has led to the development of more precise disease modeling platforms. Furthermore, the investigation of the interaction between hiPSCs and extracellular matrix(ECM) at the 3D level, and subsequently modeling the central nervous system, such as the blood-spinal cord barrier (BSCB) and blood brain barrier (BBB), has been investigated to a limited extent. Therefore, the first objective of this study is to investigate the interaction between hiPSC-derived organoid differentiation and 3D scaffold or hydrogel network. The second objective is to utilize hiPSC-derived organoids to construct a 3D in vitro model that can recapitulate structures and functionalities similar to those in the human body, such as the BSCB. Models of the BBB have been explored for decades, and the transition from 2D to 3D modeling methods has been well-established. However, the authentic BBB involves fluid blood, exerting shear stress on the endothelial cell layer. Thus, there is a need for the development of a dynamic BBB structure to enhance BBB modeling.Auxetic materials are those capable of displaying a negative Poisson's ratio, which indicates the degree to which a material contracts or expands transversally when axially strained. Human stem cells are sensitive to the mechanical properties of their microenvironment, including surface properties, stiffness, and Poisson's ratio. In this study, six different auxetic polyurethane (PU) foams with varying elastic moduli (0.7-1.8 kPa) and Poisson's ratios (-0.1 to -0.5) were fabricated to investigate lineage specification of human induced pluripotent stem cells (hiPSCs). The cells exhibited differential adherent density and differentiation capacity on different auxetic foams. Surface modification with chitosan and heparin promoted hindbrain and hippocampal markers, but not forebrain markers, during neural patterning of hiPSCs. Furthermore, properly surface-engineered auxetic scaffolds could enhance vascular differentiation of hiPSCs. This study presents a versatile and multifunctional scaffold fabrication approach that could lead to the development of a suitable system for establishing hiPSC culture models for applications in neurovascular disease modeling. The spinal cord is also a important components of central nervous system (CNS) and controls the different motions of the human body. The injury of spinal cord (SCI) also cause disability with less effective repairing method. Hence, the development of specific spinal cord organoids(hSCOs) for SCI treatment is necessary. Based on methylacrylated (MA) hyaluronic acid (HA), different HA hydrogels for generation and vascularization of spinal cord organoids derived from hiPSCs. In particular, the effects of viscoelasticity of the HA hydrogels on spinal cord organoid patterning were investigated. The morphogenesis, regional patterning, and vascularization of human spinal cord organoids (hSCOs) were influenced by different hydrogels. Dorsal marker expression was evaluated where more viscoelastic hydrogels can promote dorsal marker expression, while softer hydrogels resulted in higher interneuron marker expression. This study also found differences when generating the blood-spinal cord barrier with the coculture of hSCOs and human blood vessel organoids. In addition, Yes-associated protein nuclear translocation was determined to reveal the mechanism of cell-ECM mechano-transduction. Moreover, the hiPSC-derived blood vessel organoids were cocultured with hSCOs and pericytes for making transwell and 3D micro fluidic BSCB models. Lastly, hiPSCs exhibit multipotency, allowing them to differentiate into various cell types or tissues, making them valuable for applications in tissue engineering and injury repair. Nevertheless, hiPSCs pose significant challenges due to low consistency in target cell differentiation and a tendency for cancer-like infinite proliferation. [Furthermore, the impact of shear stress on the secretion and cargo profiles of hiPSC-derived organoids, particularly extracellular vesicles (EVs) such as the subset 'exosomes,' is recognized. [Comment: Consider clarifying how shear stress impacts the secretion and cargo profiles of hiPSC-derived organoids for greater clarity.] Exosomes show promising potential as an alternative in stem cell therapy to some extent. Additionally, encapsulating them with different hydrogels can be explored to control the rate of EV release.

FILENAME: Cohen_fsu_0071E_18557.pdf

TITLE: When It's Time to Take Your Eye off the Ball: Preparation for Life after Collegiate Sport

AUTHOR: Cohen, Kaitlin E.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Eccles, David W.

MEMBER (university representative): Cougle, Jesse R. (Jesse Ray), 1975-

MEMBER (committee member): Eklund, Robert C. (Robert Charles), 1958-

MEMBER (committee member): Becker, Martin Swanbrow

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Psychology and Learning Systems

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (114 pages)

ABSTRACT: Collegiate athletes are at risk of exposure to crises-like outcomes when transitioning out of their sport. These outcomes include anxiety (Alfermann, 2000), depression (Brewer et al., 1993), reduced self-worth, identity confusion (Park et al., 2013), and social dysfunction (Blakelock et al., 2016; Brown & Potrac, 2009; Gouttebarge et al., 2016). This study involved the development and testing of an intervention aimed at reducing these outcomes. Specifically, the intervention was developed to educate collegiate student-athletes about the potential challenges and psychological changes they could expect to experience when retiring from their sport, and to offer strategies that the student-athletes can employ when navigating these retirement difficulties. Participants recruited for the study were current NCAA collegiate student-athletes in the United States. Measures included participants' knowledge of the retirement process, their behaviors in preparation for the retirement process, their perceptions of social support, and athletic identity. Participants completed a pre-test comprising these measures. Participants were then randomly assigned to a control or treatment group. Participants in the control group viewed a 14-minute sport retirement video presentation about facts about NCAA retirement (e.g., advanced education attainment among NCAA student-athletes) that were not theorized to be related to the key challenges of retirement or relevant coping strategies. The treatment group viewed a 14-minute sport retirement education video presentation that concerned concepts theorized to be related to the key challenges of retirement and relevant coping strategies. Participants then completed a post-test and a four-week follow-up test comprising the study measures. Findings revealed that, in relation to the control condition, the intervention significantly increased participants' perceived knowledge about sport retirement challenges, but had no significant effect on the remaining variables. In conclusion, this study has provided some evidence that the intervention developed for this study might be useful in raising awareness in student-athletes of the retirement process. Applied implications of this research study are considered for student-athletes, coaches, parents, and sport organizations including the NCAA. Recommended avenues of future research are also outlined.

FILENAME: Coker_fsu_0071E_18177.pdf

TITLE: Pre-Service Science Teachers' Learning to Leverage Students' Thinking in the Two-Worlds Pitfall

AUTHOR: Coker, Ryan

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Southerland, Sherry A., 1962-

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Jaber, Lama

MEMBER (university representative): Khurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (university representative): Kurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (committee member): Catena, Emily Plummer

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: School of Teacher Education

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (204 pages)

ABSTRACT: Pre-service science teachers develop their teaching practices within and across the university and school contexts of their teacher education programs. The practices and visions of teaching and learning emphasized in each context are often disjointed, a problem referred to as the "two-worlds pitfall." Responding to the call for teacher education programs to better support pre-service teachers' work towards teaching that is responsive to students' thinking, this study is situated within the university and subsequent school contexts of a teacher education program. Taking an asset-based approach to pre-service teachers' learning, this study understood pre-service teachers as agentive sense makers as they appropriated teaching practices across contexts. Three pre-service science teachers participated in this qualitative case study, and the research question about how pre-service teachers appropriated teaching practices across the school and university contexts relied on the development of case narratives from analysis of interview materials, lesson planning documents, and teaching observation. These case narratives distilled central teaching practices through which pre-service teachers processes of appropriation could be understood. The findings highlight how pre-service teachers' appropriation of practices across contexts aligned with their orientation to students' thinking as problems or as resources, and that their appropriation and orientations to students' thinking were consistent across the contexts of the two-worlds pitfall. Pre-service teachers' experiences with tensions in their school contexts highlighted their agency to maintain, re-envision, and reject the visions of teaching that did or did not align with their patterns of appropriation and orientations to students' thinking that were consistent across contexts. As such, this study challenges traditional models of the two-worlds pitfall that anticipate significant shifts in pre-service teachers' practices across contexts. Rather, this study highlights the availability of productive ideas about responsive and rigorous instruction in pre-service teachers' thinking, and missed opportunities for teacher educators to draw out and leverage those ideas to support pre-service teachers' development of teaching that capitalizes on students' thinking.

TITLE: Increasing Underrepresented Students in Stem Fields Using Informal Science Education

AUTHOR: Coley, Camille E.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Zuilkowski, Stephanie Simmons

MEMBER (university representative): Dodds, Benjamin

MEMBER (committee member): Perez-Felkner, Lara

MEMBER (committee member): Park, Toby J.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (107 pages)

ABSTRACT: This comprehensive study explores the experiences of underrepresented students who have participated in informal science education programs at the American Museum of Natural History (AMNH). Using qualitative methods, including interviews and participant observations, the research uncovers transformative insights shaping the educational landscape.The study focuses on 10 students who have participated in the AMNH Lang Program, an Informal Science Education (ISE) initiative for New York City students starting in the fifth grade and ending in the twelfth grade. Semi-structured interviews provided data, which was analyzed using a combination of a priori, in vivo, and values coding. A central finding reveals the holistic impact of these programs on students' academic trajectories, acting as catalysts for broadening horizons and discovering, and in some cases reaffirming STEM passions. The holistic influence of out-of-school time learning through ISE challenges conventional notions of informal education's impact on a student's entire educational journey. Emphasizing the tangible role of hands-on experiences, participants of this study highlighted the significance of physically engaging with scientific concepts by bridging the gap between theoretical knowledge and real-world applications.Beyond academics, the study uncovers the profound role of ISE programs in shaping the identity of underrepresented students within the STEM community. These programs become pivotal in forming a STEM identity, dispelling stereotypes, and empowering students to see themselves as integral members of the scientific community. Mentorship emerges as a powerful force, with mentors sharing similar backgrounds crucial in guiding students through academic and career complexities. Tailored mentorship programs for underrepresented students serve as inspirational anchors beyond immediate educational contexts. Intrinsic motivation derived from enjoyable science-based experiences within the programs is emphasized, suggesting that incorporating enjoyment into STEM education enhances long-term commitment. The development of a supportive community among participants and peers is highlighted as a motivational ecosystem, contributing to sustained motivation and shared commitment to success. Participants draw a clear link between program involvement and the decision to pursue STEM-related degrees and careers, emphasizing the enduring impact on long-term career trajectories. These insights contribute to the discourse on the effectiveness of informal science education programs, promoting diversity and inclusion within STEM. Recommendations for administrators, leaders, practitioners, and researchers include expanding hands-on experiences, strengthening mentorship programs, promoting diversity, and facilitating collaborative efforts between formal and informal education. Implementing these recommendations can create more inclusive, impactful, and effective informal science education programs for underrepresented students, both locally and within the larger educational landscape. This study serves as a roadmap for transformative action, ensuring that underrepresented students not only enter but thrive in the dynamic STEM landscape that fuels U.S. innovation.

TITLE: Hydrochemical and Deep Learning Investigations of Groundwater-Surface Water Interactions in the Eogenetic Karst Systems of Florida

AUTHOR: Compare, Kyle Alexander

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Ye, Ming

MEMBER (university representative): Meyer-Bäse, Anke

MEMBER (committee member): Young, Seth A.

MEMBER (committee member): Wang, Yang, (Graduate Assistant in Teaching)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (124 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation implements three studies related to understanding the impacts of groundwater-surface water interactions on both the aquatic geochemistry and water quantity of karst spring systems. The first study examined aquifer and spring geochemistry following a series of sinkhole lake dry-downs in the Wakulla Springshed of north Florida, where lake water was injected into the aquifer. Geochemical data showed groundwater values in a down-gradient monitoring well varied widely on the daily time scale with evidence that lake water weathered the aquifer confining unit as it recharged. No long-term impacts were seen at the well, and no impacts were seen at the spring. The second study aimed to model spring stage at Wakulla Springs using spatially distributed groundwater, surface water, and meteorological data from a monitoring network within the springshed. Different combinations of input variables were tested, and the model that considers a conceptual understanding of meteorological, groundwater, and surface water process was seen to perform the best. The final study trained a complex, interpretable neural network model using meteorological and springshed data from multiple springsheds of the Outstanding Florida Springs to create a universal model of eogenetic karst spring flow. The results were limited by the small number of springs used to train the model but were largely positive as it made accurate springflow predictions and could explain which input variables were impacting springflow predictions. These three studies show successful applications of applying established and new techniques to study groundwater-surface water interactions in the eogenetic karst environments to provide insight on Florida's karst spring systems and provide future directions for additional work in this field.

AUTHOR: Cozac, Marina

ABSTRACT: In three essays, this dissertation explores how marketing strategies, both in the development and marketing of food and media, influence consumer well-being. Chapter 2 explores maladaptive consumption and the future of food, examining new consumption trends and phenomena. Specifically, I study emerging trends in the marketplace related to (1) sustainability and alternative protein sources and (2) technology in food production and the supply chain. I explore the emerging trends in terms of implications for marketing theory and research, managers, and public policymakers, as well as their connections with the United Nation's Sustainable Development Goals. In Chapter 3, I explore the consumers' preference for snacks. Specifically, I explore how an emerging labeling and promotion strategy for "fuel snacks" impacts consumer evaluations and perceptions. Furthermore, I study how snacks labeled in such a way appeal to consumers with certain characteristics – namely, consumers under caregiving stress. In doing so, I propose a dynamic effect of fuel snacks, such that the effects of snack perceptions differ by labeling and promotion strategies, and how they appeal to certain consumer segments. Finally, in Chapter 4, I explore how various labeling strategies and characteristics affect consumers' beliefs about mis- and disinformation. I theorize how the timing of warning labels, the content of the misinformation, and consumers' alignment with the content impacts perceptions about the mis- and disinformation and subsequent downstream behaviors. I present five studies demonstrating that some warning labels successfully reduce the belief of misinformation while others backfire. Taken together, this dissertation seeks to provide insights into when and why labeling and promotion might undermine or support consumer well-being.

TITLE: Identity and Its Influence on the Saxophonist's Sense of Taste

AUTHOR: Cummings, Jared

MEMBER (professor directing treatise): Deibel, Geoffrey Scott

MEMBER (university representative): Buchler, Michael Howard, 1966-

MEMBER (committee member): Keesecker, Jeff

MEMBER (committee member): Large, Karen McLaughlin

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (58 pages)

ABSTRACT: There is a plethora of articles and documents by scholarly figures articulating their views on what constitutes "good" art. Whether it's Halbert Britan or Milton Babbitt , the common strategy within aesthetic discourse is to claim that "certain objects or forms please us 'naturally' by virtue of certain human universals" and assert "the belief that a norm and thus 'standard' of correct and defective taste can be derived accordingly." In other words, those attuned to a given community's sensibilities are morally sound, have "good taste," and are superior to the flawed individuals in opposition to the community's proclivities. The saxophone, invented in 1838, found itself at a point in history where classical music in the twentieth century became increasingly splintered, allowing for different aesthetics to exist simultaneously, resulting in greater stratification of taste between laymen and professional musicians. This document will use the saxophone and its repertoire in a case study that will explore the saxophone's history, how it can influence the development of a saxophonist's identity, and how our identity influences our artistic palate and sense of musical value.

FILENAME: Cushing_fsu_0071E_18568.pdf

TITLE: Cortical-Hippocampal Interactions and Spatial Learning Are Impaired in Alzheimer's Disease and 40 Hz Stimulation Recovers Cognition

AUTHOR: Cushing, Sarah D.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Wilber, Aaron A. (Aaron Albert)

MEMBER (university representative): Hurdal, Monica K.

MEMBER (committee member): Vincis, Roberto

MEMBER (committee member): Martin, Christopher Basil

MEMBER (committee member): Eckel, Lisa A.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Psychology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (141 pages)

ABSTRACT: Spatial learning is impaired in humans with preclinical Alzheimer's disease (AD), and we've previously reported similar impairments in a mouse model of AD. Spatial navigation impairments are one of the earliest symptoms to appear in this disease, and could be the result of impairments in navigational computations, memory encoding or retrieval, or some combination of navigational and memory impairments. Both cortex and hippocampus are important for memory encoding and navigational computations, with interactions between these two regions supporting these processes. Memory reactivation during sleep is critical for learning related plasticity, and memory formation is correlated with hippocampal (HPC) sharp wave ripple (SWR) density, cortical delta waves (DWs), cortical spindles, and the temporal coupling of these events - postulated as physiological substrates for memory consolidation. Further, HPC-cortical dyscoordination is prevalent in individuals with AD. Thus, we hypothesized impaired memory formation mechanisms in HPC-cortical networks could account for spatial memory deficits. We assessed sleep architecture, SWR/DW dynamics and memory reactivation in a mouse model of tauopathy and amyloidosis (3xTg-AD) implanted with a recording array targeting parietal cortex (PC) and HPC. Mice underwent daily recording sessions of rest-task-rest while learning the spatial reorientation task. We assessed pattern reactivation by matching activity patterns from the approach to the unmarked reward zone to patterns during slow wave sleep (SWS). AD mice had more SWS, but reduced SWR and spindle density. The increased SWS compensated for reduced SWR and spindle density so there was no reduction in SWR or spindle number. In control mice hippocampal SWR-PC DW coupling was strengthened in post-task- sleep and was correlated with performance on the spatial reorientation task the following day. However, in AD mice SWR-DW and spindle-DW coupling were impaired. Thus, reduced SWR-DW coupling may cause impaired learning in AD and spindle-DW coupling during short rest-task-rest sessions may serve as a biomarker for early AD related changes in these brain dynamics. Previously, various forms of 40 Hz stimulation have been shown to clear AD pathology in mice and improve functional connectivity in preclinical AD patients. Thus, we assessed HPC-cortical coordination in 40 Hz or Sham stimulated 3xTg-AD/PVcre mice learning the spatial reorientation task. We implanted a 16-tetrode recording array targeting PC and HPC and an optical fiber targeting HPC. Daily recording sessions of rest-task-rest began as mice learned the VM, followed by HPC optogenetic stimulation, either 40 Hz or Sham. We assessed sleep quality metrics, DWs in cortex, and SWRs during SWS. Only 40 Hz stimulation increased 40 Hz power in HPC and to a lesser extent also PC. In SHAM stimulated mice SWR-DW cross-correlations were reduced, similar to 3xTg-AD mice. In 40 Hz stimulated mice, this phase-locking was rescued. Furthermore, the 40 Hz stimulation restored performance on the VM compared to Sham mice. However, this rescued HPC-cortical coupling no longer predicted performance as in NonTg animals. Instead, SWRs and DWs independently predicted performance in 40 Hz mice only. We also found reduction of amyloid beta (Aβ) in PC and ventral CA1, but no reduction in dorsal CA1, synaptically closer to stimulation. Thus, 40 Hz stimulation of HPC rescued learning and memory related functional interactions in the HPC-PC network during sleep and as a consequence rescued impairments in spatial navigation, despite a decoupling between HPC-cortical coupling and learning and memory. Furthermore, the observed effects seems to be mediated by direct 40 Hz impacts on brain dynamics (or another yet uncovered mechanism), due to an absence of robust glia, Aβ, and tau effects, contrasting previous reports. In addition to sleep, HPC-PC interactions are important in active navigation computations. In navigation, HPC is involved in creating a cognitive map-like representation of the environment. PC is involved in the translation of this cognitive representation based on body-centered location into the appropriate navigation decision. Thus, we tested the hypothesis that impaired HPC-cortical interactions during navigation underlie deficits in spatial navigation in a mouse model of AD. We decoded correct and incorrect trials from HPC and PC neural data on the spatial reorientation task. 3xTg-AD mice showed a different cross-region pattern compared to control, indicating that HPC-PC coordination impairments during active navigation may contribute spatial navigation deficits. Additionally, 3xTg-AD mice showed a shift in how the HPC mapped the spatial-reorientation-task, indicating underlying dysfunction in HPC may also contribute to spatial navigation deficits.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Psychology in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 7, 2024.

TITLE: Synthesis and Properties of High Entropy Spinel Oxides

AUTHOR: DC, Bijay

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Beekman, Christianne

MEMBER (committee member): Dobrosavljević, Vladimir

MEMBER (committee member): Baumbach, Ryan E.

MEMBER (committee member): Tripathi, Vandana

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Physics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (54 pages)

ABSTRACT: High entropy oxides (HEO) are the oxides containing five or more metals in a single lattice andthe large composition space suggests that properties of interest can be readily optimized. Magnetic correlation in HEOs that inherently depend on the coordination geometry, valence, spin state, and type of metal cations that are hybridized with the bridging oxygen, are naturally affected by an extreme diversity of neighboring ionic configuration. In this dissertation, we synthesized the bulk target of high entropy vanadium oxide, as the spinel vanadate and ferrite is a magnetically frustrated system an interesting non-collinear spin textures at low temperatures. We report the epitaxial growth of AF e2O4,(where A site contains five elements MgO, Fe2O3, NiO, CuO, CoO) thin films on the substrates spanning a range of strain states. We successfully grew the single crystalline thin films on different substrates of MgO, MgAl2O4, and STO where the crystal structure changed from its bulk cubic to a tetragonal unit cell which is confirmed by the Rigaku X-ray diffraction. These films show smooth surfaces, high crystallinity, and strong magnetic responses at room temperature. The perturbations in the crystal structure lead to interesting magnetic properties in the AF e2O4 thin films. We investigated the magnetic behavior in the material as the temperature-dependent magnetization measurements performed on AFe2O4 film show a magnetic transition onset above the room temperature regardless of the strain state. Strain effects have a strong influence on magnetization responses. For the tensile strained AFe2O4 film grown on MgO substrate, out- of-plane shows the hysteresis with the higher coercive field which indicates the easy axis on the out-of-plane direction. But in the case of slightly compressed film on a-axes and strained on c-axes strained AFe2O4 film on MAO substrate the out-of-plane shows slightly smaller hysteresis with a smaller coercive field which moves the easy axis towards an in-plane direction. The differences in the magnetic behavior between the bulk and thin film, in both the magnetic structure and anisotropy, provide insights on tuning the compositionally complex materials that may be applicable in the next-generation memory devices.

TITLE: Socially Just Peer Leaders: Exploring the Experiences and Development of Peer Leaders to Support Social Justice Development in Their Peers

AUTHOR: Dement, Mary Elizabeth

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Guthrie, Kathy L.

MEMBER (university representative): Jones, Maxine Deloris

MEMBER (committee member): Beatty, Cameron C.

MEMBER (committee member): Hu, Shouping

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (126 pages)

ABSTRACT: With the current priorities and challenges surrounding equity in higher education, many institutions are looking for new resources to support diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) goals at their institutions. One resource that has been shown to be underutilized across social justice development in higher education are peer leaders. While some institutions may have peer leader groups that specialize in supporting social justice initiatives, peer leaders, unless it's their primary function, are not being trained on social justice or utilized at most institutions of higher education to support social justice development. However, peer leaders have been found to be very impactful on the development and experience of their peers throughout college, but because peer leaders are not exploring social justice in training, it limits their ability to support their peers in the topic. Throughout this, a qualitative exploratory study is explored that was facilitated with peer leaders at Stetson University to understand how peer leaders serve as socially just leaders within a campus community and what support institutions can provide to develop peer leaders to serve as socially just leaders. Individual interviews and focus group interviews were conducted to gain perspective from peer leaders, their understanding of leadership and social justice, their application of socially just leadership, and areas of support they looked for from the institution. The culturally relevant leadership learning model served as the theoretical framework for this study which supported the development of interview questions, analysis of data, and development of recommendations from the study. Research within this study found common trends from the peer leaders in the ways in which they supported their peers as socially just leaders through common themes and sub-themes. And the study also found commons trends in the ways in which the peer leaders were looking for further support from the university to be socially just leaders. Results in the study suggest that peer leaders, no matter the focus of their peer leader role, have the ability to serve as socially just leaders and peer leaders are looking for support from their institutions to help them in serving as socially just leaders in their peer leader roles. Results also breakdown different ways in which peer leaders are serving as socially just leaders within the campus community.

TITLE: Using Multiple Case Studies to Explore MTSS-B in Elementary Schools

AUTHOR: Dennis, Denise L.

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Root, Jenny Rose

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Dennis, Lindsay Rae

MEMBER (university representative): Jones, Tamara Bertrand

MEMBER (committee member): Fleury, Veronica

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Program in Special Education

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (188 pages)

ABSTRACT: The purpose of this qualitative exploratory multiple-case study was to explore how school-based teams make decisions and implement a Multi-Tiered System of Support for students exhibiting problem behavior (MTSS-B). Mandates require the use of MTSS to support both academic (MTSS-A) and behavioral needs (MTSS-B) of K-12 students. The definitions, guidelines, and structures for MTSS-A are more consistent and well-researched than those for MTSS-B. Little is known about how school-based teams make decisions about implementing MTSS-B and the factors they identify as influencing those decisions. It is important to learn how MTSS-B team members engage in the process at each tier (1, 2, and 3), how they develop interventions of increasing intensity, and what factors influence individual and team decision-making. Chapter One introduces the importance of understanding the history of disproportionate discipline and identification for special education services and provides a brief literature review of research previously conducted about how teams, fidelity, and culture are related to MTSS-B and how Contingency Theory and contingent decision-making have been connected to systems including schools. Chapter Two is the methods section where the rationale and details of this multiple case study are provided including how I increased trustworthiness and how the data was collected and analyzed. Chapter Three provides findings of the analyzed data both within and across cases. The themes developed are evidenced using invivo codes provided by participants. Overarching themes reflect some significant differences in how MTSS-B is implemented at each school. Differences are attributed to the factors considered by teams such as the home life of students, poverty, drug use, students' exposure to domestic violence, lack of supervision, homelessness, and the violent neighborhood where School 2 is located. School 1 identified factors such as the poverty experienced by their students and the often-unrecognized need for academic support. The types of behaviors exhibited by students were described as mainly classroom disruptions at School 1 and as physical aggression at School 2, requiring different approaches to consequences. Chapter Three concludes with a synthesis of how the elements of the exploratory framework are represented in how teams report implementing MTSS-B, how fidelity may contribute to the current operations of the teams, and how culture is represented by the factors influencing decision-making. Chapter Four's discussion ties components of the exploratory framework and collected data to previous research. Teams both report using a wide variety of factors, variables, and contingencies both subjective and objective to guide decision-making. This use of additional contextual and environmental variables indicates the likelihood that while teams report the use of traditional data-driven decision-making additionally, they are engaging in the contingency theory of decision-making. The chapter concludes with limitations and implications for future research.

TITLE: The Intersection of Episcopal Identity, Elitism, and Social Justice Practices in the Elementary Classroom

AUTHOR: Derryberry, Quentin M., III

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Khurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Kurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (university representative): Eklund, Robert C. (Robert Charles), 1958-

MEMBER (committee member): Milligan, Jeffrey Ayala

MEMBER (committee member): Zuilkowski, Stephanie Simmons

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (134 pages)

ABSTRACT: Elite private institutions, renowned for their exceptional academic offerings and rigorous selection processes, attract top-tier students and faculty; however, exclusive private schooling has perpetuated social and economic disparities by granting unequal advantages to select groups, deepening educational gaps in society. This dissertation investigated the integration of social justice principles in the educational framework of an elite private Episcopal institution in a major Florida metropolitan area. Guided by the ethos of the U.S. Episcopal Church and its commitment to inclusivity and social justice, the study delved into how teachers at the study site navigated the implementation of social justice-oriented themes in their classrooms. Drawing upon critical theory, the research explored the challenges and approaches of seven selected teachers known for their dedication to social justice values. Through purposeful sampling and multiple data collection methods—including semistructured interviews, focus groups, classroom observations, and participant equity walkthroughs—the study elucidated the complexities and nuances of integrating social justice into classroom practices in an elite educational setting. Key research questions examined teachers' definitions, approaches, enactments, and negotiations of social justice, shedding light on the ways these principles are manifested and challenged in the school community. This single-case study offered an in-depth exploration, unraveling the intricate interplay between social justice values and educational practices in the context of an Episcopal school committed to fostering diversity, equity, and inclusion. Key findings suggested that some educators found their motivation in spiritual or religious themes, (a) emphasizing service and philanthropy as a way to give back to others, (b) drawing inspiration from various world religions, and (c) aligning efforts with the school's Christian mission. Conversely, another group expressed focus on promoting equality, catalyzing social transformation, and empowering marginalized voices by prioritizing systemic change over mere acts of service. Despite these differing perspectives on social justice, both groups acknowledged the privileged status of their students and described their aims to instill a sense of responsibility toward serving others, whether through direct assistance or empowerment. The participants viewed socially just classroom environments as inclusive spaces that fostered trust and belonging, where students could make mistakes, engage in critical analysis, and receive differentiated support. Conversely, educators also discussed facing challenges in implementing social justice principles due to Florida's social climate, lack of organizational mission alignment, and time constraints. Despite these obstacles, the research aimed to uncover the underlying causes of inequity by examining how teachers conceptualized and enacted social justice in their classrooms amid external pressures. The study identified three key themes: (a) the role of elite private Episcopal schools in perpetuating social reproduction and elitism, (b) the crucial role of teachers in fostering Episcopal values and social justice advocacy, and (c) the potential of the Episcopal identity to serve as a powerful force for promoting justice in various forms. Overall, the findings and recommendations provide guidance for elite Episcopal schools seeking to reaffirm their commitment to justice and equality, emphasizing the importance of instilling Christian values of democracy and egalitarianism while raising awareness of students' privileges and moral obligations to contribute to a fair society.

TITLE: A Comprehensive Assessment of Advantages and Disadvantages from Electric Tugboat Deployment in Maritime Transportation

AUTHOR: Devarapali, Shanmukh Sai Chandra Prasad

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Dulebenets, Maxim A.

MEMBER (committee member): Sobanjo, John Olusegun, 1958-

MEMBER (committee member): Elwardany, Michael

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (136 pages)

ABSTRACT: The shipping industry is one of the significant sources of pollution and global warming. About 2.5% of worldwide greenhouse gas emissions in 2018 came from the shipping industry. Conventional tugboats are viewed as one of the contributors towards the overall amount of emissions produced from maritime transportation. The International Maritime Organization (IMO) estimates that tugboats account for 2% of global shipping emissions, including nitrogen oxides (NOx), sulfur oxides (SOx), and particulate matter (PM). Electric tugboats could be a promising alternative to these issues because they don't emit any harmful gases. Furthermore, electric tugboats do not produce as much noise as conventional tugboats. However, certain aspects should be carefully considered before the wide deployment of electric tugboats would be feasible, including financial viability of using electric tugboats, impacts on society, legal framework for using electric tugboats, and the overall practicality of deploying electric tugboats.This research mainly focuses on a comprehensive assessment of advantages and disadvantages from electric tugboat deployment in maritime transportation. First, all the basic background information associated with the development and deployment of electric tugboats is reviewed in detail. Second, a thorough literature review is conducted focusing on different aspects, including safety issues associated with tugboats, tugboat scheduling, electric tugboats versus conventional tugboats, environmental issues, salvage tugboats and other types of tugboats. Third, a comprehensive evaluation of electric tugboats is performed based on all the information acquired along with the interviews that were performed with the leading experts in the tugboat industry. Last but not least, the financial viability and economic performance of electric tugboats using econometric techniques is assessed as a part of this thesis research as well. Electric tugboats consistently demonstrate a greater initial capital outlay, although offer substantially reduced ongoing operational expenses owing to their enhanced efficiency and diminished maintenance needs. Consequently, they emerge as the most economically appealing alternative for long-term planning. On the other hand, conventional tugboats may seem more economically advantageous in the short term, but they ultimately accumulate significantly more expenses over time, especially in the face of increasing annual costs (e.g., unexpected increase in the cost of diesel fuel, unexpected increase in maintenance costs). Hybrid tugboats present a viable compromise, exhibiting certain cost benefits in comparison to the conventional and electric tugboat options. Therefore, the existing obstacles related to electric tugboat deployment have to be further investigated and addressed in the following years. The conducted research would be of essence to researchers and industry practitioners and can serve as a valuable reference for the relevant future studies.

TITLE: Advanced Functional Regression Models in Biomedical Data Analysis

AUTHOR: Ding, Shengxian

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Huang, Chao

MEMBER (university representative): Nowakowski, Richard S.

MEMBER (committee member): Srivastava, Anuj, 1968-

MEMBER (committee member): Barrientos, Andrés Felipe

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Statistics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (101 pages)

ABSTRACT: Due to the rapid development of imaging acquisition techniques, a large amount of large-scale biomedical studies on neuro-related diseases have been established, such as Alzheimer's Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) study, the Human Connectome Project (HCP) study and the UK biobank (UKB) study. These databases have myriad data types, including genomic data, phenotypic data, imaging data, clinical outcomes, and many others. Among the studies on biomedical data, functional regression has received the most attention in functional data analysis (FDA). However, existing statistical methods in this field still face challenges while considering unknown confounders caused by imaging heterogeneity, non-Euclidean imaging data, or imaging data with jump discontinuities. To tackle these challenges, we propose several functional regression models for biomedical data with different structures. First, the function-on-scalar regression model is a powerful tool for building the relationship between the functional responses and covariates of interest. Although it has been widely applied in many large-scale neuroimaging studies, most existing approaches fail to take into account the nonlinear relationship and the unknown confounders caused by imaging heterogeneity. In particular, the potential heterogeneity may be caused by the differences in the study environment, population, design, protocols, and other unknown factors. To address this challenge, we develop a single index function-on-scalar regression model to investigate the nonlinear relationship between functional responses and covariates of interest while adjusting for unknown confounding factors caused by potential imaging heterogeneity. Both estimation and inference procedures are established for unknown quantities in our proposed model. In addition, the asymptotic properties of estimated functions and detected confounding factors are also systematically investigated. The finite-sample performance of our proposed method is assessed by using both Monte Carlo simulations and a real data example on the diffusion tensor images from the ADNI study. Second, causal mediation analysis is widely utilized in neuroscience to investigate the role of brain image phenotypes in the neurological pathways from genetic exposures to clinical outcomes. However, it is still difficult to conduct a genome-wide mediation analysis with the shapes of brain regions as mediators due to several challenges including (i) large-scale genetic exposures, i.e., millions of single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs); (ii) nonlinear Hilbert space for shape mediators; and (iii) statistical inference on the direct and indirect effects. To tackle these challenges, this paper proposes a mediation analysis framework with high dimensional genetic exposures and shape mediators. First, to address the issue caused by the high dimensionality in genetic exposures, a fast genome-wide association analysis is conducted to discover potential genetic variants with significant genetic effects on the clinical outcome. Second, the square-root velocity function representations are extracted from the shapes of the subcortical brain structure, which fall in an unconstrained linear Hilbert subspace. Third, to identify the underlying causal pathways from the detected SNPs to the clinical outcome implicitly through the shape mediators, we proposed a framework consisting of a shape-on-scalar model and a scalar-on-shape model. Furthermore, the bootstrap resampling approach is adopted to investigate both global and spatial significant mediation effects. Finally, our framework is applied to the ADNI corpus callosum shape data, and we successfully identify the mediation effect of a subset of candidate SNPs on Alzheimer's Disease through some specific subregions of the corpus callosum. Finally, most existing methods in functional data analysis assume the smoothness of the functional responses and the coefficient functions or require some smoothing techniques before fitting the functional responses into the statistical models. However, this is often violated in biomedical imaging data, which usually contains spatially contiguous regions or effect regions with relatively sharp edges due to the physical or biological reasons. Thus they tend to blur the image data near the edges or jumps. While the pixel or voxel based methods ignore the spatial information of imaging data, they fail to characterize the spatial correlations.Thus, it is essential to propose an appropriate framework to reveal the relationship between imaging responses and the covariates of interest, while taking the discontinuous property and spatial correlation into account simultaneously. To address these challenges, we proposed a Bayesian hypothesis testing framework on image-on-scalar regression model with mixed effects, and consider wavelet basis decomposition to account for the sudden transitions in the imaging responses. To depict the spatial correlation between grids for each observation, a conditional auto-regressive (CAR) model is utilized. Due to the advantage of Bayesian analysis in hypothesis testing, we propose a Bayesian framework for an image-on-scalar CAR model using a set of Normal - Inverse-Gamma - Uniform priors, introducing the local indicators to conduct block-wise hypothesis tests efficiently and flexibly.

TITLE: Understanding the Bio-Nanointerface and Sensor Design Based on Inorganic Nanoparticle Conjugates

AUTHOR: Dridi, Narjes

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Mattoussi, Hedi

MEMBER (university representative): Tang, Hengli

MEMBER (committee member): Strouse, Geoffrey F.

MEMBER (committee member): Roper, Michael Gabriel

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (202 pages)

ABSTRACT: Inorganic nanocrystals have garnered significant attention due to their unique physical and optical properties, spurring extensive research into their development for technological applications like electronic devices, solar cells, and biomedical diagnostics. Tailoring these nanocrystals for specific environments requires precise control over their photophysical, mechanical, and chemical properties. Particularly in bio-related applications, engineering the surface of these nanomaterials to be hydrophilic, biocompatible, and amenable to further bioconjugation while maintaining stability in challenging conditions is crucial. This dissertation aims to explore new ligands to passivate the surfaces of inorganic nanomaterials, preserving their structural and optoelectronic integrity and ensuring long-term stability. Additionally, the dissertation investigates the formation of protein corona on metallic nanocrystals, focusing on understanding the factors governing corona formation and strategies for prevention through ligand design. Furthermore, we explore leveraging the optical properties of gold nanoparticles to design biosensing tools with high sensitivity, specificity, and rapid assay times. In Chapter 1, fundamental optical, physical, and chemical characteristics of plasmonic, semiconductor, and magnetic nanomaterials are described. Synthetic chemistry and surface coating techniques are briefly outlined, with recent advancements in surface engineering and ligand design being highlighted. Various effective methods for bioconjugation on nanoparticle surfaces are explored. Additionally, "protein corona" is defined, its composition is examined in terms of factors influencing it, and its implications for biology and the environment are discussed. Finally, notable examples of bio-applications involving inorganic nanomaterials are discussed. Chapter 2 presents a novel series of polymer ligands with multi-coordinating sites, which were designed using the hydroxamate anchoring motif. These ligands were subsequently employed for coating luminescent quantum dots, gold nanoparticles, and iron oxide nanoparticles. The synthesis of the ligands involved a nucleophilic addition reaction between poly(isobutylene-alt-maleic anhydride) and amine-terminated moieties, including the hydroxamate precursor (NH2OH-HCl) and short polyethylene glycol hydrophilic blocks. This synthesis method allowed the architecture and stoichiometry of the final compound to be adjusted. It was found that these hydroxamate-based polymers were strongly coordinated with ZnS-overcoated quantum dots (QDs), Au nanoparticles (AuNPs), and iron oxide nanoparticles (IONPs), resulting in stable dispersions for all three systems. Chapter 3 examines the non-specific adsorption of proteins on AuNPs by strategically altering the structures of a series of DHLA-based ligands. Electrophoretic mobility is employed to monitor potential corona formation on AuNPs when exposed to bovine serum albumin (BSA) or serum samples, allowing the kinetics of binding to be determined. It is indicated by our findings that AuNPs capped with hydrolipoic acid (DHLA), a small alkyl-COOH, are susceptible to size-dependent interactions with proteins. Insight into the deposition of proteins on the surface of nanomaterials is provided by theoretical calculations using a close-packed model. Corona formation is significantly reduced by coating AuNPs with polyethylene glycol- or zwitterion-appended DHLA. Furthermore, protein adsorption is further characterized using UV-Vis spectroscopy and dynamic light scattering. The significance of surface chemistry and nanomaterial size in corona formation, and potentially preventing it, is underscored by our results. In Chapter 4, the application of plasmonic nanoparticles for sensing purposes is explored. A charge-mediated diagnostic tool for detecting early-stage cancer biomarkers is developed by leveraging the sensitivity of AuNPs' localized surface plasmon resonance to interparticle distance. Three sets of peptides, each with three specific segments, featuring oppositely charged amino acids at their ends to balance the overall peptide charge, are designed. Two of these peptides are used as substrates for matrix metalloproteinase-14 (MMP-14), a cancer biomarker, while the third is utilized as a negative control. When the cleaved peptide undergoes enzymatic digestion, its interaction with negatively charged AuNPs triggers their assembly in a concentration- and time-dependent process. The assay is investigated to determine how varying the size of the nanoparticles affects it, different peptides are explored, and enzyme kinetics are tracked. It is demonstrated by our results that the sensor has a nanomolar range Limit of Detection (LoD) and minimal cross-reactivity with other abundant proteins in serum. The rapid assay time suggests promising applications for the design of future diagnostic tools for cancer and other diseases. In Chapter 5, the findings and implications detailed in this dissertation are summarized, accompanied by a discussion of the future prospects in corona science and biosensor design.

FILENAME: Dross_fsu_0071E_18516.pdf

TITLE: Education through Incarceration: Access to Education within Florida's Prisons

AUTHOR: Dross, Megan M.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Ecton, Walter

MEMBER (university representative): Newman, Joshua I., 1976-

MEMBER (committee member): Herrington, Carolyn D.

MEMBER (committee member): Mokher, Christine G.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (75 pages)

ABSTRACT: Across the United States a significant number of individuals find themselves incarcerated each year. For the state of Florida, this number represents one of the highest in the country (Carson, 2021). Prior research has indicated that incarcerated populations across the country tend to have a lower literacy level and less education experience than most (Bender et al., 2016; Cho & Tyler, 2010; Dewey et al., 2020; Lockwood et al., 2015; Pompoco et al., 2017). The addition of education to one's experience while serving their time in prison can not only improve these things but also their post-release job opportunities and the individual's quality of life while serving their time (Cho & Tyler, 2010; Courtney, 2019; Lockwood et al., 2015; McCorkel & DeFina, 2019; Pompoco et al., 2017). Knowing the benefits education can bring, this study looks to understand access to education programs for those housed in a Florida Department of Corrections facility. Specifically, this study examines what community and institutional factors may predict the offering of career and technical education (CTE) programs and academic and special education (ASE) programs and why. Through a series of logistical regressions, this study found that there are several factors that can predict certain education offerings both at the county and facility levels. For CTE programs, positive factors predicting that a facility will offer CTE include location in a rural county, the number of facilities within an area, being privately run, and potentially new legislation. For ASE programming, the size of the correctional facility population as well as the gender served were positive factors on the probability of program offering. Within both areas, there are also factors that can reduce the probability of program offering. For CTE programs these include increased enrollment within post-secondary education within the county, the race of the county population, the custody classification level of the correctional facility, gender served at the facility, and the percentage of residents committed to a correctional facility each year. For ASE programming, institutions in rural counties have a lower likelihood of offering ASE coursework. There are several study implications that focus on increasing access to education programs for those currently incarcerated in Florida. First is evaluating the connection between rural communities and correctional education offering. For CTE programs, location in a rural county is a positive relationship, while for ASE programs it is not. Understanding the support and value the rural community is bringing to CTE education can not only help to expand it, but also address what challenges may come to offering basic education in the same way. Additionally, the population of both the county and facility were significant in the odds of program offering. For counties with an increased diversity, odds of CTE program offerings declined. For every 1% increase of Black residents, the probability of CTE programs were lower by 10.4%. A similar trend was seen for those classified as Other showing 25.9% lower odds. Looking at the population of residents, it is important to dive deeper into this analysis, breaking down the population into further subgroups to truly understand the outcomes. Additionally, correctional facilities serving male residents showed a higher probability of ASE programs, but a lower probability of CTE programs. Focusing on the facility itself, both those locations with a highest custody classification of community or maximum saw lower odds of CTE program offering as compared to other custody classifications. In contrast, privately run facilities saw higher probability of CTE programs. While the study did conclude that education access was present for those incarcerated within Florida, several factors were identified that could hinder the offering of these programs in certain facilities and areas. The thing found most impactful was the location where an individual was housed. Focusing on both the physical location as well as the custody designation given to the facility, the likelihood of CTE and ASE program offerings differed. With a goal of expanding programming to all, knowing why both the opportunities and challenges exist provides context to expand partnership and legislation within the state system.

FILENAME: DuPree_fsu_0071E_18482.pdf

TITLE: Agency and Equanimity: Neo-Pyrrhonian Reflections on Action, Free Will, and Moral Responsibility

AUTHOR: Dupree, Matthew L.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Mele, Alfred R., 1951-

MEMBER (university representative): Kavka, Martin

MEMBER (committee member): Clarke, Randolph K.

MEMBER (committee member): Kearns, Stephen, 1979-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Philosophy

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (314 pages)

ABSTRACT: I proceed according to a skeptical, Pyrrhonist inspired metaphilosophy to address two perennial issues: the nature of human agency and our culpability in acting. After unpacking this approach, as well as offering some initial remarks that lay out the playing field, I work to accomplish two things. First, I problematize a picture of human beings and their agency in which they amount to the independent sources of what they do—such that they can be held accountable in a fashion that presupposes such things. Second, I offer a replacement intended to fill the void left by critique: a different orientation toward action, free will, and moral responsibility. By pursuing these tasks, I follow the skeptic way as it shows itself to me—in which one is to offer both a skeptical critique and a skeptical solution to philosophical problems.

TITLE: Exploring the Experiences of MSW Students: from an HBCU to a PWI

AUTHOR: Edwards, Carol Campbell

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Ludwig, Eric

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Jones, Tamara Bertrand

MEMBER (university representative): Newman, Joshua I., 1976-

MEMBER (committee member): Beatty, Cameron C.

MEMBER (committee member): Moraguez, Daniel

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (111 pages)

ABSTRACT: HBCUs have contributed to the formation of strong leaders who have challenged many assumptions of our nation's founders, defended our sovereignty when attacked by internal and external enemies, and sacrificed for the betterment of their communities. HBCU campuses include opportunities for Black students to engage in religious and community service and to identify with cultural strengths that are expected to help them succeed (Albritton, 2012). HBCUs have higher retention and graduation rates for Black students, and "African American students attending HBCUs are up to 33% more likely to graduate than African American students attending a similar non-HBCU" (Gordon et al., 2021, p. 333). HBCUs are known to provide students with faculty mentors, supportive learning experiences, and a sense of belonging on campus (Kim & Conrad, 2006). Students Although some HBCUs offer MSW programs, participants' decision to attend graduate school at FSU was motivated by the need for a clinically oriented program, internship opportunities, and a desire for new experiences. Following undergraduate studies, 74.8% of graduate social work students attend predominately White institutions (PWIs). However, Black students at PWIs reported that discrimination, isolation, and a lack of support services negatively affected their experiences and served as a distraction to learning (Banks, 2020; Beasley, 2020; Person & Christensen, 1996). Additionally, research exploring Black students' experiences transitioning to a PWI for graduate studies has focused on science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) careers (Allen & Dika, 2020; Charleston et al., 2014; McGee & Martin, 2011). While there is a benefit in understanding the experiences of these students, the increase in the number of Black students pursuing careers in social work and other behavioral sciences warrants research (Bowie et al., 2011). Also, while Rasheem and Brunson (2018) added valuable research contributions focused on Black women and HBCU graduate social work programs, this study expands the conversation to address the unique experiences of Black HBCU graduates seeking MSWs at PWIs. The literature included in this study expands Black students' voices and provides diverse approaches to understanding how to create educational environments that meet their needs (Allen & Dika, 2020; Ladson-Billings, 2013). Deconstructing deficit-based paradigms and elevating the voices of researchers engaged in developing culturally relevant pedagogy provides educational systems with an opportunity to create academic environments that value the intellectual and cultural strengths that students possess (Ladson-Billings, 2017; Royal & Gibson, 2017; Yosso, 2005). Using a qualitative case study design, this study examined the experiences and perceptions of 17 Black Master of Social Work (MSW) students enrolled in the Florida State University (FSU) College of Social Work (CSW) who obtained an undergraduate degree from an HBCU. According to data from the FSU Office of Institutional Research, Black MSW student enrollment increased from 539 students in 2019 to 875 in 2023. The study findings are extricated through brave conversations filled with candor, wit, and resilience as participants recounted the cultural dissonance between their HBCU and PWI experiences. As a result, the study findings identify the cultural strengths and expectations HBCU graduates bring to PWI graduate social work programs, the environmental challenges Black students contend with, and the differences they encounter in faculty and peer relationships. The findings from this study provide implications that advance inclusive academic experiences for Black HBCU graduates attending Predominantly White Institutions (PWIs) for their MSW. To provide comparable levels of support Black students receive at HBCUs, PWIs must better meet the needs of Black students (Banks et al., 2020; Beasley, 2021). Credle and Dean (1991) noted that PWIs must create policies and practices that better meet African American students' culture and academic expectations if they are committed to retaining them. In accordance with the ADEI standards, CSWE's EPAS, and the FSW CSW DEI Plan, this study directly implicates aspects of social work education at PWIs that address implicit and explicit curricula, utilizing inclusive strategies that emphasize student identity, faculty development, and student engagement (Banks et al., 2020; Beasley, 2021; Herzig, 2004).

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Education.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 5, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Antiracism, Culture, Diversity, HBCU, PWI, Social work

TITLE: Trump, Twitter, and January 6th: A Qualitative Analysis of Social Media Frames and the Attack on the Capitol

AUTHOR: Edwards-Heller, Natalie

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Proffitt, Jennifer M.

MEMBER (committee member): Dale, Katherine R.

MEMBER (committee member): McDowell, Stephen D., 1958-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Communication and Information

CORPORATE NAME: School of Communication

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (120 pages)

ABSTRACT: This thesis is a qualitative analysis of the framing used in President Donald Trump's 2020 election-related tweets from April 2020 through January 6, 2021, the day of the attack on the U.S. Capitol, from the perspective of political communication theory. The tweets were analyzed using Fairclough's Critical Discourse Analysis to allow for examination of the text, the discursive practices, and the social practices within the former president's tweets. Analysis, which included textual analysis, as well as consideration of the historical resources of the Final Report of the Select Committee to Investigate the January 6th Attack on the United States Capitol and contemporaneous news articles, revealed that Trump framed his election-related tweets in five interconnected narrative frames: (1) rigged election, (2) making the Red Mirage look real, (3) us v. them, (4) media bias, and (5) stop the steal. Through these frames, communicated to his supporters via his Twitter account, Trump was able to direct, participate, and ultimately end the attack on the U.S. Capitol. Further, implications of the research for communication theory, social media, and United States government are discussed, limitations are presented, and areas of future research are suggested.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the School of Communication in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 29, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Critical Discourse Analysis, Frames, January 6, Political Communication, Social Media, Trump

TITLE: Developing Self-Efficacy through Experiential Education: A Case Study in High School Self-Efficacy Development in Florida

AUTHOR: Eller, Joshua A.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Milligan, Jeffrey Ayala

MEMBER (university representative): Guerette, Amy R.

MEMBER (committee member): Moraguez, Daniel

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (93 pages)

ABSTRACT: Research on self-efficacy and how it is developed in K-12 educational spaces has primarily focused on traditional classroom spaces and activities. Little research has focused on self-efficacy development in the context of outdoor experiential learning. Through this study, I use focus groups, in-depth interviewing, and on-line journal prompts to explore how junior and senior high school students participating in a co-curricular leadership program describe their experiences of self-efficacy development through the program's outdoor learning experiences. Using a thematic analysis approach, I developed three core themes common to the experiences: inspiration from others, growth and transformation, and emotional resilience. Consistent with previous research on self-efficacy, participants identified performance accomplishment as the major pathway by which self-efficacy developed.
