FILENAME: Ellsworth_fsu_0071E_18288.pdf

TITLE: Investigating Venom Complexity and Venom Resistance Using Scolopendromorpha and Drosophila

AUTHOR: Ellsworth, Schyler A.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Rokyta, Darin

MEMBER (university representative): Sang, Qing-Xiang

MEMBER (committee member): Burgess, Scott C.

MEMBER (committee member): Hughes, Kimberly A., 1960-

MEMBER (committee member): Houle, David

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Biological Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (117 pages)

ABSTRACT: Many venom proteins have presumably been convergently recruited by taxa from diverse venomous lineages. These toxic proteins have characteristics that allow them to remain stable in solution and have a high propensity for toxic effects on prey and/or potential predators. Despite this well-established convergent toxin recruitment, some toxins seem to be lineage specific. To further investigate the toxic proteins found throughout venomous lineages, in chapter one we performed venom proteomics and venom-gland transcriptomics on two individual red bark centipedes (Scolopocryptops sexspinosus). Combining the protein phenotype with the transcript genotype resulted in the first in-depth venom characterization of S. sexspinosus, including 72 venom components that were identified in both the transcriptome and proteome and 1,468 nontoxin transcripts identified in the transcriptome. Ten different toxin families were represented in the venom and venom gland with the majority of the toxins belonging to metalloproteases, CAPS (cysteine-rich secretory protein, antigen 5, and pathogenesis-related 1 proteins), and -pore-forming toxins. Nine of these toxin families shared a similar proteomic structure to venom proteins previously identified from other centipedes. However, the most highly expressed toxin family, the adamalysin-like metalloproteases, has until now only been observed in the venom of snakes. We confirmed adamalysin-like metalloprotease activity by means of in vivo functional assays. The recruitment of an adamalysin-like metalloprotease into centipede venom represents a striking case of convergent evolution. In chapter two, we investigated the evolution of venom proteins and we tested two different hypotheses of venom evolution. Whole gene duplication followed by nucleotide differentiation is one of the simplest mechanisms to develop new functions for genes. However, the processes underlying multigene family evolution remain controversial. We utilize multigene families found within the diversity of toxic proteins in venom to test two separate hypotheses related to venom evolution, the two-speed mode of venom evolution and the rapid accumulation of variation in exposed residues or RAVER model. The two-speed mode of venom evolution proposes that different types of selection impact ancient and younger venomous lineages with negative selection being the predominant form in ancient lineages and positive selection being the dominant form in younger lineages. The RAVER hypothesis states that instead of different types of selection acting on different ages of venomous lineages, the different types of selection will selectively contribute to amino acid variation based on whether or not the residue is exposed to the solvent. This follows the longstanding understanding of protein evolution that suggests that residues found within the structural or active regions of the protein will be under negative or purifying selection, while residues that do not form part of these areas will be more prone to positive selection. To test these two different hypotheses, we compared the venom of 26 scolopendromorph centipedes from six currently recognized species from across North America using both transcriptomics and proteomics. First, we estimated the phylogenetic relationships of the centipedes used in this study and then characterized the diverse the venom components from across the identified clades. From this diversity of venom family proteins, we conducted selection-based analyses and compared them with the three-dimensional properties of the venom proteins. We found support for both venom evolution hypotheses through the prevalence of negative selection across all proteins and found evidence of positive selection occurring on residues that were exposed to the solvent, while the structural and less solvent exposed residues corresponded with higher rates of negative selection. Through the use of phylogenetics, proteo-transcriptomics, and selection-based analyses, we were able to describe the evolution of venom from an ancient venomous lineage and support principles of protein evolution that directly relate to multigene family evolution. In chapter three, we examined how a phenotype and the corresponding genotype of one species can affect the phenotype and genotype of a coevolving species. Coevolution, or the reciprocal selection between two interacting species, is a key mechanism for the generation and maintenance of adaptive variation. To understand the genetic mechanisms of coevolution, we first need to establish the genotype-by-genotype interactions that contribute to reciprocal selection. However, linking a singular complex trait to its genotype is one of the most difficult challenges in biology, and that difficulty increases when linking the genotypes of two traits that are acting interspecifically. To disentangle the genetic mechanisms behind coevolving traits, we investigated the interaction between two complex traits, venom and venom resistance. To connect the genetics mechanisms behind venom and venom resistance, we performed an extreme quantitative loci mapping study to uncover the genetic mechanisms underlying venom resistance through injecting two distinct centipede venoms into Drosophila. Through injecting a mainly proteolytic venom and a mainly neurotoxic venom, previously described through proteo-transcriptomics, we revealed a unique genome-wide response to venom resistance. We identified a unique genetic response to both venom types, where the mainly proteolytic venom was associated with biological processes relating to cell adhesion, cytoskeleton organization, synapse organization and nervous system development, while the principally neurotoxic venom was only associated with synapse organization. This comparative approach also uncovered a sex-specific response to venom resistance, which has not yet been described in the literature. To verify the function of the causal genes from our genotype-to-genotype map of venom and venom resistance, we performed an RNAi knockdown study which implicated genes and genetic pathways already described in the literature and uncovered novel pathways that could lead to venom resistance. Through an experimental approach, we comparatively characterized the genetic basis of complex traits and molecularly linked interspecific traits, adding to our understanding of venom and venom resistance and how organisms can coevolve.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Biological Science in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): November 20, 2023.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Darin R. Rokyta, Professor Directing Dissertation; Qing-Xiang A. Sang, University Representative; Scott C. Burgess, Committee Member; Kimberly A. Hughes, Committee Member; David C. Houle, Committee Member.

SUBJECT: Ecology

SUBJECT: Evolution (Biology)

TITLE: A Hybrid Particle and Coupled Moment-of-Fluid Level Set Method for Multiphase Flows

AUTHOR: Estebe, Cody

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Sussman, Mark

MEMBER (university representative): Wang, Xiaoqiang

MEMBER (committee member): Bao, Feng

MEMBER (committee member): Lee, Sanghyun

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mathematics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (110 pages)

ABSTRACT: A new algorithm that hybridizes massless marker particles with the coupled level set moment-of-fluid method to improve the interface reconstruction in multiphase flow problems is proposed. This new method aims to take advantage of both near-interface and on-interface Lagrangian marker particles in a similar fashion to the Particle Level Set (PLS) Method, first introduced by Enright et al. [28]. In contrast to Enright et al. who used particles to improve the mass conservation of the level set method, in this thesis the utility of the particles are studied to improve the slope reconstruction for the multimaterial moment of fluid (MOF) method [54]. Additionally, prior to this, PLS methods have not been implemented on N-phase flow problems involving more than two materials. The proposed method is volume-preserving. Furthermore, we hypothesize that deriving slopes from particles overcomes the surface tension checkerboard instability of the MOF method first discussed by Ye et al. [116]. Ye et al. developed the ``Continuous Moment of Fluid'' (CMOF) method in order to overcome this checkerboard instability. It is asserted in this thesis that augmenting the interface representation with meshless particle produces similar results to that of the CMOF method, at a lowered computational cost. The new coupled particle level set and moment of fluid method (PLSMOF) is demonstrated on benchmark tests in 2d, 3d axisymmetric ``R-Z", and 3d problems including rigid body motion, two phase flow, and incompressible multiphase flow problems undergoing phase change involving several different materials with `triple-points'. Comparisons are made between the new PLSMOF method proposed herein, the CMOF method, and the MOF method for multimaterial multiphase flows.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Mathematics in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 2, 2024.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Mark Sussman, Professor Directing Dissertation; Xiaoqiang Wang, University Representative; Feng Bao, Committee Member; Sanghyun Lee, Committee Member.

ABSTRACT: ALL YOU CAN EAT centers queer-femme expression within a cis/hetero-normative patriarchal male gaze. Its poems explore identity via an eclectic, pop-culture-informed, and thoroughly gurlesque self-portraiture of its speaker, presented in slam-style monologues as well as formal and experimental verse. True to the implication of its title, this manuscript further caters its craft and styles to a wide range of poetic tastes, as ALL YOU CAN EAT balances narrative, music, image, and form within a contemporary confessional poetics: There are cows and aliens in this manuscript, as well as Emily Dickinson and Meryl Streep. There are dysfunctional family dynamics compounded by a mother's cancer diagnosis, struggles with the body and self-image, and there are bagel and vegan cake-related accidents. Meanwhile, ALL YOU CAN EAT's speaker seeks to reclaim themself from objectification and fetishization in their quest for self-development. Within the combination of these ingredients, ALL YOU CAN EAT contrasts dichotomies of hunger and indulgence, realism and surrealism, sincerity and humor, trauma and joy, as well as girlhood safety and the perils which accompany feminine sexual maturity.

TITLE: Mobile Homes Drive

AUTHOR: Freeman-Moser, Alyssa

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Stuckey-French, Elizabeth

MEMBER (committee member): Winegardner, Mark, 1961-

MEMBER (committee member): Roberts, Diane, 1959-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of English

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (333 pages)

ABSTRACT: Mobile Homes Drive is the story of a mother, Nessa, raising a teenage daughter alone in a trailer park in the mid-nineties. When Nessa discovers neighbor Justin's dead child in a hot car, she finds herself amid a culture war. The town's sympathies do not extend to Justin, a recovering drug addict, though Nessa believes the child's death was an accident. At the front of the movement against Justin is Shelby Fuller, pastor of the local church and Nessa's boss. Nessa's testimony as witness to the incident is challenged as Shelby uses the child's death to kick off a bid for town mayor. Months later, participation in Justin's defense prompts Shelby to fire Nessa. Meanwhile, Shelby plans to demolish Mobile Homes Drive, where Nessa lives, to appease his constituents' prejudices against poverty. To legally outmaneuver the powerful clergyman, Nessa consults Justin's attractive attorney, Brent. Just as Nessa's new relationship blooms, her estranged husband Dale returns with a pregnant fiancé in tow. When Dale discovers an inappropriate relationship between his daughter and Pastor Shelby's adult son, Dale threatens jobless, homeless Nessa's custody of their daughter. Mobile Homes Drive contemplates the subtleties of a small-town class system, the role of Christianity in Southern politics, and the tangle of familial relationships.

TITLE: Are Journalists Still Deadnaming? : Journalistic Practices and Rhetorical Choices in Reporting on Murdered Transgender People

AUTHOR: Fulk, Hannah

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Houck, Davis W.

MEMBER (committee member): Proffitt, Jennifer M.

MEMBER (committee member): Nudd, Donna M.

MEMBER (committee member): Lantz, Brendan

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Communication and Information

CORPORATE NAME: School of Communication

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (104 pages)

ABSTRACT: According to research from FSU's Hate Crime and Policy Institute, since early 2010, print journalists have been deadnaming (i.e., calling a transgender person by their birth name when they have changed their name as part of their gender transition) and misgendering transgender victims of violence in fatal crime reporting across the U.S. These are hateful acts toward the LGBTQ+ community, and affected transgender people have been repeatedly misrepresented in mainstream media now for over a decade. Though the LGBTQ+ movement has progressed immensely, there are concentrated geographic regions that showcase high numbers of transgender murder victims, and even higher numbers of offensive journalistic practices regarding trans lives and deaths. In order for researchers, journalists, and activists to eliminate such journalistic practices, they must first understand the recent landscape of journalism and how news content on anti-transgender violence has changed in the last decade. In the master's thesis, "Are Journalists Still Deadnaming? Journalistic Practices and Rhetorical Choices in Reporting on Murdered Transgender People," I utilize quantitative research methods to explore first, the foundation for this media phenomenon by collecting basic statistics on news coverage from 1980-2010; then, I utilize qualitative methods based on political economy of media and rhetorical criticism to deeply analyze the structure and copy of articles written on transgender murder cases from 2016-2022. My research questions include 1) How, if at all, has the use of deadnaming and pronouns changed from 2016-2022 in journalistic reporting on murdered transgender people? 2) What themes are present in journalistic writing that communicate a political or ideological viewpoint on transgender people in relation to their murder? 3) Are the life narratives of murdered transgender people featured in the news reporting on their deaths? Using this data, I draw conclusions and recommend changes to newspaper journalism to avoid media misrepresentation of murdered transgender people in the future.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 1, 2024.

ABSTRACT: The topic of sustainability, in regard to cruelty-free and sustainable efforts from brands, has become growling popular with the younger generations, specifically in the cosmetic industry. This study investigated the impact of cosmetic companies' regarding branding cruelty-free and sustainability on consumer engagement by looking at likes, followers, comment numbers and other Instagram metrics. The literature review highlighted important studies about animal testing theories, legitimacy theory, corporate social responsibility, customer relationship management, sustainability, and cruelty-free branding, and Kolter's 5 A's of Marketing. Another significant finding was that cruelty-free brands will use the later stages of the 5 A's of Sales Marketing, like act and advocate which encourage consumers to use and purchase their products. The findings of this study also indicate that cosmetic brands that post about their CSR initiatives use the later stages of the 5 A's of Sales Marketing.

TITLE: Performance Enhancement of Thermoelectric Devices: Synthesis of Novel Materials and Thermal Evaluations

AUTHOR: Galeano-Cabral, Jorge R.

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (90 pages)

ABSTRACT: Thermoelectric materials hold tremendous promise for advances in fundamental science and practical applications; particularly for robust electricity generation in extreme and remote environments. However, for most materials, the energy conversion efficiency is limited by the proportionality between the electrical and thermal conductivities and small values of the Seebeck coefficient for metals. Despite these limitations, promising thermoelectric properties have been reported forsome Yb-based heavy-fermion compounds. In this dissertation, I explore the hypothesis that the thermoelectric properties of those family compounds, due to their novel structure with exotic electronic and magnetic properties, can be further enhanced through chemical substitution. Additionally, I elaborate on the manufacturability of thermoelectric devices using these compounds and their possible application for cooling probes.

FILENAME: Garavito_fsu_0071E_18740.pdf

TITLE: Applying Howard Gardner's Theory of Multiple Intelligences and Framework of Teaching for Understanding to Pedagogical Approaches for Tuba Fundamentals

AUTHOR: Garavito, Ramon

MEMBER (professor directing treatise): Hightower, Patricia Y.

MEMBER (university representative): Dunnigan, Patrick, 1957-

MEMBER (committee member): Large, Karen McLaughlin

MEMBER (committee member): Moore, Christopher, 1965-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (81 pages)

ABSTRACT: In the 1983 publication, Frames of Mind, Howard Gardner presented his Theory of Multiple Intelligences, which challenged the notion of a quantifiable single general intelligence, g, often measured as IQ. Gardner determined the criteria for the selection of various individual intelligences present in all humans and used these criteria to suggest the existence of seven intelligences: linguistic intelligence, musical intelligence, logical-mathematical intelligence, spatial intelligence, bodily-kinesthetic intelligence, and two personal intelligences; i.e., intrapersonal and interpersonal intelligences. This theory rapidly gained traction in the field of education due to its potential for aiding in the development of adaptable methods of teaching and learning. In his 1999 publication, The Disciplined Mind: What All Students Should Understand, Gardner applied his Multiple Intelligences Theory to an educational framework for facilitating understanding. Gardner's work on cognition and pedagogy has been successfully applied in many disciplines, and the present treatise aims to utilize this framework to create and label a variety of approaches to fundamental tuba pedagogy and inspire others to do the same in this and other contexts. In the pages below, the reader can expect to learn about the tenets and justification of Gardner's Theory of Multiple Intelligences, his framework of teaching for understanding, and be introduced to different methods of teaching the fundamentals of breathing, sound production, intonation, range, dynamics, and articulation in tuba pedagogy from the lens of Gardner's framework of teaching for understanding and his Theory of Multiple Intelligences. This research can be expanded into other concepts within tuba pedagogy, and the contents herein may prove useful to teachers seeking to diversify their teaching.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Treatise submitted to the College of Music in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Music.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 05, 2024.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Matthew Hightower, Professor Directing Treatise; David Patrick Dunnigan, University Representative; Karen Large, Committee Member; Christopher Moore, Committee Member.

FILENAME: Garcia_fsu_0071N_18760.pdf

TITLE: An Investigation of Music Therapists' Perceptions and Practice for Persons with Diabetes Mellitus

AUTHOR: Garcia, Kaitlyn M.

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Standley, Jayne M.

MEMBER (committee member): Gregory, Sarah Dianne

MEMBER (committee member): Iwamasa, Dawn

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (55 pages)

ABSTRACT: The purpose of this study was to assess music therapists' knowledge of music therapy research for treatment for persons with diabetes mellitus (DM). Participants (N = 236) for this study were music therapists who were members of the Certification Board of Music Therapists. Participants were emailed a link to an online survey and results were sent to the researcher after completion. Results indicated a significant difference between how well music therapists who are working with persons with DM know music therapy research for treatment of DM (M = 1.1, SD = 0.30) compared to music therapists not working with persons with DM (M = 1.47, SD = 0.76), t (167) = 4.14, p < .05, d = 0.64. There was also a significant difference regarding how comfortable music therapists felt working with persons with DM (M = 3.8, SD = 1.13) compared to their wiliness to work with persons with DM (M = 4.4, SD = 0.92), t (364) = -4.75, p < .05, d = 0.49. Results suggest that, while music therapists working with persons with DM know music therapy research better than those not working with persons with DM, they still do not know music therapy research well. Music therapists are, however, comfortable, and very willing to work with persons with DM.

FILENAME: Gardner_fsu_0071N_18767.pdf

TITLE: A Simplified Dynamical Framework for the Great Plains Nocturnal Low-Level Jet and Its Impact on Storm-Relative Helicity

AUTHOR: Gardner, Jonathan Leighton

MEMBER (professor co-directing thesis): Chagnon, Jeffrey M.

MEMBER (professor co-directing thesis): Cai, Ming, 1957-

MEMBER (committee member): Wing, Allison

MEMBER (committee member): Hart, Robert E. (Robert Edward), 1972-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (70 pages)

ABSTRACT: A simplified model of the Great Plains Nocturnal Low-level Jet (NLLJ) is formulated to include the classical inertial oscillation (Blackadar) and baroclinic (Holton) mechanisms. Time and height dependent solutions are analytically obtained with and without baroclinic forcing. Solutions are shown to be consistent with results from previous literature and observations. A novel application of this model is that it is applied to evaluate the temporal evolution of storm-relative helicity (SRH) overnight. That is, the NLLJ evolution is analytically linked to SRH_{0-1 km} to gauge its impact on magnitudes of environmental shear favorable for supercells and tornadoes. It is found that the NLLJ can contribute to sustaining SRH_{0-1 km} > 100 m^2 / s^2 for more than eight hours of the nocturnal period, provided there is sufficient baroclinic forcing to drive stronger amplitude oscillations of the winds.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.

FILENAME: Germanton_fsu_0071N_18698.pdf

TITLE: Structure, Dynamics, Rheology, and Char Yield of Preceramic Systems: Preceramic Polymer Grafted Nanoparticles Suspended in Preceramic Polymers

AUTHOR: Germanton, Gary L.

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Ramakrishnan, Subramanian

MEMBER (committee member): Hallinan, Daniel T., Jr.

MEMBER (committee member): Ricarte, Ralm

MEMBER (committee member): Kennemur, Justin Glenn

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemical and Biomedical Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (87 pages)

ABSTRACT: Preceramic polymers (PCPs) offer advantages in producing ceramics due to their processability and ability to tailor their chemical structure. However, challenges such as volume shrinkage and mass loss during pyrolysis often result in pores and cracks. PCP-grafted ceramic nanoparticles (PCPGNP) have been proposed and studied as a solution to volume shrinkage and mass loss problems. PCPGNPs also help to reduce aggregation and to control the nanoparticle arrangement. The neat state of these PCPGNPs has been characterized with respect to thermal properties and rheology. Dispersing PCPGNPs in commercial preceramic polymer matrices is another attractive, but unexplored, route to control the rheological and char yield properties of the matrices. In this work, a systematic rheological study of well-defined mixtures of a commercial PCP, SMP-877, and PCPGNPs (silica with poly(1,1-dimethylpropylsilane) corona) was executed to develop design rules for the processing of such mixtures. A rheological study demonstrated the effect of increasing particle concentration on network formation with percolation occurring between 50-60 wt%. Samples above the percolation threshold also exhibited higher viscosities and rapid shear thinning thus demonstrating their printability. X-ray photon correlation spectroscopy (XPCS) corroborated the rheology and showed two diffusive modes when the material was above percolation. Mixtures of PCPGNPS and SMP-877 had synergistically higher char yields upon thermal treatment and pyrolysis. XPCS and rheological measurements during thermal treatment identified thermal jamming of the polymer grafts as a key factor in improving the char yield. With the insights gained here we expect these mixed systems to provide advanced inks for additive manufacturing of ceramics for aerospace applications.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the Department of Chemical Engineering in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 3, 2024.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Subramanian Ramakrishnan, Professor Directing Thesis; Daniel Hallinan, Committee Member; Ralm Ricarte, Committee Member; Justin Kennemur, Committee Member.

TITLE: Working to Get 'Woke: ' Three Essays on Organizational Efforts to Improve Civic Engagement, Gender Equity and Diversity

AUTHOR: Ghadimi, Adela Z.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Fay, Daniel F.

MEMBER (university representative): Proffitt, Jennifer M.

MEMBER (committee member): Berry, Frances Stokes

MEMBER (committee member): Wright, James E.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Social Sciences and Public Policy

CORPORATE NAME: School of Public Administration and Policy

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (299 pages)

ABSTRACT: Through three independent essays, this manuscript addresses improving civic engagement, gender equity, and diversity within organizations through three unique lenses. The first paper explores the experiences of participants from a national leadership training organization providing the type of training and network building connections that those who are typically removed from the privilege to power pipeline fail to access. Ensuring a diverse workforce is often listed as an organizational goal or achievement, but aside from being understudied, it is also not utilized to its max capacity for organizational performance. Developing human capital among a diverse workforce remains critical for a representative and responsive public service, yet evidence-based recommendations for public training and development programs remain understudied. The second paper is based on a mixed methods gender equity study of a large police department and highlights opportunities for continued growth and improvement to allow masculine organizations to attempt to reach gender parity among their workforce and subsequently, their workforce's interactions with the residents they serve. The third paper is an exploratory descriptive case study investigating how an advocacy group, a public sector union, can influence voter turnout and voter registration and contribute to an uptick in civic engagement through voting. Implications for future coalition building and the need to expand future literature to study public sector labor unions in the field of public administration beyond focusing on collective bargaining activities.

FILENAME: Gil_fsu_0071E_18599.pdf

TITLE: The Effects of the First Language on the Second: A Psycholinguistic Investigation of Bilingual Lexical Processing and First Language Attrition

AUTHOR: Gil, Ana Laura

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Sunderman, Gretchen L.

MEMBER (university representative): Wood, Carla, (Speech-Language Pathology Professor)

MEMBER (committee member): Muntendam, Antje

MEMBER (committee member): Leeser, Michael J.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Modern Languages and Linguistics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (311 pages)

ABSTRACT: Research on language and cognitive processes in bilinguals over the past few decades has underscored the activation of words in the first language (L1) during comprehension and production of the second language (L2) (e.g., Dijkstra, Van Jaarsveld, & Ten Brinke, 1998; Van Heuven, Dijkstra, & Grainger, 1998; Hermans, Bongaerts, De Bot, & Schreuder, 1998;Lemhöfer, et al., 2008). This activation extends bidirectionally, with words from the L2 also influencing the processing of the L1 (e.g., Van Hell & De Groot, 2008; Linck, Kroll, & Sunderman, 2009; Schmid & Jarvis, 2014; Schmid & Keijzer, 2009), leading to cross-linguistic interference (CLI) in bilinguals' language processing. However, the nature and extent of this interference may vary depending on the bilingual's dominant language and immersion context. L1-dominant bilinguals may struggle to control interference from their L1s, while the opposite may hold true for L2-dominant bilinguals, even when their L2 is not their native language. Consequently, the formerly dominant L1 of some bilinguals may exhibit signs of attrition. This dissertation explores the relationship between attrition and L2 acquisition, addressing two key questions: (1) to what extent does context (place of residence) and nature of bilingualism influences the amount and direction of cross-language interference? and (2) to what extent (if any) is the activation of form and meaning modulated by the nature of the lexical relationships and individual differences measures? And, if effects are found, how does sentence context modulate those effects? The contribution of this study stems from the novel examination of two types of semantic extensions: a) new meanings or words that share form but do not share any semantic relationship across languages; and b) extended meanings or words that share form and at least one semantic sense across languages. Additionally, synonyms, unrelated words, cognates, interlingual homographs and translation pairs are also included to explore form-meaning interactions. The comprehension of words with varying degrees of form-meaning relatedness is evaluated in two tasks: (1) a semantic-relatedness decision task (SRDT) within and across languages and (2) a self-paced reading task (SPR). Sentence cues in unilingual language contexts are manipulated in congruent and incongruent conditions to assess interference effects. Participants also complete a flanker task as a measure of cognitive control and a battery of proficiency measures. These tasks are implemented across five participant groups: Page 12 of 308 (1) monolingual speakers of English in the U.S, (2) monolingual Spanish speakers in Argentina, (3) L1 Spanish-L2 English bilinguals in the USA, (4), L1 Spanish-L2 English bilinguals in Argentina and (5) L1 English- L2 Spanish learners in the USA. Results from this study indicate that immersion context influences the direction of language interference, with more L2 to L1 effects observed for immersed bilinguals compared to non-immersed counterparts, and with both groups being vulnerable to CLI effects compared to monolinguals. Despite extended exposure in an L2 dominant context, bilinguals can maintain their L1 proficiency, contradicting L1 attrition views. The activation of form-meaning relationships is directly related to the nature of the lexical relationships, with orthographically and semantically related words (e.g., cognates; extended meanings) showing processing advantages over orthographically related but semantically unrelated words across languages (e.g., false friends, new meanings). Within-language semantic competitors cause more interference during processing compared to unrelated words. Inhibitory control mechanisms or language dominance do not significantly attenuate CLI effects from form-meaning competitors in the non-target language. Results from the SPR revealed that sentence context can modulate interference effects, facilitating the resolution of lexical ambiguities and form-meaning relationships. However, language cues from a sentence alone are not sufficient to constrain CL competition, highlighting the importance of semantic information conveyed by the sentence context for language non-selectivity to occur. Overall, bilingual characteristics, including the type of bilingual, linguistic exposure/experience and levels of L1-L2 proficiency all seem to influence language processing. This dissertation contributes to the field of psycholinguistics of bilingualism, language attrition and second language acquisition. It highlights the importance of understanding language-attrition as a bridge between first- and second-language lexical processing.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Modern Languages and Linguistics in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 25, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): bilingualism, cross linguistic interference, first language attrition, language contact, psycholinguistics, second language acquisition

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Gretchen L. Sunderman, Professor Directing Dissertation; Carla Lynn Wood, University Representative; Antje Gerda Muntendam, Committee Member; Michael J. Leeser, Committee Member.

TITLE: Mixed Methods Analysis of "Under What Conditions" Modified Schema-Based Instruction "Works"

AUTHOR: Gilley, Deidre P.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Root, Jenny Rose

MEMBER (university representative): Jones, Tamara Bertrand

MEMBER (committee member): Fleury, Veronica

MEMBER (committee member): Cabell, Sonia Q.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: School of Teacher Education

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (203 pages)

ABSTRACT: The purpose of this dissertation was to extend the literature base for teaching students with intellectual and developmental disabilities (IDD) mathematics and self-determination skills using an evidence-based practice called modified schema-based instruction (MSBI). Chapter one provides the rationale for teaching both mathematics and self-determination skills to students with IDD, highlighting the correlation between both skill sets and positive post-secondary outcomes. This chapter presents the rationale for conducting this dissertation, which extends from prior MSBI research and is grounded in educational theory. To answer the five proposed research questions, this dissertation uses a mixed methods embedded experimental design. This dissertation follows mixed methods publishing recommendations by presenting the findings across multiple manuscripts (i.e., chapters). Chapter two presents the findings from the quantitative single-case design exploring the effects of teacher- and paraprofessional-delivered MSBI targeting personal finance mathematics word problems by students with IDD in a small group setting. Results indicate a functional relation and strong effect sizes between MSBI and learned mathematics skills of students with IDD, further adding to the extant literature base of positive student outcomes produced during MSBI instruction. Chapter three presents the findings from the integrated mixed methods results exploring how, why, and under what conditions MSBI works for teaching mathematics to students with IDD through a rigorous evaluation of fidelity of implementation. Findings provide important contextual information for how differentiated instructional delivery of MSBI can impact student outcomes; additionally, results identified six influences impacting instructional delivery and student outcomes, adding novel information for under what conditions MSBI is effective in teaching mathematics to students with IDD.

FILENAME: Gonzalbez_fsu_0071E_18610.pdf

TITLE: Looking Inward: Identifying the Local within the Global in Late Fifteenth-Century Sevillian Artworks

AUTHOR: Gonzalbez, Nina Maria

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Loic, Erika

MEMBER (university representative): Howard, Keith David

MEMBER (committee member): Leitch, Stephanie

MEMBER (committee member): Niell, Paul B., 1976-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Fine Arts

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Art History

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (205 pages)

ABSTRACT: The Iberian city of Seville offers a case study of motif and iconographic transference in the late Middle Ages and Early Modern era. Previous scholars have addressed the idea of transference through a formal lens without consideration for the cultural and historical contexts that surround it, and have previously noted, though rarely explicated, a Sevillian school of painting. The limited foundational studies on late fifteenth- and early sixteenth-century artworks in Seville, most published in the early twentieth century, focus on stylistic categorization and the indiscriminate application of terms such as Hispano-Flemish and mudéjar. My dissertation nuances these terms through an investigation of the artworks' place and development in a Sevillian context, specifically parsing local and global stylistic and iconographic influences apparent in the works. My work addresses the local outside of the simple framework of mudéjar, the stylistic qualification meant to designate ornamentation, architecture, and motifs showing Islamic stylistic influence but created within a Christian Iberian context. A close study of how prints and printing in general functioned in Seville and Granada clarifies how iconographies were transferred across media as well as how specific motifs were deployed in efforts to convert Muslims and Jews. While many prints do not survive, my dissertation reconstructs how they were employed by the citizens of Seville. The function and purpose of prints varied significantly: many were kept in the home and used for personal devotion by so-called Old Christians; they were distributed to non-Christians and new converts, and helped to prevent accusations of apostasy; and they served as models for painted and carved panel compositions. Additionally, terminology like "mudéjar" does not work for a Sevillian context where Islamic decorative motifs were strongly connected to the culture and history of the city. Tracking how, when, and why these motifs were copied and transferred sheds light on the global function of Iberian artworks and provides insight into how these methods operated more broadly. My research highlights connectivity and diversity in a way that impacts current studies and modern understandings of how we can define globality in the Middle Ages.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Art History in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 1, 2024.

FILENAME: Gordon_fsu_0071E_18591.pdf

TITLE: Structural and Biophysical Characterization of La Related Proteins

AUTHOR: Gordon, Blaine Hunter

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Silvers, Robert

MEMBER (university representative): Stefanovic, Branko

MEMBER (committee member): Li, Hong, (Chemistry and Biochemistry)

MEMBER (committee member): Yang, Wei

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (105 pages)

ABSTRACT: La related proteins (LARPs) form a superfamily of 7 distinct, homologous RNA regulatory protein which utilize a tandem La domain and ribonucleotide recognition motif (RRM), termed the La module, to recognize their individual RNA targets. LARP6, in vertebrates, functions to regulate the coordinated synthesis of type 1 collagen peptide mRNA during wound healing processes through the specific recognition of an mRNA secondary structure, the 5' stem loop (5'SL). This stem loop is located at the junction between the 5' untranslated region and protein- encoding region of mature type 1 and type 3 collagen mRNA, preoccupying the translation initiation codon. Prolonged injury from chronic disease, lifestyle, or aging results in the hyperactivity of wound healing mechanisms. Overactive myofibroblasts, which excrete extracellular matrix material (ECM) composed primarily of type 1 collagen, fill functional parenchymal tissue space with nonfunctional scaffoldings which rigidifies the tissue or organ. This hyperactivity results in fibrotic scarring which is progressively less reversible and was associated with >17% of mortalities globally prior to 2020. LARP6 acts as a central regulatory element of type 1 collagen mRNA, governing the potential for high-volume collagen excretion and is therefore operative in the development of fibrosis.Recent work, from our lab and others, presented evidence that La related protein 1 (LARP1) lacks an RRM downstream from the La domain. Instead, the intrinsically unstructured region contains a type 2 polyadenylate binding protein association motif (PAM2) sequence which is recognized by the C-terminal MLLE domain of cytosolic polyadenylate binding protein (PABPC1). The PAM2 motif of LARP1 and other protein functions to protect, circularize, regulate, or destabilize 3' polyadenylated tails of RNA polymerase II transcripts. The PAM2 motif of xi LARP1 deviates from the canonical physiochemical composition and standard length of the consensus sequence from other PAM2 motif-containing protein. In this work novel features of LARP6 substrate recognition and LARP1A PAM2 motif recognition are investigated by NMR spectroscopy and biophysical analysis, as neither system crystalized in our hands. LARP6 can recognize 5'SL RNA without the explicit requirement of the RRM domain, which was previously reported to be mandatory for specific, high-affinity binding. The structure of the LARP6 La domain, residues 79-183, in complex with a 35-nucleotide model of the 5' SL has been determined by NMR spectroscopy. Specificity conferring arrangements of the La domain and 5'SL explain the ability of the La domain to function as an isolated domain. The alternative MLLE recognition elements within the LARP1 PAM2 motif have also been investigated. This motif deviates in its N-terminal segment from the canonical composition of other PAM2 motifs which have been co-crystallized with the MLLE domain. Chemical shift perturbation of isotopically enriched MLLE domain in the presence of PAM2 peptides, coupled with molecular dynamics simulations, elucidates how the differences between these PAM2 still result in similar binding modes on MLLE. This work is concluded with a review of methyl-detected NMR methods for determining allosteric motions or interactions with the kinetic cooperativity model of human glucokinase as a case study.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 28, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Collagen, La Related Protein, MLLE, NMR, PAM2

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

TITLE: The Effects of Online Synchronous versus Online Asynchronous Abacus Professional Development

AUTHOR: Grillot, Leanne Elizabeth

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Schoen, Robert C.

MEMBER (university representative): Ganley, Colleen M.

MEMBER (committee member): Lewis, Sandra

MEMBER (committee member): Tuttle, Michael Jerome

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: School of Teacher Education

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (291 pages)

ABSTRACT: Professional development is viewed as a lifelong learning process for educators to improve student instruction and professional skills (Darling-Hammond et al., 2017). Online professional development for teachers of student who are visually impaired (TVIs) provides opportunities for continuing education, including for earning of recertification hours. With the rapid growth of online professional development, there is a need to assess the efficacy of synchronous and asynchronous options (Rowe, 2019). The purpose of this quantitative study was to compare two types of abacus professional development, online synchronous and online asynchronous, provided to TVIs to determine if a significant difference existed for growth of abacus knowledge, participant engagement, and participant satisfaction. Moore's transactional distance theory (1973) provided a conceptual framework for the study. The results of the analyses found that participants (N = 93) in both conditions had learning gains. The repeated-measures analysis of variance (ANOVA) suggested the participants in the asynchronous condition had greater gains in abacus knowledge, but the proximity of the p-value (p=.051) to the customary threshold of .05 makes it difficult to use the p-value to draw conclusions regarding the statistical significance of this difference. Participants reported approximately the same levels of engagement or satisfaction in both conditions. This study adds to the very limited literature on differences in educational outcomes for online synchronous and asynchronous professional development for TVIs. The fact that online asynchronous professional development appears to have impacted learning growth more than online synchronous professional development was intriguing. This study suggests that online learning environments can be engaging and satisfying whether delivered synchronously or asynchronously.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 18, 2024.

FILENAME: Gunter_fsu_0071E_18479.pdf

TITLE: Understanding the Relationship among School Conditions, Job Satisfaction, and Teacher Intention to Stay in Charter Schools versus Traditional Public Schools

AUTHOR: Gunter, Kelly P.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Herrington, Carolyn D.

MEMBER (university representative): Guerette, Amy R.

MEMBER (committee member): Iatarola, Patrice

MEMBER (committee member): Zuilkowski, Stephanie Simmons

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (109 pages)

ABSTRACT: The purpose of this research is to understand the relationship among school conditions, teacher job satisfaction, intention to stay, and school type (charter versus traditional public schools) and to determine if school conditions, and thereby job satisfaction, influences teachers' intention to stay in the field. Understanding this is critical to addressing teacher shortages from a policy and practical perspective. Data was collected from 275 teachers in four Florida counties, with comparable samples of charter and traditional public schools, through an online Qualtrics survey and all survey responses remained anonymous. Data was analyzed using descriptive statistics and independent samples t-test, multiple regression and multiple logistic regression analysis, and ANOVA to determine if significant relationships exist. The findings noted that of eight school conditions, six of those conditions were scored higher by charter school teachers, with one not significant and another higher by traditional public school teachers. None of the school conditions predicted a teacher's intention to stay in the field and only three (salary, high-stakes testing, and student behavior) significantly related to teacher job satisfaction. Of those three, only high-stakes testing and student behavior showed a statistically significant difference when accounting for the type of school.

FILENAME: Gutierrez_fsu_0071E_18641.pdf

TITLE: Teogonía

AUTHOR: Gutierrez-Melendro, Nicolas

MEMBER (professor directing treatise): Callender, Clifton

MEMBER (university representative): Jiménez, Alexander, 1963-

MEMBER (committee member): Ugay, Liliya

MEMBER (committee member): Gümrükçüoğlu, Osman Eren

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (75 pages)

ABSTRACT: Teogonía is a symphonic poem in five sections based on the mural, Teogonía de los dioses chibchas, by Luis Alberto Acuña. Each section introduces one of the Chibcha Gods and the creation story of the Muisca people. Other references that inspired me are symphonic works by Latin-American composers: Silvestre Revueltas, Alberto Ginastera, José Pablo Moncayo, and Arturo Márquez. This work was written in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Music from Florida State University. Based on the mural located at the Hotel Tequendama in Bogotá, Colombia, Teogonía is meant to depict the creation story of the Muisca, or Chibcha people. While there are many more characters in the mural, this orchestral work illustrates the five principal Gods of the creation story: Chiminigagua, Súe, Chía, Chibchacum, and Bochica. The piece opens with Chiminigagua, the all-powerful God and creator of the universe. This character is represented by a three-note motive [D-F-G] which is the basis of the piece and reappears in each of the following sections. The piece begins in a primordial state of the universe until the spark of creation which leads into the second section. Súe is the God of the sun and represents light and energy. This upbeat section is characterized by the use of traditional Colombian dance rhythms, most prominently, the bambuco. These rhythms can be identified by the simultaneous and alternating groupings of two and three. The third section depicts the moon Goddess, Chía. In mythology, Chía and Súe are married and perpetually follow each other in the sky. This section is about their love and culminates in the single moment they can be together, during an eclipse. The fourth section tells the story of Chibchacum, God of thunder and rain. The orchestra, here, depicts the great storm that flooded the world, wiping away the corruption that had spread. The final section introduces Bochica who is commonly seen as the messenger of Chiminigagua. Bochica arrives after the great flood on a rainbow and strikes the ground with his staff creating the Tequendama falls. He teaches the Musica people about moral norms, ways to organize their states, agriculture, metalworking, and crafts. This final section concludes the piece and combines statements of all previous Gods' themes.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the College of Music in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Music.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 1, 2024.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

FILENAME: Hackett_fsu_0071E_18529.pdf

TITLE: Propriétaires in Plain Sight: The Legal and Economic Autonomy of Married Women in Southern France, 1750-1815

AUTHOR: Hackett, Caroline S.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Blaufarb, Rafe

MEMBER (university representative): Clark, Jessica Homan, 1980-

MEMBER (committee member): Frank, Andrew, 1970-

MEMBER (committee member): McClive, Catherine

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of History

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (211 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation explores women's property ownership in the south of France from 1750-1815, with a particular emphasis on an overlooked group of women in Bas Languedoc, centered around Montpellier. The study investigates the impact of women's legal and marital status on their economic agency, filling a gap in historical scholarship that has neglected this specific group. In contrast to other regions of France where customary law prevailed, women in the south, subject to written law, enjoyed legal and social empowerment enabling them to independently own and manage property. This assertion applies regardless of social and demographic variables. The argument is substantiated by a blend of qualitative and quantitative evidence. Three in-depth case studies featuring prominent married women- the Marquise de Spinola, the Marquise de Murs, and Catherine Rose Mallié- serve as illustrative examples. These case studies highlight women's formal property ownership and their active engagement in wealth management through activities such as litigation, transactions, leasing, and philanthropy. To complement the case studies, a meticulous examination of notary and tax records reveals the breadth and prevalence of women's property ownership. Geographic comparisons and temporal analyses further illuminate the varied landscape of women's economic autonomy over time. This dissertation argues for the importance of regional perspectives in understanding French history, emphasizing the necessity to provincialize historical narratives for a more nuanced comprehension of women's diverse experiences. Furthermore, it challenges conventional assumptions about the limitations of marriage as an institution, encouraging historians to move beyond passive interpretations of its role in shaping women's economic agency.

ABSTRACT: This research delves into the complex history of Chitimacha-speaking communities to form a speculated migrations route during the French Colonial era. This research analyzes historical documents, archaeological findings, and georeferenced maps to unravel Chitimacha-speaking communities' migration through Louisiana to the western Atchafalaya Basin, address the gap of knowledge of the Chitimacha-Speakers' past, and shed light on challenges that this research and archaeology face. Analysis of pottery sherds helped place the current study area into regional context through comparisons to findings from previous investigations. A Coles Creek-Plaquemine component is proposed for 16SMY2 and 16SMY12 because of the pottery sherds recovered from previous archaeological investigations in the region. The other three current archaeological investigation areas do not have enough data to be placed into context.

TITLE: Dovetailing

AUTHOR: Hamilton, Liesel

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Roberts, Diane, 1959-

MEMBER (university representative): DuVal, Emily H.

MEMBER (university representative): Duval, Emily

MEMBER (committee member): Hand, Molly

MEMBER (committee member): Howard, Ravi

MEMBER (committee member): Weise, Jillian Marie

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of English

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (195 pages)

ABSTRACT: Dovetailing is a collection of nineteen personal essays about my experience with debilitating anxiety and depression. In the collection, I use birds as a mechanism to explore mental illness, with each essay focusing on a specific bird. Throughout the collection, I braid my experience seeing each essay's titular bird with research about birds, mental illness, literature, or other topics. The entire structure of the book mirrors the experience of being consumed by mental illness and learning to cope with and accept that illness. The opening essays of the collection are shorter, more fragmented, and contain more repetitions, mirroring the way anxiety is cyclical, as well as the way it fragments the way one experiences the world. As the collection progresses, the essays become more linear and less focused on anxiety, mirroring the way the narrator better understands her anxiety and no longer considers it an all-consuming experience. The final essay in the collection, "Passeridae," is fragmented and follows the narrator through a difficult spell of anxiety. Ending the collection this way allows the collection to counter the notion that anxiety and mental disorders can be "cured." While the essay collection investigates the way that the narrator finds watching birds a healing and grounding process, it also rejects the common nature writing cliche that nature exists to be healing. Instead, birdwatching has become a part of the narrator, just as she has accepted anxiety and depression as part of her. Accompanying these creative essays is a critical essay that examines the goals and inspirations behind my creative work.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of English in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 1, 2024.

ABSTRACT: Music therapy research (93%) has indicated the impact of music therapy on older adults with dementia, which is enhancing the quality of life, decreasing stress and agitation, improving mood, increasing cognitive and language skills, and improving physical movement. FILENAME: Hartman_fsu_0071E_18504.pdf

TITLE: Methods of Shape Analysis: Optimal Transport, Geometric Measure Theory, and Deep Learning

AUTHOR: Hartman, Emmanuel

MEMBER (professor co-directing thesis): Bauer, Martin

MEMBER (professor co-directing thesis): Klassen, E. (Eric), 1958-

MEMBER (university representative): Srivastava, Anuj, 1968-

MEMBER (committee member): Needham, Thomas

MEMBER (committee member): Asllani, Malbor

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mathematics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (192 pages)

ABSTRACT: In this dissertation, we address the development of mathematical frameworks for computationally feasible methods to compare and analyze large datasets of complex-shaped data. We discuss several projects at the intersections of optimal transport, geometric measure theory, elastic shape analysis, and geometric deep learning that contribute novel algorithms for the practical analysis of shape data and develop the theoretical foundations of shape analysis. We propose a supervised deep geometric learning method to achieve a parameterization-invariant calculation of the square root velocity (SRV) shape distance function. This method learns the invariance of the SRV metric to reparameterizations by implementing a shape-preserving data augmentation method during the training process. Moreover, we propose an unsupervised geometric deep learning method that utilizes methods from geometric measure theory to learn parameterization-invariant feature vector representations of curves and shape graphs. This method provides a robust and efficient approach for the classification of shape data and the identification of point-to-point correspondences between curves and shape graphs. Additionally, we discuss several methods within a framework of relaxed matching between surfaces with respect to a family of second-order Sobolev metrics. These methods combine Riemannian metrics from elastic shape analysis for shape comparison, along with a relaxed matching loss from the domain of geometric measure theory, to solve the correspondence problem. The adoption of weighted varifold representations of shapes facilitates the matching of shapes with different topological structures, accommodating noise, occlusions, and partial matching problems between shapes. Furthermore, we provide a comprehensive framework to perform statistical analysis of populations in the space of shapes. We also describe the restriction of this model to shapes that undergo deformations within a basis of biologically relevant or physically feasible deformations. We also discuss a project studying connection between the Square Root Normal Field (SRNF) elastic shape pseudo-metric and the Wasserstein Fisher-Rao (WFR) unbalanced optimal transport metric. By studying this connection, we construct algorithms and deepen the theoretical understanding of the SRNF and WFR metrics. Specifically, we offer a characterization of the closure of the SRNF map and shapes that are indistinguishable with respect to the SRNF metric. Furthermore, we propose a formulation of the WFR as a diffeomorphic optimization problem related to Gallou\"{e}t and Vialard's recent extension of the Riemannian submersion result of Otto.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Mathematics in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): February 23, 2024.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Rawling, Piers

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (97 pages)

ABSTRACT: Animal ethics is the branch of ethics concerning non-human animals. Population ethics is the branch of ethics concerning ethical issues related to who will exist or the number of people that will exist. In this dissertation, I argue for some views in animal ethics by appealing to insights from population ethics, and I argue for some views in population ethics by appealing to some insights from animal ethics. There are five chapters. The first chapter introduces the project, while the subsequent chapters each present one of four independent essays. The chapters can be read in any order and each one is self-contained. In the second chapter, I defend a virtue ethics approach to animal ethics. In the third chapter, I discuss an objection to my approach to animal ethics, namely that my approach runs counter to common sense. In the fourth chapter, I defend a theory of well-being that helps us to avoid the so-called "repugnant conclusion," a conclusion that many population ethicists desire to avoid. In the fifth chapter, I defend a view about the so-called "non-identity problem," by denying the distinction between doing and allowing harm in what I refer to as "non-identity cases".

FILENAME: He_fsu_0071E_18535.pdf

TITLE: Advanced Control Techniques for Inverter-Based Resources and Instant Grid Synchronization

AUTHOR: He, Yuchen

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Li, Yuan

MEMBER (university representative): Ordóñez, Juan Carlos, 1973-

MEMBER (committee member): Li, Hui, 1970-

MEMBER (committee member): Anubi, Olugbenga Moses

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (146 pages)

ABSTRACT: The contemporary power grid landscape is witnessing a transformative shift. As the integration ofrenewable energy resources intensifies and decarbonization objectives gain prominence, there is a discernible migration from traditional synchronous generator (SG)-based systems to inverter-based resources (IBRs). This shift, while promising, heralds the dawn of a modernized electric power grid characterized by unparalleled flexibility and adaptability. Despite the potential advantages, this transition presents complex challenges. At the forefront is the phase-locked loop (PLL), a critical synchronization mechanism for the AC power grid. While its role in inverter controls is essential, it has been linked to issues such as oscillations and subsynchronous harmonics. Additionally, the "black start"process remains a significant concern. For SGs, initiating a black start can be time-consuming, often taking tens of minutes due to factors like the mechanical inertia of generators, extended energizing transients, and system control latency. In the context of IBRs, the black start process is similarly constrained, especially by the bandwidth limitations of the PLL. To address these challenges, this thesis presents a novel PLL-free inverter control approach. Impressively, this new control, even without the PLL, offers a faster transient response to various grid changes while maintaining a low steady-state error. We also introduce advanced startup methods for IBRs. Our hysteresis-based technique allows inverters to connect to the grid within one fundamental cycle without inrush current and is resilient to grid voltage distortions. Further, we propose a switching-cycle-based startup method, enabling inverters to become operational within just two switching cycles, without any inrush current. Together, these innovative methods not only improve the black start process for IBRs but also enhance the overall stability and resilience of power systems.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 8, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Grid-tied, Inverter based resources, Renewable energy, Synchronization

FILENAME: He_fsu_0071E_18600.pdf

TITLE: Support-Seeking on Social Media: Navigating Acculturation and Academic Integration among International Graduate Students

AUTHOR: He, Dan

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Dennen, Vanessa P., 1970-

MEMBER (university representative): Jaber, Lama

MEMBER (committee member): Klein, James D.

MEMBER (committee member): Staudt Willet, K. Bret

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Psychology and Learning Systems

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (174 pages)

ABSTRACT: Pursuing higher education in a foreign country entails numerous challenges and opportunities for development for international students. Social media allows individuals adapting to a new environment to connect, communicate, collaborate, network, and learn, overcoming geographical, temporal, linguistic, cultural, and social boundaries. In this study, I explored how international graduate students used social media to seek support for acculturation and academic integration, as well as their perceptions of the benefits and challenges of using social media for support-seeking. I employed a naturalistic multiple-case study design to investigate this phenomenon relating to international graduate students' acculturation and academic integration with social media. I selected participants through snowball and purposeful sampling. The inclusion criteria included that students were in the same university, had finished their first year of study in their academic program, and used social media regularly for support-seeking. The primary inclusion criterion was that students had spent their first year of study in their educational program and used social media regularly for support-seeking. I balanced participant samples based on demographic backgrounds, including country of origin, field of study, and gender, to understand diverse students' experiences.Participants were eleven international graduate students from seven countries studying in education, social science, humanities, and STEM programs, with an average age of 27. Data were collected through two semi-structured interviews via Zoom and ten participant-generated digital artifacts via Padlet from each participant depicting their use of social media for acculturation and academic integration. Data were transcribed, cleaned, and anonymized before data analysis. I adopted inductive and deductive thematic analysis, guided by Activity Systems Analysis (ASA), as the analytic framework for my data analysis. I used the qualitative data analysis software NVivo to facilitate data analysis. The study findings revealed that international graduate participants' primary objectives for using social media were to receive emotional and social support, manage daily and academic tasks, and integrate into their local and academic communities. Participants used a mix of home-country and U.S. social media platforms, with some employing a wide range of platforms and web services and others opting for a few selective ones. Participants purposefully tailored social media platforms to suit the groups of people they interacted with, the tasks they addressed, and their personal preferences and topics at hand. The advantages of using social media for support-seeking included affordability, convenience, vast access to information, and extended social and incidental learning opportunities. However, several tensions arose from negative experiences, such as emotional distress related to social media engagement, with some intensified by algorithms designed for mindless scrolling. Commonly reported tensions included digital distractions, compulsive use of social media, and mindless scrolling. Other tensions included varying information quality and limited access to different language information sources. Accordingly, implications for practice and future research were discussed, including implementing social media curricula to support students' effective use of social media for personal and professional goals while adapting to their new cultural and educational environment.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Educational Psychology and Learning Systems in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 27, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Academic integration, Acculturation, Informal learning, International graduate students, Professional development, Social media

TITLE: Verb Ventures: Comparative Study on Implicit and Explicit Grammar Interventions for Mls

AUTHOR: Hines, Kiana

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Wood, Carla, (Speech-Language Pathology Professor)

MEMBER (university representative): Terry, Nicole Patton

MEMBER (committee member): Hall-Mills, Shannon S.

MEMBER (committee member): Barton-Hulsey, Andrea

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Communication and Information

CORPORATE NAME: School of Communication Science and Disorders

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (169 pages)

ABSTRACT: Spanish-English speaking multilinguals (MLs) with Developmental Language Disorders (DLD) have greater difficulty with verb morphology compared to their typically developing peers. Patterns of error are observed in both monolinguals and MLs. However, there are more studies that have explored the effectiveness of grammar intervention targeting verb morphology for monolinguals compared to MLs. Moreover, there are even fewer studies that compare the effectiveness of implicit and explicit approaches used in grammar interventions. Therefore, the purpose of this study is to examine an adapted alternating treatment single case design (AATD) to compare the (1) effectiveness of implicit and explicit approaches used in grammar interventions that target the inflectional past tense –ED and third person singular –s (3S) and (2) efficiency of the implicit and explicit approaches for acquiring the past tense –ED and 3S. The study includes third-fifth grade Spanish-English speaking MLs with and without DLD.
