FILENAME: Hofelich_fsu_0071E_18611.pdf

TITLE: Schenkerian Approaches to the Music of Dmitri Shostakovich

AUTHOR: Hofelich, Trevor C.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Clendinning, Jane Piper

MEMBER (university representative): Thomas, Shannon

MEMBER (committee member): Grasso, Julianne

MEMBER (committee member): Jones, Evan Allan

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (224 pages)

ABSTRACT: This study explores tonal states in the music of Dmitri Shostakovich (1906–1975) by examining harmony and voice leading from a Schenkerian perspective. Chapter 1 examines Shostakovich's realignment with socialist aesthetic ideologies in 1936, demonstrating how traditional idioms and forms in works written after the Pravda attacks enable a wider range of access points for tonal analysis. Methodologies derived from Russian theoretical thought such as modal lowering and modal derivation address surface relations; however, they do not make connections between local modal elements and large-scale tonal structure. Analyses by David Fanning and Sarah Marlowe demonstrate that while modal and chromatic behaviors are exhibited at foreground levels, these events represent post-tonal intensifications of customary idioms that unfold within broader tonal designs. Schenkerian processes of mixture and tonicization illustrate how Shostakovich's modal-chromatic qualities can be contextualized within tonal frameworks. Building on the modal and tonal analytical models from Chapter 1, Chapter 2 investigates how selected passages from Shostakovich's music articulate tonal structures in a variety of post-1936 works, including the second movement of String Quartet No. 9, the fourth movement of String Quartet No. 3, and Prelude Nos. 4, 13, and 22 from the Twenty-Four Preludes and Fugues, op. 87. Schenkerian theory contextualizes modal and chromatic inflections in String Quartet Nos. 3 and 9 within deeper levels of counterpoint and through the processes of simple, secondary, and double mixture. In Prelude Nos. 4, 13, and 22, Shostakovich's emulation of Baroque contrapuntal techniques produces foreground and middleground structures that resonate with customary linear models in the Bach-to-Brahms tradition. Although static structures are generated in Prelude Nos. 4 and 22, prolongational techniques express their monotonal designs. Chapter 3 examines the tonal structure of the Passacaglia from Shostakovich's Violin Concerto No. 1. At the middleground level, this movement produces a static bass line and an incomplete Urlinie (\hat{5}–\hat{4}–\hat{3}). The passacaglia rotations navigate tonal pathways through goal-oriented counterpoint, motivic confirmation of structural thirds, and local bass arpeggiations. The ground bass expands the tonic through surface-level arpeggiations, interior \hat{5}–\hat{1} motions, and the linear idiom 5–6–5 above the tonic pedal, producing a static harmonic state in the first half of the middleground. In the second half, the modulatory function of the cadenza is expressed as it transitions into the last movement, illustrating how chromatic voice leading bridges the F minor key area of the Passacaglia with A minor. Although Schenkerian theory does not accommodate modulations at the structural level, Chapter 3 introduces a model for contextualizing harmony and voice leading in Shostakovich's attacca transitions. The second case study explores tonal expressions in the second movement of Symphony No. 12. Chapter 4 demonstrates how modal lowering and mixture generate chromatic elements in the second movement's themes, motives, and secondary key areas. The modally lowered theme establishes a monotonal state through third motions, tonic arpeggiations, and 5–6–5 gestures. A linear framework for the second movement elucidates how its secondary key areas function as chromatic embellishments of standard contrapuntal procedures. A Schenkerian approach illustrates tonal closure within the obligatory register, producing a melodic structure that resonates with customary Urlinien. Lastly, Chapter 5 analyzes selected passages from Shostakovich's "formalist" works in 1927–1936, including opera Lady Macbeth of the Mtsensk District, the first movement of Symphony No. 4 in C Minor, and Symphony No. 2. These works present challenges to Schenkerian methodologies in that they provide fewer access points for tonal orientations. Analysis of tonal structure and voice leading in these pieces is complicated by mutable passages that generate subsets of pitches that compete for centricity, counterpoint that lacks directed motion toward a tonal goal (non-functional counterpoint), and melodies with modal orientations that are less responsive to tonal methodology. The studies provide a foundation for tonal applications to Shostakovich's music. Ultimately, the analyses demonstrate that many components of Shostakovich's compositional process are addressed by a Schenkerian approach.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the College of Music in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 19, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Russian modal theory, Schenkerian analysis, Shostakovich, Triadic post-tonality

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

FILENAME: Holt_fsu_0071E_18505.pdf

TITLE: The Source and Composition of Glacier Dissolved Organic Matter

AUTHOR: Holt, Amy Dehner

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Spencer, Robert G. M.

MEMBER (university representative): Lester, Sarah

MEMBER (committee member): Chanton, Jeffrey P.

MEMBER (committee member): Hood, Eran

MEMBER (committee member): Mason, Olivia Underwood

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (140 pages)

ABSTRACT: Mountain glaciers export ancient, energy-rich, and highly bioavailable dissolved organic matter (DOM) to freshwater and marine ecosystems, influencing downstream carbon cycling and supporting food webs. Despite its importance and the sensitivity of mountain glaciers to climate change, the sources of organic matter (OM) underpinning glacier DOM composition and its high bioavailability remain poorly constrained. To date, our understanding of the glacier carbon cycle has been formed from a handful of glaciers in a small number of regions (typically Greenland, Alaska, and the High Mountains of Asia), where geographically disparate studies have yielded different conclusions as to the dominant source of glacier OM. For example, studies in Greenland have suggested glacier DOM is predominately microbial in origin, whereas studies based in Alaska and Tibet postulate DOM to be primarily atmospheric deposition-derived. Implicitly, these studies indicate there may be regional and global heterogeneity in glacier DOM source and composition, which would have implications for understanding the fate of glacier-derived DOM and the age of carbon respired across glacier-fed ecosystems. In this dissertation combined analytical approaches (including molecular-level and carbon isotopic techniques) are used to assess glacier DOM composition across regional and global gradients. We highlight the glacier DOM pool as a distinct and dynamic carbon pool in the global carbon cycle, with significant diversity in DOM source and composition at both intra-regional and global scales. By analyzing global variability in composition across 136 glacier outflows covering six continents, we demonstrate glacier DOM is regionally distinct, where its composition is largely determined by the relative contribution of OM from in situ production and atmospheric deposition. We combine molecular-level, and bulk and compound-specific black carbon isotopic analyses, to show that anthropogenic deposition (i.e., fossil fuel combustion byproducts) has impacted glacier carbon cycling at the global scale. Nonetheless, in regions downwind of industrial centers (e.g., Alaska) the glacier OM pool is likely older and more stable in composition compared to remote regions (e.g., Ecuador), where glacier DOM is likely predominately derived from in situ production. In glaciers dominated by in situ production, the DOM exported to downstream and marine ecosystems is likely younger in radiocarbon age and relatively more aliphatic (i.e., energy-rich). Using novel respiratory carbon recovery system experiments for a subset of glacier outflows in southeast Alaska, we conclude this modern, in situ produced OM, may underpin the high bioavailability of the glacier dissolved organic carbon (DOC) pool. Thus, although globally glacier DOC is ancient and bioavailable, a modern pool of OM may underpin its high bioavailability. Together, these findings have wide ranging implications for how we contextualize the glacier carbon cycle and the role of glacier-derived DOC in downstream ecosystems.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Earth Ocean and Atmospheric Sciences in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 8, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Carbon Cycle, Cryosphere, Dissolved Organic Matter, FT-ICR MS, Glaciers, Radiocarbon

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Robert G. M. Spencer, Professor Directing Dissertation; Sarah Lester, University Representative; Jeff Chanton, Committee Member; Eran Hood, Committee Member; Olivia Mason, Committee Member.

FILENAME: Hoppe_fsu_0071E_18465.pdf

TITLE: Exploring the Relationship between Cultural Intelligence and Burnout in Teachers

AUTHOR: Hellman-Hoppe, Genevieve D.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Zuilkowski, Stephanie Simmons

MEMBER (university representative): Dodds, Benjamin

MEMBER (committee member): Akiba, Motoko

MEMBER (committee member): Herrington, Carolyn D.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (97 pages)

ABSTRACT: The purpose of this Dissertation in Practice was to explore the relationship between cultural intelligence and burnout in teachers. This purpose was rooted in a growing trend of teachers reporting a significant degree of burnout and education frequently being noted as one of the most stressful professions in the job market (Johnson et al., 2005; Saloviita & Pakarinen, 2021). In particular, teachers who work with a culturally heterogeneous student body face challenges with linguistic, behavioral, and social differences which can result in work-related stress which, if unmanaged, leads to burnout (Dilg, 2003; Dubbeld et al., 2019; Gutentag et al., 2018). Since cultural intelligence is an indicator as to how successful a person will be navigating culturally diverse environments and has been related to outcomes associated with job performance and job satisfaction (Baluku et al., 2019), it is worth exploring whether a relationship exists between the four factors of cultural intelligence and the three factors of burnout. This exploratory research study used a quantitative approach with a survey method. Research participants included 153 PK-12th grade teachers working at an international boarding school located in South Florida. Data collected was analyzed through the lens of three research questions:What level of cultural intelligence (CQ) and degree of burnout are reported by teachers working at an international school in the United States? How do the levels of teacher CQ and degree of burnout differ by teachers' demographic characteristics? What are the relationships between the four factors of cultural intelligence and the three factors of burnout in teachers working at an international school in the United States? The data was analyzed using descriptive statistics, independent t-tests, and a series of multiple linear regression models. The results of the study are reported in two parts. First the descriptive statistics and results from the t-tests for the mean differences of each factor of CQ and each factor of burnout between demographic groups are reported. Second, multiple linear regression models were fitted, and the results of each model were addressed. All data analyses were conducted using SPSS. The results of the multiple linear regression analyses are especially important as this research found that teachers with high motivational cultural intelligence tend to report lower degrees of emotional exhaustion and depersonalization and higher degrees of personal accomplishment. This study expands the knowledge on cultural intelligence in educators by finding that Motivational CQ was the only factor statistically significantly related to all three factors of burnout. Moving forward, it is recommended that educational leaders focus on professional development aimed at increasing a teacher's motivational cultural intelligence as this may lead to a decrease in their burnout. Two limitations of this study are the small sample size and the fact that all teachers work at the same school. Therefore, it is suggested that future research examines the relationship between cultural intelligence and burnout by surveying a larger sample size of teachers who work at multiple schools to allow for greater generalizability of the results.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Education.

NOTE (Date of Defense): January 30, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Burnout, Cultural Intelligence, Teacher

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Stephanie Zuilkowski, Professor Directing Dissertation; Benjamin Dodds, University Representative; Motoko Akiba, Committee Member; Carolyn Herrington, Committee Member.

TITLE: Social Skills in Music Therapy Practice: A Content Analysis on AMTA Journals from 1964-2024

AUTHOR: Howland, Ethan VandeRee

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Gooding, Lori F. (Lori Fogus)

MEMBER (committee member): Iwamasa, Dawn

MEMBER (committee member): Standley, Jayne M.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (117 pages)

ABSTRACT: The purpose of this content analysis was to ascertain specific practices, demographics, and research formats used to teach or improve social skills in music therapy practice. A history of interdisciplinary research on social skills is presented, followed by an in-depth analysis of 181 journal articles published in the American Music Therapy Association (AMTA) journals. These publications were categorized by their degree of relevance to the practice of teaching social skills. Although a frequently assigned treatment goal and a topic of considerable interest, there remains disagreement among professionals on how to operationally define social skills. The results reflect this discrepancy but provide some useful recommendations on how to successfully treat social skills in music therapy practice with a variety of populations. The most common social skills addressed in music therapy practice were those of initiating verbal communication (49%) and self-regulation (19%). Interventions addressing social skills were implemented by board-certified music therapists typically to children and adolescents with developmental disabilities (31.8%) and mental health disorders (15.4%) using applications with musical instrument play (32%) and group singing (22.9%). Implications for future practice and research are discussed.

FILENAME: Huang_fsu_0071E_18593.pdf

TITLE: Protein Ligand Binding Molecular Dynamics Simulations and Large-Scale Lead Identification

AUTHOR: Huang, Zilin

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Yang, Wei

MEMBER (university representative): Huang, Chen, (Professor of Scientific Computing)

MEMBER (committee member): DePrince, A. Eugene, III

MEMBER (committee member): Ouyang, Bin

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (141 pages)

ABSTRACT: In drug discovery, predicting protein-ligand binding structures and affinities is crucial for lead identification. Over the past decades, molecular dynamics simulation-based approaches have gained prominence in this endeavor. Despite some progress, achieving accurate and efficient protein-ligand binding prediction remains challenging. This doctoral dissertation addresses several challenges by focusing on understanding the molecular dynamics sampling bottleneck, developing an accurate isobaric-isothermal ensemble, and creating an automated program to streamline simulation workflow for large-scale lead identification.Enabling sufficient and robust sampling for quantitative protein-ligand binding prediction is challenging in molecular dynamics simulation. Motivated by specific viewpoints on existing sampling challenges, active developments were made largely in four categories: unguided free energy sampling methods, geometry-based free energy sampling methods, alchemical free energy sampling methods, and trajectory stratification approaches. We systematically analyzed these representative methods. In particular, we focus our discussion on essential features of these methods and derive our viewpoint that the orthogonal space sampling problem is the major bottleneck for all of the existing methods. Future areas of improvement that need to be explored was also expanded. The isobaric-isothermal (NPT) ensemble mimics conditions often encountered in chemical and biochemical experiments. Thus, its accuracy is important in obtaining correct biomolecular dynamics and thermodynamic properties in molecular dynamics simulations. We introduced "MTK-Langevin", a novel NPT ensemble method meticulously optimized the critical components that significantly improve the accuracy and efficiency. Specifically, MTK-Langevin: 1) incorporated correction terms to the equations of motion for the desired NPT partition function, 2) used the Langevin piston algorithm for barostat thermalization to reduce mass-dependent ringing effects, 3) integrated the barostat using BAOAB scheme to ensure minimal error and high stability, and 4) optimized parameters for improved equilibration efficiency. Tests showed MTK-Langevin achieved accurate temperature and pressure control with fast equilibration. Alchemical free energy simulations entail intricate steps, making manual setup labor-intensive and error prone. Practical lead identification campaigns often require numerous calculations, rendering manual setup impractical. To address this, we developed "AutoAlchem" to automate the simulation workflow. AutoAlchem streamlines topology generation, system building, equilibration, GPU-accelerated production runs, and data analysis. Tested in lead optimization, it consistently delivers accurate and efficient setup. Key features of AutoAlchem include integration of enhanced sampling methods and active learning techniques, allowing for large-scale simulations with high recall rates while sampling only a subset of molecules. In summary, these studies highlighted the sampling bottleneck during protein ligand binding process and developed an NPT ensemble method and an automated workflow aimed at enhancing the accuracy and efficiency of protein ligand binding prediction.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 26, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): computer-aided drug design, lead identification, molecular dynamics, protein ligand binding prediction

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Wei Yang, Professor Directing Dissertation; Chen Huang, University Representative; Albert Eugene DePrince, III, Committee Member; Bin Ouyang, Committee Member.

FILENAME: Hull_fsu_0071N_18769.pdf

TITLE: We Hear the Desert Singing: Dialogic Soundscapes in Early Mormon Hymnody

AUTHOR: Hull, Seth Jordan

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Eyerly, Sarah

MEMBER (committee member): Von Glahn, Denise, 1950-

MEMBER (committee member): Gunderson, Frank D.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (125 pages)

ABSTRACT: From its inception, Joseph Smith Jr.'s Latter Day Saint Movement, and by consequence, many of the hymns that accompanied this religious tradition, have been preoccupied with place and geography. Looking to Latter Day Saint scripture, as well as Smith's particular theologies of Millennialism, embodiment, and exaltation, this thesis contextualizes the descriptions of place within early Latter Day Saint hymns as both soundscapes and a dialogue with the movement's own sacred geography. These hymns served as tools of sonic placemaking, imbuing the landscape with meaning for the Latter Day Saints as the main body of the movement migrated westward, from New York to Ohio, Missouri, Illinois, and finally as refugees to the Salt Lake Valley in the Great Basin area of the American West. As musical negotiations with the North American continent and the larger globe, these Latter Day Saint hymns enabled their writers and performers, European and Euro-American settlers and colonizers, to interact with their surroundings and create a sonic space for themselves in the New World.

TITLE: Design of Sustainable Ultra High Performance Concrete (UHPC) Using a Multi-Scale Framework

AUTHOR: Islam, Md. Mashfiqul

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Zhang, Qian

MEMBER (university representative): Liang, Zhiyong (Richard)

MEMBER (committee member): Jung, Sungmoon

MEMBER (committee member): Sweat, Rebekah

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (137 pages)

ABSTRACT: Ultra high performance concrete (UHPC) is an advanced construction material for civil infrastructure development due to its supreme mechanical characteristics and distinct durability properties. There is a notable surge in the application of UHPC, particularly in highway infrastructures in the United States. The current dissertation addresses two critical challenges regarding the implementation of UHPC structures. The first part of the dissertation investigates the impact of fiber orientation and construction processes on the structural performance of UHPC. A comprehensive synthesis of existing literature and the UHPC structural design specifications and recommendations worldwide is conducted to understand how construction processes impact fiber orientation in UHPC elements and how this influence should be addressed in UHPC design. In the second part of the dissertation, sustainable UHPC materials are developed using a multi-scale and probabilistic design approach. A key challenge with UHPC is its high price and high environmental impact from carbon emissions associated with the use of manufactured steel fibers. This study explores the feasibility of using recycled steel fibers (RSF) derived from waste tires in UHPC production. The characteristics of RSF are comprehensively characterized, and their influence on the pullout behavior is determined through experimental and analytical methods. A multi-scale probabilistic framework is then employed to facilitate the design of UHPC composites incorporating RSF. The cost of UHPC production using MSF and RSF are calculated and compared where RSF based UHPC showed significantly lower production cost. The embodied carbon and embodied energy for these UHPCs are also calculated and again RSF based UHPCs showed more sustainability with significantly lower values for these parameters. In conclusion, the dissertation contributes to the sustainable development of UHPC structures by addressing key issues such as fiber orientation and utilizing recycled materials, ultimately enhancing the environmental and economic feasibility of UHPC applications in infrastructure construction.

FILENAME: Izenwasser_fsu_0071E_18585.pdf

TITLE: Essays on the Economic Impact of Micromobility

AUTHOR: Izenwasser, Jordan

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Ihlanfeldt, Keith R.

MEMBER (university representative): Peng, Fang

MEMBER (committee member): Rodgers, Luke P.

MEMBER (committee member): Yang, Cynthia Fan

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Social Sciences and Public Policy

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Economics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (75 pages)

ABSTRACT: Chapter 1 explores how shared micromobility impacts other transportation networks, specifically taxi markets in New York City. I exploit the spatial variation in the rollout of Citi Bike dock stations in a difference-in-differences research design. I find that Citi Bike and taxis are substitutes, with the average taxi market experiencing a 3.2% decline in trips each week. Heterogeneity analysis suggests that this effect is largely driven by rider substituting for relatively short trips. Two potential mechanisms are explored; direct substitution to Citi Bike and substituting from taxis to use Citi Bike and public transportation in tandem. I find evidence that both mechanisms generate the observed substitution pattern. Chapter 2 explores how transportation stations impact local crime. Most studies on the link between crime and transit stations focus on public transportation, however, there is limited evidence for other transportation alternatives, like micromobility. Using a spatial difference-in-differences research design, we provide evidence that bike share docking stations cause a significant increase in crime within 25 meters by leveraging data on Citi Bike and reported crime in New York City. Our results are robust across various estimators and counterfactuals, and we find heterogeneous effects depending on the type of crime and the time of day a crime was reported to have occurred. These findings provide insights into the external costs of micromobility, offering policymakers further information when considering its adoption as a transportation alternative. Chapter 3 investigates the impact of shared micromobility access on self-reported drunk driving using data from the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System survey for Selected Metropolitan/Micropolitan Area Risk Trends. By exploiting the heterogeneous rollout of shared micromobility services in the metropolitan area in a difference-in-differences research design, I estimate a small but negative point estimate for the effect of micromobility access on self-reported drunk driving. Standard errors for the estimates are large, resulting in statistically insignificant results. Therefore, I remain agnostic in the interpretation of my results.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 29, 2024.

TITLE: Leveraging Emergence for Enhanced Planning and Decision-Making in the Built Environment: Applications in Resilience and Sustainability Planning

AUTHOR: Jalloul, Hiba

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Choi, Juyeong

MEMBER (university representative): Vanli, Omer Arda

MEMBER (committee member): Abichou, Tarek

MEMBER (committee member): AbdelRazig, Yassir

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (148 pages)

ABSTRACT: The built environment consists of various, diverse, and independent systems distributed across different organizational levels, such as team, project, regional, state, and national, creating a structured hierarchy. Interactions within and between these hierarchical levels, involving human participants, physical resources, and policies, are crucial for the functionality and efficiency of these systems. However, these interactions—physical, spatial, logical, and cyber in nature—can lead to unexpected 'emergent' properties or behaviors not anticipated in the original design of the systems.Emergence, a concept well-recognized in systems engineering, has not been fully integrated into research and practice related to the built environment. Scientific attempts to study processes in the built environment often adopt a reductionist perspective, treating the outcome of the built environment as the sum of its individual elements, thus simplifying and neglecting the complexity arising from continuous interactions among components. This simplification can overlook emergent behaviors that significantly influence planning and management across various areas, including construction productivity, safety, infrastructure planning, and operations, either positively or negatively. Considering the magnitude and nature of impact of any resultant emergent behavior on the holistic outcome of operations and processes in the built environment, it is crucial to acknowledge and account for emergence during planning and decision-making. This necessity becomes especially vital within the framework of resilience and sustainability planning, where achieving ambitious goals demands a holistic approach that transcends isolated entity planning. To date, research exploring emergence within engineering contexts has been limited. Even among the limited engineering studies that recognize the potential impact of emergent behavior and its significance, formalized analysis approaches are lacking. Moreover, none of these studies have endeavored to regulate the interactions underlying emergent behavior in pursuit of more favorable outcomes. As such, the potential of incorporating the concept of emergence in built environment planning and decision-making, particularly within the realms of sustainability and resilience, remains largely untapped. This research seeks to fill this gap by developing a formalized framework for effective modeling, analysis, and control of emergent behavior. It begins with establishing a taxonomy of emergent behaviors, classifying them into four distinct types based on (a) nature of underlying interactions, (b) level of complexity, and (c) boundaries of information available. This taxonomy is then used as a foundation for a three-step framework – (i) classification, (ii) operationalization, and (iii) implementation – for the systematic modeling and analysis of the different types of emergence within construction and infrastructure engineering and management applications. This study demonstrates the efficacy of the developed framework in augmenting and guiding system- and operational level planning and decision-making within the contexts of infrastructure resilience and construction sustainability planning through two case studies. The first case study examines the disparities in the resilience of municipal solid waste management systems (MSWMSs) during the COVID-19 pandemic stemming from their complex socio-technical interactions. Specifically, empirical investigation of the operation of MSWMSs during the course of the pandemic was conducted in order to investigate the variance in their adopted adaptation pathways as a function of their systems characteristic, particularly in terms of composition, topology, and control. Subsequently, these variances were used to explain the emerged resilience performance of MSWMSs, particularly with regards to (i) the resourcefulness of each system in establishing and implementing response measures and (ii) its rapidity in recovering and adapting to increasingly complex and dynamic conditions. Findings from this case study serve as a foundation for enhancing the resilience of MSWMSs to future pandemics and other disturbances. The second case study investigates the improvements or reductions in the productivity of heavy equipment during demolition debris sorting operations stemming from their spatial interactions. Specifically, lab-based scaled models of demolition operations utilizing small-scale excavators were employed to monitor the variables impacting the underlying spatial interactions, particularly (i) the proximity between excavators and (ii) the orientation of excavators during operations. Statistical models were subsequently established to explain the resulting impact on the collective productivity based on these variables. The insights gained from this case study provide a basis for optimizing excavator allocation and spatial arrangement during material separation operations to maximize the recovery of recyclable demolition waste.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 1, 2024.

TITLE: Essays on the Impacts of Medicaid Expansion on State Governments, Hospitals, and Individuals: Focusing on Financial Aspects

AUTHOR: Jang, Jaeyoung

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Lee, Keon-Hyung

MEMBER (university representative): Carr, Dawn C.

MEMBER (committee member): Tang, Tian

MEMBER (committee member): Atkins, Jennifer

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Social Sciences and Public Policy

CORPORATE NAME: School of Public Administration and Policy

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (100 pages)

ABSTRACT: Following the Affordable Care Act (ACA), state governments have had the option to expand the eligibility of Medicaid programs since 2014. The expansion states increased the eligibility threshold to 138% of the federal poverty line, which allows more individuals to be covered by the program. In the first year, twenty-seven states, including the District of Columbia, decided to expand the program. However, several states hesitated to adopt the expansion, primarily due to concerns regarding the potential increase in fiscal burdens. Therefore, it is imperative to investigate whether Medicaid expansion significantly impacts state budgets thoroughly. Furthermore, Medicaid expansion also affects hospitals and healthcare providers, as it leads to a decrease in the uninsured rate and expands coverage. Consequently, it is crucial to examine how expansion alters managerial conditions and decision-making processes within healthcare organizations. Moreover, given that the primary goal of Medicaid expansion is to improve access to care for low-income individuals, it is imperative to assess the policy outcomes in a more precise and comprehensive manner. This necessitates thorough evaluation and analysis to understand the extent to which Medicaid expansion achieves its intended objectives and addresses the healthcare needs of low-income populations effectively. In this regard, this dissertation aims to provide a more clear and comprehensive understanding of the impact of Medicaid expansion by investigating from the perspectives of state governments, hospitals, and low-income individuals. To assess whether the expansion imposes an excessive fiscal burden on the states that adopt the policy, I explore how the number of Medicaid enrollees, expenditures for the program, and overall state fiscal conditions respond to a sudden economic downturn and analyze whether states expanded the programs should bear more fiscal burden compared to states that have not adopted it. Also, I focus on the fact that nonprofit hospitals have been criticized for providing benefits to their communities at an insufficient level despite enjoying enormous amounts of savings due to their tax-exemption status. Employing the principal-agent theory to understand the decision-making mechanisms underlying this behavior, I investigated whether Medicaid expansion mitigates this agency problem. Moreover, to offer a more comprehensive evaluation of Medicaid expansion's impact on access to care, I analyze whether the benefits of the policy are distributed differently among individuals depending on the presence of accessibility barriers. The findings of my study indicate that the Medicaid expansion would not significantly increase the fiscal burden for the states while allowing many people to stay insured during economic recessions. Also, the expansion affects the managerial conditions of nonprofit hospitals by decreasing their costs of uncompensated care. Despite this saving, hospitals are found not to change their behavior and to keep their scrutiny in providing financial assistance to their patients. In addition, my finding shows that Medicaid expansion relieves the financial burden of healthcare for low-income people, but the benefits are not universal to them. When individuals have low accessibility to their healthcare providers, they still have limited access to care even though they have have same health conditions and income levels. That is, there exists a disparity in the benefits from Medicaid expansion among the low-income groups. With these findings, I contribute to the relevant literature by offering a deeper understanding of the impact of Medicaid expansion, both theoretically and empirically. By exploring the nuances of Medicaid expansion's effects on state budgets, healthcare organizations, and access to care, my research provides valuable insights into the multifaceted implications of this policy. Furthermore, I offer practical implications for policymakers to understand the true costs of Medicaid expansion better and identify areas for policy refinement to enhance access to care effectively. By highlighting the potential challenges and opportunities associated with Medicaid expansion, policymakers can make informed decisions to optimize the policy's effectiveness and ensure equitable access to healthcare for all individuals.

TITLE: A Protocol Evaluation Framework for System-Level Shipboard Power System Controls

AUTHOR: Jean-Pierre, Jerry P.

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Pamidi, Sastry V.

MEMBER (committee member): Faruque, Md Omar

MEMBER (committee member): Foo, Simon Y.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (61 pages)

ABSTRACT: Shipboard power systems (SPS) are increasing their reliance on communication systems. Communication enables system-level controls to coordinate the usage of the SPS and provide significant improvements (e.g., size, weight, cost). Communication is commonly divided into layers (application, presentation, session, transport, network, data link, physical). While the lower layers have not had significant changes, the application layer is constantly in flux. New protocols are often introduced, providing new capabilities to facilitate communication.Real-time simulation (RTS) is a tool that has been effectively utilized to study SPSs. Many models and techniques exist. Similarly, the simulation of computer networks exists. However, leveraging these Real-time simulation tools/facilities for evaluating protocols has received little attention. Currently, a co-simulation environment of the SPS electrical system and its computer network provides a way to evaluate the operation of SPS models and assess their capabilities. Protocols are typically defined in the communication system. Yet not much is known about the potential impact of these protocols. This work proposes a framework to evaluate application layer communication protocols in the communication system of system-level SPS controls using RTS. The framework's effectiveness was demonstrated by analyzing Modbus TCP and Data Distribution Service (DDS). The network utilization metric was used to compare and contrast the protocols.

TITLE: Overparenting and Emerging Adults' Romantic Relationship Efficacy: The Moderating Role of Individual Cultural Beliefs

AUTHOR: Jiao, Chengfei

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Cui, Ming, 1971-

MEMBER (university representative): Maner, Jon K.

MEMBER (committee member): Fincham, Frank D.

MEMBER (committee member): Kimmes, Jonathan G. (Jonathan Gene)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Human Development and Family Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (106 pages)

ABSTRACT: Romantic love and intimacy are critical for emerging adults to explore self-identity. Relationship efficacy is a cognitive process related to conflict management that plays an important role in romantic relationship development and quality. Overparenting, characterized by high control and involvement, could undermine the development of emerging adults. Despite the potential negative impact of overparenting, the association between overparenting and relationship efficacy remains unexplored. Furthermore, differences related to norms in romantic relationship development and parenting practices across cultures should be considered, particularly between individualistic societies in the U.S. and collectivist societies in Asia. Using a person-centered approach, this study aimed to investigate the associations between profiles of overparenting and relationship efficacy in the U.S. and Hong Kong. Additionally, the potential moderation by individual-level cultural beliefs was explored to investigate whether these associations vary by horizontal individualism, vertical individualism, horizontal collectivism, or vertical collectivism. Data were collected from 235 American and 303 Hong Kong Chinese emerging adults who were currently in a romantic relationship. Overparenting was assessed across academic, financial, relational, health domains. Results from latent profile analysis (LPA) revealed three profiles in the U.S sample and two profiles in the Hong Kong sample. Regression analyses indicated that an "overall high overparenting" profile was associated with the lowest level of relationship efficacy in both samples. A distinct "overall medium overparenting, but high in financial and low in relational overparenting" profile emerged in the U.S. sample which was related to the most optimal relationship efficacy among American emerging adults. Additionally, moderating effects by individual cultural beliefs suggested that, in the U.S. sample, individuals with higher vertical individualism beliefs were found to be more susceptible to the negative impact of "overall high overparenting" on relationship efficacy compared to those who experienced "overall low overparenting." Implications, future directions, and limitations were further discussed.

TITLE: FPGA-Based Accelerator Generation for Artificial Neural Networks

AUTHOR: Johnson, Christopher Wade

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Meyer-Baese, U. (Uwe), 1964-

MEMBER (committee member): DeBrunner, Linda S.

MEMBER (committee member): Foo, Simon Y.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (51 pages)

ABSTRACT: Artificial neural networks (ANNs) are a pivotal component of highly successful modern Artificial Intelligence (AI) applications, such as OpenAI's ChatGPT. FPGA's capabilities of parallelism and efficiency provide an opportunity to provide quicker computation of ANNs than both CPUs or GPUs, whilst consuming much less power in both in data center and edge computing environments. A custom instruction component for the Nios II soft processor and supporting software were developed to allow easy, configurable generation and deployment of high-performance ANN inference on FPGA devices. The custom instruction performs integer matrix-vector multiplications, with each column of the product computed in parallel with pipelined multiply accumulate units. Nios II embedded computer systems were created both with and without the generated custom instruction. FPGA device resource utilization and execution time were evaluated for each system when performing ANN-based image classification on the MNIST handwritten digit database. Speedups of over 300x were achieved when using the custom instruction, at the expense of higher FPGA resource utilization.

TITLE: Investigating Biologic Repeatability at Different Biological Levels: The Genomic and Phenotypic Response to Parallel Phenotypic Artificial Selection in Drosophila Melanogaster and D. Simulans

AUTHOR: Jones, Luke T.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Houle, David

MEMBER (university representative): Arbeitman, Michelle N. (Michelle Nina)

MEMBER (committee member): Hughes, Kimberly A., 1960-

MEMBER (committee member): Burgess, Scott C.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Biological Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (164 pages)

ABSTRACT: Repeated evolution in biology is widespread among morphologic forms but also recognized at essentially all biological levels. Organisms achieving the same functional goal is reported at the level of simple biochemical pathways, complex tissue types, and even social behaviors. Before the advent of the sequencing revolution, studies of repeated evolution centered on morphologic data. With the power of current DNA technologies researchers are increasingly focusing on understanding how repeated forms at the phenotypic level arise at the genetic level. Most of the trait's biologists' study are likely continuous and polygenic in nature. Additionally, within diploid sexual organisms, these traits often could exist within populations which consist predominantly of standing genetic variation, opening the door for drift to create genetic variance dictated by history and not fitness. To investigate genetic repeatability from standing genetic variation and retain a possible insight into macroevolutionary outcomes I designed an experiment using two recently diverged species of Drosophila. To create a parallel phenotypic response, we designed a parallel divergent artificial selection experiment in D. melanogaster and D. simulans predominantly selecting on a multi-trait index of proportional length of the three major leg segments. We complimented the phenotypic experiment with population-based whole genome DNA sequencing of individuals from the initial populations and the evolved populations artificially selected for fifteen generations. An experimental design resulting in low estimates of Ne and concurrently strong selection yielded a complicated and idiosyncratic genetic response even within replicates of a species. Evolve and Resequence and convergent evolution experimental designs and null hypotheses often use an expectation that repeated genetics underlies repeated phenotypes. We suggest more skepticism that repeated phenotypes might not be the product of parallel genetic responses for complex quantitative traits..

TITLE: Social Media's Role in Addressing Educational Inequity: Focusing on Prospective First-Generation Students' College Exploration

AUTHOR: Jung, Daeun

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Dennen, Vanessa P., 1970-

MEMBER (university representative): Rutledge, Stacey A.

MEMBER (committee member): Klein, James D.

MEMBER (committee member): Caskurlu, Secil

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Psychology and Learning Systems

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (156 pages)

ABSTRACT: This study explores the role of social media in addressing educational inequity, focusing on prospective first-generation students' college exploration. The study answers two questions: (1) how do prospective first-generation students describe their social media usage related to college? (2) how do prospective first-generation students describe the role of social media in their college choice system? To achieve this goal, I employed interviews and social media diaries. Eleven high school seniors whose parents did not complete a 4-year college/university participated in the study. Social media diaries were adopted to capture participants' daily social media usage related to college. Interviews were conducted to delve into their lived experiences in detail. I analyzed the collected data using reflexive thematic analysis. For the first research question, I examined specific platforms participants utilize: Instagram, TikTok, YouTube, Facebook, Reddit, Discord, GroupMe, and Twitter. Among them, a subreddit r/A2C (Apply to College), the only niche social media site specifically designed for college information, was used by only one participant, implying the crucial role of a knowledgeable friend. The general pattern of network engagement showed that participants remained within their existing networks rather than forming new connections via social media. Participants explored diverse topics related to college, encompassing majors, options, applications, scholarships, and transitions. For the second research question, the findings revealed that participants were exposed to college information daily. Under the overall influence of social media, however, three contradictory subthemes were identified: vicarious experience vs. not your experience, thought-provoking vs. not leading to actions, and inspiring vs. distressing. The contradictory themes indicate the complex roles of social media in addressing educational inequity. The findings showed that social media plays a beneficial role in prospective first-generation students' college choice system, albeit with enduring boundaries and constraints. Such complex realities indicate that participants' digital experiences are not transcending the boundaries existing in their non-digital world but rather are deeply intertwined with them, underscoring the existing structural inequities that marginalized teens are faced with. The study suggests implications for research and practice to provide better support for prospective first-generation students' postsecondary educational opportunities.

TITLE: In Defense of Longstanding Anger

AUTHOR: Karabiyik, Christina

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Westlund, Andrea C. (Andrea Carol)

MEMBER (committee member): Clarke, Randolph K.

MEMBER (committee member): Bukoski, Michael

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Philosophy

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (54 pages)

ABSTRACT: This paper introduces the concept of longstanding anger and seeks to address the thought that maintaining anger indefinitely is corruptive to the character of the agent and destructive to relationships. It denies that anger is inherently harmful and argues that it plays a significant role in the moral landscape as a method of 'valuing the valuable' that cannot be replicated through forgiveness. The paper argues that forgiveness is not morally superior to anger, and our reasons for condemning anger often have to do with discomfort surrounding the presence of discord, rather than anger being unfitting. Anger is explored within its role as a social emotion as conditions are set out for how and when anger can reasonably be maintained indefinitely, showing how it can fittingly not diminish, even upon the death of the wrongdoer. The paper suggests that longstanding anger arises from circumstances when an unrepentant wrongdoer maintains their commitment to the wrong and can be resolved either by the wrongdoer or through recognition of the wrong by the greater social community.

TITLE: The Underrepresentation of Racially and Ethnically Minoritized Allied Healthcare Faculty: An Exploratory Study of Faculty Experiences and Perceptions in Colleges Serving Rural Areas in Florida The Underrepresentation of Racially and Ethnically Minoritized Allied Healthcare Faculty: An Exploratory Study of Faculty Experiences and Perceptions in Colleges Serving Rural Areas in Florida

AUTHOR: Kent-Smith, Shana

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (93 pages)

ABSTRACT: The National Center for Education Statistics (NCES, 2022) reported that White faculty members constituted 74% of the total number of faculty, while racial and ethnically minoritized groups, including Black, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander, and Native Americans, collectively comprised less than one-fourth of faculty members. Comparatively, a decade ago, NCES, (2013) illustrated similar trends, with only 21% of racially minoritized faculty showcasing negligible progress over the past 10 years. This underrepresentation extends beyond specific disciplines, suggesting a systemic issue prevalent across academia, especially in allied healthcare programs. According to Salsberg et al. (2021) study of 10 healthcare professions, there is a notable underrepresentation of Black, Hispanic, and Native Americans compared to their respective proportions in the population. The allied healthcare programs in this study include Cardiovascular Technologist, Emergency Medical Service, Diagnostic Medical Sonography, Radiographer, Occupational Therapist Assistant, and Respiratory Care. This abstract qualitative exploratory study aimed at to examine racial minority faculty experiences and perceptions of difficulties and success within allied healthcare full-time faculty in colleges serving the rural areas of Florida. Understanding the challenges faced by racially and ethnically minoritized faculty members is critical for addressing the persistent underrepresentation in allied healthcare fields (Abdul-Raheem, 2016; Allen & Garg, 2016; Kaplan et al., 2018) by identifying the challenges of underrepresentation, and effective interventions to enhance racially minoritized healthcare faculty recruitment and retention. Addressing this shortage is pivotal for fostering diversity among faculty, improving graduation outcomes for diverse allied healthcare students, enhancing cultural competence within the healthcare workforce, and ameliorating healthcare disparities in underserved rural communities. By shedding light on biases, microaggressions, and skepticism regarding qualifications, the findings from this research underscore the pervasive nature of bias within academic environments. Consequently, academia faces an urgent imperative to confront these disparities and cultivate inclusive climates where all faculty members are valued for their scholarly contributions. Initiatives focusing on mentorship, professional development, and supportive leadership emerge as pivotal pathways to empower minoritized faculty to navigate and surmount prevailing obstacles. Addressing systemic barriers and fostering diversity, equity, and inclusion are crucial for enabling all faculty members, irrespective of background, to thrive and contribute effectively to academia and healthcare (Nair & Adetayo, 2019; Poole & Brownlee, 2020; Ratledge, 2020) The implication of this study for allied healthcare is the key necessity to recruit and retain a minoritized allied healthcare faculty by promoting mentorship and a supportive network for professional development. Overcoming system biases are critical to dismantling barriers faced by a minoritized faculty member, promoting their success, and enriching the cultural variety of healthcare education and profession. Moreover, the implications of this study extend beyond academia to inform broader societal conversations about systemic racism, discrimination, and social justice. The study contributes to ongoing efforts to address disparities in various sectors, including student experiences, institutional leadership dynamics, policy frameworks, and diversity and inclusion endeavors. Effective interventions necessitate decisive leadership action bolstered by robust policy frameworks to improve healthcare disparities in resource allocation and promote equitable support structures for all faculty. Mitigating stereotypes, biases, and resource disparities while fostering supportive leadership and mentorship is crucial for creating an environment where all faculty members feel valued, supported, and empowered to succeed (Luster-Edward & Martin, 2018; Llama et al., 2019; Kelly et al., 2017; Kelly & McCann, 2014). The study's findings supported recommendations needed for further research to advance knowledge about the experiences of minoritized faculty within academia and inform evidence-based interventions to mitigate disparities and promote a sense of belonging, intentional support, and welcome. Acknowledging and addressing the challenges faced by racially and ethnically minoritized allied healthcare faculty is crucial for institutions to fulfill their mandate of providing equitable opportunities for scholarly engagement and professional advancement. Pursuing these research avenues is essential for realizing academia's standard as an inclusive and intellectually vibrant community fostering the holistic development of all academic members in higher education. The exploratory study revealed support recommendations for practice to advocate for racially and ethnically minoritized full-time faculty members. The combination of proactive leadership for an engaging support system, cultural awareness training, and professional training to identify and navigate bias for all employees, and an intentional mentorship program to encourage collaboration and a supportive network is essential for minoritized healthcare faculty members to succeed.

FILENAME: Kershaw_fsu_0071E_18692.pdf

TITLE: Build Your Own Living Space: Architecture and the Politicized Body in the Work of Lygia Clark

AUTHOR: Kershaw, Julia Talmadge

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Bick, Tenley C.

MEMBER (university representative): Shields, Sara Scott

MEMBER (committee member): McLane, Yelena

MEMBER (committee member): Niell, Paul B., 1976-

MEMBER (committee member): Dowell, Kristin L.

MEMBER (committee member): Amor, Mónica

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Fine Arts

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Art History

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (319 pages)

ABSTRACT: In modernist and contemporary art history, abstract art has long been associated with issues surrounding autonomy and breaks with figurative art. Scholarship surrounding the development of abstract art in Brazil has tended to focus on those connections in addition to its receptions by local art critics Ferreira Gullar and Mário Pedrosa and trajectories of European movements in abstract art, namely De Stijl, neoplasticism, and concrete art. While these readings have recognized important lineages for abstraction contextualized within the visual arts, the intersection between abstraction in Brazil and architecture remains understudied in comparison. I examine the work of Brazilian postwar and contemporary artist Lygia Clark (1920–1988) to show how her work is just at home in fields of painting and sculpture as it is in disciplines of architecture and design. By forging these connections outside of the visual arts, Brazilian abstract art in the postwar period became a political cultural tool of modern architecture and space, as well as an outlet for civilians to contribute to Brazil's status as a growing modern nation by constructing modernist spaces. Through formal and social art historical analysis of the work of Lygia Clark, this dissertation revises histories of abstraction in postwar Brazilian art to better account for understudied contexts of architecture, public space, and the built environment. Clark is best known for her interactive geometric Bicho (Critter; 1960–1966) sculptures and association with the neoconcrete group (1959–1961), the Brazilian artistic avant-garde recognized for its participatory artwork. Much like the histories of abstract art to which she belonged, namely concrete and neoconcrete art, her contributions are often tied to painting and sculpture, despite her career-long engagement with architecture. In response to this historiographic problem, this dissertation addresses Clark's sustained work in and engagement of architecture such as her little-known works, including her ink drawing of a street scene from 1948 and a mural mosaic from 1951, still extant in Rio. Examination of her training and collaboration with landscape designers and architects reveals her synthetic approach to the arts, which facilitates new debates about integrative approaches to the arts that tend to focus on De Stijl and the Bauhaus. Chapter Two, "Staircases, Interiors, and Studies of Space: The Early Works, 1948–1953," focuses on the earliest and often overlooked stage of Clark's career—where her architectural engagement began—prior to her affiliation with concretism with the Grupo Frente in the mid-1950s. Chapter Three, "Clark's Models of Houses and Architectural Interiors: Displays of Modernist Living," provides the first in-depth study of Clark's small-scale models of homes from 1955 to 1964, of which she made six. This chapter argues that Clark re-envisioned neoconcrete art—a form of abstract art—as manipulatable architectural models that engaged with local and global trends of architecture and provided opportunities for viewers to construct home layouts. Chapter Four, "'Walking Along:' Path-Making as Spatial and Subversive Interventions," analyzes Clark's sculptural action and abstract sculptures in politicized contexts of Brazil. Fostering interventionist spatial imaginaries, Caminhando (Walking; 1963), and Trepante (Climber; 1965), and Trepante e caixa (Climber and Box; 1964), use "the winding path" as a strategy to subvert authority by questioning spatial and architectural boundaries of the built environment. Chapter Five, "Clark's Articulation of Architectural and Environmental Imaginaries," examines the sculptural objects, entitled Caixas de fósforos (Matchboxes, 1964) and Arquitetura fantástica bichos (Fantastic Architecture Critters; 1963), the installation, entitled A casa é o corpo: penetração, ovulação, germinação, expulsão (The House is the Body: Penetration, Ovulation, Germination, Expulsion; 1968), and propositions, entitled Arquitetura Biológica II (Biologic Architecture II; 1969) and Estruturas vivas (Live Structures; 1969) as case studies. As articulations of anti-authoritarian architectural and environmental imaginaries in varying degrees, these sculptural objects, installations, and propositions demonstrate how space and structure provided outlets to challenge authority and question the possibilities of architecture, while also intensifying environments and feelings associated with political repression under Brazil's military dictatorship. Using formal and social art historical analysis, supported by extensive archival and field research conducted in Brazil, Argentina, England, and the United States, this dissertation addresses existing gaps between visual art and architecture in the field of art history, particularly in histories of abstract art. Rather than situating Clark's work mainly in relation to histories of neoconcrete art and its broader legacies of painting and sculpture, I have instead mapped out a new trajectory for her practice based on architecture and urbanism as politicized sites of modernism in and out of Brazil in the postwar decades. In doing so, this project also formulates a new term in relation to Clark, the "artist-architect," a helpful designation for artists who straddle the line between the visual arts and the built environment. This term can encourage global intersections across potentially disparate areas and periods. Analyzing works of "artist-architects" across media can also present experimental grounds for transgressive practices of resistance and self-expression.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Art History in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 5, 2024.

FILENAME: Kim_fsu_0071E_18520.pdf

TITLE: The Role of Individual Differences and Effect of Task Repetition with Written Corrective Feedback in L2 Writing Development

AUTHOR: Kim, Jeungeun

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Li, Shaofeng

MEMBER (university representative): Sunderman, Gretchen L.

MEMBER (committee member): Hiver, Philip V.

MEMBER (committee member): Jones, Ithel

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: School of Teacher Education

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (206 pages)

ABSTRACT: Research on Task Based Language Teaching (TBLT), and learning has developed significantly in recent years. As a result of the popularity of TBLT, numerous studies in second language acquisition (SLA) have explored the effect of task repetition on L2 performance. However, while previous task repetition studies mainly focused on the effects of repeating the same task on the complexity, accuracy, and fluency (CAF) of oral language production, limited research has examined the influence of different types of task repetition on learners' written production. Moreover, although written corrective feedback has been extensively investigated in SLA, the synergy effect between task repetition and written corrective feedback in shaping the quality of individual writing task output has not received adequate attention. Notably, no study has yet compared the influence of two types of task repetition (identical repetition and procedural repetition), by providing two distinct types of feedback—direct feedback and metalinguistic feedback, on written production for upper-intermediate adult EFL learners. To address this research gap, the current study investigated the effect of task repetition and two types of feedback on the accuracy of students' written task performance. Additionally, recognizing the growing importance of individual differences (ID) in SLA, this study investigated the role of individual differences constructs such as working memory capacity, L2 writing anxiety, and L2 writing motivation on L2 learners' written production. Additionally, the level of motivation and anxiety to complete learning tasks was identified as another important factor contributing to individual variation (Kormos & Wilby, 2019). Task motivation is a complex construct influenced by various contingencies associated with multiple actional contexts, making it more intricate than a simple composite of general and state motivation (Dornyei, 2002, 2005). Therefore, beyond general L2 writing motivation and L2 anxiety, the study also examined task-specific anxiety and motivation, which are transitory, to determine whether their levels change over time during task performance. Eighty adult Korean EFL learners participated in four intact classes randomly assigned to four treatment groups: identical repetition + direct feedback, identical repetition + metalinguistic feedback, procedural repetition + direct feedback, and procedural repetition + metalinguistic feedback. A pretest and posttest were employed. The two identical repetition groups repeated the same writing procedure with the same picture description, while two procedural repetition groups repeated the same writing procedure with different picture descriptions. Two types of feedback (direct and metalinguistic) were provided for each task repetition condition. To measure learners' writing development, overall accuracy and accuracy on three target structures (past tense, articles, and prepositions) were assessed. L2 writing motivation and L2 writing anxiety were measured before the treatment sessions began to explore learners' general orientation of motivation and anxiety toward L2 writing learning. However, task motivation and task anxiety were measured after they performed writing tasks each week as outcome measurers to observe their patterns. Questionnaires were used for all these four constructs, Lastly, a reading span test (RSPAN) was used for the working memory test. Results from ANCOVA indicated that the procedural task repetition groups significantly outperformed the two identical task repetition groups in overall accuracy and past tense accuracy. Regarding the role of individual differences in working memory, motivation, and anxiety, multiple regressions revealed distinct results based on treatments under each group. For both procedural task repetitions, anxiety was a positive predictor, while working memory was a negative predictor. In contrast to the two procedural task repetitions, anxiety was a negative predictor for both identical task repetition groups. Lastly, two-way repeated measure ANOVA results showed distinct motivational patterns after writing between the two task repetition groups. The two procedural task repetition groups increased their motivation, whereas the two identical task repetition groups decreased task motivation over time. Nevertheless, repeating either content or procedures appeared to alleviate learners' task-specific anxiety in writing tasks. The findings further our understanding of the language learners' perceived motivational and emotional factors influenced by task implementation and instructional strategies in the language learning context. These findings provide valuable insights into L2 pedagogy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): February 27, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Individual differences, L2 writing anxiety, L2 writing motivation, task repetition, working memory, written corrective feedback

TITLE: Inventive Response: How Teachers' Responses to Students' Writing Prompt Invention

AUTHOR: Kirchner, Claire Elizabeth

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Neal, Michael R.

MEMBER (committee member): Domínguez Barajas, Elías, 1968-

MEMBER (committee member): Graban, Tarez Samra

MEMBER (committee member): Catena, Emily Plummer

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of English

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (128 pages)

ABSTRACT: This illustrative case study investigates teachers' formative written responses to students' writing, and how those responses could be inventive for students' future composing practices. It engages with the concept of "invention" from a rhetoric/composition standpoint in order to ask: To what extent do different formative written responses on student writing function inventively? What are students' perceptions of instructors' written responses on their papers? How can these written responses prompt students to respond inventively in future writing and revisions? There is a general lack of writing assessment or response literature engaging explicitly with invention, even though much of it touches on relevant invention-related concepts, like "topoi" or "heuristic" (Connors, Lunsford 209; Melzer). This research critically considers that literature and makes a case for inventive response, because students' generativity in their writing could be compatible with the growth-oriented characteristics of formative feedback. The study uses existing scholarship alongside the research questions to inductively analyze three document-based, semi-structured interviews with student writers at Florida State University. Through answering narrative inquiry-based and descriptive questions, the interviewees indicated generativity in response by perceiving teachers' feedback as conversational, interpretive, and contextually-influenced. Further, the interviews compellingly implied that positive and question-based teacher comments led students to invent new writing ideas, new writing strategies, and new writing confidence. Based on these findings, the study concludes by pointing to connections for future research, and by providing practical suggestions for teachers to implement more inventive response.

TITLE: Influencing Intermolecular Interactions between Metal Oxide Bound Molecules via Post-Fabrication Atomic Layer Deposition

AUTHOR: Knorr, Erica S.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Hanson, Kenneth G.

MEMBER (university representative): Collins, David C. (David Christopher)

MEMBER (committee member): Alabugin, Igor V., (Professor)

MEMBER (committee member): Roper, Michael Gabriel

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (104 pages)

ABSTRACT: Intermolecular interactions of metal-oxide bound molecules can have a substantial impact on the electrochemical and photophysical processes of molecules and their subsequent performances as catalysts, sensors, or electron injectors in solar energy conversion. Inherent to the metal oxide-organic molecule interface is the close proximity of molecules, which can facilitate interactions and processes including aggregation, triplet-triplet annihilation, excimer formation, singlet fission, dimerization, and more. These processes can be either advantageous or disadvantageous for a given application, which makes the intentional formation or inhibition of such interactions critical. We have made efforts to understand the role of post-loading atomic layer deposition (ALD) on ZrO2-bound molecules, in which the precursor for an inert metal oxide (Al2O3) reacts with the ZrO2 surface. Both decreased surface loading density of molecules and an increasing number of ALD overlayers resulted in a decrease in excimer formation. However, photoluminescent and femtosecond transient absorption measurements were still dominated by excimer features. These results suggest that ALD may provide a post-surface loading means of influencing such intermolecular interactions. Instead of reacting solely with the ZrO¬¬2 surface, our current research investigates the effects of ALD directly reacting with functionalized, metal-oxide bound molecules.

TITLE: Symmetry without Skepticism: Compromising with Rosen on Moral Ignorance and Responsibility

AUTHOR: Kost, Brenden

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): LeBar, Mark

MEMBER (committee member): Clarke, Randolph K.

MEMBER (committee member): Bukoski, Michael

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Philosophy

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (27 pages)

ABSTRACT: Gideon Rosen famously defends a novel skeptical conclusion about moral responsibility, arguing that we are never warranted in confidently judging that any particular someone X is morally blameworthy for some particular action A. Alternative accounts might seem preferable to Rosen's, at least on the grounds that they are more consistent with our current blaming practices. However, Rosen's opponents tend to avoid his conclusion by advocating what Alvarez and Littlejohn call the "asymmetry thesis," essentially the thesis that non-normative ignorance is excused in a different way than moral ignorance. In doing so, they reject a crucial premise in Rosen's argument. I argue that one needn't give up what I will call Rosen's "symmetry thesis" in order to avoid his ultimate conclusion. I first motivate a reason for wanting to preserve symmetry by detailing an objection to symmetry-denying quality-of-will views. I then attack the final premise in Rosen's skeptical argument, essentially relying on plausible assumptions about standards of justification and the general commonplace of akratic action.

TITLE: Towards Quantum-Secure Blockchain: Architectural Designs and Evaluations

AUTHOR: Kumar, Rajat

MEMBER (professor co-directing thesis): Liu, Xiuwen, 1966-
