ABSTRACT: The adoption of quantum computing presents a considerable risk to the security of traditionalcryptographic methods, including those used in current blockchain technologies. Quantum algo- rithms, especially Shor's and Grover's, can efficiently solve problems that classical cryptographic algorithms rely on for security, rendering them vulnerable to attacks. This thesis explores the creation of quantum-resistant blockchain platforms to address this critical issue. The research begins with a comprehensive study of the prevailing blockchain infrastructure and the potential vulnerabilities posed by quantum computing, with a particular focus on con- sensus algorithms and cryptographic primitives. Various post-quantum cryptographic approaches, including lattice-based cryptography and quantum-safe digital signatures, are investigated for their suitability in securing blockchain systems against quantum threats. The thesis presents an original contribution in the form of a novel quantum-safe blockchain protocol that utilizes advanced cryptographic techniques to provide robust security in the quantum era. The proposed protocol is rigorously analyzed and evaluated for its effectiveness in various applications, including cryptocurrency, healthcare, tokenization and real world assets. The findings of this research underscore the urgent need for transitioning to quantum-resistant blockchain systems. The thesis offers a practical framework and guidelines for designing and im- plementing secure quantum-resistant blockchain architectures, taking into account the challenges and considerations involved in such a transition. By addressing the imminent threat of quantum computing to blockchain security, this research aims to forge resilient and forward-looking blockchain systems. The outcomes of this thesis have sig- nificant implications for ensuring the continued viability, security, and trustworthiness of blockchain technology against the advancements in quantum computing.

TITLE: Faculty Motivations for Embedding Librarians in Undergraduate Courses at Sun Sand State College

AUTHOR: Kuni, Kayla

ABSTRACT: Community colleges are institutions that provide access to higher education to anyone with a high school diploma or GED (Kim & Dolan, 2015). It seems that there is some room for development when explaining what embedded librarians should do, and what embedded librarians should not do. Much of this knowledge comes about through relationships development, and ongoing communication, between the embedded librarian and the faculty member.

FILENAME: Kuper_fsu_0071E_18656.pdf

TITLE: An Immigrant Paradox in the Black Box? : Evaluating in-Prison Maladaptive Behaviors among Foreign-and Native-Born Persons

AUTHOR: Kuper, Julie L.

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Copp, Jennifer E.

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Turanovic, Jillian J., 1985-

MEMBER (university representative): Tripodi, Stephen J.

MEMBER (committee member): Hay, Carter H.

MEMBER (committee member): Brancale, Julie Mestre

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Criminology and Criminal Justice

CORPORATE NAME: College of Criminology and Criminal Justice

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (146 pages)

ABSTRACT: The U.S. regularly incarcerates its residents, where time spent behind bars is overwhelmingly negative (Massoglia, 2008a; Rose & Clear, 1998). But not all persons have an equal chance of incarceration. State and federal policies target ethnically heterogenous neighborhoods in ways that lead to residents' disparate surveillance, arrest, and incarceration, even while research demonstrates that such policies are damaging (Menjívar & Abrego, 2012; Peterson & Krivo, 2010). Contrary to traditional criminological theory, evidence suggests that cultural diversity may work to keep individuals and their communities safer (Wright & Rodriguez, 2014). Indeed, an immigrant paradox has been found, where immigrants are less likely to commit violence, use substances, or offend, though they are more often exposed to criminogenic environments (Salas-Wright et al., 2016).Criminological literature takes this protective effect of diversity for granted, neglecting to unpack the immigrant paradox. It is unknown whether the immigrant paradox extends to prison—where foreign-born persons are less likely to exhibit mental health crises or engage in misconduct—or if incarceration will undo their resilience. Yet effective correctional policy must be sensitive to the diversity of those incarcerated. Guided by theory and research on the immigrant paradox, prison misconduct, and mental health behind bars, the goal of this study is to examine whether incarcerated native- and foreign-born persons vary in the number and kinds of misconducts they engage in and/or mental health crises they experience. Further, this dissertation examines whether relationships vary by sources of heterogeneity within the immigrant group, including sending country, race, and detainer status. To solve these research puzzles, this study asks three primary research questions. First, do incarcerated immigrants differ from non-immigrants in their involvement in prison misconduct? Second, do incarcerated immigrants differ from non-immigrants in their likelihood of experiencing an in-prison mental health crisis? Third, and finally, do incarcerated immigrants who are subject to deportation differ from those who are not in their involvement in prison misconduct or experience of a mental health crisis? Data from administrative records on the full population of incarcerated adults housed in a state prison in the western U.S. between 2010 and 2020 (N=58,289) are used. Over 13% (N=7,697) of individuals come from over 120 different countries, not including the U.S. or its territories. Data trace all administrative details of individuals' in-prison experiences from intake to release. This rich information, coupled with the growing diversity of this western state, render this system ideal for advancing theory and research on the bounds of the immigrant paradox. Analyses find support for an in-prison immigrant paradox, but they further reveal that the effect of immigrant status varies by race. That is, incarcerated immigrants are expected to engage in fewer counts and types of misconduct than their non-immigrant counterparts and are less likely to experience in-prison mental health crises. But patterns differ for property misconduct and are not uniform across racially diverse individuals. Instead, the immigrant paradox is pronounced among Latinx persons, where these individuals are less likely to engage in most types of prison infractions and have lower odds of mental health crises compared to those of other races. Alternatively, White immigrants more often experience mental health crises behind bars relative to immigrants of color. These differences signify that the protective factors that drive the immigrant paradox may not be readily available to all foreign-born persons, that diverse persons present with diverse in-prison needs, and that prior experience with hardship may be one reason that immigrants are resilient to adversity. Finally, incarcerated immigrants who face deportation only slightly differ from those who do not in their involvement in misconduct or their experience of mental health crises. While immigrants with detainers were less likely to engage in drug misconduct or experience in-prison mental health crises than those without, findings did not significantly differ by detainer status for overall misconduct or any other infraction type. As such, incarcerated immigrants may already anticipate deportation, and certain characteristics about immigrants who receive detainers may matter more than the threat of deportation itself. Yet further investigation of the effect of deportation is needed. Broadly, the substantive effect of the immigrant paradox is diminished in a prison setting and is conditioned by heterogeneous statuses of immigrants, but it is not erased. Treating immigrants harshly for fear that they pose a dangerous criminal threat is unfounded and is only successful in perpetuating legal violence against them. While additional work is needed to further unpack the immigrant paradox in incarcerated settings, we must be mindful of clumsy, overly punitive social policies that harm foreign-born populations.

TITLE: The Role of Semiconducting Electronic Structure on Static and Transient Plasmonic Properties

AUTHOR: Kuszynski, Jason Eric

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Strouse, Geoffrey F.

MEMBER (university representative): Xiong, Peng

MEMBER (committee member): Nienhaus, Lea

MEMBER (committee member): Hanson, Kenneth G.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (135 pages)

ABSTRACT: The field of plasmonics as a whole is gathering widespread interest due to their wide range of applications and new technology advancements because of their enhancement of light-matter interactions. Although scientists have largely used noble metals plasmonic metals such as gold, silver, or aluminum, the growing field of plasmonic semiconductor nanocrystals (PSNCs) still require extensive research towards how the semiconducting electronic structure impacts relevant properties such as charge carrier mobility, conductivity, and near field enhancement. This work focuses on how the host nanocrystal density of states directly impacts and modifies the plasmonic properties of interest in both the static and ultrafast transient time regimes. Chapter 1 introduces the concept of plasmons starting from the simple harmonic oscillator model leading to the free electron model's critical relationship for plasmon frequency, carrier density, and carrier effective mass. From there, the concept of band theory is introduced, and the interactions of charge carrier quasiparticles with the semiconducting electronic structure are outlined and discussed. Chapter 2 introduces the intermediate band semiconductor, Cu5FeS4, where magnetic circular dichroism is used to analyze the carrier effective mass as a function of applied magnetic field. Chapter 3 introduces one of the highest energy PSNCs in literature to date, WO3-x, where transient absorption relaxation dynamics are deconvoluted for plasmon and optical band gap excited regimes. Chapter 4 turns to CuxFeS4 (x=3,5,7), where the ratio of Cu:Fe is shown to modulate the hole-phonon and phonon-phonon transient absorption relaxation rates correlated with carrier effective mass and plasmon damping frequency respectively. Overall, this thesis showcases that static plasmon properties correlate well with transient plasmonic properties, where experiments such as magnetic circular dichroism and transient absorption are effective tools for developing the correlations needed for predicting desired plasmonic properties when designing novel PSNCs for future applications.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 25, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): nanocrystals, plasmonics, semiconductors, spectroscopy

TITLE: Navigating Systemic Barriers and Cultivating Seeds of Change: Latina Preservice Teachers' Journeys into Stem Education

AUTHOR: Kasper, Victor

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Jaber, Lama

MEMBER (university representative): Perez-Felkner, Lara

MEMBER (committee member): Southerland, Sherry A., 1962-

MEMBER (committee member): Beatty, Cameron C.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: School of Teacher Education

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (163 pages)

ABSTRACT: Teachers of Color bring valuable assets into the classroom and play a vital role in empowering marginalized students (Brown, 2014; Dee, 2004), however these teachers remain severely underrepresented, especially in STEM fields (Irwin, 2022, 2023; NCES, 2020). Meanwhile, preservice teachers (PSTs) of Color often confront marginalization including lack of representation, isolation, and pressures to assimilate in teacher education programs situated in historically white institutions (HWIs) (Gist, 2017; Haddix, 2010; Hayes & Fasching-Varner, 2015). More specifically, Latina STEM PSTs encounter gender stereotypes, unwelcoming climates, and assumptions questioning their abilities (McGee, 2020; Ong et al., 2018). Understanding the barriers that these Latinas face, alongside their sources of resilience and resistance, can inform policies and curriculum to better support minoritized teacher candidates (Kohli, 2021). As such, the central question guiding this study asks: What are the experiences of three Latina STEM preservice teachers at a historically white institution (HWI)?Using frameworks of Latinidad, LatCrit theory (Solórzano & Yosso, 2001), and transformational resistance (Solórzano & Bernal, 2001), this study examines Latinas' intersectional barriers and resilience in white-dominated contexts of STEM and teacher education. Through two semi-structured interviews with each PST, aimed at eliciting their narratives on motivations and experiences in their program, I analyze using qualitative methods how these PSTs navigated systemic inequities and explore their resistance to systemic oppression (Hannegan-Martinez et al., 2022; Solórzano & Yosso, 2001). Findings revealed four key patterns in Latina PSTs' journeys: (1) gendered and racialized microaggressions which affected their emotional and psychological wellbeing; (2) stark underrepresentation in STEM courses heightening isolation and self-doubt; (3) inspiration and motivation from personal experiences to pursue teaching of marginalized students, and (4) advocacy for engagement with sociopolitical issues affecting communities of Color within teacher preparation programs. Despite barriers imposed by dominant structures, the Latina PSTs displayed transformational resistance as they leveraged wisdom from lived experiences to inform their aspiration to teach (Yosso, 2005). Findings center the participants' knowledge and lived experiences to inform teacher preparation practices in ways that could better support other Latina PSTs in STEM. This study makes an important contribution by applying LatCrit frameworks to elucidate Latinas' diverse lived experiences at the intersection of race, gender, and class (Chavez-Moreno, 2023) and by positioning Latin* identities as assets for STEM teaching (Fierros & Delgado Bernal, 2016). Additionally, the study highlights the ongoing resilience and resistance of Latina STEM educators against layered oppression (Hannegan-Martinez et al., 2022). More broadly, the study underscores the urgent need for greater inclusiveness, representation, and cultural responsiveness in teacher education. This includes fostering spaces for minoritized PSTs to share their counterstories, openly discuss oppression, and nurture critical consciousness towards social justice (Kohli, 2021; McGee, 2021; Solórzano & Yosso, 2002).

TITLE: Aerobic Exercise-Mediated Prevention Against Glucocorticoid Myopathy in Aged Skeletal Muscle

AUTHOR: Laskin, Grant R.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Gordon, Bradley S.

MEMBER (university representative): Chase, P. Bryant

MEMBER (committee member): Hwang, Hyun Seok

MEMBER (committee member): Solis, Christopher

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Health, Nutrition, and Food Sciences

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (118 pages)

ABSTRACT: Older adults are vulnerable to glucocorticoid-induced muscle atrophy and weakness, with sex potentially influencing susceptibility to those effects. Aerobic exercise can reduce glucocorticoid-induced muscle atrophy in young rodents. However, it is unknown whether aerobic exercise can antagonize glucocorticoid myopathic features in aged muscle. The objectives of this study were to define the extent to which sex influences the development of glucocorticoid myopathy in aged muscle, and to determine the extent to which moderate intensity aerobic exercise training protects against development of myopathy. 24-month-old female (n=30) and male (n=33) mice were randomized to either sedentary or aerobic exercise groups. Within their respective groups, mice were randomized to either daily treatment with injections of dexamethasone (DEX) or saline. Following treatments, the contractile properties of the triceps surae complex were assessed in situ. DEX marginally lowered muscle mass and soluble protein content in both sexes, which was attenuated by aerobic exercise only in females. DEX-treated females expressed greater sub-tetanic contractile properties in a sex-specific manner, which were not influenced by aerobic exercise. DEX increased muscle fatigue in both sexes, but aerobic exercise prevented the fatigue induction only in females. The sex-specific differences to muscle function in response to DEX treatment coincided with sex-specific changes to the contents of protein related to calcium handling, mitochondrial quality control, and glucocorticoid receptor in muscle. These findings define several important sexually dimorphic changes to aged skeletal muscle physiology in response to glucocorticoid treatment and define the capacity of short-term aerobic exercise to protect against those changes.

FILENAME: Lawrence_fsu_0071N_18687.pdf

TITLE: Expression Regulation of the Phospholipase A2 Gene Family in Cottonmouth Snakes (Agkistrodon Piscivorus)

AUTHOR: Lawrence, Kylie C.

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Rokyta, Darin

MEMBER (university representative): Miller, Brian G.

MEMBER (committee member): Hughes, Kimberly A., 1960-

MEMBER (committee member): Beerli, Peter

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Biological Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (53 pages)

ABSTRACT: The genetic mechanisms that regulate transformation of genetic material from genotype tophenotype influence evolutionary response to environmental change and promote species diversity. Identifying molecular regulatory mechanisms that affect gene expression is challenging for researchers because they are complex, highly variable, and affect nearly every phase of gene expression. Venom provides an ideal system for studying adaptive evolution as it is a complex phenotype used for prey capture and defense that is subject to strong selective pressures. Snake venom in particular appears to have arisen through rapid evolution, resulting in a conserved set of toxin gene families that are expressed at highly diverse rates across a wide range of taxa. The venom secretion is the result of a fairly straightforward genotype-to-phenotype map, which allows researchers to study expression at various points along the central dogma. To further investigate the evolution of venom gene expression, in Chapter 1 we characterized the venom profile of the Cottonmouth Snake (Agkistrodon piscivorus). We found that across their geographic range, A. piscivorus venom expression consists primarily of proteins in the Phospholipase A2 (PLA2) gene family. In total, we identified nine complete PLA2s tandemly arrayed in the A. piscivorus genome of a female snake collected from the Apalachicola National Forest (ANF) in north Florida, which is more than in any previously characterized North American pit viper. The array contains four expressed PLA2s, one copy of the basic PLA2-K and three copies of the acidic PLA2-A that appear to be the result of gene duplication. This PLA2 region is consistent with the PLA2 arrays of previously annotated hemorrhagic-type rattlesnakes, which lack the characteristic heterodimeric PLA2s in neurotoxic rattlesnake venoms. We found that expression of the four toxin PLA2s varied among individual A. piscivorus, but in all cases PLA2-K was expressed most highly in the venom gland. In Chapter 2, we aimed to determine whether expression variation of the four toxin PLA2s were differentially expressed among the sampled individuals. We collected snakes from the three recognized subspecies of A. piscivorus : The Florida Cottonmouth (A. p. conanti), the Western Cottonmouth (A. p. leucostoma), and the Eastern Cottonmouth (A. p. piscivorus) and performed RNA-sequencing to quantify venom gland expression. We found that only one copy of the acidic PLA2-A1c was differentially expressed between Florida (A. p. conanti) and Continental (A. p. leucostoma and A. p. piscivorus) individuals. This differential expression seemed largely driven by relatively high expression of PLA2-A1c in half of the sampled Florida individuals. Despite the high conservation of the PLA2s gene array across sampled individuals, we did find that this expression variation may be driven by sequence variation found only in the three more high-expression Florida individuals. We identified one synonymous single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) in the coding region of Exon 2 of PLA2-A1c that was only present in these individuals. We believe that this SNP could be in linkage with regulatory elements that control PLA2 expression, and thus may explain the increased relative expression. In addition to differential expression among individuals, we all found that PLA2 paralogs are expressed at varying amount within a given individual. In Chapter 3, we aimed to characterize the genomic architecture that may regulate expression of the PLA2 gene family in A. piscivorus. To achieve this, we used ATAC-sequencing of two individuals collected from North Florida (ANF) to characterize accessible chromatin and H3K27ac CUT&RUN sequencing of one individual collected from North Florida (ANF) to identify regions containing active enhancers. We found several regions of interest that may regulate PLA2 expression in A. piscivorus, including open chromatin regions just upstream of each of the four expressed PLA2s that likely contain promoters and large regions of open chromatin downstream of the four expressed PLA2s. We also found three distinct CUT&RUN sequencing peaks associated with active enhancers located between each PLA2-A and their associated unexpressed PLA2-C. These regions are homologous to the third exon of the non-venom expressed PLA2-E, which also shares the associated peak. We used Sequence Capture sequencing reads from 147 individual A. piscivorus to determine whether sequence variation in the identified enhancer and promoter peaks could contribute to PLA2 paralog expression. However, we found that these regions were highly conserved among sampled individuals. Therefore, future works should further investigate the identified peak regions to determine what regulatory elements may be present and contribute to PLA2-expression.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 20, 2024.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

TITLE: Screening for Balance: The Relationship between Overparenting, Parental Autonomy Control, Low Self Efficacy, and Social Media Addiction Among Emerging Adults

AUTHOR: Lee, Tse-Yen

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Cui, Ming, 1971-

MEMBER (committee member): Fincham, Frank D.

MEMBER (committee member): Kimmes, Jonathan G. (Jonathan Gene)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Human Development and Family Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (40 pages)

ABSTRACT: Over the recent years, social media use has become increasingly prevalent among American adults. While the impact of the rise of social media platforms is ubiquitous, researchers revealed that emerging adults (individuals between 18 and 29 years of age) are more vulnerable to social media addiction than other populations. Theories and research have suggested overparenting as a potential predictor for emerging adults' problematic technology use. Specifically, the theory of emerging adulthood and self-determination theory offer explanations for the detrimental effects of overparenting behavior in the lives of emerging adults, as they seek autonomy and independence at this stage. Further, studies have linked overparenting to emerging adults' internet addiction, as well as game and social media addictive behaviors. Nevertheless, the underlying mechanisms through which overparenting impacts social media addiction remain understudied in the literature. Therefore, the present study examined the association between overparenting and social media addiction among a sample of emerging adults. Parental autonomy control and low self-efficacy were also assessed as potential mediators for this association. College students (N = 545) completed surveys at three time points over 12 weeks. Structural equation modeling suggested that overparenting was positively related to social media addiction via higher levels of parental autonomy control and lower levels of self-efficacy. Future directions and implications of the present study were provided.

FILENAME: Lee_fsu_0071N_18752.pdf

TITLE: Il Divino Musicista: Music and Sound in Dante's Commedia

AUTHOR: Lee, Robert Alexander

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Eyerly, Sarah

MEMBER (committee member): Brewer, Charles E. (Charles Everett)

MEMBER (committee member): Coggeshall, Elizabeth

MEMBER (committee member): Faulk, Barry J.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (109 pages)

ABSTRACT: As one of the most widely printed and read texts in the world, Dante Alighieri's Commedia has firmly established its place in the global literary canon. Written between 1308 and 1320, the Commedia quickly became a widely disseminated and studied text. The first lectura dantis, or public readings and accompanying lectures about the poem by the great Giovanni Boccaccio, were held mere years after Dante's death, and study of the poem has continued for the past 700 years. Its enduring cultural and linguistic value for the Italian people have solidified Dante as a godlike figure in Italian history. The study of diegetic sound and music in the poem, however, has largely been overlooked or ignored, with a few exceptions. This thesis contributes to scholarship on the music and sound in Dante's Commedia, responds to existing Dante scholars such as Francesco Ciabattoni and sound studies scholars such as R. Murray Schafer and Aimée Boutin, and offers a collection of my thoughts and interpretations on the subject. I argue that Dante crafted an intentional sonic design into the fabric of the poem, and that through analysis of the design we are able to learn more about both the poem and poet. Using the text as an archive of sonic memory that tells the reader significant and culturally relevant information about the city of Florence and its surrounding area in the Middle Ages, I seek to develop a new methodology through which word and music scholars may "listen in" to the past through literature. I also engage with protopsychomusicology and the affective power of music through the ears of Dante. Scenes such as the interaction with the musician Casella in Purgatorio 2 suggest the use of music in an intentionally comforting or healing manner. Although sparse and uncertain, in biographical accounts scholars speculate that Dante may have had epilepsy (or a similar condition), and through the poem I argue that he used music in a therapeutic manner to treat his own condition, similarly to modern medical music therapy. Finally, I look at the sonic remnants of the past in the poem and consider how Dante used audible memory to recall and relate to past literary voices and sought to establish a cultural epic through sonic memory. Dante adopted and adapted elements of epic throughout his work in order to secure his place in literary history, and through this I argue for the relevance of sound in this channel of study. Through this thesis I open avenues for future exploration of the sonic design of the Commedia and establish new ideas with which future Dante and sound studies scholars may approach this and other similar texts.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the College of Music in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Musicology.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 25, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Affect, Casella, Dante, Music, Music Therapy, Sound Studies

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Sarah Eyerly, Professor Directing Thesis; Charles E. Brewer, Committee Member; Elizabeth Coggeshall, Committee Member; Barry Faulk, Committee Member.

TITLE: An Exploration of the Experiences of First-Generation Students at a Private, Business-Focused University

AUTHOR: Leturmy, Aimee C.

MEMBER (committee member): Hu, Shouping

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (102 pages)

ABSTRACT: This qualitative case study explored the experiences of first-generation students with varying levels of support at Bentley University, a private, business-focused university in the Northeast. Data was collected through semi-structured interviews with 11 first-generation students that represented different ethnic/racial backgrounds, gender identities, class standing, and majors. The study found that while first-generation students of color had established supportive communities on campus, they often struggled with feelings of inadequacy in foundational business courses. Participants also had challenges accessing high impact practices, such as internships and studying abroad. Bentley prides itself on providing broad opportunities for students, including international education and career development, so these first-generation student experiences do not align with the university's efforts to support all students.

TITLE: Improving Local Government Capacities for Interlocal Collaborations and Citizen-Government Interactions

AUTHOR: Li, Wenhui

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Berry, Frances Stokes

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Tang, Tian

MEMBER (university representative): Butler, William Hale

MEMBER (committee member): Fay, Daniel F.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Social Sciences and Public Policy

CORPORATE NAME: School of Public Administration and Policy

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (92 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation contributes to the intersection of public administration, public policy, and public management by exploring avenues to enhance local government capacities for interlocal collaborations and citizen-government interactions. The first study investigates the joint influence of yardstick competition and managerial stability on bolstering interlocal collaborations for public service delivery, utilizing panel data from municipal governments in Florida for empirical testing. Regarding citizen-government interactions, the second paper focuses on public assessments of local government sustainability strategies and performance. Survey experiment results reveal that citizens exhibit distinct preferences regarding sustainability strategies contingent upon sustainability performance conditions, with these preferences further diverging across different subgroups. Furthermore, the third paper examines how administrative burden reductions by local governments can improve the permitting efficiency of energy infrastructure projects for applicants. The findings suggest that reducing eligibility cost can expedite permitting time for applicants in the short term, especially within low-income and high-minority communities, while reducing collaboration cost can accelerate the application process in the long run, particularly across non low-income and low-minority communities.

TITLE: Charting New Waters: Intersectional Identities in STEM--a Focus on Asian International Women

AUTHOR: Li, Yang

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Perez-Felkner, Lara

MEMBER (university representative): Ke, Fengfeng

MEMBER (committee member): Hu, Shouping

MEMBER (committee member): Khurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (committee member): Kurshid, Ayesha

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (151 pages)

ABSTRACT: This study illuminates the nuanced experiences of Asian international women students in Computer and Mathematical Sciences, and Engineering doctoral programs in the United States, a domain historically shaped by male dominance, White supremacy, and Western ideologies. While existing literature on gender and racial-ethnic disparities in Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math has utilized an intersectionality framework, this investigation reveals the particular ways in which AIS women's identities are constructed and negotiated within these spaces. Employing narrative inquiries and a counter-storytelling approach, the research uncovers the intersectionality of race, foreign status, and gender identity among these scholars, demonstrating how these dimensions interact uniquely for AIS women. Key findings reveal a pronounced de-emphasis of racial identity in favor of a strong STEM identity, a strategic response to systemic marginalization and racial challenges. This prioritization reflects a culturally embedded respect for meritocracy and academic achievement, reshaped in the U.S. context by their experiences of racialization and othering.The study also highlights the salient gender identity of AIS women, exacerbated by the masculine culture of CME fields. Despite the external assumption of privilege due to their Asian and international status, these women confront significant gender stereotypes and discrimination. Their strong STEM identity, fostered through resilience and the pursuit of academic and professional excellence, emerges as a counter to traditional gender norms and a mechanism for navigating the complex landscape of gender and racial inequality in STEM. The research proposes a new conceptual framework integrating the intersectionality of AIS women's identities with the Looking-Glass Self theory, offering a comprehensive understanding of their experiences across different cultural and social contexts. This framework challenges the prevailing deficit thinking about AIS women in CME, emphasizing the complexity and resilience of their identity construction in the face of multifaceted inequalities. Implications of this study are vast, suggesting changes in research, policy, and practice to better support AIS women in STEM. By recognizing the intertwined nature of their gender, foreign, and racial identities, this research calls for a more nuanced approach in academic support, mentorship, and policy formulation to foster an inclusive environment that acknowledges and addresses the unique challenges faced by AIS women in CME fields.

FILENAME: Liebenthal_fsu_0071E_18739.pdf

TITLE: Numerical Methods for Cavity Quantum-electrodynamics and the Exploration of Hybrid Light-matter States

AUTHOR: Liebenthal, Marcus Dante

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (129 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation explores the integration of quantum electrodynamics (QED) with electronic structure theory to accurately model and understand complex light-matter interactions within optical cavities. Clever designs of optical cavities have enabled experimentalists to achieve strong light-matter coupling, where the interaction between light and matter is so strong that new hybrid light-matter states emerge, known as polaritons. These polariton states can significantly alter molecular properties and chemical reactivity, leading to potential applications in quantum information processing, quantum materials, and light-driven chemical reactions. The dissertation focuses on the development of advanced quantum chemistry methods to capture cavity-induced effects and to provide a comprehensive understanding of the underlying physics. Several key technical advancements in QED are presented, including the development of QED generalizations of coupled-cluster (CC) and equation-of-motion (EOM) CC theories, as well as a framework to automate the derivation of optimized many-body equations for QED. These correlated many-body methods are compared to QED generalizations of mean-field methods like density functional theory (DFT) and time-dependent DFT (TDDFT) for qualitative assessments of cavity-modified molecular properties. In addition, analytic gradients are derived for QED-DFT to elucidate the orientation dependence of cavity-influenced reactions and to caution against the use of unmodified geometries obtained from standard electronic structure calculations in the absence of a cavity. Through the developments of these methods, the dissertation aims to provide novel theoretical insights into cavity-controlled chemistry. Specific topics addressed include the characterization of photon character within electron-attached excited states, the relevance of orbital relaxation within mean-field theories, and the orientation dependence of cavity-influenced reactions. By bridging quantum chemistry and QED, this research paves the way for new fundamental discoveries of light and matter coupling and provides a foundation for understanding and controlling cavity-modified chemistry in experimental settings. The dissertation reflects the substantial progress in modeling complex QED systems, despite challenges regarding their computational efficiency and accuracy.

TITLE: Borrowing Using Historical-Bias Power Prior

AUTHOR: Lin, Hsin-Yu

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Slate, Elizabeth H.

MEMBER (university representative): Almond, Russell G.

MEMBER (committee member): Barrientos, Andrés Felipe

MEMBER (committee member): Liu, Rongjie

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Statistics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (123 pages)

ABSTRACT: Adaptively incorporating historical information into analyses of current data can improve the precision of inference without requiring additional new observation. Unfortunately, not all borrowing methods are suitable when limited historical studies are available. When a single historical study is available, the power priors control the amount of information to borrow via specification of a weight parameter that discounts the contribution of the historical data in a likelihood combined with current data. We develop a new type of conditional power prior called the historical-bias power prior using an empirical Bayes approach. It relaxes the assumption of the traditional power priors to allow for historical bias. Moreover, our new weight function controls the amount of borrowing and only borrows when historical data satisfy the borrowing criteria. This is achieved by embedding the Frequentist test-then-pool approach in the weight function. Hence, the historical-bias power prior builds a bridge between the Frequentist test-then-pool and the Bayesian power prior. In the simulation, we examine the impact of historical bias on the operating characteristics for borrowing approaches, which has not been explored in previous literature. The results show that the historical-bias power prior yields accurate estimation and robustly powerful tests for the experimental treatment effect with good type I error control especially when the historical bias exists. Furthermore, we extend the historical-bias power prior to account for differences in subjects' baseline covariates between the historical and current studies by implementing the inverse-probability-weighting adjustment. In the simulation, the adjusted outcomes are examined under two different scenarios based on the imbalanced subjects' baseline. The results show that the operating characteristics may be influenced by the adjustment and is associated with the degree of imbalance between subjects. However, the adjustment is effective because it mitigates the impact of the confounders between studies after borrowing, leading to more reliable inference.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Statistics in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 1, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Bayesian adaptive design, Historical control, Information borrowing, Non-concurrent borrowing, Power prior

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Elizabeth H. Slate, Professor Directing Dissertation; Russell G. Almond, University Representative; Andrés F. Barrientos, Committee Member; Rongjie Liu, Committee Member.

TITLE: Allan Willcocks' 12 Studies for Guitar: An Examination of the Allan Willcocks Pseudonym and His Impressionistic Studies for Guitar

AUTHOR: Lindley, Justin T.

MEMBER (professor co-directing treatise): Sauer, Greg

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (76 pages)

ABSTRACT: This treatise will briefly explore the reasons a composer would accredit their own works to a different name other than theirs; whether the name is of another living or deceased composer, or a name that is fabricated altogether. This will serve as a prerequisite to the central topic on hand, an examination of a set of guitar studies composed by the German classical guitar pedagogue, performer, as well as composer, Tilman Hoppstock (1961-). In 1992, Hoppstock recorded a piece by an allegedly obscure composer, Franz Werthmüller (1769-1841), and for the next 15 years managed to keep the secret that Werthmüller was merely Hoppstock's first use of a pseudonym, to present a piece written in the style of an older musical era. In 2010, Hoppstock published a set of 12 studies, for the guitar, under another obscure composer, Allan Willcocks (1869-1956). Undoubtedly, Willcocks was in fact another pseudonym used by Hoppstock, and though this British composer came with an in-depth two-page biography, facsimiles of hand-written manuscripts, and even old photographs documenting various stages of Willcocks' life, it took only two years for the true identity behind these studies to come out. This treatise will explore the alleged life of Allan Willcocks, Hoppstock's own reasons for inventing this character, why the Willcocks' 12 Studies for Guitar has proven to be a valuable addition to classical guitar literature, as well as the style in which they were written in. Provided are musical examples, biographical information, original manuscripts, photographs and even concert programs that Hoppstock put together to introduce the world of music to Allan Willcocks.

ABSTRACT: Early American women's history and the history of visual culture tend to avoid overlapping in terms of both sources and questions. This thesis will also explore the complex powerful nature of femininity in relation to societal norms and additional iconography, including transgressions of sex and sexuality, liberty, and the mother/daughter dynamic.

TITLE: From Stereotypes to Nuance: Representations of Male Queerness in Two Musicals by Jeanine Tesori

AUTHOR: Lloyd, Zachary

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Buchler, Michael Howard, 1966-

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Lumsden, Rachel, 1977-

MEMBER (university representative): Osborne, Elizabeth A., 1977-

MEMBER (committee member): Grasso, Julianne

MEMBER (committee member): Hauser, Alisa

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Music Theory and Composition

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (203 pages)

ABSTRACT: When a character enters the stage in a musical, the audience begins to make assumptions about that character based on what they see—their presented gender, race, etc. Once the character begins to act, speak, and sing, the audience learns who that character truly is. What interests me is how aspects of a character's identity become manifest on the stage. This dissertation centers on the portrayal of male queerness in two musicals by Jeanine Tesori, Shrek the Musical (2008) and Fun Home (2015). In exploring how the queerness of three characters from these two shows are represented in both material and performance, I construct a narrative that traces Tesori's works through a spectrum of representations from those that rely on stereotypes to attempt to portray queerness in a more individualized fashion. I begin by examining the character of Lord Farquaad from Shrek the Musical in Chapter Two. I demonstrate how Farquaad relies entirely on visual and sonic stereotypes to present the character as queer, and I employ Conceptual Integration Networks to highlight how it is the interactions between queer elements, such as his costuming, choreography, vocal performance, and lyrics, that code the character as gay. I then turn to Donkey from Shrek the Musical in Chapter Three, noting the extra complexity that arises with his character's depiction of both queerness and Blackness. I complicate the ways that Donkey's character uses stereotypes, questioning the methods employed by the creative team to juggle his marked identities effectively. Finally, I examine the character of Bruce Bechdel from Fun Home in Chapter Four, whose representation is far from stereotypical, instead relying on queer markers established within the musical itself. In examining the differences between how similar identities are portrayed in Chapter Five, I reveal a progressive shift in how queerness is represented on stage, moving from a stereotypical depiction used to garner laughs from the audience to a more true-to-life representation that attempts to capture the realities of being queer.

TITLE: Second-Class Citizens: Exploring the Perceptions of Racially Marginalized Staff at a Pwi

AUTHOR: Lovett, April

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Ludwig, Eric

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Guthrie, Kathy L.

MEMBER (university representative): Wright, James E.

MEMBER (committee member): Jones, Tamara Bertrand

MEMBER (committee member): Khurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (committee member): Kurshid, Ayesha

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (168 pages)

ABSTRACT: Staff members in institutions of higher education who are not faculty, such as those who work in student affairs, information technology, student business services, and other areas, may feel invisible and unappreciated. This sense of obscurity for racially marginalized staff can be intensified by discrimination and oppression that persist within these institutions, despite the implementation of diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) initiatives. Unfortunately, higher education literature that examines perceptions and experiences related to racism, oppression, and DEI initiatives tends to focus on students or faculty, neglecting the experiences of professional staff. This qualitative case study delved into the perspectives of racially marginalized professional staff concerning a predominantly White institution's (PWI) endeavors to establish a diverse, equitable, and inclusive environment, employing a critical race theory (CRT) framework. Utilizing a two-phase interview approach, encompassing walking and sitting interviews, nine participants shared their insights and experiences related to Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion (DEI) efforts on campus. The data analysis involved an inductive, iterative coding process of the interview data. Concerning participants' workplace encounters on campus, the findings underscored instances of racial and ethnic bias, discrimination, threats of violence, discrimination based on intersectional identities, being discredited in the workplace, and perceptions of being less valued by administrators compared to faculty, sometimes even facing devaluation by faculty themselves. Regarding participants' perceptions of the institution's DEI effectiveness, a majority expressed unawareness of any DEI initiatives and perceived those they were aware of as lacking permanence. Participants highlighted the challenge of insufficient racial diversity among employees, citing political interference with the institution's DEI efforts. Despite acknowledging these challenges, participants strongly felt that the institution should address DEI concerns. Additionally, the study revealed that DEI programming encountered issues when not appropriately administered, and participants displayed mixed reactions to how their White colleagues received DEI programs and initiatives. This study carries significant implications, affirming that racially marginalized staff encounter notable challenges within Predominantly White Institutions (PWIs), including instances of discrimination, bias, ridicule, violence, and devaluation. Moreover, the findings suggest that institution-sponsored Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion (DEI) programs were perceived as more performative than substantive, while grassroots-led initiatives initiated by staff members addressing diversity, equity, or inclusion demonstrated a greater potential for sustainability. Lastly, a poignant observation from one participant underscores the implication that staff being viewed as "second-class citizens" in comparison to faculty significantly contributes to their sense of devaluation within the institution. Drawing from the study's findings, four key recommendations emerged. First, institutions of higher education should take a stand against racial discrimination, microaggressions, and violence. Second, higher education institutions should take a bow, stop performing, and be intentional with their efforts to positively foster diversity, equity, and inclusion on campus. Third, institutions should take a seat and increase diverse representation among employees. Fourth, institutions should take a leap and prioritize the equal recognition and valuation of staff, mirroring the acknowledgment and opportunities afforded to faculty. In terms of future research, there is a necessity for in-depth analyses of the experiences of all higher education staff, quantitative examinations of staff and faculty salaries from an equity perspective, comparative investigations into staff policies and practices in states with restrictive DEI legislation versus those without, and further research on the effectiveness of grassroots DEI initiatives.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Education.

NOTE (Date of Defense): February 22, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): classism, CRT, DEI, racism, staff

TITLE: Exploring Administrators' Perspectives on Cultivating Sense of Belonging through Black Male Mentorship Programs at Mid-Size and Large Predominantly White Institutions

AUTHOR: Lovett, Darryl

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Beatty, Cameron C.

MEMBER (university representative): Eklund, Robert C. (Robert Charles), 1958-

MEMBER (committee member): Park, Toby J.

MEMBER (committee member): Wofford, Ann Marie

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (108 pages)

ABSTRACT: Black male students enrolled in predominantly White institutions (PWIs) face a myriad of challenges that hinder their academic success and overall well-being. These students often grapple with feelings of disconnection, stress, and isolation. According to studies, Black male students in PWIs are more likely to experience lower retention rates, higher dropout rates, and lower academic performance compared to their peers (Harper et al., 2018). This research explores the critical need to foster a sense of belonging for Black male students at PWIs, acknowledging the multifaceted nature of their experiences and the systemic barriers they encounter. Drawing on the works of Brooms (2020) and McCoy (2014), this study examines administrators' perspectives on Black male mentorship programs and their impact on Black male students' sense of belonging and success within PWIs. Employing a qualitative methodology (Merriam, 1998), this study focused on gaining insights into administrators' viewpoints on Black male mentorship programs, allowing them to share their experiences and the significance they attributed to these programs (Merriam & Tisdell, 2016). Data collection involved interviews with ten administrators directly overseeing and leading Black male mentorship programs at mid-size and large PWIs. The research questions probed how administrators utilize these programs to cultivate a sense of belonging for Black male undergraduate students and how they addressed challenges encountered in overseeing them. The findings highlight the positive impact of Black male mentorship programs, indicating that administrators perceive them as advantageous for fostering a sense of community, connection, and positive experiences. Although administrators recognized the advantages of these programs, they also highlighted areas for improvement in different aspects of the programs and within their institutions. This nuanced understanding of mentorship programs for Black male students has played a significant role in fostering a sense of belonging within PWI settings. In response to research question one, the data identified two primary themes: (1) facilitating personal connection and (2) fostering an engaging and supportive environment. These themes illuminated the ways in which mentorship programs contributed to the sense of belonging for Black male undergraduate students, emphasizing the importance of personal connections and a supportive academic environment. Addressing research question two, administrators navigated challenges through three key themes: (1) creating and executing strategies for financial resource management, (2) navigating staff and personnel management, and (3) managing the evaluation processes, sharing stories, and aligning with institutional goals. These themes unveiled the varied approaches employed by program administrators to address challenges and enhance the effectiveness of their mentorship programs. Exploring the implications of the findings, administrators demonstrated adaptability and resilience in integrating mentorship programs into institutional structures. The emergence of engaging activities and understanding program origins as crucial elements underscored administrators' ability to seamlessly align programs with institutional goals. Challenges were effectively addressed through adept financial resource management, strategic personnel navigation, and a commitment to storytelling, thus reinforcing institutional alignment. Four recommendations emerged from the findings. Recommendation one advocates for prioritizing the hiring of culturally competent staff sensitive to the unique challenges faced by Black male students and emphasizing the need for ongoing training. Recommendation two stresses the importance of establishing clear and measurable program goals, providing a roadmap for success, and enabling outcome assessment. Recommendation three encourages institutions to customize mentoring programs to meet the specific needs of their campus sizes and communities. Recommendation four underscores the need for individualized resource allocation for Black male mentorship programs. In conclusion, this research contributes valuable insights into the significance of Black male mentorship programs at PWIs, shedding light on their positive impact while addressing challenges. The recommendations offer a roadmap for institutions to enhance these programs, ultimately fostering a sense of belonging and academic success for Black male students in higher education.

TITLE: Four Stuart Kings: Arbitrary Rule and the Origins of the Life Guards

AUTHOR: Lunger, David A.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Blaufarb, Rafe

MEMBER (university representative): Cooley, L. (Lance)

MEMBER (committee member): Doel, Ronald Edmund

MEMBER (committee member): Grant, Jonathan A., 1963-

MEMBER (committee member): Dodds, Benjamin

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of History

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (386 pages)

ABSTRACT: Charles Stuart returned to his native country after fourteen years in exile. His subjects had just endured eleven years of military dictatorship under Oliver Cromwell and wanted a return to the days of monarchy. On 25 May 1660, Charles II landed in Dover and was warmly greeted by his people and the leader of the army, George Monck. They set off for London and arrived on 29 May, Charles II's thirtieth birthday. Escorting Charles into London were his Life Guards, a professional military cavalry force of Royalist supporters who followed their king into exile. Having witnessed his father's failure to keep his crown because he lacked a loyal bodyguard and seeing first-hand how a devoted household helped his cousin Louis XIV maintain his kingdom, Charles II had every intention of keeping these guards throughout his reign. The challenge was that Charles had promised to disband the military, which had become very unpopular in England and was viewed as a tool of tyranny and absolute rule. This dissertation deals with the challenges Charles II and his brother James II faced in keeping a loyal guard about them in a country that genuinely feared the institution of a standing army. The first four Stuart monarchs stubbornly believed in the Divine Right of Kings and sought to rule by the Royal Prerogative. How they wielded arbitrary powers in an era where Parliament wanted more to say in declaring laws and charting a direction for the country was challenging, and all four dealt with it differently. At the root of these challenges was how money was collected to fund wars and build armies. The Stuart kings could rule without Parliament but not raise taxes to pay for expensive armies to conduct military campaigns. For this, they had to call Parliament, and Parliament was all too aware of their growing power to the point that they used these episodes to demand more say. In this complicated world, Charles II and James II could not rule as absolutists without the Life Guards who formed the nucleus of England's standing army.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 25, 2024.

TITLE: Numerical Modeling of Hurricane Wave and Storm Surge Overtopping Sand Dunes and Barrier Island

AUTHOR: Ma, Mengdi

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Huang, Wenrui, 1961-

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Jung, Sungmoon

MEMBER (university representative): Zhao, Tingting, (Geography Professor)

MEMBER (committee member): AbdelRazig, Yassir

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (156 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation provides a comprehensive analysis of the intricate dynamics of coastal systems under the extreme stress of hurricanes. A multi-faceted study on the interactions between hydrodynamics, morphology dynamics, and various coastal defenses like sand dunes and vegetations during hurricane events is presented, employing advanced numerical modeling to enhance the understanding of coastal resilience and protection. It is constructed upon three pillars of research, each delving into different yet interconnected aspects of coastal defense mechanisms and their responses to hurricane-induced forces.The research begins by examining the protective functions of sand dunes against hurricane forces, utilizing a non-hydrostatic XBeach model (XBNH) to analyze wave dynamics with various storm surge after overtopping sand dunes. The research presents an in-depth analysis of wave behavior as they encounter sand dunes during hurricane-induced storm surges. The research focuses on Hurricane Michael as a case study, dissecting the dynamics of wave propagation, breaking, and overtopping. It offers a quantitative assessment of the dunes' ability to attenuate waves, pinpointing the conditions that precipitate maximum erosion and wave heights. The findings reveal that sand dunes are pivotal in reducing wave heights, particularly as storm surges intensify, with waves breaking at the dune base, overtopping, and losing their energy as they move inland. Through the model validation, the chapter establishes the superior performance of XBNH over the hydrostatic mode (XBSB), especially in critical metrics such as significant wave height and peak water surface elevation, where XBNH showed a markedly lower average and maximum error rates. This research not only underscores the precision of the XBNH, also provides the foundation for following research. The investigation then extends to the complex processes leading to barrier-island breaching during hurricane conditions. A case study using a two-dimensional XBNH model provides a detailed account of how hurricane-induced waves and storm surges interplay to alter island topography. The study reveals that supercritical flow conditions significantly contribute to the rapid erosion and eventual breaching of barrier islands, offering a predictive analysis of the morphological changes under extreme weather events. In addition, it provides a detailed account of the barrier-island's breaching evolution, through the analysis of bed elevation cross-sections and surge-wave profiles across various storm stages. This comprehensive examination not only reinforces the model's precision but also offers a deeper understanding of barrier island dynamics, contributing valuable knowledge to enhance coastal hazard mitigation strategies. The final aspect of the research integrates the hydrodynamic focus of the preceding chapters to explore the evolution of dune profiles, particular the role of vegetation in coastal protection. It highlights how different conditions of vegetation affect dune morphology under storm conditions. The study explores the use of the XBeach model to simulate these interactions, emphasizing the critical role of vegetation in mitigating erosion. Moreover, the chapter enriches the XBeach model's application by incorporating sensitivity analyses to different wind conditions, thereby broadening its predictive capability. The study's comprehensive approach illuminates the multifaceted relationship between vegetation, coastal morphology, and erosion processes. It highlights the indispensable role of vegetation in bolstering coastal resilience and provides strategic insights for coastal management, reinforcing the vital need for integrated environmental considerations in the design of coastal defense systems. To summarize, this dissertation underscores the importance of integrating hydrodynamics, morphological dynamics, and ecological considerations into coastal management practices. The results contribute valuable insights into the design and conservation of coastal defenses, promoting the development of more resilient communities in the face of increasing hurricane activities. Through the refined application of the XBeach model and the insights gained from its performance, the dissertation makes a significant contribution to the field of coastal engineering and environmental protection.

TITLE: Pedagogical Content Knowledge in Elementary Mathematics Teachers: A Qualitative Study of Teacher Perspectives on Instructional Practice

AUTHOR: Madison, Chanell

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Staudt Willet, K. Bret

MEMBER (university representative): Whitacre, Ian Michael

ABSTRACT: Standardized testing has elementary schools transitioning into departmentalization, where a teacher is assigned to teach a particular subject matter. Elementary education programs tend to provide a holistic approach to education that includes training in all subject matters and learner psychology. The national trend of teacher shortages as resulted in the hiring of teachers who have not attended a formal education preparation program. Departmentalized elementary teachers in mathematics enter the role without prior specialized training due to holistic teacher preparation programs or entering the profession from another role. This study explores the implementation of pedagogical content knowledge of departmentalized elementary mathematics teachers in a large urban district during planning and instruction. Pedagogical content knowledge is the specialized content knowledge needed to effectively instruct a subject matter. Despite the inconsistent evidence of planning for productive questioning, the elementary teachers demonstrated evidence of asking productive questions throughout the lesson and responding to student errors. The participants during the interview expressed the desire to increase the level of purposeful reflection on their planning and instruction as a way to improve their craft. Implications of these findings are discussed for school-level professional development programs and district-level structures for continuing education for departmentalized elementary mathematics teachers. This study contributes to the exploration of pedagogical content knowledge and teacher development specifically in the elementary setting and departmentalization that can be supported through collaborative structure and formalized reflections.

FILENAME: Malik_fsu_0071E_18628.pdf

TITLE: Simplicial Methods in Graph Machine Learning

AUTHOR: Malik, Abdullah Naeem

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Foster, Brian Joseph

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Van Hoeij, Mark

MEMBER (university representative): Bonesteel, N. E.

MEMBER (committee member): Aluffi, Paolo, 1960-

MEMBER (committee member): Farhat, Aseel

MEMBER (committee member): Farhat, Aseel

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mathematics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (121 pages)

ABSTRACT: The Weisfeiler-Leman algorithm is a powerful test of graph isomorphism, and works by iteratively isolating clusters of nodes via a coloring scheme based on binary relationships. This refinement process is akin to message passing on graph neural networks. Graph neural networks are paradigms of computation that yield powerful results for structured data based on binary relationships, and therefore their expressivity shares the limitations of the Weisfeiler-Leman test. One way to circumvent this limitation relies on identifying and working with higher relationships within the data, or by finding a better refinement criterion that can be implemented on a machine. In this thesis, we put forward data structures closely based on the identification of such higher relationships via Kan Extensions of structured data built on binary relations. These data structures are well known in algebraic topology as Simplicial Sets; the theoretical underpinnings based on the combinatorics of simplicial sets and directed graphs are explored in this thesis and, based on of it, algorithms are introduced that can identify higher-order relations. A metric that can serve as a quantification for community detection tools is also introduced, as well as the notion of a pseudoterminal vertex as a proxy for these higher relations. This helps us balance the variance-bias tradeoff necessary for generalizability of the architecture. We introduce functors that show how these higher relationships can be modelled and expanded. Finally, we propose three neural networks that benefit from the topology of these nonbinary relations. These neural networks can be ported into the standard graph neural network library to augment feature classification in a semisupervised manner. All source code is available at \texttt{https://github.com/abdullahnaeemmalik/simplicial-methods-in-graph-machine-learning}.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Mathematics in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 5, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Applied Category Theory, Directed Graphs, Graph Algorithms, Graph Neural Network, Simplicial Set, Weisfeiler-Lehman Algorithm

TITLE: Study of the Valence Transition in EuPd2Si2

AUTHOR: Mardani, Masoud

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Siegrist, Theo

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Beekman, Christianne

MEMBER (university representative): Salters, Vincent J. M.

MEMBER (committee member): Greene, Laura H.

MEMBER (committee member): Reina, Laura

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Physics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (208 pages)

ABSTRACT: Europium exhibits two stable valence states, Eu2+ and Eu3+, with energies closely matched, wherein the magnetic Eu2+ state is significantly larger than the nonmagnetic Eu3+. EuPd2Si2 (EPS) undergoes a bulk valence state transition from Eu~3+ to Eu~2+ while cooling. The phase diagram of the EPS compound differs from that of other typical rare-earth 1:2:2 compounds with valence instability. Therefore, the valence transition of the EPS compound cannot be explained by theoretical models of other compounds and remains rather mysterious. This study aims to construct a comprehensive phase diagram of the EPS crystal structure during the valence phase transition, while varying chemical substitution, temperature, and magnetic field.Chapter one discusses X-ray crystallography and crystal structures. Chapter 2 delves into the electronic and magnetic states of lanthanides and specifically europium. Curie's susceptibility of the magnetic divalent europium atoms and the Van Vleck paramagnetism susceptibility of the non-magnetic trivalent europium atoms are discussed. A literature review on the valence instability of 1:2:2 rare-earth compounds, especially the EPS compound, is presented in chapter three. Chapter four covers the efforts on the growth and characterization of the pristine and below 5% chemically substituted EPS compounds. The temperature-dependent X-ray diffraction (XRD) powder measurements by the APS synchrotron and our in-lab XRD machines will be discussed. In the EPS and its low-doped compounds, another smaller unit cell appears beside the high-temperature EPS (HT-EPS) unit cell. The new low-temperature EPS (LT-EPS) unit cell is related to the Eu3+ valence state. A magnetic valence transition was observed in the DC magnetic susceptibility measurements at temperatures where the unit cell transformation starts. In the next chapter, in the 10 to 20 % alloyed samples of EPS, the linear thermal coefficient can suddenly increase or slowly decrease to up to 3.5 times, or stay constant at all temperatures. Finally, the four thermal expansion trends are explained qualitatively by the available space for the europium atoms in the unit cell in chapter 6. The analysis of powder patterns of EPS at high magnetic fields and low temperatures in Cell 5 of MAGLAB has been conducted in chapter 7. Key findings include the magnetic field's enhancement of the HT-EPS phase, driving the valence transition temperature lower. The weight fraction of the EPS phase demonstrates a linear dependence on temperature, particularly around the temperature equating HT-EPS and LT-EPS weight fractions. Moreover, quadratic relationships with magnetic field strength are observed, along with hysteresis effects influencing the symmetry of these relationships. Finally, some of my other side projects that I have done during my study at FSU are presented. Cu2ZnSn(S,Se)4 (CZTSSe) semiconductor materials serve as excellent absorber layers in thin-film photovoltaic devices, yet their low open-circuit voltage hinders mass production. Unlike CZTSSe, Ag2ZnSnSe4 (AZTSe) possesses a favorable bandgap of 1.4 eV, making it a promising candidate to replace toxic or scarce materials in photovoltaics. Powder AZTSe was successfully synthesized. In an attempt to grow single-crystal AZTSe via the chemical vapor transport method, Ag8SnSe6 and SnSe2 phases were obtained. Further exploration focused on Ag8SnSe6's potential as a thermoelectric material, highlighting its superionic conductivity. By constructing a comprehensive electron density map of Ag8SnSe6, the path of silver atoms inside the single crystal was determined. Additionally, efforts to grow AuPbSbS3 and (Au0.5Cu0.5)PbSbS3 for renewable energy applications via chemical vapor transport were explored. Another study investigates the impact of light and temperature on the optical properties and stability of mixed-ion perovskite thin films, demonstrating slight peak shifts under elevated temperature conditions, potentially indicating anisotropic thermal expansion. Additionally, doping with Cs shows improved performance and stability compared to other compositions, as evidenced by XRD measurements. Another study examines the chemical composition of shark teeth artifacts from archaeological sites using XRD analysis, revealing residues that provide insights into ancient tool applications. Despite challenges posed by uneven surfaces, the integration of XRD patterns uncovers phases like hematite, shedding light on ancient material usage and cultural practices.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 5, 2024.

TITLE: Decision Theory, Action Guidance, and Moral Uncertainty

AUTHOR: Masotti, Joseph Vincent

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Rawling, Piers

MEMBER (committee member): Mele, Alfred R., 1951-

MEMBER (committee member): Bukoski, Michael

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Philosophy

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (40 pages)

ABSTRACT: Some philosophers have recently argued that a decision-theoretic model of rational choice can guide us to the answer of what it is appropriate to do in situations of moral uncertainty (i.e., uncertainty about what one ought to do). By proposing and defending this view, these philosophers aim to show how decision-theoretic procedures provide us with action guidance even when we have yet to settle all of the issues in normative ethics. In this paper, I argue that decision theory is never action-guiding in cases of moral uncertainty. I thus suggest that because of this limitation on decision theory's action-guiding capacities, it fails to fulfill the role that these philosophers hope to show that it has. I consider several objections to my argument and reply to each of them.

TITLE: Envisioning a Fat-Positive Theatre: Critical Receptions of Fat Bodies Onstage

AUTHOR: Mattson, Jordan

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Osborne, Elizabeth A., 1977-

MEMBER (committee member): Thomas, Aaron C.

MEMBER (committee member): Fahmy, Sarah

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: School of Theatre

CORPORATE NAME: School of Theatre

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (115 pages)

ABSTRACT: This thesis investigates how critics respond to the fat body onstage, aiming to better understand how to develop positive fat representation. Through my research, I advocate for theatre to develop fat-positive practices. I argue that fat positivity in theatre must go beyond simply including fat bodies onstage. A fat-positive theatre would cast fat bodies in all roles, while maintaining the sensitivity that the fat body carries unique cultural assumptions and may require material changes to the theatrical processes. Adopting these fat-positive practices would involve a radical acceptance of fatness onstage.My research examines three notable plays as case studies to understand how the fat body is performed and received onstage in the United States. My first case study, 'night, Mother, takes place in the 1980s as a landmark example of how casting a fat body affected a production's reception. The other two case studies, Untitled Feminist Show and Fat Ham, focus on the 2010s and 2020s, to examine how recent shifts in fat activism and body-positive movements have impacted cultural understandings of the fat body. My research seeks to understand how these cultural shifts connect to critical receptions of the fat body onstage. Through these case studies, I aim to craft a narrative around the shifting ways we conceptualize the neutral body and how the fat body challenges this unspoken assumption. In this thesis, I use the term "neutral body" to refer to bodies that fit the cultural norms of an ideal performer and "non-neutral bodies" to identify fat bodies that visibly break the traditional mode of what we expect an actor to look like. This framework provides a way of thinking about how fat bodies are routinely excluded from representation and highlights the unspoken assumption that the fat body is not the ideal body.
