TITLE: Does Reform Lead to Success for All? : Examining Student Outcomes Following Developmental Education Reform

AUTHOR: McCoy, Kiaira

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Mokher, Christine G.

MEMBER (university representative): Berry, Frances Stokes

MEMBER (committee member): Park, Toby J.

MEMBER (committee member): Perez-Felkner, Lara

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (170 pages)

ABSTRACT: Community colleges provide access to higher education for a wide range of prospective students with diverse interests and educational goals. With more than 60 percent of incoming community college students deemed as academically underprepared for college-level work, traditionally, students have been required to enroll in one semester or more of developmental coursework before beginning college-level classes. Several studies demonstrate traditional remedial education models seldom increase students' skills and contribute towards success in outcomes such as persistence, passage of gateway courses, or credential completion (Bailey & Phillips, 2016; Goudas & Boylan, 2013; Jaggars & Bickerstaff; 2018). Recent developmental education reform efforts include models that have proven to be successful in accelerating the time it takes for students to successfully matriculate through developmental coursework (Edgecombe et al., 2013; Jaggars & Stacey, 2014). These reform models include options for students to enroll directly in college-level courses simultaneously with support courses as with corequisite courses, curricula changes and interventions which consolidate multiple standalone courses into one single semester as with compressed courses, intensive advising policies, and alternatives to traditional placement assessments which result in a higher likelihood of placement accuracy and success in college-level coursework. Overwhelmingly, studies examining the outcomes of students who participate in developmental reform models have found benefits relative to traditional developmental models, however, these studies largely consider the effects of one type of developmental model or the presence or lack thereof of any type of developmental policy (Bahr et al., 2019; Barbitta & Munn 2018; Cho et al., 2012; Jaggars et al., 2013; Ran & Lin, 2019). Additionally, many studies have failed to examine whether certain types of developmental policies are more effective than others and if this differs based on gender and race/ethnicity. With states adopting varying developmental education reform policies to improve student progression into college-level coursework and beyond, this study examined how recent state modifications to placement policies, compressed/corequisite modalities, or changes to advising/academic planning have affected student persistence trends. Using a modified version of Wang's theoretical model of momentum for community college student success, I conceptualized developmental reform policies based on how they may function to contribute towards the momentum of students, and therefore, outcomes such as first-year retention and graduation rates. Drawing data from the Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System, this study used a difference-in-differences approach between the years of 2012 to 2020 to observe student success outcomes before and after implementation of developmental education policy reform models, while comparing outcomes among non-adopting states. This study considered how developmental reform policies in a national context contribute to academic momentum and student success outcomes such as persistence and completion. Results in the aggregate provide evidence that the presence of developmental education reform policies in states increase institutional retention and completion rates more so than institutions within states that do not adopt reform policies. Additionally, when disaggregating results by type of developmental education reform policy, there are no differential impacts on student outcomes, with one exception, holistic reforms which may more negatively impact outcomes. Lastly, while developmental education reforms aided in increasing overall student outcomes, gaps in graduation rates among genders and racial/ethnic groups were observed, with disparities between certain groups widening at institutions within states with reforms.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): January 25, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): community college success, developmental education, education policy reform, student success

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Christine Mokher, Professor Directing Dissertation; Frances Berry, University Representative; Toby Park-Gaghan, Committee Member; Lara Perez-Felkner, Committee Member.

FILENAME: McDaid_fsu_0071E_18468.pdf

TITLE: School Principals' Perceptions: Factors That Influence School-Based Leader Retention

AUTHOR: McDaid, Rebecca A.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Herrington, Carolyn D.

MEMBER (university representative): Berry, Frances Stokes

MEMBER (committee member): Milligan, Jeffrey Ayala

MEMBER (committee member): Rutledge, Stacey A.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (99 pages)

ABSTRACT: Problem of PracticeSchool principals have a powerful effect on student achievement, school culture, and teacher turnover. According to the National Association of Secondary School Principals (2020), the average career of a school principal is four years, and one in five school principals leave their schools annually. These numbers are even greater in more challenging schools with high numbers of minority students, English Language Learners, and students living in poverty. These students need the most experienced school principals, yet they often end up with the newest and least experienced. Even more alarming is that results from a recent survey conducted jointly by NASSP and the Learning Policy Institute (LPI) in 2020 indicated that 42% of school principals were considering leaving their position. This exploratory qualitative research study answers the following research question: The purpose of this study is to answer the following research question: What has motivated school principals to remain in school-level leadership? The study focuses on gaining the perspectives of principals on factors influencing school-based leaders to remain in their positions. Motivation and retention of current school leaders is critical to student growth and success, overall school achievement, and retention of school educators at all levels. This study will add to the current body of research focused on development and support of school leaders to positively impact school principal perseverance and retention. Methods Semi-structured interviews and coding methods have been used to organize and analyze outcomes effectively without losing the individuality of the participants' responses. Ten principals participated in semi-structured interviews. The stratified and purposeful sample included both males and females, principals at all K-12 levels, Title I and non-Title I schools, and urban and suburban schools. Data Analysis First cycle descriptive coding using a priori codes in conjunction with in vivo coding outcomes and second cycle coding outcomes were charted to identify dominant codes: Relevant Preparation, Relevant Experience, Relationships with Staff, the Participants' Perception of the Role/Feelings About the Role, Passion for Helping Others, Internal Drive, Future Role, Informal Collaboration with Peers, and the Mentor/Mentee Relationship. Code outcomes were clustered based on commonality. Six overarching themes emerged and were named: External Validation, Collaboration, Preparation and Support, Future Plans, Intrinsic Motivation, and Relationships. These themes answered the research question: What has motivated school principals to remain in school-level leadership? Recommendations Based on participant interview outcomes for this study, the following recommendations are offered. The first recommendation is to ensure that the right support is being provided to school leaders to positively impact the leader to be able to succeed within the role. The next recommendation is focused on collaboration. A focus on formal collaboration needs to shift from interaction in meetings to shadowing peers and a sharing of ideas to positively impact schools, leadership practices, and student achievement. Informal collaboration when supported and celebrated by school districts could potentially support school leaders professionally as well as emotionally which would positively impact retention rates. Next, mentor programs should be expanded to include both internal and external relationships. For mentoring programs to be most impactful on the decision-making of school principals, evaluation or fear of retribution should be removed, and this often results from an external match. Additionally, it is critical to establish and encourage a pipeline of leaders within a school district to ensure a continual pool of qualified leaders prepared to support and lead schools. All school districts and current leaders should identify and tap potential leaders and provide effective professional development, encouragement, and mentorship to develop leadership skills. Creating a pipeline of educators at all levels positively impacts students, schools, and school districts as a whole. Finally, salaries should increase to compensate school leaders fairly and adequately. Conclusion Addressing this research question provides answers and informs practice to improve formal and informal learning opportunities for school principals in an effort to address principal turnover rates. Ensuring that the right learning opportunities and supportive measures are in place are of the utmost importance to increase longevity of school leaders in their role to ultimately positively impact student achievement, increase teacher retention, and positively impact the climate and culture of a school community. Based on the perceptions of current school principals in this study, 6 themes have emerged from the data: External Validation, Collaboration, Preparation & Support, Future Plans, Intrinsic Motivation, and Relationships. Each plays an important role in developing and supporting school leaders. The combination of these supports and opportunities increases school principal perseverance and retention in their school-based leader role.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Education.

NOTE (Date of Defense): January 29, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Leader Persistence, Principal Retention, School Based Leader Persistence, School Principal Retention, School-Based Leader Retention, School-Based Principals

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

TITLE: Breaking Barriers, Building Resilience: Unraveling the Link between Autism Severity, Parent Stress and Access to Care in Families of Children with Autism

AUTHOR: McDowell, Chrystal

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Gonzales Backen, Melinda Airr

MEMBER (university representative): Killian, Michael O.

MEMBER (committee member): McWey, Lenore M.

MEMBER (committee member): Wu, Qiong, (Professor of human sciences)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Human Development and Family Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (84 pages)

ABSTRACT: This study explored the relationship between autism spectrum disorder (ASD) severity, parental stress, barriers to care, and family resilience among 210 parents of children with ASD. Using path analysis, the study investigated how ASD severity influences parental stress, mediated by barriers to care and family resilience. Results demonstrated positive direct effects between ASD severity and parent stress as well as significant indirect effects when including barriers to care as a mediator in this relationship. The sequential mediation effect of barriers to care and family resilience on the relationship between ASD severity and parent stress also supported partial mediation. While family resilience alone did not have a significant indirect effect on this relationship, resilience plays a significant role in the sequential mediation model alongside barriers to care. These findings emphasize the importance of comprehensive interventions that address both ASD symptoms and familial stressors. They have implications for clinical practice, research, education, public policy, and family support initiatives, suggesting the need for improved access to care and increased awareness and inclusivity.

TITLE: An Exploration of Admissions Requirements in College Based Paramedic Programs in Florida

AUTHOR: McGinnes, Rodney Scott

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Hu, Shouping

MEMBER (university representative): Tibi, Sana

MEMBER (committee member): Perez-Felkner, Lara

MEMBER (committee member): Wofford, Ann Marie

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (115 pages)

ABSTRACT: The Sullivan Report (The Sullivan Commission on Diversity in the Healthcare Workforce, 2004) identified the lack of racial diversity among health care practitioners as a major issue. This report points out that, while the U.S. population has continued to become more diverse, the composition of health care workers has not kept pace with these changes. Emergency Medical Services (EMS) workers provide advanced medical care to patients in the prehospital environment. Nationally, 11.6% of the entire workforce is African American, and 16.1% are Hispanic. Within the EMS field, African Americans represent only 6% of workers, and Hispanics represent 10.6% (U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, 2017). One possible impediment to minorities entering the EMS workforce may involve the admissions practices of post-secondary institutions offering EMS programs (Health Resources and Services Administration [HRSA], 2017). This study examined the admissions practices of Florida college-based paramedic programs to determine what they currently are and how decisions about these requirements are made. This study used a document analysis of Florida college-based paramedic program websites to determine what current admissions requirements are in place for these programs, as well as interviews with the program managers of 11 of the 25 Florida college-based paramedic programs, to determine how decisions are made about which instruments are used and how they are used in admissions processes. The study found that these programs used a variety of qualitative and quantitative instruments in their admissions processes as well as several different methods of selecting students based on these instruments. Interviews with program managers revealed that their decision-making processes were influenced by a desire to meet several goals, including selecting students they felt would successfully complete their programs, pass licensing exams, and perform as competent clinicians. They also incorporated influences from accreditors, government regulators, and employers of their graduates in their decision-making processes. Program directors relied mostly on anecdotal evidence to make these decisions, and diversity considerations did not play a meaningful part in their decision-making processes. Accreditors and regulators should provide guidance for these decision makers in this area, and research should be conducted to assess the validity of common instruments and selection processes and their effect on the diversity of these training programs.

FILENAME: McKiernan_fsu_0071E_18476.pdf

TITLE: To Hinder or to Strengthen To Hinder or to Strengthen: Adult Survivors of Child Sexual Abuse Experiences with Parent Disclosure Response Adult Survivors' of Child Sexual Abuse Experiences with Parent Disclosure Response

AUTHOR: McKiernan, Darrian M.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): McWey, Lenore M.

MEMBER (university representative): Schelbe, Lisa

MEMBER (committee member): Kimmes, Jonathan G. (Jonathan Gene)

MEMBER (committee member): Rudaz, Myriam

MEMBER (committee member): Harris, Gregory J.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Human Development and Family Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (116 pages)

ABSTRACT: Approximately 25% of women and 15% of men have reported being sexually abused in childhood. Although child sexual abuse (CSA) prevention and treatment methods have been widely supported in the literature, many survivors either never disclose or delay disclosing their abuse until later in life. The absence of disclosure presents major challenges to holistically understanding CSA prevention and treatment methods. Consequently, research attempting to uncover the barriers, influences, recipients, and impacts of CSA disclosure has become increasingly prevalent. A perceived negative response to CSA disclosure has been linked to a variety of long-term survivor consequences including revictimization, mental and physical health struggles, and relational issues. Not only is fear of others' responses one of the largest barriers to CSA disclosure, but having access to someone you can trust is also the most commonly identified influence to disclosing CSA. Unsurprisingly, survivors who decide to disclose initially do so and are primarily worried about the responses of their parents. Additionally, much of the CSA disclosure literature is oriented especially around children who disclose. It is reported, however, that survivors of CSA often delay reporting until adulthood. In order to increase feelings of safety for survivors to disclose, there is a need to strengthen our awareness of how survivors perceive their parents' responses to CSA disclosure. The present study aimed to gain an in-depth understanding of survivors' perceptions surrounding disclosure of CSA to a parent. Grounded theory qualitative methods were employed to develop a central theory surrounding the process of adult CSA disclosure to a parent. Findings highlighted a relational process through which adult survivors perceive and interpret their parent's response to CSA disclosure. Analyses concluded that parent response to CSA disclosure impacted the parent-child relationship by either hindering or strengthening it. Whether a relationship was ultimately hindered or strengthened by the CSA disclosure experience was dependent on the manner in which parents responded to the disclosure. Harmful and helpful parental responses were divided into five subthemes: statements, questions, behaviors, positionality, and follow-up actions. Other patterns discussed were wished for responses, familial context, and ongoing CSA discussions. Findings from this study provide insights for parents and clinicians, as well as future research directions.

FILENAME: McLachlan_fsu_0071N_18008.pdf

TITLE: Faunal Analysis of the Rotherwood Site (40Sl61), a Pre-Contact Mississippian Site in Upper East Tennessee

AUTHOR: McLachlan, Zoen

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Peres, Tanya M.

MEMBER (committee member): Marrinan, Rochelle A.

MEMBER (committee member): Thomas, Geoffrey P. (Geoffrey Paul)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Anthropology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (70 pages)

ABSTRACT: This thesis offers the first comprehensive exploration of the Rotherwood site (40SL61) in Upper East Tennessee, focusing on faunal remains to understand the subsistence practices of its original occupants. Located along the South Fork Holston River, this site presents a unique opportunity for archaeological investigation, being relatively unexplored and lacking scholarly publication. This study investigates subsistence strategies, social organization, and broader behavioral patterns during the Mississippian period through faunal analysis. Methodologically, the research addresses taphonomic processes, site formation factors, and the challenges of archaeological interpretation. The presence of whole animal remains suggests limited carcass sharing, challenging prevailing notions about Mississippian cultures in Tennessee. Furthermore, the abundance of vertebrate remains suggests that Rotherwood was not a freshwater mussel shell processing station, indicating a more diverse subsistence base. By examining the material evidence from Rotherwood, this study contributes to a deeper understanding of pre-contact societies in Upper East Tennessee and emphasizes the significance of faunal analysis in archaeological research.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the Department of Anthropology in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 18, 2024.

TITLE: Integrative Approaches in Genomic Analysis: Advancing Epigenetic Prediction, Twas Methodology, and Cell-Type Deconvolution in Spatial Transcriptomics

AUTHOR: Melton, Hunter

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Bradley, Jonathan R.

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Wu, Chong

MEMBER (university representative): He, Zhe

MEMBER (committee member): Niu, Xufeng, 1954-

MEMBER (committee member): Barrientos, Andrés Felipe

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Statistics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (197 pages)

ABSTRACT: In the rapidly evolving world of molecular biology, genetics and epigenetics have taken crucial roles in unraveling the complex origins of diseases. Through gene expression, genes govern the synthesis of proteins, the fundamental building blocks of life. Conventional observational studies grapple with major limitations in exploring the relationships between diseases and gene expression, leading to the advent of transcriptome-wide association studies (TWAS). Similarly, methylome-wide association studies (MWAS) have been developed to explore the relationships between DNA methylation and disease, as DNA methylation plays a key role in regulating gene expression. In Chapter 2 of this dissertation, we introduce MIMOSA (MWAS Imputing Methylome Obliging Summary-level mQTLs and Associated LD matrices), a comprehensive set of DNA methylation prediction models for use in MWAS. MIMOSA significantly improves the accuracy of DNA methylation prediction and downstream power of MWAS by training on a large, summary-level methylation quantitative trait loci (mQTL) dataset from the Genetics of DNA Methylation Consortium. We apply MIMOSA to genome-wide summary statistics for 28 complex traits and include a case study in high cholesterol. In Chapter 3, we present SUMMIT-FA (Summary-level Unified Method for Modeling Integrated Transcriptome with Functional Annotations), which extends the state-of-the-art TWAS method SUMMIT by incorporating functional annotations from the the Multi-dimensional Annotation-Class Integrative Estimation (MACIE). SUMMIT-FA improves gene expression prediction accuracy and TWAS power, which we demonstrate through its application to 24 traits and through simulations. In Chapter 4, we turn our attention to spatial transcriptomics, which measures gene expression in situ on slices of tissue. We present a novel zero-inflated hierarchical generalized transformation (ZI-HGT) model that functions as a noisy transformation for cell-type deconvolution with conditional autoregressive-based deconvolution (CARD). CARD assumes normality of the highly zero-inflated, count-valued spatial transcriptomic data, and the ZI-HGT transforms the data to better fit this assumption. Joined together, the ZI-HGT and CARD not only achieve enhanced cell-type deconvolution accuracy, but naturally quantify uncertainty in the estimated cell-type proportions through bootstrap Bayesian pointwise credible intervals. This leads to a novel, exploratory ``heterogeneity score'' for quantitative assessment of cell-type heterogeneity at different locations, which is demonstrated to coincide well with pathologist-annotated tissue layer boundaries. We apply the combined method to 12 samples of oral squamous cell carcinomas (OSCC) data to gain a better understanding of the tumor microenvironment.

TITLE: Joint Vehicle Dispatching and Redeployment for Emergency Medical Services with Multi-Critic Reinforcement Learning

AUTHOR: Mendelsohn, David

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Wang, Guang

MEMBER (committee member): Li, Ang

MEMBER (committee member): Wu, Te-Yen

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Computer Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (58 pages)

ABSTRACT: With regard to Emergency Medical Services (EMS), the response time and consistency thatthey can provide care to in need patients is of the upmost importance. The key aspects of achieving this efficiency lies in how the EMS vehicles are dispatched to a patient from the currently available fleet and how they are then redistributed to best cover the area of care. This problem can be formulated as both a Markov-Decision Process and as a Multi-Agent Markov Game in which we can find some optimal policy to best assist those in needs. Previous works have approached this problem in both the combined sense (considering dispatching and redeployment as a single problem) or as two separate systems to optimize. Deep Reinforcement Learning (DRL) has been growing in popularity over the past half decade, and applications of these advances are still underutilized for this problem. While methods within the DRL family have been applied to this problem, they typically only consider the dispatching or redistribution sides independently, there has been a growing field of interest in applying one DRL policy to multiple tasks. Our approach is centered around improving the redeployment side of the problem but we will also be exploring the benefits of using a single policy to approach two aspects of a conjoined problem to improve the response time and consistency of these vital services.

TITLE: Conjugating Representations into Lie Subgroups

AUTHOR: Miller, Jared Tristan

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Ballas, Samuel A.

MEMBER (university representative): Vafek, Oskar

MEMBER (committee member): Bowers, Philip L., 1956-

MEMBER (committee member): Fenley, Sérgio Roberto

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mathematics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (115 pages)

ABSTRACT: Properties of the space of representations of a surface group into a given simple Liegroup is a very active area of research [11, 16, 18, 1, 7, 6, 15] and is particularly relevant to higher Teichmuller theory. For a closed surface, classical Teichmuller space is a connected component of the moduli space of representations into PSL(2, R) and [11] showed that the space of positive representations into PSL(k, R) coincides with the Hitchin component. In this dissertation we study representations of finitely generated groups into PGL(k, C) and determine necessary and sufficient conditions for such a representation to be conjugate into PGL(k, R). In this way, we identify representations in the larger representation variety which are conjugate in PGL(k, C) to a representation in hom (pi_1(S), PGL(k, R)) / PGL(k, R).

FILENAME: Ming_fsu_0071E_18361.pdf

TITLE: Publication Bias in Meta-Analysis of Survival Analyses

AUTHOR: Ming, Jielin

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Becker, Betsy Jane, 1956-

MEMBER (university representative): Huffer, Fred W. (Fred William)

MEMBER (committee member): Yang, Yanyun

MEMBER (committee member): Kuang, Huan

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Psychology and Learning Systems

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (125 pages)

ABSTRACT: My dissertation explores publication-bias detection methods for meta-analyses of survival analysis studies. I simulated individual-level survival data and created pseudo studies that were combined in meta-analyses. I analyzed the pseudo study data using both Cox and AFT models, then submitted the studies to meta-analysis. I examined 120 conditions describing features of the meta-analyses, each studied with 500 replications. I analyzed the simulated meta-analyses of survival data using eight methods including three tests based on the trim and fill method (using the L0, R0, and Q0 estimators), the Copas-model test, and four Egger's tests. I calculated the rejection rates of each test based on the 500 simulated meta-analyses and analyzed them via ANCOVA models. In the unbiased meta-analyses of AFT data, all tests showed type I error rates comparable to their alpha levels. In unbiased meta-analyses of Cox data, all tests except the Egger's test at the alpha level of .05 showed low type I error rates compared to their alpha levels. In the biased meta-analyses of Cox and AFT data, all tests showed low empirical power which indicated that these traditional meta-analysis detection methods cannot detect publication bias effectively.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Educational Psychology and Learning Systems in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): November 21, 2023.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

FILENAME: Moffatt_fsu_0071E_18393.pdf

TITLE: Why Not Luck?

AUTHOR: Moffatt, Andrew

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): May, Simon Căbulea

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Rawling, Piers

MEMBER (university representative): Kelsay, John, 1953-

MEMBER (committee member): Ruse, Michael

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Philosophy

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (377 pages)

ABSTRACT: This work examines the debate between the luck and relational egalitarians. The former, including authors like Dworkin, Cohen, Arneson, Tan, and Lippert-Rasmussen, are said to view equality as deriving from the nullification of certain types of bad luck, such as by equalizing access to resources, opportunity sets, or experienced well-being. Such accounts are said to be distributive in character, as they are concerned chiefly with the way some good is distributed in a population. The latter, including authors like Anderson, Scheffler, Scanlon, and Schemmel, argue that equality consists not in any sort of distribution, such as an equal distribution of bad luck, but instead in the nature of the social relationships we are enmeshed in. When these are relations of equality, when objectionable status hierarchies are not present and individuals are treated with respect and dignity, equality obtains. I argue, in support of philosophers such as Kok-Chor Tan and Kasper Lippert-Rasmussen, that the two views are not as distinct or incompatible as generally characterized by either side of the debate. Instead, I suggest that a pluralist account which incorporates elements of both is the better choice for our egalitarian purposes. I argue for this conclusion in large part utilizing the work of Richard Rorty, whose pragmatism easily accommodates and encourages the sort of pluralism on offer. Such an account is especially important given recent advances in economics involving our understanding of the structure and behavior of capitalist systems and how they impact the mere distribution of goods. Such distributive concerns as raised by Thomas Piketty are difficult to account for if our philosophies must be entirely non-distributive in their character. Given the importance of incorporating these insights, it stands to reason that merely distributive concerns will be a part of any viable egalitarian philosophy. Broadly speaking, this work sets as its goal the defense of such distributive approaches to egalitarian philosophy.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Philosophy in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): November 10, 2023.

NOTE (Keywords): Distributive, Egalitarianism, Equality, Luck, Pragmatism, Rorty

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

TITLE: Partially Hyperbolic Systems: Closed Periodic Curves and Closed Orbits

AUTHOR: Molina Gonzalez, Braulio

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Fenley, Sérgio Roberto

MEMBER (university representative): Reina, Laura

MEMBER (committee member): Heil, Wolfgang H.

MEMBER (committee member): Bowers, Philip L., 1956-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mathematics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (122 pages)

ABSTRACT: The present work is about partially hyperbolic dynamics on closed 3-manifolds and closed periodiccurves. Partially hyperbolic systems are dynamical systems characterized by a dominated splitting of their tangent bundle into directions of contraction, expansion and intermediate behavior. The prime candidates of study are Anosov flows and partially hyperbolic diffeomorphisms. In recent years, these systems have gained a lot of interest, mainly in dimension 3, where there is lot of machinery available. In the realm of Anosov flows, the orbit structure of these systems plays a major role in understanding their properties and even helping in their classification. For skewed R-covered Anosov flows whose weak stable foliation is transversely orientable, it was shown by Fenley [7] that any two distinct freely homotopic periodic orbits are always isotopic. We were interested in knowing whether this result was also true for non R-covered Anosov flows. Our first main result is to extend this result to a class of systems generalizing Anosov flows, called topological Anosov flows. This is theorem 34. In contrast with Anosov flows, partially hyperbolic diffeomorphisms may not exhibit a very desirable property called dynamical coherence. This property means that the center direction of the system integrates into a foliation. The first example of a non dynamically coherent partially hyperbolic diffeomorphism in dimension 3 was constructed by Hertz, Hertz, and Ures [37]. The existence of non differentiable points in curves along the center direction, is what makes the system not dynamically coherent. Quite commonly, important invariant sets of regularity no more than C 0 appear in the study of dynamical systems whose regularity is C 1 or better. Seeing as periodic orbits play an important role, we wonder whether a continuous embedded (possibly non differentiable) closed periodic curve, under a partially hyperbolic diffeomorphism could be "tangent" (see remark 11.2.1) to the center direction. We show this is indeed the case in our second main result, theorem 53.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 4, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Anosov flows, dynamical systems, partially hyperbolic diffeomorphisms

TITLE: Blockchain and Corporate Disclosure

AUTHOR: Moore, Alyssa B.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Pierce, Spencer

MEMBER (university representative): Harmeling, Colleen M

MEMBER (committee member): Mauler, Landon M.

MEMBER (committee member): Billings, Bruce K.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Business

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Accounting

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (63 pages)

ABSTRACT: Firms struggle to credibly communicate privately with other firms, which leads them to rely on public disclosure to share information. Although public disclosure alleviates the credibility concerns of private interfirm communication, it comes with proprietary costs. Recent advances in blockchain technology provide a potential solution that allows firms to communicate on a shared, immutable, and private ledger which mitigates credibility concerns and avoids the proprietary costs of public disclosure. Thus, blockchain technology may reduce firms' reliance on public disclosure to corroborate private interfirm communications. Using a difference-in-difference design, I find results consistent with this argument. Specifically, I find that managers, especially those of firms that likely bear greater proprietary costs of public disclosure, decrease their public disclosure following blockchain adoption. I find that this decrease in public disclosure has negative consequences, as it leads to greater analyst forecast errors. Collectively, my results suggest that although blockchain technology can improve private interfirm communication, it may have the unintended consequence of deteriorating the public information environment through reduced public disclosure.

TITLE: Self-Compassion as Resistance: Exploring the Benefits of Self-Compassion for Queer Couples

AUTHOR: Morris, Katherine Leigh

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Kimmes, Jonathan G. (Jonathan Gene)

MEMBER (university representative): McNulty, James

MEMBER (committee member): McWey, Lenore M.

MEMBER (committee member): Rudaz, Myriam

MEMBER (committee member): Reynolds, Jamila Evans

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Human Development and Family Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (87 pages)

ABSTRACT: Self-compassion can be understood as cultivating a gentle and understanding relationship with the self. The benefits of self-compassion for romantic relationships have been well-established in the literature. Additionally, the benefits of self-compassion for LGBTQ+ individuals has also been examined. However, no studies to date have examined the associations between self-compassion and relationship outcomes for queer couples. Furthermore, given the established connection between internalized stigma and relationship quality, it is important to consider how internalized stigma may affect this association as well. Therefore, a sample of 143 queer couples was recruited to complete an online survey that assessed demographic information, self-compassion, internalized stigma, both positive and negative relationship quality, queer consciousness, and self-esteem. The data was analyzed using an Actor-Partner Interdependence Mediation Model, or APIMeM, to identify the mediating role of internalized stigma on the actor and partner effects of self-compassion and relationship quality. Self-compassion was not found to mediate the relationship between internalized stigma and relationship quality. The decision was made, then, to explore internalized stigma as a mediator between self-compassion and relationship quality, which yielded significant indirect effects, thus supporting the idea that internalized stigma helps to explain the relationship between self-compassion and relationship quality for queer couples. Additionally, self-esteem was added as a covariate, which resulted in self-compassion no longer having any significant direct or indirect associations with any of the study variables. The clinical implications of this study highlight the importance of addressing internalized stigma in queer couples who are hoping to increase relationship quality. One such way of addressing internalized stigma may be self-compassion interventions. Future directions and additional clinical implications are discussed.

TITLE: High-Achieving Teenage Students' Use of Social Media and Technology to Complete Advanced Placement Coursework

AUTHOR: Morris, Vonda H.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Staudt Willet, K. Bret

MEMBER (university representative): Myers, John P. (John Patrick)

MEMBER (committee member): Ke, Fengfeng

MEMBER (committee member): Klein, James D.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Program in Instructional Systems and Learning Technologies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (108 pages)

ABSTRACT: High-achieving teenage students (HATS) take Advanced Placement (AP) courses to fulfill two goals: boost their grade point average (GPA) and maintain or increase their class rank. To assist in accomplishing these goals, HATS access social media (SM) and technology. Smart devices, laptops, and tablets provide easy access for HATS to build social communities where exchanging knowledge, sharing opinions, and communicating messages are related to AP. Therefore, continual access to social media communities serves as a gateway for HATS to participate in academic dishonesty (AD), which can adversely affect their performance on the AP exam but ultimately challenge the traditional models of teaching and learning. This exploratory qualitative study examines the social, behavioral, and technological worlds of HATS' participation in AP courses. Twenty-one participants shared their perspectives through focus group interviews to answer why and how social media was used to complete AP coursework. Interview transcripts were coded using Atlas.ti, and these codes, along with prior research, revealed three themes for each research question: 1. Why HATS use SM emerged into the themes of personalized learning structures, time management, and building social media communities. 2. How HATS used SM resulted in developing learning strategies, fact-checking, and AD. 3. HATS's reactions to AD included various emotions, the depths of AD considered through "morally gray" lenses, and the justifications given to rationalize AD acts. The results reveal a need to redesign our current teaching and learning models rather than trying to catch HATS' engaging in AD behaviors.

FILENAME: Morrison_fsu_0071E_18685.pdf

TITLE: Collegiate Class Piano in the Western Hemisphere: An Investigation of Collegiate Class Piano Courses in North and South America

AUTHOR: Morrison, Melody

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Dumlavwalla, Diana Teresa

MEMBER (university representative): Williams, Heidi Louise

MEMBER (committee member): Springer, D. Gregory (Douglas Gregory)

MEMBER (committee member): VanWeelden, Kimberly D.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (222 pages)

ABSTRACT: Collegiate class piano for music majors has grown substantially since its beginnings in the mid-twentieth century and has been developed by music teachers and organizations. Research on collegiate group piano has increased in the past forty years, and literature on teaching strategies, professional development, technology, and perceptions of students is available. Presently, there have not been any post-pandemic studies which have collected instructor perceptions on collegiate group piano. Additionally, there is limited literature focusing on collegiate class piano outside the United States. The purpose of the study was to investigate the status of group piano instruction as well as instructor perceptions in universities throughout North and South America through a mixed methods investigation. To accomplish this goal, the researcher collected data from class piano instructors in universities across eight different countries within the Western Hemisphere. The questionnaire developed by the researcher served as the survey instrument for this investigation. The researcher used the data collected to analyze the program structure of collegiate group piano classes, investigate the materials, resources, and equipment used by instructors, as well as collect information about instructors' educational backgrounds and group piano training. The researcher sent emails to a total of 40 universities across North, Central, and South America, and received replies from 20 universities. The number of participants for the present study was 28. Results from the questionnaire indicated that piano performance (36%) was the participating instructors' most common musical concentration during their training. Other areas were reported as well such as piano pedagogy, theory/composition, collaborative piano, music education, musicology/ethnomusicology, conducting, and jazz. Out of all instructors, a slight majority (54%) had not received training specifically in group piano pedagogy. Data from the questionnaire revealed that the typical number of sequential semesters of class piano offered at universities was 3.55, with music theatre (M = 3.5, SD = 1.91) and theory/composition majors (M = 3.29, SD = 1.07) being required to take the most semesters. Weekly contact hours were reported to be slightly below 2 hours (M = 1.93, SD = 0.73). The textbook most frequently chosen from the questionnaire's list for classroom use was Alfred's Group Piano for Adults (43%), however several instructors from South America gave titles of the books and materials that they use in their classes which gave deeper insight into the curriculum used in other countries. Names of smart device applications and websites were also shared. Of the digital tools listed in the questionnaire, the most used item across all participating countries (30%) was YouTube. The questionnaire also revealed significant differences in some perceptions between North and South America. When instructors were asked to rank their students' attitudes toward the university class piano requirement, North American instructors' rankings (M = 3.4, SD = .83) were lower than South America instructors' rankings (M = 3.92, SD = .52). Another significant difference found between the two continents was that when asked to rank the importance of 11 skills commonly learned in class piano, South American respondents overwhelmingly rated chord progressions very highly (M = 4.7, SD = .4) whereas North American responses exhibited greater variability and an overall lower ranking (M = 4, SD = 1.13). The reason for this disparity is likely due to the manner in which chord progressions and accompaniment styles are taught in South American countries. Near the end of the questionnaire, instructors also shared their thoughts on the possibility of a national standard for university class piano in their countries. Those who were not in favor of a standardized curriculum mentioned that it is important to keep class content flexible, and respondents who were in favor of a national standard stated that it would be useful for more uniformity across institutions. According to the results from the research questionnaire, the researcher recommends that more rote teaching be implemented into North American class piano instruction to enhance the student learning experience. The researcher also proposes that while a standardized curriculum may not be necessary, more national guidelines can ensure consistency across universities to give students a strong foundation of piano fundamentals on which they can build upon if specialized skills are desired in the future. Finally, the researcher suggests embracing a more global perspective on piano pedagogy, and that instructors worldwide engage in increased international dialogue to foster sharing of repertoire, learning new pedagogical strategies, and nurturing mutual growth.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the College of Music in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 25, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Collegiate Class Piano, Globalization, Group Piano, North America, Piano Pedagogy, South America

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

TITLE: Learning Data-Driven Graphs with Graph Neural Networks for the Classification and Prediction of Alzheimer's Disease

AUTHOR: Mueller, Kevin

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Erlebacher, Gordon, 1957-

MEMBER (university representative): She, Yiyuan

MEMBER (committee member): Shanbhag, Sachin

MEMBER (committee member): Meyer-Bäse, Anke

MEMBER (committee member): Wang, Xiaoqiang

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Scientific Computing

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (135 pages)

ABSTRACT: To this day, the origins and prognosis of Alzheimer's disease (AD) pose significant challenges. This thesis presents a methodology to understand AD by systematically applying state-of-the-art techniques from graph neural networks (GNNs) to medical images, producing a set of individualized graphs suitable for analysis. We accomplish this task by defining a latent graph variable as an intermediate latent variable inferred in a machine learning task. As one of the first researchers to explore the use of GNNs with medical images, this thesis begins with simple machine learning tasks that gradually increase in complexity. In particular, the thesis is organized into the following four main parts: (1) establishing a baseline with standard attention-based models applied to gray matter and PET probability regions of interest (ROIs), (2) developing a 3D-CNN model for processing voxel images directly to infer a latent graph more interpretable and closely aligned to known forms of connectivity within the brain, (3) learning latent graphs for a challenging network diffusion task with synthetic and real longitudinal datasets, (4) and developing a pipeline based on statistical analysis and metrics for comparing the learned latent graphs to baseline graphs derived from standard methods to assess the performance of the latent graphs. Our experiments show that the careful application of GNNs to medical images can provide a suitable inductive bias to enhance performance compared to standard baselines such as support vector machines and multilayer perceptrons. The latent graph connectivity structure learned from our new 3D-CNN-GNN model alone is significant enough to achieve state-of-the-art precision when differentiating between patients with mild cognitive impairment (MCI) who will progress to AD and those who will maintain an MCI diagnosis, providing a set of interpretable features to uncover the mysteries surrounding AD.

TITLE: Written in the Margins: Forgotten Art Songs of the Romantic Era Transcribed for Horn

AUTHOR: Nay, Brianna M.

MEMBER (professor directing treatise): Stebleton, Michelle

MEMBER (university representative): Brewer, Charles E. (Charles Everett)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (69 pages)

ABSTRACT: Throughout the course of history, women have often been relegated to the margins ofsociety. The cultural and societal expectations kept them on the sidelines and in the footnotes of history books. Historically, women were not allowed to be composers or performers of music, especially of brass instruments until the twentieth-century. This has left a gap in the repertoire of women-composed music before the 1900s. During the nineteenth-century, many women composers produced quality music within the boundaries that society set upon them—music for voice, piano, or sometimes stringed instruments. Unfortunately, compositions for brass instruments such as French horn were seen as a masculine endeavor and most women composers avoided composing for them until the twentieth- and twenty-first- centuries. This document features six compositions by Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel, Clara Schumann, and Josephine Lang transcribed and arranged for French horn. The compositions include Fanny Mendelssohn Hensel's Schwanenlied from 6 Lieder, op. 1 and Abendbild from 5 Lieder, op. 10; Clara Weick Schumann's Liebst du um Schönheit from Op. 12 No. 14 and Warum Willst du And're Frangen; and Josephine Lang's Wenn zwei Voneinander Scheiden and Wie glänzt so hell.

TITLE: The Economics of Effective Punishment

AUTHOR: Ndum, Rodney

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Dougal, Casey

MEMBER (university representative): Mauler, Landon M.

MEMBER (committee member): Hutton, Irena

MEMBER (committee member): Cheng, Yingmei

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Business

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Finance

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (64 pages)

ABSTRACT: First we show that, since 2000 the U.S. federal government has imposed over $600 billion in penalties and spent over $5 billion in preventing fraud. Yet 87% of firms re-offend, which raises the question, is punishment effective? We analyze the effectiveness of federal monetary sanctions using U.S. courts' five criminal law rationales for punishment: retribution, specific deterrence, general deterrence, incapacitation, and rehabilitation. We show that punishment has the largest effects on retribution and rehabilitation. We measure that a $1,000,000 increase in annual sanctions is associated with 3% decrease in firm value, as measured by Tobin's Q, and a 57% improvement in Li et.al(2020) strong culture , which we use as a proxy for firm culture. We find substantial evidence that punishment effectiveness is aggravated by firm reputation, governance, and political connectedness. Next, we investigate the impact of government subsidies on corporate financial strategies, focusing on payout policies, debt reduction, and asset management. Utilizing a comprehensive dataset and employing methods to address endogeneity, we provide evidence that firms significantly alter their financial behaviors following the receipt of government subsidies. Specifically, we find evidence that firms increase payouts to shareholders, predominantly through share repurchases, after receiving subsidies. This behavior underscores a preference for returning value to shareholders when external financing conditions are favorable. We further observe a shift towards debt reduction, indicating a concerted effort to optimize capital structure and reduce financial risk. Contrary to initial hypotheses, the anticipated increase in asset investments is not sustained when endogeneity concerns are addressed, suggesting that the immediate response to subsidies does not translate into long-term asset growth. Further, our analysis identifies distinct shifts in firm behavior in theaftermath of significant economic events, during the dot-com bubble burst and the 2007 financial crisis. These periods reflect a change in how firms allocate subsidized resources, highlighting the influence of economic context on corporate financial decisions. This paper notes that while firms react strongly to both negative and positive shocks from the government, the reaction by firms to negative government shocks are broader.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Finance in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 1, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Asset Pricing, Corporate Finance, Fraud, Law and Finance, Punishment, Trust

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (80 pages)

ABSTRACT: This paper explores modern Bosniak, Serbian, and Bulgarian oral-traditional epic, three closely related Balkan cultures and traditions linked through cross-border exchange and commonality of experience within the Ottoman ecumene. The dominant gender code for men in these borderland societies of the early modern Balkans was epic masculinity, as illustrated in heroic songs (BCS junacke pjesme and Bulgarian junaški pesni.) Through my reading of these heroic songs, I identify a perplexing, submerged theme—feminine roles that scold, censure, and punish failures in epic masculinity. I argue that, ultimately, these expressions of scolding, mocking, vulgarity, and curses serve as a mechanism to maintain and reinforce epic masculinity. Moreover, this study proposes that this function may be an extension of women's child rearing role. Through examination of these female roles and their expressions in heroic epic and non-heroic epic, this study seeks to recover aspects of epic femininity in oral-traditional narrative song and hypothesize as to women's gender roles in their heroic Slavic borderland communities of the Balkans.

FILENAME: Newby_fsu_0071E_18234.pdf

TITLE: Changes in Ocean Redox over Earth's History: Developing and Utilizing Paleoredox Proxies and Constraining Oxygen Budgets

AUTHOR: Newby, Sean M.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Owens, Jeremy D.

MEMBER (university representative): Wulff, Janie L.

MEMBER (committee member): Young, Seth A.

MEMBER (committee member): Knapp, Angela Noel, 1976-

MEMBER (committee member): Salters, Vincent J. M.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (171 pages)

ABSTRACT: The Phanerozoic is typically known as an interval in which complex life has developed and thrived. However, there are multiple instances throughout this era in which climatic shifts and extinctions have made it difficult for the development of life. One of the most notable factors affecting marine biota throughout the Phanerozoic is the presence (or lack thereof) of oxygen; thus, better constraining the redox conditions of the ocean is vital during intervals of rapid change. One means to do this is through the development and improvement of novel and useful redox proxies, such as thallium (Tl) isotopes. Using marine sediments off the coasts of California, Mexico, and Peru, various low oxygen conditions were analyzed for Tl isotopes to expand settings known to record seawater values. This work expanded previous studies that failed to look into more suboxic settings and showed that the most accurate seawater records can be found in anoxic environments with elevated sulfide content in pore waters, with other less reducing conditions showing a range of values between seawater and sources. Applying this proxy to the end-Permian mass event (EPME), there are notable shifts in Tl isotopes. Not only was there a visible change towards more anoxic conditions earlier than other proxies can determine, but there was also a sudden rapid negative excursion that indicated short-term oxygenation at the onset of the extinction interval, contributing to the massive loss of life through rapid redox fluctuations. Continuing this work to the next minor extinction event chronologically, the Smithian-Spathian extinction provides a persistence of the low-oxygen conditions that was present at the very beginning of the Triassic following the EPME as well as transient redox fluctuations at the extinction interval. Lastly, to better constrain these anoxic events, a model of oxygen across Oceanic Anoxic Event 2 and the Toarcian Oceanic Anoxic Event was applied. Using these well-studied events, a model comparing excessive oxygen production from burial of organic carbon and pyrite sulfur to large igneous province erupted reductants was created, the results of which showed a large influx of reductants is capable of balancing much of the excess oxygen that should be produced during anoxic events. All of these projects show the importance of redox to understanding the development of Earth's systems, which in turn affected the development of life on the planet throughout the Phanerozoic.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Sciences in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): July 27, 2023.

NOTE (Keywords): end-Permian mass extinction, large igneous provinces, oceanic anoxic events, Smithian-Spathian boundary, thallium isotopes, trace metal concentrations

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Jeremy D. Owens, Professor Directing Dissertation; Jeannette L. Wulff, University Representative; Seth A. Young, Committee Member; Angela N. Knapp, Committee Member; Vincent Salters, Committee Member.

TITLE: A System of Systems Framework for Data Analytics in the Built Environment: A Case Study of Florida Transportation System

AUTHOR: Nickdoost, Navid

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Choi, Juyeong

MEMBER (university representative): Vanli, Omer Arda

MEMBER (committee member): AbdelRazig, Yassir

MEMBER (committee member): Sobanjo, John Olusegun, 1958-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (227 pages)

ABSTRACT: Infrastructure systems are the backbone of modern civilization, supporting our cities, economies, and way of life. Yet, they do not exist in isolation. They are continually influenced by a multitude of external social, economic, and environmental factors. These impacts may affect the structure of the built environment over time (i.e., through the evolutionary process) or the interplays between and within subsystems, thus causing emergent behaviors. In anticipation of the immense complexity of the built environment and the diversity of the influential factors, the major research challenge is finding an approach that yields engineering solutions to understand how, when, and why the evolutionary and emergent behavior of a system occurs. Answering such questions is the first step toward developing adaptive, preventive, or corrective plans and programs to enhance infrastructure resilience to external dynamics. This research proposes a framework to facilitate understanding the impact mechanisms of the external factors causing infrastructure evolution. Such knowledge is necessary to determine how a behavior evolves throughout a system. Given the diversity of the factors affecting the infrastructure system, an overwhelming amount of information needs to be continuously monitored and analyzed to comprehend the changing nature of the built environment. To address these challenges, the proposed framework uses multivariate analysis methods to identify and detect the most influential external factors driving the behaviors of the built environment system of systems. Dynamic factor models are developed to construct a composite index framework that (1) monitors and analyzes large volumes of information from numerous external factors impacting the system, (2) detects changes in the trends of the influential factors, and identifies how these changes originated within the system, and (3) analyzes how the internal system dynamics are influenced by external impacts.

TITLE: Shaping Stones: A 3D Geometric Morphometric Evaluation of Late Pleistocene and Early Holocene Adzes from Northwest Florida

AUTHOR: Noah, Olivia L.

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Mehta, Jayur M. (Madhusudan)

MEMBER (committee member): Halligan, Jessi J.

MEMBER (committee member): Marrinan, Rochelle A.

MEMBER (committee member): Patrangenaru, Victor

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Anthropology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (108 pages)

ABSTRACT: The purpose of this research project is to provide insight into 3D GM methods in regard to lithic artifact research and provide data that allows a better understanding of the variables that affect a 3D GM study and the importance of the third dimension when investigating adzes. Geometric Morphometrics (GM) quantifies the shape variation of objects while controlling for variables such as scale, size, translation, and rotation then utilizes multivariate statistics to identify trends in the data. GM maintains the shape of an object more than traditional linear measurements so that morphological comparisons can be more comprehensive than traditional linear measurements. Most of the archaeological studies that utilize GM in American archaeology focus on skeletal remains and bifacial lithic points. While 3D GM analyses of skeletal remains are often employed, the lithic analyses have largely been restricted to 2D analyses for reasons that will be covered in this thesis. Because there are not many 3D studies on lithic tools, a portion of this research will be dedicated to refining 3D GM digitization and model construction of thick lithic tools in an effort to help standardize 3D GM analysis so that the comparisons of different research projects are more robust and error introduction is better understood. The results of this analysis provided ways to increase the efficiency of 3D GM studies and indicated that the third dimension accounted for a majority of the variation present in adze morphology, suggesting that a 2D analysis would be insufficient to understand the morphological trends found within this tool type. These methods were also used to analyze a sample of adzes from three different sites as well as an assemblage with unknown provenience. When adze morphology was compared to the site locations, regional trends were able to be identified.

TITLE: ADHD Behaviors and Response to Reading Instruction

AUTHOR: Norris, Cynthia U.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Hart, Sara, (Professor of Psychology)

MEMBER (university representative): Terry, Nicole Patton

MEMBER (committee member): Wagner, Richard K.

MEMBER (committee member): Ganley, Colleen M.

MEMBER (committee member): Hammock, Elizabeth Anne Dunn

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Psychology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (63 pages)

ABSTRACT: ADHD is a behavioral cognitive correlate of achievement associated with lower reading performance. The externalizing and internalizing symptoms that characterize ADHD behaviors negatively impact the engagement of students experiencing reading difficulties and the ability to regulate attention and behavior during the reading acquisition process. There is also considerable comorbidity between ADHD and reading-related learning disabilities driven by genetic and environmental pathways. This poses challenges for interventions (i.e., an environmental factor) containing reading instruction designed to improve the reading performance of children who may be exhibiting ADHD behaviors. This study examined the associations between ADHD behaviors and response to reading instruction, using a diverse sample of at-risk kindergarten and first-grade children (N = 715) across 67 classrooms who participated in a randomized control trial evaluating the Individualized Student Instruction (ISI) reading intervention. A structural equation modeling approach assessed teacher-rated ADHD behaviors predicting response to instruction across several teacher-implemented instructional reading approaches (ISI vs. BAU). Qualitative differences in the associations based on the operationalization of ADHD behaviors (i.e., inattention, hyperactivity-impulsivity, and combined) were examined. Exploratory analyses were performed to examine whether the association between ADHD behaviors and children's response to reading instruction significantly differed by instructional group. Several subscales of the SWAN Rating scale measured ADHD behaviors. Response to instruction was based on residual gain scores in reading-related skills measured as a composite of decoding and expressive vocabulary skills from subtests of the Woodcock-Johnson III Tests of Achievement. A statistically significant negative relation was found between the ADHD behaviors and response to instruction. Higher teacher-rated ADHD behaviors predicted lower SDs in response to reading instruction. Qualitatively, the combined ADHD behaviors produced the strongest association and explained the most variance than the other ADHD behaviors. Exploratory analyses suggested that there were significant instructional group differences for inattention and hyperactivity-impulsivity but not the combined ADHD behaviors. The multiple-group models favored the ISI group. ADHD behaviors and response to instruction were more strongly related to lower responsiveness to instruction in the BAU group compared to ISI. This study highlights the role of distinct ADHD behaviors in early reading-related skills in response to reading instruction. These preliminary analyses have implications for classroom-based reading instructional practices and empirically replicating evidence to understand the influence of ADHD behaviors on efforts to remediate poor reading in children.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Psychology in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Developmental Psychology.

FILENAME: Nthiga_fsu_0071N_18563.pdf

TITLE: Exploring Forest Change Dynamics: A Synthesis of Most Commonly Identified Drivers Influencing Tropical Forest Cover Change

AUTHOR: Nthiga, Nancy

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Pau, Stephanie

MEMBER (committee member): Billo, Emily

MEMBER (committee member): Uejio, Christopher K.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Social Sciences and Public Policy

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Geography

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (55 pages)

ABSTRACT: The destruction of vast tropical forests poses a threat to both globally significant biodiversity and carbon storage. Tropical deforestation and degradation are complex phenomena driven by a combination of proximate causes, such as agricultural expansion, wood extraction, infrastructure development, and biophysical conditions, as well as broader underlying drivers, including economic, demographic, technological, and cultural factors. Here we present a comprehensive synthesis of case-based studies (n = 199) that identified proximate causes and/or underlying drivers of tropical deforestation or degradation, and quantified forest cover loss. Latin America emerged as the most frequently studied region, accounting for 42.2% of all cases. Agriculture stood out as the most commonly identified proximate cause of deforestation across all regions, constituting 84.9% of cases and was frequently identified in conjunction with other proximate causes. While recent research has emphasized the role of agricultural expansion as a prominent contributor to tropical forest cover change, we show that agricultural expansion rarely occurs in isolation. Biophysical factors, such as droughts, wildfires, and pest outbreaks, also played a significant role in forest cover loss in all regions. Rates of forest cover loss associated with different proximate causes did not appear to differ. We further examined the ability of common satellite vegetation indices of "greenness", the Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI) and the Enhanced Vegetation Index (EVI), to capture changes in tropical deforestation or degradation after forest cover loss was detected in primary studies. We found that these indices failed to show reduced greenness after forest cover loss was identified. In some cases, these indices showed increased greenness, presumably owing to conversion to intensive commercial agriculture. It appears that only in cases of complete vegetation loss from infrastructure projects such as forest conversion to roads or buildings, did NDVI and EVI decrease after forest cover loss was detected. Our results suggest that strategies for the prevention and mitigation of tropical forest cover loss should not only consider the role of agricultural expansion but also how agriculture interacts with other proximate causes. Furthermore, the vulnerability of these forests to environmental stressors is important to consider given the prominent role of biophysical factors in forest cover loss. Lastly, although NDVI and EVI are widely used in large-scale analysis of vegetation change, they appear to capture only the near-complete loss of vegetation and may be insufficient to detect other ecological impacts of tropical forest cover change.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the Department of Geography in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 4, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Agriculture, Climate Change, Forest Loss, Land-use land cover change, Tropical Deforestation, Tropical forest degradation.

TITLE: Photophysical Properties of Fluorescent Triazoles and Their Photochemical Conversion into Indoles

AUTHOR: Nusser, Brandon

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Zhu, Lei, 1978-

MEMBER (university representative): Chanton, Jeffrey P.

MEMBER (committee member): Smith, Joel

MEMBER (committee member): Hanson, Kenneth G.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (338 pages)

ABSTRACT: The photophysical and photochemical properties and the photoconversion scope and mechanism of di- and triaryl-substituted-1,2,3-triazoles are reported in this work. The ease of synthesis of regioisomers of substituted triazoles enables a systematic study on the correlation between regiochemistry and excited state properties, which include the solvent dependence of fluorescence, energy gap between singlet and triplet emitters, and propensity to photon-triggered transformations. Triazoles that carry electron (e)-donor and e-acceptor aryl substituents show high fluorescence quantum yields in weakly polar solvents and exhibit solvent-dependent fluorescence. The luminescence properties of these compounds in glass matrices at 77 K and the thermal and photo-stability of these compounds are determined. The position of the e-donor substituent has a significant impact on the fluorescence emission energy and solvent sensitivity, singlet-triplet energy gap, and photochemical reactivity and stability. Quantum chemical calculations were used to explain the experimental observations on the structural correlation with the photophysical and photochemical properties. The photochemical reactivity in the triazole conversion to indole was leveraged to study the reaction mechanism and intermediates (carbene and azirine). A new method for the synthesis of 5-cyanotriazoles was developed to expand the scope of the photoconversion of triazoles into indoles.
