TITLE: The Use of Tabletop Role-Playing Games as Adaptive Leadership Pedagogy in a Simulated Classroom Environment

AUTHOR: Ruiz-Ezquerro, Antonio

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Guthrie, Kathy L.

MEMBER (university representative): Ke, Fengfeng

MEMBER (committee member): Khurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (committee member): Kurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (committee member): Beatty, Cameron C.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (193 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation observed and analyzed the experiences of five higher education students participating in a modified tabletop role-playing game (TRPG) intentionally modified for teaching adaptive leadership concepts. The study observed participants' capacity to learn the adaptive leadership concepts taught throughout the game and the ways in which participants exhibited such learning. Further, it inquired about the influence of participants' experiences with the game on their ability to identify adaptive leadership concepts outside the game.The study followed a qualitative exploratory single-case study approach. The combination of teaching strategies selected in the study aimed to construct a case that simulates what using a TRPG as a leadership pedagogical tool in a leadership undergraduate course could look like. The participants' campaign and their interactions served as the case being observed. Data collection consisted of the recorded gameplay sessions, post-game debrief sessions, rubrics recording participants meeting the game's learning objectives, analytical memos collected throughout the study, participant interviews, written reflections, and in-game assessments. The findings suggest that TRPGs can serve as adaptive leadership pedagogical tools as long as they are supported by other leadership teaching strategies, essentially acting as a space where learners can engage with the educational content and experience applying it. The study also suggests that the type of learning participants experienced was cognitive rather than embodied and that game elements such as engaging nature, co-constructed narrative, NPC interactions, guided reflection, and in-game assessments were crucial in fostering participant interaction with the game's adaptive leadership concepts. Overall, this study provides valuable insights into the potential of role-playing games as instructional tools in a traditional educational setting.

TITLE: Music Therapists Perceptions of Working with Deaf and Hard of Hearing Children

AUTHOR: Sabat, Adrianna

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Gooding, Lori F. (Lori Fogus)

MEMBER (committee member): VanWeelden, Kimberly D.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (47 pages)

ABSTRACT: Children with hearing loss have a higher risk of not developing crucial language and communication skills without the support of early intervention services. Language development is crucial for early childhood education, cognitive and socio-emotional development. This is due to the lack of access to communicative skills and exchanges and other surrounding factors. Early intervention services include music therapy. Music therapists must have a general knowledge of working with children with hearing loss, utilize hearing loss devices, and Deaf children. The purpose of the current study was to explore board certified music therapists' perceptions of willingness, comfort, and preparedness of working with children with various levels of hearing loss and within the Deaf community. The participants answered their perceptions of (1) general benefit of music therapy, (2) preparedness from training, (3) comfort adapting music therapy, and (4) willingness to provide music therapy. The participants (N= 47) were first cycle board certified music therapists that are currently working in the Southeast region. The results revealed that the participants had overall higher perceptions of their willingness to provide services and had overall lower perceptions of their preparedness from training. Additionally, the results revealed that music therapists had higher perceptions of working with children with lower degrees of hearing loss and children with hearing loss devices. Further results and analysis are discussed within the paper.

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (102 pages)

ABSTRACT: Mexican Americans have been native to the United States for centuries, but their educational attainment numbers reflect an achievement gap. This has led to increased poverty levels, low social capital, and low quality of benefits. One way to increase social mobility for a racial group is by increasing the number of bachelor's degree holders. Because high school lays the foundation for postsecondary attainment, it is important to study college access in high school to understand how students experience and interact with this information in preparation for applying to college. This qualitative case study looked at the student experience through data collected via open ended interviews. Data was analyzed using the Psychosociocultural Theory to account for the psychological, social, and cultural barriers that are unique to the Mexican American student population. A purposeful sample recruited from Valley High School included five female students who were in the 11-25% of their class rank, first-generation to go to college, and Mexican American. The findings showed that the majority of the collected data indicated the psychological and social realms. Notably, the cultural realm did not contain substantial data. A total of seven themes were found ranging from their interactions with their peers to the value of sibling experiences. Implications for this study were gender related help-seeking behaviors for males and traditional culture roles for females. This study adds to the literature surrounding Mexican American students and their persistence to postsecondary education and shines a spotlight on the need to include student voices when creating college readiness programming in high school.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (48 pages)

ABSTRACT: Transcribing and arranging has become a popular way for musicians to expand and explore a wider range of repertoire than is available on one's own instrument. Viola virtuosi, such as Lionel Tertis and William Primrose, paved the way for transcribing works that would have been otherwise unthinkable for a violist at the time. One does not, however, need to be a virtuoso in order to transcribe music for one's instrument. Today, free music notation software, along with many other resources, makes creating transcriptions achievable for any performer. The purpose of this treatise is to provide an overview of the transcription process from a performer's perspective, so that others may it use as a guide for their personal use when transcribing music for the viola. The chapters give a brief overview of performers who created transcriptions, criteria for choosing music to transcribe, methodologies for transcribing music for the viola, and performance practices.

FILENAME: Sanders_fsu_0071E_18691.pdf

TITLE: Understanding Attitudes and Preferences Regarding Technology to Support Prospective Memory among Older Adults with Subjective Cognitive Impairment

AUTHOR: Sanders, Edie C.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Kaschak, Michael P.

MEMBER (university representative): Carr, Dawn C.

MEMBER (committee member): Charness, Neil

MEMBER (committee member): Kofler, Michael J.

MEMBER (committee member): Martin, Christopher Basil

MEMBER (committee member): Boot, Walter Richard

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Psychology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (82 pages)

ABSTRACT: Prospective memory (PM), the ability to remember to execute an intention in the future, is critical for the performance of everyday tasks important for independence and quality of life. PM failures are associated with negative health, financial, and social outcomes, and are more frequent with increased age and can be even greater for older adults with a cognitive impairment such as subjective cognitive decline (SCD). Technology holds promise for providing everyday PM support for older adults with cognitive impairment, but little is known regarding their attitudes and preferences toward technology-based PM support. The present work utilized an online survey and focus groups to examine the attitudes of older adults with SCD toward technologies to support PM. 188 older adults with SCD and 190 older adults without SCD completed an online survey and answered questions about a variety of technologies to support PM in different activity areas. A separate sample of 24 older adults with SCD participated in online focus groups and were probed about their perception of the use of technology devices for supporting PM, benefits they feel they might derive from these devices, and potential costs or barriers to using them. Results show that the attitudes of older adults with SCD 1) differed based on the type of device and the type of activity the technology is meant to support, 2) were more positive than those of older adults without SCD, and 3) were associated with individual difference factors such as attitudes toward technology in general, technology proficiency, frequency of memory failures, health, and age. Results suggest that older adults with SCD might prefer using mobile apps relative to other devices and technology to support healthcare relative to other activities. Older adults with SCD also showed privacy concerns related to voice-activated assistants and using technology to manage finances. Results indicate that older adults with SCD may be a promising population to target using technology-based solutions, and the type of device and type of activity being supported are important to consider in the development of technology solutions to enhance independence and well-being.

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 4, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Aging, Attitudes, Cognitive Impairment, Prospective Memory, Technology

TITLE: Integrating Research into Conservation: Using Satellite Telemetry and Population Monitoring to Inform the Management of Hawksbill Turtles in Brazil

AUTHOR: Santos, Armando Jose Barsante

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Fuentes, Mariana

MEMBER (university representative): Burgess, Scott C.

MEMBER (committee member): Ceriani, Simona A.

MEMBER (committee member): Grubbs, R. Dean

MEMBER (committee member): Huettel, Markus

MEMBER (committee member): MacDonald, Ian R. (Ian Rosman)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (186 pages)

ABSTRACT: Marine ecosystems are increasingly threatened by human activities, highlighting the urgent need for effective conservation strategies. This dissertation focuses on the hawksbill turtle (Eretmochelys imbricata) in Brazil as a case study to enhance marine conservation efforts. Recognized as keystone species for their ecological significance and classified as Critically Endangered by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), the charismatic flagship species, hawksbill turtle, serve as sentinel, important indicator for the health of marine biodiversity. Utilizing satellite telemetry and population monitoring, key demographic parameters and spatial ecology of nesting hawksbill turtles were investigated. The utilization distribution by tracked turtles overlapped with Marine Protected Areas (MPAs) and the potential threats, offered insights into broader marine conservation strategies. The second chapter advances our understanding of marine turtle population dynamics by refining the accuracy of demographic parameter estimates, specifically clutch frequency, which is pivotal for assessing marine turtle populations. Such parameter is broadly used to estimate number of individual nesting females based on the total number of nests, which often times is the only information available. In addition, this chapter demonstrate the significant impact of the presence of transient turtles on these estimates and are informative for study designs that aim estimate total number of nesting females within a season or for the population at large. The third chapter breaks down their nesting, foraging, and migratory behaviors to inform conservation management. A significant contribution of this work is the identification of key migratory corridors and foraging areas, particularly for the subpopulation from Rio Grande do Norte, Brazil, highlighting the need for spatially explicit conservation goals and targets. The effectiveness of Brazil's coastal MPAs in protecting the vital habitats for nesting hawksbill turtles was assessed. The findings reveal mismatches in the current MPA network, leading to recommendations for strategic MPA expansion and management, emphasizing ecological-scale approaches over political boundaries to accommodate the species' extensive migratory patterns. The research advocates for MPAs to not only cover high-use areas identified through telemetry but also to implement protection levels tailored to the hawksbill turtles' specific needs. Furthermore, the fourth chapter provides a nuanced understanding of hawksbill turtle internesting behavior, using a novel approach to discretize hidden behaviors during this critical period. Besides evidencing high fidelity to nesting beaches and residence areas, mapping the behaviors provided essential insights into their vulnerability to specific threats, including vessel strikes and accidental capture in fishing gear. It proposes evidence-based strategies to enhance MPA effectiveness, integrating technological advancements with conservation biology to inform policy and management decisions. The study's findings underscore the importance of adaptive management strategies, responsive to the evolving understanding of hawksbill turtle ecology. Beyond hawksbill turtles, the research offers a framework for applying similar conservation strategies to other marine species, underlining the potential for species-specific efforts to catalyze broader and effective environmental management and conservation. The dissertation calls for continued research and adaptive management in response to the dynamic nature of marine ecosystems and emerging threats, highlighting the role of science in effective conservation policies.

NOTE (Keywords): Adaptive management, Behavioral Ecology, Conservation Policy, Conservation strategies, Demographic analysis, Marine spatial planning

TITLE: Theory and Evaluation of Undergraduate Stem Education Interventions

AUTHOR: Šaras, Emily Daina

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Reynolds, John K.

MEMBER (university representative): Perez-Felkner, Lara

MEMBER (committee member): Barrett, Anne E., 1971-

MEMBER (committee member): Buggs, Shantel

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Social Sciences and Public Policy

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Sociology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (213 pages)

ABSTRACT: The United States higher education system has developed strategies to prepare students for Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math (STEM) careers as the STEM labor market expands. One set of educational interventions, known as STEM Intervention Programs (SIPs), employs extracurricular activities to engage and retain STEM major students. These SIPs often target underrepresented racial-ethnic minority (URM) students, low-income students, and women to reduce social disparities in STEM education. However, studies assessing the effectiveness of SIPs in improving STEM retention, graduation, and career outcomes have produced inconsistent results. Another area of racial-ethnic inequality in STEM education is the faculty roster, particularly in terms of representation, hiring, and promotion practices. Increasing the number of URM STEM faculty members addresses two main issues: equitable representation and providing URM STEM students with race-matched instruction, mentorship, and role models. Extracurricular SIPs and Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion (DEI) hiring initiatives for URM STEM faculty are common strategies for promoting racial-ethnic equity in STEM education. However, these efforts, along with other DEI campaigns, have shown limited success in improving academic experiences and outcomes for marginalized groups, including URM STEM students. Some of the implicit bias in STEM education can be categorized as institutional racism, which is perpetuated through the policies, practices, and structural elements of organizations. These institutional features create barriers for URM STEM scholars and faculty during their education, hiring, and promotion, limiting race-matched learning opportunities for URM STEM undergraduates.This dissertation seeks to advance the literature by investigating the relationship between institutional racism and SIPs: does underrepresentation of Black and Hispanic/Latino STEM faculty undercut the intended benefits of SIPs on academic and career outcomes of URM participants? Using a quantitative research design, this study examines the impact of SIPs and the underrepresentation of URM STEM faculty on individual and cohort outcomes. Analyzing institutional datasets of three complete, consecutive cohorts of undergraduates from a predominantly white higher education institution, this study examines how SIP participation and URM faculty exposure relate to the success of URM STEM students. As previous research has found the long-term benefits of SIP participation to partially depend on other student characteristics and experiences, the present study also explores whether the benefits of URM-targeted SIPs differ from other SIPs and how these benefits compare with exposure to URM faculty in the classroom. I analyzed how these practices and their associated outcomes relate to the persistence of institutional racism in STEM education. To contextualize and validate the quantitative findings, I triangulated my findings with my advisor and committee members with substantive expertise, teasing out the details and broader meanings of the quantitative results. Ultimately, the strongest positive relationships observed between inputs and desired STEM graduation outcomes was between URM STEM faculty exposure and timely STEM graduation. Increasing URM STEM faculty exposure may improve timely graduation outcomes, reduce student loan debt, and prepare URM STEM graduates for the workforce. In contrast, high-cost extracurricular programming may not move the needle URM STEM students' graduation goals. In sum, this case study provides insights into the limited benefits of programs that many universities have implemented to retain URM STEM students and interprets those lackluster results as demonstrating the key tenet of Critical Race Theory known as "interest convergence."

NOTE (Date of Defense): April 1, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): critical race theory, diversity equity and inclusion, interest convergence, race-matched teaching, STEM education, STEM intervention programs

TITLE: Emotional Convergence in Soccer Penalty Kick Shootouts an Exeprimental Examination Using Vitual Reality Emotional Convergence in Soccer Penalty Kick Shootouts an Experimental Examination Using Virtual Reality

AUTHOR: Sayag, Yanai

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Wolf, Svenja Anna

MEMBER (committee member): Eklund, Robert C. (Robert Charles), 1958-

MEMBER (committee member): Eccles, David W.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Psychology and Learning Systems

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (70 pages)

ABSTRACT: Emotional experiences and expressions are integral parts of sports. Emotions in sports were commonly examined on the individual level. From an interpersonal perspective, the EASI model (Van Kleef, 2009) describes emotions as signals sent to the environment. When perceived by others, emotional signals provide information about the person expressing the emotion and about the environment. Previous research also examined interpersonal emotional processes in naturalistic and experimental designs. Specifically, the process of emotional convergence was documented in soccer penalty kick shootouts. This current study examined the influence of viewing teammate's performance outcome (i.e., IV1) and post-performance emotional expressions of pride or shame (i.e., IV2) on participant's (i.e., perceiver) pre-performance emotional state and subsequent performance. An on-the-field between-participants experimental design was conducted, in which previous penalty kick viewing was manipulated using a pre-recorded Virtual Reality video. Participants (N = 93) viewed one of six experimental condition videos, reported their emotional state and related cognitions, and shot a penalty for their team's common goal. Results indicated no significant differences between groups in pre-performance emotional states, although a non-significant trend in anxiety was observed. The data revealed that perceived emotions were significantly influenced by the observed performance outcome, regardless of the emotional expression. Subsequent performance was significantly affected by previous penalty outcome, and a trend regarding the emotional expression appeared in the data. The results of the study are discussed within the elements of the EASI model (Van Kleef, 2009) and other relevant literature (e.g., context and perceived emotions, ironic processing). Plausible explanations for lack of consistency with previous literature are offered. Future research is encouraged to examine interpersonal emotional processes (e.g., emotional convergence) in advanced experimental designs such as using new technologies, as well as in naturalistic settings. Further, we recommend that athletes develop effective emotion regulation strategies to mitigate the potential negative effects of negative (e.g., shame) emotional expressions on individual and team performance.

FILENAME: Saylor_fsu_0071E_18652.pdf

TITLE: Dragon Year

AUTHOR: Saylor, Timothy Dallas

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Kirby, David, 1944-

MEMBER (university representative): Valisa, Silvia, 1971-

MEMBER (committee member): Hamby, Barbara, 1952-

MEMBER (committee member): Epstein, Andrew, 1969-

MEMBER (committee member): Mewhinney, Matthew

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of English

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (101 pages)

ABSTRACT: In Dragon Year, the speaker explores their emerging queer and polyamorous identity amidst one failing relationship and another burgeoning one. At its core, this is a story of ode and elegy. The speaker looks back at the people and places who have made and unmade them. In the pain of rebirth, the speaker thinks often of death, including the suicide of a personal idol, YouTube gamer Desmond "Etika" Amofah. Indeed, video games recur throughout the work, demonstrating that digital landscapes and characters have also played a large role in the speaker's navigation of self. The poems are organized around four sections. The first introduces the speaker's current situation in media res; the second delves into the past and early formative situations; the third is a sort of quiet climax, a dark night; and the fourth is an emergence into a jubilant yet unsure future. Like Frank O'Hara suggests in his famous manifesto "Personism," these poems take place between people. Some of the poems deal explicitly with romantic love, especially potential love lost, as in "Applebee's," where the speaker admits, "I love you, and you know / though I've never said it, / and you don't love me, though we sit close / and talk a secret language." Other poems play out more of a family drama, such as "On the Plain of Dura in the Province of Delaware" and "Self-Portrait with Oathkeeper & Oblivion," in which the speaker laments their inability to protect their younger sister from their parents' divorce deep in the past. Formally, I strike a wide range throughout this book. Though most of the poems count as free verse, I employ a contemporary take on several traditional forms, such as the sonnet (e.g. "Winter Lights: Three Scenes"), the pantoum (e.g. "Blue Gucci"), the blazon (e.g. "Blazon featuring Zelda Mixtape & Coconut Oil"), the ode (e.g. "Ode to Just Dance, Lindy Hop, & The Great Gatsby"), and the contrapuntal (e.g. "At Least Spiritually"). I also experiment with forms that carry syntax along paratactically such that the entire poem is one sentence (e.g. "Lights Out Ode"). Spirituality is an important undercurrent in this book. I've been Catholic my whole life, and that provides some consistent tension in my navigation of queerness and other complex contemporary topics. Many poems in this book demonstrate a wrestling with faith—a refusal to give in and also a refusal to give it up (e.g. "Ode to Boudin, Hurricanes, & Street Performers"). In comparison to other books or the poetry market, I'd say this book owes a debt to Christian Wiman, whose works such as Every Riven Thing or Once in the West demonstrate a tense relationship with faith, a holding on even as the speaker fights back. Wiman's work, like mine, also demonstrates a deep commitment to tight, intentional form and strong musicality, though Wiman's musicality is even more pronounced than mine. I would also consider my narrative style in the lineage of Barbara Hamby and David Kirby. I expect this book would appeal to readers of poetry who are interested in queer spirituality and in poetry books that can strike a wide variety of forms, from the compressed lyric to the syntactically-expansive narrative. Though the book's final section attempts some sense of acceptance and closure, even then the speaker is just on the brink of returning to the beginning of pain again. In the final poem, "Traverse Town," during a game of mini-golf, they conclude, "I'm so color drunk I'd almost say it's / enough: tonight let's not play therapy, / pack boxes, reach for each other's bodies. / I'll birdie the next one—betcha / an ice cream. You say, let's fucking go."

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 22, 2024.

TITLE: Teacher Beliefs about Mathematics Teaching and Learning and Classroom Achievement Growth

AUTHOR: Schultz, Heather A.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Akiba, Motoko

MEMBER (university representative): Tibi, Sana

MEMBER (committee member): Iatarola, Patrice

MEMBER (committee member): Harbatkin, Erica

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (92 pages)

ABSTRACT: The study conducted in Dolphin County School District offers a comprehensive exploration of teacher beliefs among K-8 educators, specifically focusing on perspectives related to mathematics instruction. The findings reveal a diverse array of beliefs, shedding light on nuanced aspects of transmissionist, facts-first, and fixed instructional plan beliefs.An examination of background characteristics and their relationship with teacher beliefs emphasizes the intricate nature of these beliefs within the teaching community. The study identifies a weak connection, highlighting the diverse array of perspectives held by educators. Factors such as gender, race, and teaching experience contribute to this complexity, emphasizing the need for a nuanced understanding of the interplay of these factors in shaping teacher perspectives on mathematics education. Professional development emerges as a crucial factor influencing teacher beliefs. However, the study reveals a lack of statistically significant correlations between professional development and teacher beliefs. This calls for a critical reevaluation of existing professional development initiatives, urging the district to ensure their content aligns effectively with instructional practices that enhance mathematics education. The multiple regression analysis accentuates the substantial impact of teacher beliefs on average classroom math score growth. Teachers endorsing traditional approaches are associated with lower student performance, while those embracing more progressive beliefs exhibit a positive influence. Notably, overall teacher beliefs wield a particularly strong influence on student outcomes, emphasizing the significance of fostering innovative and student-centered approaches to teaching mathematics. While the study acknowledges the existence of conflicting research, particularly concerning culturally relevant beliefs, it underscores the need for a more extensive study dedicated to beliefs about the teaching and learning of mathematics. This recognition of the complexity of teacher beliefs aligns with the observations made by Beswick (2007), emphasizing the necessity for a more in-depth understanding of these intricate aspects. In response to these findings, several recommendations are proposed for Dolphin County School District. Firstly, a thorough evaluation and refinement of professional development programs are essential to ensure their efficacy in shaping teacher beliefs. Internal examinations of belief consistency, encouragement of curriculum flexibility, and initiatives promoting innovative teaching approaches are prioritized to foster a cohesive instructional culture. Additionally, the district is encouraged to actively support a culture of continuous learning and collaboration among teachers through communities of practice. By implementing these recommendations, Dolphin County School District can position itself as a leader in cultivating a teaching environment where beliefs align with effective instructional practices. This proactive stance is poised to enhance the quality of mathematics education within the district, ultimately resulting in positive impacts on student outcomes. The district's commitment to continuous improvement and the provision of high-quality education for all students is evident in these recommendations, reflecting its dedication to fostering an environment conducive to both teacher and student success.

FILENAME: Sheets_fsu_0071E_18521.pdf

TITLE: Exploring Current Preferences and Perceptions of Residence Hall Construction Standards

AUTHOR: Sheets, Daniel

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Schwartz, Robert A.

MEMBER (university representative): Fay, Daniel F.

MEMBER (committee member): Jones, Tamara Bertrand

MEMBER (committee member): Guthrie, Kathy L.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (206 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation explored the current perceptions and preferences for residence hall construction lifespan standards among campus master planners and housing administrators in higher education. Historically, universities have built residence halls with the intention of them spanning many decades (Guckert & King, 2004). However, there has been a recent trend for housing departments to design and build new residence halls with the intent to tear them down in a much shorter time frame, perhaps 30 years or even less. Several factors have played into this developing trend, such as financial constraints, delivery deadlines, perceptions of flexibility, and consumer expectations. Beyond just how a college or university campus is built, this topic also contributes to the framework of how higher education administrators view the role and impact of campus residence halls. One of the theoretical concepts at play in this study is campus ecology, which can be described as the transactional processes in which environments promote growth and development for participants. Some theorists focus not only on the environment, but also the participants' perceptions of it (Evans et al., 2010). This study was conducted using both a quantitative survey tool as well as qualitative interviews. In total, 92 people from 46 institutions across the 10 states included in the SEAHO (Southeast Association of Housing Officers) region were surveyed. Another criteria of institutional involvement were select factors of the Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education. The total survey response rate was 53%, with a usable response rate of 45%. From there, three qualitative interview participants were selected from the survey participants. There were several key findings. Only one-third of survey participants indicated that the intended building lifespan of their last-constructed residence hall was over 50 years old. A quarter of respondents indicated their school has intentionally built a residence hall with a shorter lifespan. Seventy one percent of participating schools have not done a P3 project. For the 13 schools who have done a P3, only four selected construction standards intended to have that facility last longer than 50 years. Participants were asked to share what key factors they believe played a role in the decision to intentionally build residence halls with shorter lifespans. First costs, speed of delivery, P3 projects, and projecting the need to replacing buildings sooner due to the changing needs of students, and perception of flexible design were the responses. There was division on whether flexible design was best achieved through short- or long-lifespan buildings. Another salient point was the need for key decision makers and designers to understand and apply how residence halls differ from other spaces on campus. The conversation around P3s revealed significant hesitation for a variety of reasons, but one interviewer gave strategies for their campus attempts to mitigate many of these concerns. Fifty five percent of participants indicated they preferred building residence halls to last at least 50 years. There is a strong desire to be aware of students' wants, needs and perceptions. There is also concern about how the residence halls will adapt and over time with these changes of student desire. Most of the interview discussions did not favor the strategy of shorter lifespan buildings, citing factors such as lack of trust that both financial resources and campus footprint would be available 20-30 years in the future. A variety of financing strategies were indicated, but bonding was overwhelmingly the avenue being used. About 60% of respondents said that financial capacity has at least a significant amount of influence on determining the construction design standards for new residence halls. In the interviews, the lack of available institutional debt capacity was cited as a major factor for both shorter-lifespan buildings as well as alternate funding/delivery methods. Another challenge is that some schools are directing their revenue-producing operations (like housing) to pursue external funding methods to keep that debt off the institution's books, reducing the school's debt capacity and potentially creating more capacity for other campus projects. An interviewee positively commented that using a P3 delivery method shortened the time frame for securing funding versus going through a more traditional bonding process. While this mixed methods study explores administrators' current practices, perceptions, and preferences, it also points towards more. In short, these factors set the tone and affect the environment in which students live, study, and engage. If these settings are perceived to be unreliable, reduced, or not tailored to their intended audience (residents), the institution will miss the mark on providing intentional spaces for student growth and development.

TITLE: From Enemies to Frenemies: A History of Chinese Children's Anti-Japanese Memories from Fictional Playing to Digital Gaming, 1921-2024

AUTHOR: Shi, Huaqing

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Culver, Annika A., 1975-

MEMBER (university representative): Lee, Laura H.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of History

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (234 pages)

ABSTRACT: As a part of the developing scholarship in childhood studies, propaganda studies, Cold War China, and transwar studies of World War II history, this project examines the changing propagandistic themes that informed Chinese role-playing games, from fighting demon-like Japanese enemies in the 1960s to enjoying playful Japanese opponents in the 2010s. By surveying the role real children and players played in reshaping China's memories of the Fifteen Years War (1931- 1945), this dissertation aims to understand the interactions between children and states, propaganda and reality, identity and memory, as well as games and grand strategy presented with children's images and actual children's experiences with playthings. Based on primary sources from official Chinese propaganda channels toward children in the People's Republic of China (PRC), such as New Year's paintings, posters, broadcasts, youth newspapers, magazines, and Chinese children's publications in these channels, this project argues that Chinese children have been playing active roles in shaping Chinese propaganda throughout the history of the PRC. By focusing on children's own experiences and their own voices, this dissertation attempts to recenter the essential roles Chinese children played not only in the Fifteen Years War but also in the continuing Communist effort to maintain China's revolutionary fervor during the Cold War era and beyond.

FILENAME: Shonde_fsu_0071E_18581.pdf

TITLE: Molecular Sensitization Enabled Organic Metal Halide Hybrids and Complexes for Radiation Scintillation

AUTHOR: Shonde, Tunde Blessed

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Ma, Biwu, 1980-

MEMBER (university representative): Hellstrom, Eric

MEMBER (committee member): Shatruk, Mykhailo

MEMBER (committee member): Nienhaus, Lea

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (191 pages)

ABSTRACT: High-energy radiations such as X-rays and Gamma rays have become integral to our daily lives. They are utilized in various fields, including medical imaging, security screening, and scientific research. However, an efficient and reliable detector is required to unlock their potential fully. Scintillators play a crucial role in this process as they convert these invisible high-energy radiations into visible light photons. Despite years of research and numerous breakthroughs, scintillators still face significant challenges.Currently, the most commonly used scintillator materials are inorganic, such as NaI:Tl and CdWO4. While these materials are somewhat effective, they have some drawbacks. They are expensive to produce, and some may even be toxic. Additionally, many of these inorganic crystals do not meet the specific requirements of modern applications. As an alternative, organic materials like anthracene and stilbene have been explored as scintillators. Organic materials offer advantages over their inorganic counterparts, such as low cost, short scintillation decay time, and ease of processability. However, among many other challenges, their conversion efficiency or ability to convert radiation into charge carriers is a significant drawback. In this dissertation work, we explored the combination of the merits of both inorganic and organic materials into a single system addressing issues such as radiation absorption, scintillation light yield production, and radioluminescence decay lifetime. This work involved material and molecular design, material synthesis, characterization, processing, device fabrication, and application. The first part of this dissertation focused on increasing radiation absorption, enhancing scintillation light yield, and achieving a short radioluminescence decay lifetime. We explored three different methods. In Chapter 2, we investigated using organic metal halide hybrids as sensitizers to planar organic molecules (light emitter). We achieved spatial proximity and excellent spectral overlap between the sensitizer and the light emitter by embedding planar organic dye molecules and organic metal halide hybrids in a polymer matrix. This resulted in efficient energy transfer and a significant enhancement of radioluminescence. We also discussed challenges such as residual tailing emission and fluorescent quenching resulting from aggregation. In Chapter 3, we addressed some problems encountered in Chapter 2 with a new design concept. We ionically coupled an Aggregative-Induced Emissive (AIE) organic cation with a high Z metal halide anion, promoting efficient sensitization. This work synthesized and fully characterized a zero-dimensional (0D) organic metal halide hybrid, with the high Z metal halides acting as X-ray sensitizers and AIE organic cations as emitters. These materials were easy to prepare at low temperatures and exhibited high light yields with short decay lifetimes, dramatically enhancing X-ray scintillation. We also discussed efforts to improve solution processability in Chapter 4, where the AIE organic molecule was covalently bonded to derive an organic metal halide complex, achieving better solution processability. This covalently bonded complex demonstrated efficient molecular sensitization with zinc chloride, leading to high-energy radiation harvesting and charge transfer to the organic emitting units.The second theme of this dissertation, discussed in Chapter 5, focused on our approach to achieving scintillator-specific applications, particularly in radiotherapy. We utilized molecular engineering to control the effective Z value of organic metal halide hybrids, aiming to develop a scintillator with similar radiation interaction with water and body tissue. The work highlights the potential of organic metal halide hybrids in radiotherapy applications. In the appendix, a few of the new structures discovered during the course of this dissertation's experimental work are highlighted. Overall, this dissertation contributes to developing new scintillator materials and improves our understanding of the structure-property relationship in these materials. The findings can guide the design and application of scintillator materials and other optoelectronic devices. By addressing the challenges in scintillator development, this work paves the way for more precise and accurate detection of high-energy radiation in various fields, ultimately benefiting both scientific research and human safety.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 27, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Dosimetry, Organic metal complexes, Organic metal halide hybrids, Radiation, Scintillator, Sensitization

TITLE: Charity as a Foundation of Ethics

AUTHOR: Sigourney, Tucker

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Westlund, Andrea C. (Andrea Carol)

MEMBER (university representative): Kelsay, John, 1953-

MEMBER (committee member): Clarke, Randolph K.

MEMBER (committee member): LeBar, Mark

MEMBER (committee member): Schwenkler, John Louis

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Philosophy

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (184 pages)

ABSTRACT: It seems to me that the greatest contribution which Christianity has made to the history of ethics is its claim that what we should do, above all else, is love—love everyone with no exceptions. It is strange to me that this insight has generally not survived in contemporary ethics. Though our dominant ethical theories always mention love at some point, they seldom give it the seat of honor. This dissertation, then, is an argument that they should: that our ethical theories, secular ones included, should be founded on love. Perhaps that sounds like a strange suggestion. (You may say, "Are you suggesting that contractualism, for example, should be founded on love? Well… it isn't. If it were it would not be contractualism.") The structure of my argument therefore begins with some remarks on ethics as a project. Why might it be the sort of thing that is best approached with the tools of charity? I then turn to an example—one possible ethics of charity (and quite a compelling one, in my view), borrowed largely from Thomas Aquinas. Finally, I employ this Thomistic theory to the issue of forgiveness and correction, as a way of showing how such a theory works itself out in application. The hope is that the overall picture is one on which the ethical-theoretical utility of love is clearly on display.

NOTE (Submitted Note): Dissertation submitted to the Department of Philosophy in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 18, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): charity, ethics, forgiveness, love, Thomas Aquinas

FILENAME: Smith_fsu_0071E_18526.pdf

TITLE: Emotional Support Animals in on-Campus Housing: An Exploration of Roommate and Suitemate Experiences

AUTHOR: Smith, Erin Christine

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Guthrie, Kathy L.

MEMBER (university representative): Ganley, Colleen M.

MEMBER (committee member): Beatty, Cameron C.

MEMBER (committee member): Hu, Shouping

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (75 pages)

ABSTRACT: This qualitative case study, which took place at Ringling College of Art and Design, explores the experiences of students in on-campus where emotional support animals (ESAs) are present. With rising disability diagnoses on college campuses and an increasing number of requests for students to be allowed to keep an emotional support animal, it is important to examine their impact on the living experiences of students who share living spaces. Between June and August of 2023, a convenience sample of returners and first-time college students at Ringling College of Art and Design were contacted about completing the study, which consisted of 56 students. Out of the 56 students, 12 students decided to complete semi-structured interviews about what they knew about ESAs, their personal experiences, and their thoughts on how living on campus with an ESA was beneficial or not. The researcher aimed to address the broader question of "How does the presence of an emotional support animal influence the experience of the roommate or suitemates in on campus housing?" through questions related to participant's knowledge of the roles of ESAs, their experiences with ESAs, and their personal beliefs of the benefits and downfalls of the animal in on-campus housing. Findings showed participants without their own ESA varied in their knowledge of ESA policy and procedures. Despite no personal experience regarding ESA approval and accommodation on campuses, participants offered their opinions about the roles of ESAs along with a lack of knowledge related to the application process and possible misinformation about the specifications of an ESA. Participants reported good experiences with the owners of ESAs, indicating the potential for community-building and for mature relationships to address problems arising from the presence of an ESA. Self-mediation and communication practices among suitemates were reported, demonstrating a collective willingness to implement potential solutions to the animal's presence. Finally, roommates assessed living with ESAs as mainly positive, contributing to their emotional wellbeing and to positive relationships among residents. Some respondents were able to identify advantages like being able to self-soothe during stressful or depressive episodes, or shared happy moments with the ESA, but there were also ongoing criticisms of existing policies, specifically regarding the number and types of animals and their movement. The findings of the study offer translatable lessons on how to better disseminate information about ESAs, about how to foster community-building efforts, and about how to increase communication and outreach between residents. Among these, certain suggestions might include developing targeted educational sessions, enhancing avenues of knowledge dissemination, and perhaps even rethinking or amending ESA rules so as to cultivate more close-knit and supportive campuses. The findings address many important knowledge gaps, ensure compliance with federal law and campus policies, and encourage community. With appropriate college and university policies, guidelines and supports in place, uncertainty surrounding the rights of ESAs in on-campus housing complexities can be resolved, ensuring institutions may provide greater continuity of care for students experiencing mental illness and create campuses that are friendly for both students and ESAs.

FILENAME: Song_fsu_0071E_18590.pdf

TITLE: Dynamics of Single and Dual Supersonic Impinging Jets and Response to Adaptive Microjet-Driven Control

AUTHOR: Song, Myungjun

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Alvi, Farrukh S.

MEMBER (university representative): Sussman, Mark

MEMBER (committee member): Kumar, Rajan, (Professor of Mechanical Engineering)

MEMBER (committee member): Hubicki, Christian M.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mechanical Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (256 pages)

ABSTRACT: Short Take-Off and Vertical Landing (STOVL) aircraft achieve the required lift by vectoring thrust toward the ground. These jets impinging on the ground exhibit strong resonance induced by a feedback mechanism, consisting of downstream-traveling large-scale coherent structures and upstream-propagating acoustic waves. Consequently, this resonance produces a highly unsteady flowfield, leading to high noise levels, harmful structural vibrations, and significant lift loss. Moreover, the presence of multiple impinging jets leads to the generation of a fountain flow, which further adds to the complexity of the flowfield dynamics. Understanding the flowfield and applying effective flow control methods are essential to reducing these negative consequences for STOVL aircraft.In the present study, the flowfields of a single supersonic M1.5 jet in over-expanded, ideally-expanded, and under-expanded conditions (NPR = 3, 3.67, and 4.5, respectively) are examined. For dual impinging jets, the configurations include a Mach 1.5 supersonic jet paired with an additional sonic jet at NPRs of 2 and 3. The goal of effectively controlling the inherent resonance for this flow is achieved through the use of microjet arrays. This requires a better understanding of the properties and parameters governing this flow, which was achieved through a systematic study of first single and then dual jets using a variety of experimental and analytical tools. Firstly, the influence of microjet hardware on acoustics, both passive and active, is examined across a wide range of impingement distances (H/D from 0.75 to 10) at a fine resolution (D/16). This approach enables a precise quantification and in-depth characterization of resonance phenomena. Findings indicate that the use of external microjets, which inject into the jet shear layer near the nozzle exit, proves less effective for the over-expanded jet condition at NPR of 3. Consequently, the over-expanded Mach 1.5 supersonic jet condition at NPR = 3 is selected as the representative condition, given the challenge in attenuating jet resonance at this condition. At selected impingement distances, schlieren flow visualization and stereo particle image velocimetry (SPIV) are employed to further elucidate the flow dynamics and the impact of this control technique. Furthermore, an in-depth analysis is conducted to enhance the understanding of the role of large-scale coherent structures in jet resonance. Despite the importance of large-scale coherent structures, also referred to as disturbances, comprehensive discussion on the disturbance convection velocity has been limited due to the challenges posed by nonintrusive measurement requirements. To determine the convection velocity of disturbances in the jet shear layer, high-speed schlieren flow visualization is carried out, and phase bin-averaged wave diagrams are constructed from the image sets. A parametric analysis is performed to examine the influence of nozzle pressure ratio on the convection velocity and phase lead/lag at specific impingement distances. The results reveal that the impingement tonal frequency is nearly independent of the disturbance convection velocity, except in cases of staging behavior. A slower downstream convection velocity of the disturbance corresponds to larger coherent structures, resulting in increased noise levels. Based on the observation of acoustic standing waves, an acoustic speed-based frequency model has been proposed. With the help of the allowable frequency range calculated from the vortex-sheet model, this model can provide a good approximation for the majority of axisymmetric impingement tonal frequencies. To enhance the noise reduction capabilities of microjet control, additional microjets have been introduced into the diverging section of the supersonic nozzle along with the externally installed microjets. The control system for microjet pressure and on/off status has been further upgraded, and a genetic algorithm has been utilized at selected impingement distances to optimize the microjet configuration for noise reduction. This optimized approach, especially with the staggered microjet configuration, has led to significant noise reduction achievements, including a reduction of over 12 dB in OASPL and up to 32 dB in impingement tones at specific impingement distances. Most notably, the optimized microjet configuration has effectively attenuated impingement tones across the entire scanned range of impingement distances (H/D from 0.75 to 10), covering over-expanded, ideally-expanded, and under-expanded jet conditions. Furthermore, the response of lift loss to microjet control across a range of impingement distances under different NPR conditions has been evaluated. Lift loss was assessed by measuring pressures on the lower surface of the lift plate. Microjet control has been shown to effectively reduce lift loss at lower impingement distances. For instance, lift loss at an H/D of 0.75 reaches up to 8% of the nozzle's isentropic thrust, which is decreased to 3% upon activating microjet control. Conversely, activating microjet control at higher impingement distances slightly increases lift loss. In-depth analyses of turbulence intensity distribution were conducted, revealing that the presence of large-scale coherent structures in the wall jet significantly contributes to higher lift loss. Furthermore, microjet control is observed to increase entrainment locally near the nozzle exit. In dual jets configurations, the acoustic characteristics and the response to external microjet control on the supersonic nozzle are examined for both dissimilar and matching NPR conditions. For the dissimilar NPR condition, the supersonic nozzle operates at an NPR of 3, while the sonic nozzle is set to an NPR of 2. In contrast, in the matching NPR condition, both nozzles operate at an NPR of 3. Modal decomposition techniques are utilized on time-resolved schlieren image sets to elucidate the interactions between the jets. Microjet control applied in the dual jets configuration has demonstrated better noise attenuation across an extended range of impingement distances, in contrast to its application on a single jet configuration, which showed effectiveness within a more limited range of impingement distances. Volumetric flowfields of both dissimilar and matching NPR configurations have been reconstructed using the scanning Stereo Particle Image Velocimetry (scanning-SPIV) technique. Additionally, oil surface visualization on the impingement surface has been performed, providing a detailed perspective on the flowfield. To the best of this author's knowledge, these volumetric, whole field measurements are the first of their kind for this complex flowfield. The highly-resolved velocity field provides unique insights into the three-dimensional flow dynamics and the intricate interactions between the fountain flow and the jet shear layer. Furthermore, in the dual jets configurations, the responses of acoustic performance and lift loss to the optimized microjet configuration, initially determined for a single jet condition, are evaluated over a range of impingement distances.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Mechanical Engineering in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctoral of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 28, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Acoustics, Impinging jet, STOVL, Supersonic

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Farrukh S. Alvi, Professor Directing Thesis; Mark Sussman, University Representative; Rajan Kumar, Committee Member; Christian Hubicki, Committee Member.

TITLE: Snare the Signal in the Vision Jungle: The Subfunctionalization of STX3 Ohnologs and Their Chaperone STXBP1B in Zebrafish Cone Vision

AUTHOR: Song, Sixian

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Fadool, James M.

MEMBER (university representative): Gunjan, Akash

MEMBER (committee member): Tang, Hengli

MEMBER (committee member): Taylor, Kenneth A.

MEMBER (committee member): Vincis, Roberto

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Biological Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (120 pages)

ABSTRACT: The vertebrate neural retina acts as a light detector, where photons are transduced into chemical and electrical signals at the brain. Phototransduction takes place in the photoreceptor cell outer segment (OS). Rods are responsible for dim light vision; cones are responsible for color vision and high spatial resolution. Visual information is transmitted from photoreceptor synapses to bipolar cells in the inner retina. The signal is encoded in the ribbon synapses of these two types of retinal neurons. Humans rely upon cone vision. Most mammalian models are nocturnal, and their retinas are rod-dominated. Zebrafish has emerged as a powerful model for studying gene function and neural development. Zebrafish is diurnal; cone out-number rods in twenty-to-one in larval retina. Behavior assays have shown that zebrafish are largely dependent on cone vision. My projects utilized zebrafish as genetic models to investigate the role of the soluble N-ethylmaleimide-sensitive factor attachment protein receptor (SNARE) complex in cone and bipolar cells. The SNARE complex is a central membrane fusion machinery that is essential for synaptic transmission and membrane trafficking. Mutations in SNARE proteins have been implicated in microvillus inclusion disease (MVID) and a spectrum of neuronal developmental disorder such as encephalopathy and retina dystrophy. The t-SNARE protein syntaxin-3 (Stx3) and syntaxin-binding protein-1 (Stxbp1) are exclusively expressed in the photoreceptor and bipolar cell of the retina. Stx3 is crucial for photoreceptor development, rod OS morphogenesis, and synaptic vesicle exocytosis in ribbon synapses, whereas the role of Stxbp1 in the retina is largely unknown. Zebrafish (Danio rerio) have emerged as a powerful model organism for studying gene function. Whole genome duplication has resulted in two STX3 ohnologues in zebrafish, Stx3a (Chr.1) and Stx3b (Chr.14). Utilizing the CRISPR-Cas9 targeting system in the zebrafish model, my studies have demonstrated that Stx3a is specifically essential for cone development and cone-driven vision, whereas Stx3b ensures the signal transmission fidelity of bipolar cells. Our previous study found that Stxbp1b, a Stxbp1 ortholog in zebrafish, is essential for photoreceptor survival. I have shown that Stxbp1b is crucial for the protein stability of both Stx3 ohnologs in zebrafish. Collectively, my studies demonstrate that the subfunctionalization of Stx3 ohnologs in photoreceptors and bipolar cells, along with their chaperone Stxbp1b, are essential for cone vision in zebrafish.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 29, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Nystagmus, Photoreceptor degeneration, Stxbp1, Syntaxin-3 (Stx3), Zebrafish retina

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

SUBJECT: Biology

DEGREE: Doctoral

FILENAME: Starr_fsu_0071E_18508.pdf

TITLE: Carbon Dynamics in a Changing Arctic Landscape: Characterizing Dissolved Organic Matter across Multiple Scales

AUTHOR: Starr, Sommer Faith

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Spencer, Robert G. M.

MEMBER (university representative): Pau, Stephanie

MEMBER (committee member): Chassignet, Eric P.

MEMBER (committee member): Chanton, Jeffrey P.

MEMBER (committee member): Wickland, Kimberly P.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (197 pages)

ABSTRACT: Northern high-latitude freshwater systems are an essential link between terrestrial and marine carbon cycles, transporting organic matter from ecosystems on land to the Arctic Ocean. However, polar regions are warming faster than the global average due to anthropogenic climate change, potentially releasing hundreds of tons of carbon currently stored in peatland and permafrost soils. Arctic ecosystem dynamics are also changing under continued warming, and changing land cover and hydrology will alter the amount and composition of organic matter exported by surface waters. Dissolved organic matter (DOM) is a crucial component of the carbon cycle, with the global DOM pool rivaling the amount of carbon stored in the atmosphere. The composition of DOM is fundamentally linked to its reactivity and, as such, partially determines whether mobilized DOM will be mineralized and released as greenhouse gases or stored on long time scales in marine systems. Understanding DOM dynamics in Arctic freshwater systems is thus crucial to understanding the impacts of climate change.This dissertation investigates DOM sources, molecular composition, and processing pathways across the pan-Arctic watershed and uses a suite of investigative tools, including optical measurements, Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometry (FT-ICR MS), and spatial analysis, to investigate how a changing Arctic landscape may impact DOM dynamics. The research focused on four distinct areas: refining dissolved organic carbon (DOC) fluxes from the pan-Arctic watershed, characterizing the influences of peatland cover and permafrost on exported DOM, evaluating how DOM composition and microbial community influence the processing of DOM, and characterizing the composition and reactivity of DOM from non-vascular plant sources. DOM composition varied across ecosystems, reflecting the chemodiversity inherent to this carbon cycle component. In the Onega River, a relatively small and understudied high-latitude river, DOM exhibited a uniquely terrestrial signature throughout the year with muted seasonal changes, contrasting with the dramatic seasonality of DOM composition in larger watersheds. Scaling data from the Onega River increased the estimated pan-Arctic annual DOC flux by approximately 50% from previously reported estimates, suggesting that including smaller watersheds is important for improving pan-Arctic modeling estimates. The Onega River watershed is unique from the six largest Arctic rivers by being permafrost-free and having a large proportion of its area covered by wetlands; thus, its unique molecular signature is likely driven by these landscape features. The relationship between these landscape features and DOM composition is explicitly revealed through an analysis of DOM composition across a latitudinal gradient in West Siberia, demonstrating that peatland extent and permafrost influence have observable impacts on DOM exported by rivers. DOM composition from permafrost-free watersheds exhibited greater variability, higher molecular weight, and a more terrestrial signature than permafrost-influenced watersheds. Peatland extent explained much of the variance in measured variables, with watersheds with greater peatland extent exhibiting more heterogenous DOM composition. However, permafrost effectively acts as a switch on this peatland influence, and so these data demonstrate that DOM from previously permafrost-influenced watersheds may become more heterogeneous and exhibit a more terrestrial signature as permafrost thaw continues. A novel bioincubation experiment was conducted to explore further how these landscape features and their impacts on DOM composition affect DOM biolability and to determine whether the introduction of microbes from one type of soil to another impact DOC loss over time. Leachates created from two wetland depths of wetland soil and soil from two ages of permafrost at distinct filtration levels allowed for the simulation of the mobilization and potential mixing of DOM and microbes from these sources under continued permafrost thaw. Data from these bioincubations demonstrated that the source and composition of DOM, not the microbial community, was the factor that determined DOM biolability and processing. Pleistocene permafrost produced compositionally unique DOM that exhibited an approximately 70% DOC loss rate over time, highlighting the high bioavailability of DOM mobilized as these deposits thaw. Warming not only affects permafrost but impacts the distribution of vegetation on the landscape. Lignin phenol analysis and optical measurements of individual moss and lichen leachates were conducted to explore how shrub expansion and associated loss of moss and lichen cover in the Arctic may impact DOM dynamics. Moss leachates produced high concentrations of biolabile DOM enriched in p-hydroxy phenols; however, the general aromaticity of the DOM and not the phenol composition appeared to be the primary driver of DOC loss over time. Overall, these data characterized DOC export and DOM composition across a wide range of sources and regions in the pan-Arctic watershed and highlight the need for further research to continue elucidating DOM dynamics in the Arctic.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Physical Environmental Science.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 5, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Arctic biogeochemistry, dissolved organic matter, FT-ICR MS, peatlands, permafrost, surface water

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Robert G. M. Spencer, Professor Directing Dissertation; Stephanie Pau, University Representative; Eric P. Chassignet, Committee Member; Jeff P. Chanton, Committee Member; Kimberly P. Wickland, Committee Member.

TITLE: Using the Moist Static Energy Variance Budget to Evaluate Tropical Cyclones in Climate Models Against Reanalyses and Satellite Observations: Model Resolution, Ocean Coupling, and Cloud Interactions

AUTHOR: Starr, Jarrett

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Wing, Allison

MEMBER (committee member): Misra, Vasubandhu, 1970-

MEMBER (committee member): Diamond, Michael

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (98 pages)

ABSTRACT: Tropical cyclones (TCs) are observed in general circulation models (GCMs) as well as reanalyses. However, itis known that GCMs and reanalyses struggle to accurately represent TCs and have biases in the TC frequency and intensity distributions. By employing the column-integrated moist static energy (MSE) variance budget as a process-oriented diagnostic, we can analyze the model representation of physical processes that help or hinder the development of TCs. Specifically, we analyze the radiative and surface flux feedback terms within the MSE variance budget across 5 different reanalysis datasets and 19 different GCM simulations. Binning and compositing of TC snapshots by maximum velocity and minimum sea level pressure allows for comparison across the GCMs and reanalyses of the feedbacks at a given intensity, as well as an examination of how the feedbacks vary with storm intensity. We find that the surface flux feedback on TC development is weaker in coupled models. Ocean coupling also influences radiative feedbacks, because the TC-induced sea surface temperature (SST) cooling reduces the surface upward longwave radiative flux. Across all models, the longwave radiative feedback positively contributes to TC development and is driven by cloud effects. Models differ regarding the role of the shortwave radiative feedback, though it is generally smaller than the longwave. Regarding the intermodel spread in surface flux and radiative feedbacks at a given intensity, models with coarse resolution differ more from each other and from reanalyses than those with high resolution. These results can help us understand how differences in model representation of physical processes lead to model differences in TC intensity.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 21, 2024.

TITLE: Paper Rings Carry Weighty Things: How Kepler's Printed Spheres Function as Mathematical Instruments

AUTHOR: Sumrall, Raigen

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Leitch, Stephanie

MEMBER (committee member): Pericolo, Lorenzo, 1966-

MEMBER (committee member): Loic, Erika

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Fine Arts

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Art History

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (50 pages)

ABSTRACT: Johannes Kepler's Tabula III in the Mysterium Cosmographicum (1596), printed in Kepler's dissertation at the University of Tübingen, is a diagram containing the spheres in space and the geometric figures that determine the proportional spaces between them. By utilizing the method of visualization taught through images in texts of astronomy published in northern Europe in the early modern period to introduce his new geometric model of the universe, Kepler solidified visualization as a necessary component of viewing astronomical models. Because astronomical models of the 16th century did not visually support the investigation of metaphysics, Kepler created a model that would allow the viewer to investigate such matters. I argue that in doing so, Kepler created an object-diagram that not only animates the viewer's visualization of space, but also its celestial mechanics. Additionally, the diagram sits upon a sculptural, geometric base, which has not been addressed in art historical treatments of the image. Using a semiotic analysis of the individual components of the diagram, the relationships between the diagrammatic components and the sculptural base become evident. The functions of the diagram, in combination with the base, turn the image into a mathematical instrument.

FILENAME: Taleb_fsu_0071E_18546.pdf

TITLE: The Impact of Block Copolymer Structures on Thermal Conduction and Dynamics in Composites

AUTHOR: Taleb, Omar Mohamad

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Hallinan, Daniel T., Jr.

MEMBER (university representative): Schlenoff, Joseph B.

MEMBER (committee member): Alamo, Rufina G.

MEMBER (committee member): Locke, Bruce R.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemical and Biomedical Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (189 pages)

ABSTRACT: Thermal management is crucial in everyday life across a range of applications, influencing our safety, comfort, and efficiency of various technologies. Composite material combines different materials to achieve a mutually unique property that cannot be achieved by one homogenous material. Composite material used for thermal management offers a unique opportunity to enhance overall thermal performance. Composite material is a key player in addressing challenges related to heat dissipation and temperature control due to its ability of incorporating lightweight and thermal properties. In this dissertation, we developed a numerical finite-difference model for 2D transient diffusion in lamellar structures. The explicit application is heat transfer, but it could equally be applied to dielectric constants, magnetic susceptibilities, electron/ion conduction, and mass diffusion as well. The control volume contains two phases A and B. The phases have different transport parameters. The modeling aims to evaluate the effect of grain size, grain boundaries, and phase contrast on apparent transport properties of composite materials, such as laminates, polycrystalline materials, and block copolymers, by examining a progression of increasingly complex structures. To validate the model, effective transport parameters of parallel and perpendicular structures from the numerical model are compared to analytical expressions. Effective Medium Theory provides an analytical expression in the limit of many, small, randomly oriented grains. The impact of coarse grains on transport is investigated. Specifically, the model is used to examine how the apparent transport parameters trend from the limit of a homogeneous material to small randomly oriented grains containing two different phases. The effective thermal conductivity (averaged over many random structures) was found not to be a function of grain size. However, the standard deviation decreased exponentially with decreasing grain size, reaching less than 2% variation for transport through 15 grains. Thus, the appropriate Effective Medium prediction is reliable for a surprisingly few number of grains, and connectivity of the more conducting phase is important only in coarse grains with significant contrast. In addition to the 2D lamellar model structure, we focus on examining the impact that geometric structure has on the thermal conductivity of multi-phase constructs in multiple 3D-printed PLA samples. We explore alternative structural configurations beyond planar arrangements, specifically we focus on cylindrical and gyroid shapes. We investigate how various infill percentages and infill materials influence the thermal conductivity of these structures. By precisely controlling the infill percentages and incorporating different infill materials with varying thermal conductivities, PLA samples can be tailored to simulate various thermal conductivity contrasts observed in practical applications. In this study, we explore the thermal conductivity of PLA structures with different infill percentages and two distinct infill materials: air and thermal paste. Air represents the least conductive material at 0.026 W/(m K), and thermal paste exhibits high thermal conductivity at 5 W/(m K). The experimental results are compared to an analytical model prediction to confirm the efficacy of the model in predicting the thermal performance of these complex structures. Finally, the design of advanced composite nanostructured material requires a fundamental understanding of material behavior at several length scales from nanometer to macroscopic, linked by mesoscopic structure and dynamics. In this work, the structure and dynamics of high molecular weight polystyrene-b-poly(ethylene oxide) (PS-b-PEO) block copolymers (BCPs) were studied. The BCPs exhibited microphase separated cylindrical and lamellar morphologies. Structural dynamics were measured with X-ray photon correlation spectroscopy (XPCS) in the small-angle regime. Morphologies and domain sizes were evaluated using small angle x-ray scattering (SAXS), scanning electron microscopy (SEM), and atomic force microscopy (AFM). The PS-b-PEO grain size was controlled by different processing conditions, a combination of solvent vapor annealing during solution casting and thermal annealing, were investigated. The grain sizes were evaluated using SAXS, were found to depend weakly on processing only for the rubbery majority BCP and the results showed that the grain size variation depends on which block formed the matrix majority. The structural relaxation times were examined as a function of PS volume fraction, temperature, morphology, and structural sizes. Well above the glass transition temperature (Tg) of PS, all samples exhibited stretched autocorrelation decays and diffusive dynamics. Near Tg of PS the dynamics of all samples was anomalous with compressed autocorrelation decays and hyperdiffusive dynamics. This transition occurred at 153 °C or 1.13 Tg of PS. Surprisingly, the structural relaxation times do not correlate with grain size, indicating that PS dynamics and out-of-equilibrium state play the dominant roles in structural dynamics of these strongly phase segregated BCPs.
