TITLE: Professional Learning for Online Teaching: A Multiple-Case Study of Higher Education Instructors in Hong Kong

AUTHOR: Tang, Yuen Man

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Dennen, Vanessa P., 1970-

MEMBER (university representative): Latham, Don, 1959-

MEMBER (committee member): Klein, James D.

MEMBER (committee member): Ke, Fengfeng

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Psychology and Learning Systems

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (126 pages)

ABSTRACT: University instructors often lack the knowledge and skills to effectively facilitate learning and teaching in the online environment. Instructors in higher education institutions (HEIs) have faced common challenges to online teaching, such as a lack of digital literacy, access to software and hardware resources and training, and pedagogical and content-related concerns. The rapid transition to fully online teaching necessitated by the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic brought many of these instructional issues to the foreground; however, online teaching also encompasses the integration of online tools into traditional classroom environments, as well as blended or hybrid instructional formats. In this dissertation, I define online teaching broadly to include all such formats of online teaching. In this multiple-case study, I aimed to investigate the online teaching challenges of higher education instructors in Hong Kong and to examine the approaches to professional learning these instructors took in order to address the challenges they encountered. I employed qualitative methods in this study, including conducting individual semi-structured interviews with instructors working at a tertiary university in Hong Kong that specializes in teacher education and collecting artifacts from the participants that related to their professional learning experiences. I found that instructors experienced online teaching challenges that encompassed content-related, pedagogy-related, technology-related, and motivational factors, thereby providing insights for both practice and future research into improving online teaching competencies and experiences for instructors. My findings highlight the importance of integrating both formal and informal professional learning approaches to address online instruction challenges. Formal professional development (PD) programs, such as university workshops and certificate courses, provided structured learning opportunities for instructors. Informal PD through social media platforms and professional networks facilitated collaborative learning and knowledge sharing, and was often engaged in to supplement formal PD. The integration of both formal and informal PD approaches was suggested to provide a comprehensive and personalized professional learning experience. Furthermore, I adopted Activity Systems Analysis (ASA) as a framework to analyze my findings regarding the professional learning strategies of higher education instructors in response to their online teaching challenges. The research implications of ASA included investigating the compensatory role of informal PD, understanding the time-intensive nature of informal PD tasks, exploring customization possibilities for software tools, and examining the impact of mandatory informal PD on instructors' workloads.

TITLE: Co-Metabolic Degradation of 1,4-Dioxane

AUTHOR: Tesfamariam, Ermias Gebrekrstos

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Tang, Youneng

MEMBER (university representative): Ye, Ming

MEMBER (committee member): Huang, Chen, (Professor of Scientific Computing)

MEMBER (committee member): Chen, Gang, 1969-

MEMBER (committee member): Farner, Jeffrey M.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (156 pages)

ABSTRACT: 1,4-Dioxane is a synthetic chemical used as a stabilizer of chlorinated solvents and as a solvent in several industrial processes and commercial products. It is identified as an emerging water contaminant and classified as "likely to be carcinogenic to humans". Removal of 1,4-dioxane from wastewater is challenging due to its high water solubility, low Henry's law volatility constant, and low partition coefficients. Bioremediation is a promising treatment method for removing 1,4-dioxane from water as it is potentially eco-friendly and cost-effective. Some microorganisms can use 1,4-dioxane as a sole carbon and energy source, and the degradation of 1,4-dioxane can be enhanced when primary substrates are provided to promote microbial growth. The main objective of this research was to investigate the co-metabolic biodegradation of 1,4-dioxane. The first objective focused on kinetic parameters for ethane biodegradation and co-oxidations of ethane and 1,4-dioxane. Based on experiments combined with mathematical modeling, it was found that ethane promoted 1,4-dioxane biodegradation when the initial mass ratio of ethane:1,4-dioxane was <9:1 mg-COD/mg-COD, while it inhibited 1,4-dioxane degradation when the ratio was >9:1. A model-independent parameter estimator was used for kinetic-parameter estimation, and all parameter values for 1,4-dioxane were consistent with literature-reported ranges. The results support that bacteria that co-oxidize ethane- and 1,4-dioxane had a competitive advantage over bacteria that can use only one of the two substrates. The minimum 1,4-dioxane concentration required to sustain steady-state biomass with 1,4-dioxane as the sole primary substrate was 1.3 mg-COD/L. As 1,4-dioxane concentrations at most groundwater sites are less than 0.18 mg-COD/L, providing ethane as a primary substrate is vital to enhance biomass growth and 1,4-dioxane bioremediation. The second objective investigated the biodegradation of 1,4-dioxane using ethane as a primary substrate in an O2-based membrane biofilm reactor (O2-MBfR). Based on more than 800 days of continuous operation of two O2-MBfRs with different influent ethane concentrations over the various stages, it was found that an ethane:1,4-dioxane mole ratio of around 300:1 was required to remove 1,4-dioxane from 100 µg/L to ~10 µg/L and from 10 µg/L to 2 µg/L. Results from the microbial community analysis showed that Rhodococcus and Mycobacterium were the two dominant genera in both MBfRs. The third objective of this research was to investigate the biodegradation of ethane and 1,4-dioxane in the O2-MBfR by developing a mathematical model. A higher ethane supply resulted in biofilm growth, with the biofilm's active biomass dominated by ethane- and 1,4-dioxane-co-oxidizing bacteria. At >200:1 ethane to 1,4-dioxane mole ratio and <1.9 mg m-2 d-1 1,4-dioxane loadings, the 1,4-dioxane removal was >70%. On the other hand, high ethane (>300:1 ethane to 1,4-dioxane mole ratio) at high 1,4-dioxane loadings (>4 mg m-2 d-1) inhibited 1,4-dioxane biodegradation to <30%. The findings underscore that at low 1,4-dioxane loadings, ethane is an essential primary substrate to maintain sufficient biofilm growth for 1,4-dioxane degradation. In the fourth objective, 1,4-dioxane-metabolizing mixed cultures were enriched by periodically spiking 1,4-dioxane at low concentrations (<1 mg/L). Five 1,4-dioxane-metabolizing pure cultures LCD6B, LCD6D, WC10G, WCD6H, and WD4H were isolated and characterized. The partial 16S rRNA gene sequencing showed that the five strains were related to Dokdonella sp. (98.3%), Acinetobacter sp. (99.0%), Afipia sp. (99.2%), Nitrobacter sp. (97.9%), and Pseudonocardia sp. (99.4%), respectively. Compared to the literature, these strains have lower half-maximum-rate concentrations (1.8 to 8.2 mg-dioxane/L), lower maximum specific 1,4-dioxane utilization rates (0.24 to 0.47 mg-dioxane/mg-protein d)), higher biomass yields (0.29 to 0.38 mg-protein/mg-dioxane), and lower decay coefficients (0.01 to 0.02 d-1). These are characteristics of microorganisms living in oligotrophic environments. Although the adsorption kinetics and isotherms of several water pollutants have been widely studied, little is known about the adsorption kinetics of 1,4-dioxane. In the fifth objective, the kinetics of 1,4-dioxane adsorption by AmberSorb and Granular Activated Carbon (GAC) were investigated. A homogeneous surface diffusion model was developed to describe the adsorption of 1,4-dioxane in continuous flow and batch systems. The external mass-transfer and internal diffusion coefficients of 1,4-dioxane for AmberSorb (1.79x10-3 cm/min and 3.52x10-4 cm2/min) were determined about five- and thirty-fold larger than that of their corresponding parameters for GAC. For both adsorbents, the adsorption was limited by the mass-transfer across the fluid film that covers the adsorbent and the adsorbent-adsorbate interaction at the adsorbent surface but not limited by the diffusion within the adsorbent. While the mass-transfer across the external fluid film affected the maximum 1,4-dioxane removal percentage and the adsorption rate, the isotherm parameters mainly controlled the adsorption capacity and adsorbent service life.

ABSTRACT: This research studied an approach for the characterization of tensile properties of continuous carbon nanotube (CNT) yarns to potentially use as the primary composite reinforcement in aerospace applications. FILENAME: Tietsworth_fsu_0071N_18724.pdf

TITLE: Understanding the Cu-Sn Mixing Heat Treatment and Its Effects on the Formation of Nb3Sn in Rod-in-Tube Wires of Varying Cu: Sn Ratios

AUTHOR: Tietsworth, John

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Larbalestier, D. (David)

MEMBER (committee member): Cooley, L. (Lance)

MEMBER (committee member): Krick, Brandon

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mechanical Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (34 pages)

ABSTRACT: This work explores the effects of changing the Cu:Sn ratio in Nb3Sn Rod in Tube (RIT) wires togain a better understanding of the Cu-Sn mixing process prior to Nb3Sn formation. Internal Tin Nb3Sn wires like the Rod Restack Process ®(RRP) always have complexities associated with the Cu-Sn mixing steps. Imperfect mixing compromises the ultimate performance of the wire. From this point of view RIT wires are of special interest because all the Cu and Sn is contained within one tubular filament that in principle offers a simplified window into the mixing and subsequent A15 layer growth. Here we examined wires with Cu:Sn atomic ratios of 3:1 and 6:5. We tested new multistep heat treatments motivated by the Cu-Sn phase diagram, observing both Cu-Sn and A15 phase formation around key transition temperatures. Problems with eliminating low Sn α phase compositions from RIT wires with a Cu:Sn ratio of 3:1 were previously discussed by Segal et al [1]. and here his experiments were extended by using higher temperature Cu-Sn mixing steps above 500C. Using the heat treatment step 525◦C/96h, we were able to eliminate the α phase at the Nb-Core interface prior to the A15 reaction step by completely mixing the Cu-Sn core. However, this achievement did not lead to improved properties like we initially expected. In some cases, wires with worse CuSn mixing prior to A15 formation step had better properties than those with a mixed core. None of these wires produced good superconducting properties when compared to other common wire designs RRP, PIT, and the Bronze process. However, the internal Cu:Sn ratio is seen to influence the superconducting properties. Wires with an internal Cu:Sn ratio of 3:1 significantly underperform compared to the wires with the starting composition of 6:5. We found that the reaction path for 3:1 (and bronze wires) avoids the nausite phase (generally thought to be deleterious to Jc) always found in RRP wires while the 6:5 wire reaction always went through nausite with decomposition into NbSn2, Nb6Sn5 and then A15 at high temperatures. Furthermore we recorded that a key difference between RIT and RRP is that RIT exhibits a larger spread in the normal to superconducting transition curve following the same heat treatment. This transition was shown to be a result of gradients in at%Sn across the Nb3Sn layer.

TITLE: Milk for Gall

AUTHOR: Tombasco, Natalie

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Hamby, Barbara, 1952-

MEMBER (university representative): Valisa, Silvia, 1971-

MEMBER (committee member): Caputi, Celia R.

MEMBER (committee member): Suárez, Virgil, 1962-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of English

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (105 pages)

ABSTRACT: Milk for Gall's title alludes to Lady Macbeth's renunciation, "Unsex me…Come to my woman's breasts, / And take my milk for gall," and (re)vises it for a postmodern feminist epic woman-spreading through a Y2K kingdom that houses a Lolita Army, Shitshow Barbie, and strange entanglements with literary figures. This collection begins with a "primordial sigh," descending into realm after realm, self after self, questioning "how do you hold yourself together" while facing a barrage of patriarchal contradictions. Tombasco "rummages for loveliness" in works as broad as those by Emily Dickinson, René Magritte, and Yorgos Lanthimos and navigates situationships with "Orpheus fuckboy[s]," cultivating a nomenclature all her own—nimble, lush, rhythmic verse that restlessly seeks to answer, "what is my / true utterance?" In the wake of #MeToo, the dismantling of Roe v. Wade, and the increasing climate threat, she dissects any yearning for potential motherhood, but instead, demands a new role: "I don't mean to upset the natural order or anything / but when might I get to play Prometheus? give myself / to the birds?" Milk for Gall is a coming-of-age poetry collection that follows a speaker from pre-birth to girlhood, into womanhood and beyond. Throughout these different life stages, her identity is sculpted by what comes through various high and low art mediums and she questions notions of femininity.

FILENAME: Tripathi_fsu_0071E_18398.pdf

TITLE: Parametric Characterization of Fluid-Structure Interaction on a Compliant Panel in High-Speed Flows

AUTHOR: Tripathi, Akriti

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Kumar, Rajan, (Professor of Mechanical Engineering)

MEMBER (committee member): Oates, William

MEMBER (committee member): Shoele, Kourosh

MEMBER (university representative): Hallinan, Daniel T., Jr.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mechanical Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (158 pages)

ABSTRACT: The need for increased efficiency and performance of high-speed aircraft has led to the need for a reduction in aircraft weight. One option is to use thinner and lightweight skin panels at different regions of the aircraft, such as the fuselage, wings, engine inlet, and control surfaces. When such an aircraft operates at high speeds, the shock wave generated or impinging on those surfaces interacts with the surface boundary layer, leading to the well-known phenomenon of shock wave boundary layer interactions (SBLI). SBLI on rigid surfaces has been heavily researched in the past and a sufficient understanding of parameters affecting SBLI has been obtained, including its detrimental effects on the flight vehicle. However, there is a lack of sufficient understanding of the effects of SBLI over thin surface panels that led to fluid-structure interactions (FSI) and high cycle fatigue damage of flight vehicles and detrimental effects on the lives of the crew operating on such missions. Previous studies have shown that FSI on a compliant panel is a highly coupled problem depending on several parameters such as the shock impingement location, pressure and temperature gradients, shock strength, boundary layer thickness, Mach number, material properties, etc., and therefore difficult to analyze compared to the SBLI on a rigid surface. The present study aims to decouple the effect of some of these parameters to simplify the analysis and better understand FSI at high-speeds. In this experimental investigation, one parameter is varied at a time to study its effect on the mean and dynamic characteristics of FSI on a compliant panel at supersonic speeds. Experiments were carried out at the Florida Center for Advanced Aero-Propulsion (FCAAP) supersonic and Pilot wind tunnels. The model geometry consists of a compliant panel with a cavity on its underside embedded in the tunnel wall. The cavity was pressurized to different values simulating various flight conditions, resulting in different levels of static deflection of the panel. The panel was subjected to an impinging shock generated by a shock generator at two locations, namely, the central and 3/4$^{th}$ length of the panel and three cavity pressures equal to ambient, upstream static, and vacuum were tested. In addition, the effect of two shock strengths (by varying the shock angle), two Mach numbers (M = 2, 5), and two boundary layer thicknesses were studied. Several flow diagnostic techniques such as high-speed shadowgraph, surface oil flow measurements, panel deflection measurements, and steady and unsteady pressure-sensitive paint measurements were employed to study the mean and dynamic flow features of the interaction. The results show that the interaction over the panel is curved or three-dimensional, compared to the nominally two-dimensional interaction over a rigid plate. The level of curvature of the interaction or the separation line is a function of the shock impingement location and the cavity pressure. The mean separation bubble length along the panel centerline was modified in the case of interaction over the panel compared to the rigid plate. An increased width of the upstream influence region was observed in the case of the compliant panel compared to the rigid plate for most of the cases tested, indicating increased unsteadiness. The centerline pressure distributions over the panel are a strong function of the shock impingement location and pressure gradient across the panel. The response of the panel to the turbulent boundary layer at supersonic speeds was observed to be multi-modal and excited by the turbulent structures within the boundary layer of varying lengths and time scales. Compared to the natural structural modes of the panel, these interaction modes were observed to shift to relatively higher frequencies. In the presence of an impinging shock, some modes were amplified, indicating a strong coupling between the panel and the shock. An increase in frequency was also observed compared to the no-shock case, for both shock impingement locations and all cavity pressures. This may be due to the increased forcing generated by the shock impingement. For a fixed shock impingement location, the effect of the cavity pressure was to amplify and excite different modes of the panel. While the higher cavity pressures excite the lower order modes, the case with cavity at vacuum was observed to excite higher order modes. The pressure spectra corresponding to cavity at vacuum is relatively broadband indicating reduced coupling. For a fixed shock strength, an increase in the boundary layer thickness was observed to increase the separation bubble length over the rigid plate and the compliant panel. The sensitivity of the separation line to cavity pressure modification was observed to increase in the case of a thicker boundary layer. The mean separation bubble length was observed to increase with an increase in the shock strength for the panel as well as rigid plate interaction. Considerable progress has been made toward addressing the objectives of the current study. The remainder of the goals, namely the unsteady aspects of the fluid-structure interaction for an increased boundary layer thickness, Mach number, and shock strength, will be investigated. 3D deflection data obtained using LASER vibrometry, pressure using PSP, and velocity using PIV measurements will be further analyzed. The results from this study will help designers and analysts to design structures that can withstand the detrimental effects of the aeroelastic coupling encountered at high speeds. It will also aid in generating an experimental database for validating numerical solvers for FSI. It will help develop higher-order aeroelastic models with detailed structure modeling and separated flow effects using the reduced-order modeling approach.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Mechanical Engineering in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 8, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Compliant Panel, Flow Separation, Fluid Structure Interaction, Mach number, Shock Boundary Layer Interaction

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Rajan Kumar, Professor Directing Thesis; William Oates, Committee Member; Kourosh Shoele, Committee Member; Daniel Hallinan, Jr., University Representative.

TITLE: Gold Rush Cherokees: Pursuing Prosperity in the Nineteenth Century

AUTHOR: Turgel-Ethier, Rhiannon

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Frank, Andrew, 1970-

MEMBER (university representative): Peres, Tanya M.

MEMBER (committee member): Mooney, Katherine Carmines

MEMBER (committee member): Koslow, Jennifer Lisa, 1970-

MEMBER (committee member): Doel, Ronald Edmund

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of History

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (232 pages)

ABSTRACT: Gold Rush Cherokees looks at the centrality of gold rushes to Cherokee history and the importance of Cherokees to the history of American gold rushes. More specifically, these chapters investigate Cherokees' lived experiences in the California gold mines and their discovery of gold in Colorado in the 1850s. After discovering gold in Georgia in the 1820s and then being forced to relinquish these claims, hundreds of Cherokee men and women became central actors in the more well-known gold rushes of the mid-nineteenth century. With the gold-mining skills and expertise Cherokees developed during the Georgia gold rush, many Cherokee men and women took the overland trail and set up gold mining companies in California in 1849 and 1850. A Cherokee company from Georgia was the first to discover gold at Pike's Peak, a discovery that launched the Colorado gold rush in 1858. Thus, as opportunities in California diminished, many joined other miners in the new mining communities in Colorado. In these western gold mining spaces, these refugees of colonization and removal became colonizers of the west. Some Cherokee miners made fortunes while participating in these gold rushes. However, most experienced hardships on the overland trails and in the mines, which led many of the Cherokee miners to return home to the Cherokee Nation in Oklahoma, or to their communities in Georgia and North Carolina that had avoided removal.

ABSTRACT: My Dissertation in Practice concentrated on sexual assault in community colleges with a focus on a mid-western community college. The purpose of this quantitative descriptive exploratory research study was to explore students' knowledge and awareness of the policies and procedures with respect to sexual assault as well as support services available for victims of sexual assault in a community college setting. The purpose was to also to learn about students' perspectives on the usefulness of sexual assault training if they received training. The following research questions and sub-question guided the study: RQ 1: How knowledgeable and aware are the students at a Mid-Western community college of sexual assault?Sub-Question: Are there significant differences in knowledge and awareness of sexual assault based on the students' full-time or part-time status? RQ 2: What are the students' perspectives on the usefulness of sexual assault training at a Mid-Western community college? A quantitative approach was the chosen methodology for this study. My findings concluded that 28 students did not receive sexual assault training. Most of the students were at least moderately knowledgeable (16) about how to report a sexual assault at this school but least aware (18) of where they can find 24/7 support related to sexual assault. Findings highlighted opportunities for college officials at the mid-western community college to better explore ways to engage students' knowledge and awareness of sexual assault.

TITLE: Precedented Times, Precedented Measures: Exploring the Theatre-as-Body's Recurrent Adaptations to Plague and Pandemic-Induced Trauma

AUTHOR: Twichell, Kae Milne

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Salata, Kris

MEMBER (committee member): Thomas, Aaron C.

MEMBER (committee member): Fahmy, Sarah

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: School of Theatre

CORPORATE NAME: School of Theatre

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (98 pages)

ABSTRACT: By employing an organic theory that views theatre as a living body, this thesis explores how theatre has adapted to pandemics throughout history. It suggests that theatre, like the human body and mind, operates as a complex adaptive system, evolving in response to crises. The study examines three historical pandemics—the Athenian Plague, the Spanish Influenza, and COVID-19— through the theatre-as-body framework, highlighting theatre's resilience and healing role in society. This exploration reveals two remarkable adaptations within the theatre-as-body's immune system: catharsis as a purgative release, allowing audiences to emotionally cleanse themselves of collective trauma, and disavowal as a protective mechanism, enabling the theatrical space to momentarily distance spectators from the harsh realities and uncertainties of pandemics. This thesis emphasizes theatre's ability to creatively respond to challenging circumstances and, therefore, reinforce its cultural function.

TITLE: Paradigms of Parenting: Intensive Parenting across Identities Explored through Mixed Methodology

AUTHOR: Unhjem, Lexie

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): McWey, Lenore M.

MEMBER (university representative): Radey, Melissa

MEMBER (committee member): Wu, Qiong, (Professor of human sciences)

MEMBER (committee member): Kimmes, Jonathan G. (Jonathan Gene)

MEMBER (committee member): Reynolds, Jamila Evans

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Human Development and Family Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (120 pages)

ABSTRACT: Intensive parenting involves parents centering their children's needs, spending most of their free time engaging with them, and following the advice of child experts. Although most studies on intensive parenting have been qualitative, one group of researchers developed a quantitative measure for intensive parenting attitudes called the Intensive Parenting Attitudes Questionnaire (IPAQ). Studies have shown mixed results in terms of intensive parenting attitudes being linked with positive and negative outcomes. However, scholars have pointed to this construct as being rooted in White, middle-class ideals that are not necessarily accurate for parents with other identities and the IPAQ has failed to show measurement invariance across racial groups. The current literature lacks representation in understanding the experiences and effects of intensive parenting in racially and economically diverse populations, therefore, it is reasonable to question whether intensive parenting is a valid construct for all parents. This dissertation aimed to discover the extent to which this concept may or may not be inclusive for parents who do not identify as White and/or middle-class. Through theories of intensive parenting and intersectionality, this dissertation utilized a convergent mixed-method design to test the content validity of the IPAQ through a confirmatory factor analysis and measurement invariance analyses. Additionally, through semi-structured interviews, this study aimed to discover how key domains of intensive parenting were described. A racially, ethnically, and economically diverse sample of parents was recruited resulting in 465 participants for quantitative analyses, and 15 parents were selected for qualitative interviews. This study aimed to answer the following research questions: Among a racially and economically diverse sample of parents, what is the content validity of the IPAQ? And among a racially and economically diverse sample of parents, how are key domains of intensive parenting described? Through the confirmatory factor analysis, results indicated that the data did not fit the five-factor model of the IPAQ well. Seven alternative models were run to find better model fit and with one of these models, measurement invariance analyses were conducted. These tests revealed that the alternative model only showed configural invariance across racial groups but demonstrated scalar invariance across racial groups. Qualitative results suggested that intensive parenting is a relevant concept in a racially and economically diverse sample, as descriptions of the key domains were consistent with previous literature. The quantitative and qualitative data were merged through an integrative analysis to discover how results converged, diverged, and were expanded upon. These findings highlighted how contextual variables, such as race and socioeconomic status, played a key role in the quantitative and qualitative results. While intensive parenting appears to be an important construct in a racially and economically diverse sample, more research is needed to fully understand how to quantitatively measure intensive parenting attitudes, specifically for racially marginalized populations.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Human Development and Family Science in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 25, 2024.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

TITLE: Effects of a Pre-Laboratory Simulation in the Chemistry Lab

AUTHOR: Vagle, Angelica

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Ke, Fengfeng

MEMBER (university representative): Ganley, Colleen M.

MEMBER (committee member): Klein, James D.

MEMBER (committee member): Dennen, Vanessa P., 1970-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Psychology and Learning Systems

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (109 pages)

ABSTRACT: The 21st century technology has advanced to become an accessible beacon of education.The physical boundaries of the chemistry laboratory have expanded with the use of innovative virtual lab simulations despite disparate results from previous investigations of student performance comparing virtual lab simulations with traditional laboratory teaching methods. The need to characterize performance holistically and evaluate a combination of virtual labs with traditional methods has prompted a paradigm shift. This dissertation aims to examine the effectiveness of a low immersive virtual chemistry pre-lab simulation that complements the traditional chemistry laboratory in achieving student cognitive and skill-based learning outcomes and student experiential satisfaction in the General chemistry I course. The student achievement measures include cognitive and skill-based outcomes, time on task, and student experiential satisfaction taken for two General chemistry I experiments. A quasi-experimental with repeated post-tests only with a control group research design is implemented at a Florida state college. A convenient sample of General chemistry I course sections is randomly assigned to either a combination of virtual pre-lab simulation with a traditional chemistry laboratory (treatment) or traditional pre-lab and chemistry laboratory (control). The covariance (ANCOVA) analysis of repeated cognitive and lab skills measures revealed that the treatment group significantly outperformed the control group in both cognitive post pre-lab tests. However, the control group attained the greatest increase in cognitive scores between the post pre-lab and post lab tests. The time of task revealed significant differences, though not consistently for the same group, highlighting a difference between laboratory topics. The lab-skills tests showed that both groups performed similarly with no significant difference suggesting that neither approach may have contributed to their lab skills development. Students also had similar experiential satisfaction with no significant difference between the virtual pre-lab simulation and the pre-lab in the traditional laboratory manual.

FILENAME: VanMeter_fsu_0071E_18704.pdf

TITLE: Process-Structure-Property Relationships of Ultralow Wear Polytetrafluoroethylene Composites

AUTHOR: Van Meter, Kylie Elizabeth

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Krick, Brandon

MEMBER (university representative): Liang, Zhiyong (Richard)

MEMBER (committee member): Larbalestier, D. (David)

MEMBER (committee member): Shoele, Kourosh

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mechanical Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (287 pages)

ABSTRACT: Polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) is a thermoplastic polymeric material that is chemically inert, vacuum compatible, has a low surface energy, and has a large operating temperature range due to its high melting temperature. PTFE is also the lowest friction bulk polymer, which has led to its use as a solid lubricant in a wide variety of application spaces including, but not limited to, friction modifiers in oils and greases and in low friction coatings. However, PTFE suffers from extremely high wear rates, which limits its ability to be used as a bulk solid lubricant material. The addition of filler materials to bulk PTFE has resulted in wear rates that are 10-10,000x lower than PTFE alone. There are several wear reducing mechanisms for PTFE composite materials that have been developed in previous studies, including: 1) the prevention of crack propagation and delamination of PTFE, 2) the mechanochemical alteration of the material at the sliding interface, and 3) the modification of the sliding interface through filler accumulation and inclusion, which reinforces the material at the sliding interface. This work seeks to further understand the wear reducing mechanisms for ultralow wear PTFE composite materials under varying contact conditions, and to develop process-structure-property relationships for a multi-polymer composite material, PTFE and poly ether ketone ketone (PEKK) blends, and link these relationships to fundamental wear mechanisms. In this work, an ultralow wear composite is developed - a PTFE-PEKK blend. PEKK is a thermoplastic polymeric material with excellent mechanical, thermal, and chemical properties but suffers from high friction and moderate wear. It is found that PTFE-PEKK composite materials can result in wear rates which are 1,000 – 10,000x lower than the wear rates of bulk PTFE, and low wear behavior can be produced at high weight percent loadings of PEKK. The wear and friction behaviors along with the mechanical and thermal properties of the composites are found to be dependent on the ratio of the content of PTFE and PEKK in the composite. The environmental sensitivity of the material was investigated, demonstrating that the wear reducing mechanisms of the composite do not depend as heavily on mechanochemically developed species at the interface that many other low wear PTFE composite materials rely on, but require the accumulation of PEKK at the sliding interface. This PTFE-PEKK composite material's structure and properties can be changed significantly through the thermal processing conditions that the material undergoes, which is found to be due in large part to a thermal degradation mechanism present in PEKK at temperatures necessary for processing PTFE and PEKK composite materials. Thermal degradation of the PEKK in the composites and subsequent crosslinking of the material leads to an increase in storage modulus of the composite, and a decrease in the viscous response of the composite with increasing temperature. Wear rate and friction coefficient are found to decrease with increasing thermal degradation of the PEKK in the composite. Other materials are investigated, including alumina particles and poly ether ether ketone (PEEK), which is a thermoplastic material within the same family of polyaryletherketones as PEKK. Wear and friction measurements, along with chemical analysis of the sliding interface using infrared spectroscopy, are performed on composites comprised of PTFE blended with PEEK and PTFE filled with alumina. Through the variation of sliding contact conditions and contacting materials, it is found that the PTFE-alumina composite requires a high surface energy gradient and hard sliding countersurface to initiate the filler particle breakdown and reincorporation into the tribofilm that leads to the development of tribochemical species and the low wear behavior. In contrast, PTFE-PEEK composites achieve ultralow wear through the accumulation of PEEK at the interface but do not need a hard countersurface to achieve this, and benefit from contacting surfaces which are conformal, do not abrade the material, and have similar surface energies.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Mechanical Engineering in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 22, 2024.

NOTE (Keywords): Friction, Polyetherketoneketone, Polytetrafluoroethylene, Tribology, Ultralow Wear

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Brandon A. Krick, Professor Directing Dissertation; Zhiyong Liang, University Representative; David C. Larbalestier, Committee Member; Kourosh Shoele, Committee Member.

TITLE: Sustainable Production Labor in Academic Theatre: How the University Can Shape the Industry

AUTHOR: Vaught, Piper

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Osborne, Elizabeth A., 1977-

MEMBER (committee member): LaReau, Brandon

MEMBER (committee member): Salata, Kris

MEMBER (committee member): Sammarco, Casey

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Fine Arts

CORPORATE NAME: School of Theatre

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (99 pages)

ABSTRACT: Since its inception in the early twentieth century, academic theatre has used practical production experiences as a link between education and the professional industry. This experience was propelled by the educational pioneers, George Pierce Baker, Hallie Flanagan, and Thomas Wood Stevens, claiming production work as an essential tool for industry improvement and professionalization. However, universities struggled with the placement of this non-traditional academic work, frequently leaving it to be an extra-curricular component and placing large amounts of additional labor on student participants. Today, contemporary collegiate theatre programs continue the tradition of practical production work as tools of industry improvement and professionalization, with this requirement now codified by the National Association for Schools of Theatre's (NAST) accreditation standards. This thesis will trace the history of production work in academic theatre from the early programs such as Harvard and Yale to Florida State University's current School of Theatre (FSU SOT). This history will culminate in an exploration of educational ideals in practice as an examination of my autoethnographic approach as the calling stage manager for one of FSU's fall productions. This experience allows a glimpse at how FSU's ideals manifest in the production process, focusing on the labor of student participants and the sustainable systems that have been implemented to protect the wellbeing of these students. This thesis proposes that academic theatre more closely returns to the original mission of industry improvement, working as a try-out space for sustainable labor practices that can shift the professional industry away from its current normalization of burnout and exhaustion.

NOTE (Keywords): academic theatre, professionalization, stage management, sustainable labor

FILENAME: Vazquez_fsu_0071N_18759.pdf

TITLE: Modeling the Effects of Single Letter Frequency on Single Letter Naming Times

AUTHOR: Vazquez, Cristian E.

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Schatschneider, Christopher

MEMBER (committee member): Compton, Donald L., 1960-

MEMBER (committee member): Kaschak, Michael P.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Psychology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (36 pages)

ABSTRACT: Research has shown that the frequency of patterns in everyday print influences the naming speed of those patterns. The present study aims to investigate the impact of single-letter frequency on naming time in the Rapid Automatized Naming (RAN) task, specifically the isolated (discrete) version. While previous literature has extensively explored word frequency effects on recognition speed, the influence of single-letter frequency in print on single-letter naming time remains underexplored and inconclusive. The significance of understanding factors that impact letter naming speed lies in its correlation with word reading ability and its role in serial letter naming, which has demonstrated a stronger connection to reading than discrete letter naming. This study sought to determine if single-letter frequency significantly influences naming times in the discrete task and whether single-letter naming time or frequency uniquely predicts naming time in a primed RAN task. These were measured in a study of 108 college-aged students. Results showed that reaction times varied by both the person and the letter in the discrete RAN task. However, single-letter frequency did not account for this variance. The results also showed that reaction times varied by both the person and the letter in the primed RAN task as well. Surprisingly, single letter frequency and discrete RAN emerged as unique predictors of primed RAN accounting for a significant proportion of the variance in reaction times. This finding was unexpected. Single-letter reaction time varying between letters has important implications for measuring RAN assessments that are commonly used in progress monitoring. Single-letter naming time differences may account for some of the variability between forms using different letters. Although letter frequency did not account for this variability, future research should investigate what other factors may explain this variability between letters.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the Department of Psychology in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.

TITLE: Skies and Horizions for Wind Ensemble Skies and Horizons for Wind Ensemble

AUTHOR: Villane, Nicholas James

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (72 pages)

ABSTRACT: Skies & Horizons is a collection of pieces for wind ensemble connected through figurative and literal concepts pertaining to the ground, earth, sea, sky, and stars. The work is divided into ten pieces, totaling twenty-three minutes in length. Succinct and full of character, each piece explores various possibilities, in which the wind ensemble and its subsections can offer. Throughout history, our place on this planet and university have served as a point of inspiration for philosophers, artists, explorers, musicians, and numerous other fields. Concepts and inspiration for the work have manifested in the pieces: Horizon Expanse (1'), Separating Circle (1:45'), Celestia (2:30'), Mirage (2'), Kite-Flying (3'), Redwoods (3'), Soarin' (2:30'), Sky Dive (2:45'), Vanishing Point (2:00'), and Fireside (3:30') for a combined duration of approximately 24 minutes. While unified under the concept of Skies & Horizons, each piece are distinct in their own right. Horizon Expanse opens the work with a powerful fanfare, Three pieces feature the subsection of the wind ensemble, Mirage – percussion, Redwoods – woodwinds, Soarin' – brass. Separating Circle and Vanishing Point represent intricate and technical pieces with angular motives and rhythmic patterns, while Celestia, Kite-Flying, and Sky Dive incorporate more flowing, melodic passages. Fireside concludes the work with a requiem in a celebration for life lived and loved.

TITLE: How I Make It through: An Exploratory Study of the Experiences of Black High School Males in a Predominantly White Community

AUTHOR: Vinson, Stephen A.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Rutledge, Stacey A.

MEMBER (university representative): Wright, James E.

MEMBER (committee member): Iatarola, Patrice

MEMBER (committee member): Park, Toby J.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (111 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation utilizes a basic qualitative exploratory approach to examine the schooling experiences of eight Black high school males in a predominantly White community. It seeks to understand how they define and make sense of their own mental health and well-being through a theoretical framework of Mental Health and Well-being: A Socio-Ecological Model (Michaels et al., 2022). The findings of this dissertation revealed that the schooling experiences of Black males is multifaceted, with both positive and negative aspects that influence their understanding and management of their mental health and well-being. Despite this complexity, participants generally expressed a positive overall mental health, attributing this to a range of coping skills they would employ when faced with challenging situations. While peers and school staff were perceived as sources of support in navigating challenges, they were also identified as contributors to issues related to school belonging, safety, and racial identity. Participants discussed the pressures of acceptance while also navigating instances of racism and microaggressions from their peers and school staff. However, participants were able to acknowledge that their involvement with extracurricular activities and the support provided by their school regarding mental health and well-being, had a positive impact, mitigating some of the challenges faced by Black males. The implications of this study are relevant for school officials, administrators, teachers, researchers, and families, providing insights into how to better support Black males attending schools in predominantly White communities. Keywords: Black Males, High School, Mental Health and Well-being, White Communities

FILENAME: Vojvodin_fsu_0071E_18220.pdf

TITLE: Mechanochemical Synthesis, Characterization, and Quadrupolar NMR Crystallography of Multicomponent Crystals

AUTHOR: Vojvodin, Cameron Spencer

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Schurko, Robert W.

MEMBER (university representative): Hill, S. (Stephen Olof)

MEMBER (committee member): Latturner, Susan

MEMBER (committee member): Silvers, Robert

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (305 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation focuses on the mechanochemical synthesis of several families of multicomponent crystals (MCCs), their characterization by multinuclear solid-state NMR (SSNMR) and powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD), and their structure determination by single crystal XRD (SCXRD) and/or NMR-guided Rietveld refinements. All MCCs reported herein are inorganic-organic hybrids featuring different combinations of simple organic molecules with alkali or ammonium chloride salts, and sometimes water. The MCCs were prepared via ball milling, with syntheses optimized for maximum yield and efficiency. NMR crystallography (NMRX), which features a combination of multinuclear SSNMR, XRD methods, and dispersion-corrected plane-wave DFT calculations, was used to validate, refine, and in some cases, aid in solving the crystal structures via Rietveld analysis. The NMRX work herein relies upon quadrupolar nuclides (i.e., those with spin > ½), with an emphasis on 35Cl SSNMR of chloride ions (Cl–) present in each MCC, as well as alkali metal SSNMR (7Li, 23Na, 39K, 87Rb, 133Cs). Additionally, comparisons of experimental and calculated 35Cl electric field gradient (EFG) tensors are presented as guiding metrics for structural validation, and to elucidate their relationships to molecular-level structures and crystallographic symmetry. In Chapter 2, five MCCs of the form NR4Cl:xUrea·yH2O (R = H, Et, n-Pr; x = 1, 2; y = 0, 2) were prepared to demonstrate the utility of 35Cl SSNMR for use in NMRX investigations. 35Cl SSNMR spectra reveal powder patterns that act as spectral fingerprints for each MCC, while also detecting residual educts not observed in corresponding PXRD patterns. DFT calculations on geometry-optimized structures yielded 35Cl EFG tensors in good agreement with experiment, except for NH4Cl:Urea; hence, ab initio molecular dynamics (aiMD) simulations were used to study the impact of molecular motions of NH4+ cations on the 35Cl EFG tensors, and their concomitant use for structural characterization. Chapter 3 explores accelerated aging (AA) reactions that produce four of the MCCs from Chapter 2, using in situ and ex situ 35Cl SSNMR and ex situ PXRD for monitoring. Different aspects of the AA reactions were investigated, such as mechanical activation (ball milling vs. gentle mixing), environmental conditions (temperature and humidity), sample packing and unpacking, and different reactant ratios. Comparisons of the AA reactions yielding NH4Cl:Urea and NEt4Cl:2Urea demonstrate that the induction times dramatically impact reaction rates. Reaction mixtures of NPr4Cl and urea in 1:2 and 1:3 ratios produced MCCs with very different AA rates, and revealed a series of transient species, offering insight into competitive kinetic and thermodynamic effects on AA reactions. In Chapter 4, two classes of MCCs of the forms MCl:xCA (CA = cyanuric acid; M = Li, Na, Rb, Cs; x = 1, 2) and MCl:xBA∙yH2O (BA = barbituric acid; x = 1, 2; y = 0, 2; M = Li, Na, K, Rb, Cs) were prepared with ball milling. Twelve MCCs were characterized using multinuclear SSNMR, including 35Cl, 13C, and alkali metal nuclides, as well as PXRD and SCXRD methods. Seven novel MCl:xBA∙yH2O MCCs were discovered, and new crystal structures are reported for five of these. Alkali metal SSNMR spectra aid in determining the number of distinct sites and rapidly detecting residual educts. Comparison of experimental and calculated 35Cl EFG tensors suggests they are influenced by both H⋯Cl– hydrogen bonds and electrostatic interactions involving alkali cations. Finally, Chapter 5, which combines many ideas from the preceding chapters, features three MCCs of the form MCl:Urea∙xH2O (M = Li, Na, Cs; x = 0, 1) that were prepared via ball milling and NMRX-guided Rietveld refinements to solve their crystal structures. 35Cl SSNMR was the most useful technique for their characterization, due to its inherent sensitivity to different H⋯Cl– hydrogen bonding configurations. 23Na MAS NMR allowed for the in situ monitoring of the autocatalytic degradation of NaCl:Urea∙H2O. All characterization data were used to inform the initial structures for Rietveld analysis, with final Rietveld structures subjected to DFT geometry optimizations, enabling exploration of relationships between the local hydrogen bonding environments of the chloride ions and NMR interaction tensors. It is anticipated that the synthetic methods herein will be used to generate a broad range of MCCs of increasing complexity, featuring different metal ions, simple organic molecules, and ratios of components. These highly efficient syntheses, in combination with the characterization protocols described herein, could be beneficial for the design of new quadrupolar NMRX techniques for validating, refining, and solving the crystal structures for a wide range of MCCs where conventional characterization methods fall short, perhaps even allowing for the prediction of hitherto unknown structures in tandem with modern crystal structure prediction methods.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): July 12, 2023.

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (59 pages)

ABSTRACT: The purpose of this content analysis was to explore the current literature published in American Music Therapy Association journals regarding vocational skills for adults with intellectual and developmental disabilities (I/DD). A content analysis of 15 articles was completed and analyzed for (a) the prevalence of literature addressing vocational skills and rehabilitation with individuals with I/DD, (b) the methodologies used in research on this topic, (c) the music therapy goals and interventions discussed in current literature, and (d) the settings in which music therapists address vocational skills with individuals with I/DD. Of the articles analyzed, most research was found in Journal of Music Therapy, with only three articles published on the topic within the last 20 years. The most prominent goal in the literature was social and interpersonal skills, and instrument play was the most mentioned type of intervention. Due to the gap in literature, further and more current research is needed on music therapy and vocational skills with individuals with I/DD.

TITLE: A Case Study of Elementary Preservice Teachers' Environmental Literacy

AUTHOR: Wagner, Lauren E.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Ibourk, Amal

MEMBER (university representative): Roehrig, Alysia D., 1975-

MEMBER (committee member): Southerland, Sherry A., 1962-

MEMBER (committee member): Jones, Ithel

MEMBER (committee member): Braaten, Melissa L.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: School of Teacher Education

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (198 pages)

ABSTRACT: Scholars have advocated for more environmental education (EE) within elementary preservice teacher education through science methods courses as elementary preservice teachers have consistently demonstrated limited environmental literacy. This is critical as environmental issues continue to threaten our world, preservice teachers must demonstrate the environmental literacy needed to teach our youngest students about the impacts of these problems on communities. The goal of this qualitative case study was to explore how four preservice teachers who engaged in a semester of EE demonstrated environmental literacy and reflected on instructional practices that aligned with the Ambitious Science Teaching instructional framework that was implemented during the science methods course. In-depth interviews with preservice teachers, along with an analysis of their written work during the semester, revealed that they drew on their own funds of knowledge to demonstrate knowledge and a sense of concern about environmental issues and the impact they have on communities in different ways. However, preservice teachers mainly showed individualistic ideas about these problems and were reluctant to take action within the community to address them. This research also suggests future instructional approaches to strengthen preservice teachers' environmental literacy to best prepare them to engage their future elementary students in EE, helping our youngest learners understand more about the world around them.

FILENAME: Walia_fsu_0071E_18625.pdf

TITLE: Understanding the Effects of Higher-Order Assembly on the Structure of Sulfite Reductase

AUTHOR: Walia, Nidhi

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Stroupe, M. Elizabeth (Margaret Elizabeth)

MEMBER (university representative): Yang, Wei

MEMBER (committee member): Dennis, Jonathan Hancock

MEMBER (committee member): Bass, Hank W.

MEMBER (committee member): Yin, Qian (Assistant professor of biological science)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Biological Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (132 pages)

ABSTRACT: Oxidoreductase enzyme complexes are one of the known biomolecular machines, which play a cru- cial role in cellular biochemistry including metabolic, signaling, and electron transport pathways. In these complexes, individual subunits can oligomerize to form homo-multimers or hetero-multimers and can transiently interact with redox enzyme partners to perform multistep enzymatic reactions. Multi-subunit oxidoreductases can show inter- and intra-subunit domain interactions by switching from open to closed conformations in order to deliver electrons to their oxidase partners. Assimi- latory sulfite reductase (SiR) is an NADPH-dependent multidomain oxidoreductase that catalyzes sulfur reduction to produce sulfide, the bioavailable form of sulfur for subsequent synthesis of biomolecules. In Escherichia coli, SiR is a dodecameric holoenzyme, consisting of eight subunits of a flavoprotein (SiRFP) and four subunits of a hemoprotein (SiRHP). SiRFP is a diflavin reductase, a homolog of cytochrome P450 reductase (CPR) that is composed of the following domains: a FMN binding flavodoxin (Fld)-like-domain, a connection domain interrupting FAD/NADPH bind- ing FNR (Ferredoxin/NADP+ reductase)-like-domain and a flexible linker connecting Fld and FNR domains. This flexible linker is ∼ 30 amino acids long and remains crucial for transferring electrons from one domain to another. SiRHP is a metal-harboring domain that contains a siroheme (iron- containing tetrapyrrole) cofactor at the active site covalently coupled with Fe4S4 cluster through cysteine conjugations. Chapter 1 provides an introduction of multi domain oxidoreductases with a main focus on SiR and its homologs.Chapter 2 provides information about small-angle scattering technique including both neutron scattering and X-ray scattering. Small-angle neutron scattering (SANS) and neutron contrast variation technique are discussed in detail. SANS is used to analyze the solution structure of proteins and gives information about the radius of gyration, inter atomic distances between the particles, shape and size of the protein sample and also gives an approximate idea about the molecular weight of the sample. Chapter 3 includes the structural characterization of the SiR complex. SANS, neutron contrast variation, analytical ultracentrifugation and other biophysical techniques showed that SiR is an asymmetric complex. SiRFP undergoes compaction in the complex as compared to the free SiRFP and the four SiRHP binds at the periphery of the complex. This study showed the first solution structure of the SiR complex. Chapter 4 provides information about the two conformationally restricted variants of SiRFP and showed the possibility of open and closed conformations of SiRFP. This study showed the presence of domain crossover in SiRFP which indicates that the Fld domain of one polypeptide can interact with the FNR domain of an adjacent polypeptide. The SANS measurements provide the first model of the possible arrangement of eight subunits of SiRFP and showed that the N-terminal helical bundle acts as a central core of the complex. Chapter 5 presents a study about a novel variant of SiRFP which forms a tetramer. The N- terminus region of SiRFP consists of only 52 amino acids which oligomerizes to form an octamer. This study showed that four amino acids (Y39, F40, Q22, Q47) of the SiRFP's N-terminus region play a crucial role in the oligomerization of the eight copies of SiRFP. These residues show aromatic stacking (Y39, F40) and salt bridge interactions (Q22, Q47) between the helices and thus form a strong octameric bundle. Mutating these four amino acids results in a tetrameric assembly of SiRFP. The ultra stable properties of SiRFP's N-terminus octameric helical bundle are also discussed in this chapter. Chapter 6 includes the cryo-EM studies of SiR. SiR is a challenging sample to study using cryo-EM due to its sensitivity to the air-water interface during the grid preparation. This chapter reveals that a minimal binding interface is present between the SiRFP and SiRHP dimer. This study also shows the first high resolution structure of the SiRFP/SiRHP variant and explains that this minimal interaction is governed by the N-terminus of SiRHP and the FNR domain of SiRFP. Additionally, the highly flexible Fld domain of SiRFP explains its accessibility for transferring electrons to its redox partner. The last chapter highlights the future direction of the SiR project. It explains the ongoing crystallization related work for the different variants of SiRFP. Chapter 7 also includes the trou- bleshooting of SiR's sample preparation for cryo-EM studies which aims to solve the high resolution structure of this complex.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Biological Science in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): March 22, 2024.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): M. Elizabeth Stroupe, Professor Directing Dissertation; Wei Yang, University Representative; Jonathan Dennis, Committee Member; Hank Bass, Committee Member; Qian Yin, Committee Member.

TITLE: Triple Threat: A Study of American Musical Theatre Training

AUTHOR: Waringer, Laura London

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Salata, Kris

MEMBER (university representative): Atkins, Jennifer

MEMBER (committee member): Thomas, Aaron C.

MEMBER (committee member): Arespacochaga, Chari

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Fine Arts

CORPORATE NAME: School of Theatre

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (309 pages)

ABSTRACT: Triple Threat: A Study of American Musical Theatre Training, explores the history, growth, ethics, and progression of professional musical theatre training and BFA musical theatre programs in the United States. As this type of accredited conservatory training has existed for less than sixty years, this project ultimately seeks to pioneer an intensive inquiry into the evolution of musical theatre training, both prior to its existence within the academy and in the BFA context, and trace its relationship with the professional theatre industry. The first part of this work will historicize musical theatre training in America prior to its placement within academia, highlighting the foundations of existing methodologies, delving into the backgrounds of its most influential contributors, and identifying the strengths and challenges presented by the training throughout its development. The second part will chart the history of BFA musical theatre training within academia, contextualizing the evolution of the training within the larger framework of American higher education. This portion of the work will utilize three case studies conducted from a sampling of BFA musical theatre programs across the country to recount their respective histories and evolution, gain insight into the structures and goals of each program, and assess their relationship with the professional industry. Using the information learned from the historical research and case study portions of the project, the final part of this study will address the challenges and potentialities of current musical theatre training. An encompassing scope of the entire work will examine the inherent and pathological diversity and inclusion problems in both academia and the professional musical theatre industry. I seek to analyze how both institutions inform, uphold, or challenge the other, and how both entities may strategize for progress and change in these areas to create a more equitable industry, which I propose begins with the training. My study aims to unpack the promise of "Triple Threat training" that purports to develop well-rounded performers equally proficient in acting, singing, and dancing, where the curriculum seems to be both defined and limited by a set of prescribed skill sets. While mastery of skills valued by the existing industry is an undoubtedly important component of this training, I argue that musical theatre training must evolve to emphasize the areas in which scholarship, artistry, and craftsmanship may converge, developing artist-thinkers who can identify possibilities in the industry that may not be currently presented. I thus propose that this can be achieved through a new Triple Threat training model that replaces the pillared standards of acting, singing, and dancing with artistry, advocacy, and entrepreneurship.

TITLE: It's All the Same: Genre Generalization in the American Music Industry

AUTHOR: Washington, Clinton James, III

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Gunderson, Frank D.

MEMBER (committee member): Von Glahn, Denise, 1950-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2024

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (93 pages)

ABSTRACT: In the American music industry, genre is used to efficiently organize music into digestible forms for consumers, critics, and creators. The trade-off for efficiency in this industry is fewer genre options, which leads to songs and artists being placed in imprecise categories. Across the American music industry, streaming platforms (e.g. Spotify), media (e.g. Billboard), distributors (e.g. record stores), and award shows affect how artists' music is viewed, assessed, heard, and consumed. A prime example of commercial efficiency is the misplacement of artists into specific award categories at the Recording Academy's Grammy Awards Show. In the past year, this has resulted in Drake and The Weekend, two of the biggest pop music stars in the world, withholding their music for the 2023 Grammy submission. Their decision is a reaction to the Recording Academy's inaccurate assessment of artists and their work. Across the industry, genre handling has provided many results that benefit various parties. This thesis aims to examine how the music industry's efficient approach to handling genre compares to that of the fans who consume music daily.Genre is ever-evolving by the people who make and consume it, but it is limited to the musical elements deemed a standard of that genre by American music companies. David Brackett states that the music industry uses "marketing categories" with varying rules and restrictions that are amendable to the organization of music. In contrast, fans view music as "critic-fan genres" with specific rules and qualifications for artists and songs to fit into particular genres. I will extend Brackett's genre theory by providing further insight into how the American music industry's approach to handling genre affects artists and consumers. To accomplish this, I will use ethnographic methods and music analysis to provide critical commentary and analytical proof for my discussion on genre. I understand that the music industry encompasses all areas of music, so I will use hip-hop and Latin trap as case studies to show how people associated with the most popular music genres are affected. By providing a detailed examination of how the industry and consumers view well-known genres, I would like this thesis to assist consumers and music industry insiders in learning about the various ways we can improve on the current genre classification system across the American music industry.

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (153 pages)

ABSTRACT: Dollhouse Dreams and Other Broken Things is a collection of personal essays exploring issues of the body, the historically silenced voice and shifting notions of femininity. The collection also investigates how myths that shape the body are continually carried down and reinforced by families, institutions, and culture. This essay collection is both a deconstruction of these myths and a reconstruction of what the body/home can look like—or rather what it means to (re)build after the deconstruction of patriarchal values. These essays illuminate both the holding of breath and the relinquishing of voice, but also the stirring movements towards agency. One sub-focus of this essay collection includes an interrogation of the fairy tale childhood—one that not only encourages a belief in happy endings anchored by a prince charming but also encourages this magical thinking in other avenues. Instead of doing away with these classic tales, I merge them with autobiographical essays in order to bring the woman back into these stories written by men, rebuilding and reshaping patriarchal representations of womanhood in the process.

TITLE: The Discovery, Exploration, and Evolution of Treefrog Biofluorescence

AUTHOR: Whitcher, Courtney
