TITLE: Teacher Morale and District and School Leadership in a Rural, High Poverty, and Ethnically Diverse District

AUTHOR: Johnson, Shakia

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Akiba, Motoko

MEMBER (university representative): Guthrie, Kathy L.

MEMBER (committee member): Milligan, Jeffrey Ayala

MEMBER (committee member): Jones, Ithel

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (90 pages)

ABSTRACT: The research questions addressed in this exploratory survey research were: 1) what is the degree of teachers' morale, and what perceptions do teachers have about their district and school leadership, 2) how does the degree of teachers' morale differ by their background characteristics, and 3) how are teacher perceptions of district and school leadership associated with their sense of morale, controlling for their background characteristics in the Friendship (pseudonym) County School District (FCSD)? While many studies have established the link between school leadership and teacher morale, few studies have explored teachers' sense of morale and relationship with district and school leadership using a districtwide teacher survey in an ethnically diverse and economically disadvantaged district such as the Friendship (pseudonym) County School District (FCSD). Based on a districtwide survey of 123 teachers, I found that the overall degree of teacher morale in the Friendship County School District (FCSD) is high. This study also found that the degree of morale was significantly and negatively associated with the level of stress and health impact, showing that teachers who experience more stress and negative job impacts on their mental and physical health are more likely to report a lower degree of morale. Another significant finding was that the five dimensions of school leadership and, likewise, five dimensions of district leadership are significantly and positively associated with the degree of morale; thus, teachers who perceive their leadership positively along these five dimensions are more likely to report higher morale. Implications and recommendations for district and school leadership for increasing teacher morale are offered.

TITLE: Engaging Librarians in the Science of Reading Engaging Librarians in the Science of Reading: The Implications of Direct Instruction in Evidnece Based Practice for Language and Literacy Development The Implications of Direct Instruction in Evidence Based Practice for Language and Literacy Development

AUTHOR: Johnson, Brittani R.

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Johnson, Lakeisha

MEMBER (committee member): Farquharson, Kelly

MEMBER (committee member): Romano, Mollie

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Communication and Information

CORPORATE NAME: School of Communication Science and Disorders

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (44 pages)

ABSTRACT: The purpose of this study was to first determine whether a librarian's years of experience positively correlated with their literacy knowledge and efficacy, and to second determine whether structured exposure to specific and targeted education of evidence-based strategies for literacy could enable librarians to improve their knowledge of the tenants of literacy and early language development. 10 librarians from a North Florida Public Library System were surveyed prior to and upon completion of an 8-week professional training course targeting evidence-based strategies for language and literacy development. The pre-training survey, consisting of 7 demographic, 25 knowledge, and 15 efficacy questions, intended to serve as a baseline of the librarians' knowledge of general language components, acquisition, and development, as well as their level of confidence in employing their knowledge to promote early language and literacy development (efficacy). The post-training survey consisted of the same knowledge and efficacy questions with the addition of 5 free-response questions. Data were collected on the pre- and post-knowledge and efficacy responses. All participants demonstrated an increase in the number of correct knowledge responses and increased efficacy ratings from pre-training to post-training. Additionally, years of experience was found to positively correlate with the librarians' efficacy ratings pre-training. However, years of experience was observed to have a mild negative correlation with pre-training knowledge. Implications of this study suggest that although exposure to structured training for language and literacy may be helpful in improving knowledge and efficacy in youth service librarians, years of experience in the role does not guarantee that veteran librarians will possess more knowledge than those newer to the field. A wider scope of training and content is needed to ensure strong foundations of knowledge.

TITLE: Characterizing the Interactions between Gene Delivery Polyplexes and Bio-Inspired Polymeric Surface Coatings for Localized Gene Therapy

AUTHOR: Joshi, Sailesti

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Holmes, Christina A. (Christina Andrea)

MEMBER (committee member): Driscoll, Tristan

MEMBER (committee member): Guan, Jingjiao

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Chemical and Biomedical Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (92 pages)

ABSTRACT: Nucleic acid delivery is crucial for several biomedical applications, including tissue engineering, medical implant coatings, cancer treatment and regenerative medicine. Localized delivery of nucleic acids through biomaterial substrates can overcome several difficulties associated with common systemic delivery and maintain high vector concentrations at the target site to enable increased transfection efficiency. In this project, we aim to develop substrate-based nucleic acid delivery coatings that can provide extended and localized release of non-viral gene delivery vectors for tissue engineering and regenerative medicine applications. In vitro studies are conducted to characterize the absorption and release interactions between surface coatings made of the bio-inspired and naturally derived polymers, including polydopamine (pDA), hyaluronic acid (HA), glycol chitosan (GC), and their combinations, and a model polymeric gene delivery vector composed of polyethyleneimine (PEI). PEI-DNA polyplexes N/P ratio was observed to have a statistically significant impact on the amount of DNA loaded onto each coating, while the surface coating type and concentration were surprisingly found to have no statistically significant effects. Surface-based transfection as well as bolus transfection from these coatings are studied over time for NIH3T3 and HEK293 cells. Surface-based transfection efficiencies were significantly impacted by the coating types and polyplex N/P ratios for transfection on HEK293 cells. However, for transfection on NIH3T3 cells only coating type had a significant impact on the transfection efficiencies. In conclusion, this study adds to our understanding of how different biocompatible materials interact with nucleic acid delivery polyplexes, which aids in the creation of surface coatings that facilitate effective localized nucleic acid delivery for tissue engineering and biomedical implant applications.

TITLE: Unpacking the Association between Callous-Unemotional Traits and Offending

AUTHOR: Joyner-Carpanini, Bridget

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Beaver, Kevin M.

MEMBER (university representative): Tripodi, Stephen J.

MEMBER (committee member): Mears, Daniel P., 1966-

MEMBER (committee member): Turanovic, Jillian J., 1985-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Criminology and Criminal Justice

CORPORATE NAME: College of Criminology and Criminal Justice

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (187 pages)

ABSTRACT: Until the past few decades, criminological research has almost exclusively focused on examining the link between various environmental risk factors and criminal behavior. Since then, an emerging body of research has developed exploring the association between different antisocial traits and offending. The culmination of this research has revealed personality constructs such as low self-control, impulsiveness, aggressiveness, sensation seeking, and Machiavellianism, among others to be positively associated with greater criminal behaviors. However, this area of research, also known as propensity-based studies of offending, remains incomplete. The criminological literature has largely overlooked the potential explanatory power of callous-unemotional traits when attempting to identify the diverse factors that predict assorted offending patterns, including chronic levels of offending. To be certain, research in developmental psychology has linked these traits to a host of negative life outcomes typically found within criminological studies, including offending. And yet, research in the developmental literature has yet to uncover why, and under what conditions, this link exists as well as how this association changes based on the variant of callous-unemotional traits being examined. Likewise, research examining the etiology of callous-unemotional traits has many gaps in the literature particularly concerning male-female differences as well as discerning what environmental risk factors explain such development. This dissertation will address these gaps in the literature by examining potential pathways to the development of both variants of callous-unemotional traits as well as associations between the variants and various offending measures (i.e., general, nonviolent, violent, life-course-persistent offending, and illicit drug use). The results revealed that the etiology of both variants of callous-unemotional traits is dependent upon the sex of the individual. Additionally, the environmental factors that predicted callous-unemotional traits were different based on the variant being investigated. The models examining the callous-unemotional traits-crime link likewise found that the association differed based on the variant as well as the sex of the individual. The results of these analyses also find support for the link being nonlinear and partially due to a shared genetic etiology. The implications of these findings are discussed in reference to policy, theory, and future research.

TITLE: Examination of Rating Discrepancies in Multi-Informant Assessments of Childhood Behaviors across Domains: A Meta-Analytic Study

AUTHOR: Jungersen, Colleen

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Lonigan, Christopher J.

MEMBER (university representative): Whalon, Kelly J.

MEMBER (committee member): Wagner, Richard K.

MEMBER (committee member): Joiner, Thomas, Jr.

MEMBER (committee member): Meyer, Alexandria

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Psychology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (108 pages)

ABSTRACT: Throughout the literature, there is a well-documented discrepancy between rating of children's behaviors across different informants, typically parents and teachers. Many different theories have been investigated to address the root of these discrepancies. Previous studies have examined if these discrepancies are the result of informant interacting with the child across different contexts, teacher expertise in typical childhood behaviors, parent mental health and stress, and the quality of the rating forms. The current study sought to investigate such discrepancies in a meta-analytic framework in which eleven different informant pairs were examined rating eight different behaviors categories. It was hypothesized that the informant pairs that interacted with the children in similar contexts, such as Parent-Parent and Teacher-Teacher informant pairs, would demonstrate more similar ratings. This hypothesis was supported. It was also hypothesized that there would be more agreement on more observable behaviors, such as externalizing behaviors. This hypothesis was not supported. It is important to be able to understand when such rating discrepancies occur, because the ability to anticipate such rating discrepancies can be used in both clinical and empirical research.

FILENAME: Kaminski_fsu_0071N_18183.pdf

TITLE: An Analysis and Explanation of the Representation of the 3-D Warm Core Structure in Tropical Cyclones across Various Reanalysis Datasets

AUTHOR: Kaminski, Anna

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Hart, Robert E. (Robert Edward), 1972-

MEMBER (committee member): Wu, Zhaohua

MEMBER (committee member): Bourassa, Mark Allan

MEMBER (committee member): Liu, Guosheng, (Professor of meteorology)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (63 pages)

ABSTRACT: The warm core structure of a tropical cyclone (TC) has been previously analyzed through aircraft observations, dropsondes, satellite-borne Advanced Microwave Sounding Unit (AMSU) data, and numerical simulations. It has been shown that aircraft that fly through a TC collect data that represent the warm core of a TC well; however, it has been theorized that microwave and satellite data struggle to resolve and represent the warm core structure throughout the entire center of the TC because of the coarseness of the satellite observations. Numerical simulations have been utilized to study the height of the warm core with a maximum around 4-8 km and have found that the height is nearly constant with varying intensities (Stern and Nolan 2012). This study aims to analyze the warm core structure of a TC through reanalysis datasets (ERA5, ERA-Interim, MERRA2), as these datasets are the only ones outside of aircraft and observations, that can provide long duration data of 3-D and 4-D structure. ERA5 has the finest resolution of the three datasets that are analyzed with MERRA2, and ERA-Interim increasingly coarse. The average temperature anomaly with respect to the whole basin from the zonal mean in all basins is about +4-9K in ERA5, +3-6K in ERA-Interim, and +4-8K in MERRA2 with the West Pacific basin having the highest magnitudes of average temperature anomalies. ERA5 typically sees the highest magnitude in terms of maximum average temperature anomaly while ERA-Interim sees the lowest values in all basins, in addition to most of the datasets showing tropical storms being statistically significantly cooler than all other intensities. The height of the warm core, described here as pressure, was subjectively analyzed through the geopotential height anomalies, and was found to be nearly constant with increasing intensity around 350-400 hPa, with the West Pacific having the highest warm core around 300 hPa. These results suggest that the strength of the warm core varies within each basin and within different reanalysis datasets. The resolution of the datasets carries a large role in how well the warm core is represented, however, the strength is comparable to prior works. The height of the warm core in this study showed to be more constant with differing intensities which is different than what was found in previous works where the height of the warm core increased with intensity.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.

NOTE (Date of Defense): June 29, 2023.

NOTE (Keywords): Tropical Meteorology

TITLE: Dominant Cultures: Examining Perceptions of an LGBTQ+ Campus Environment

AUTHOR: King, Kaylee M.

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Ludwig, Eric

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Jones, Tamara Bertrand

MEMBER (university representative): Whalon, Kelly J.

MEMBER (committee member): Beatty, Cameron C.

MEMBER (committee member): Guthrie, Kathy L.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (107 pages)

ABSTRACT: LGBTQ+ students exist on college campuses in greater numbers than ever before. Campus culture directly impacts how LGBTQ+ students experience college and contributes to their overall sense of belonging. Campus culture in turn is shaped by students' access to resources and the effectiveness of those resources. Students' experiences, for better or for worse, are shaped by the programming they have access to and the environment the college fosters through these programs. This dissertation in practice examines the relationship between LGBTQ+ students on Emerson College's campus and the resources they use. Utilizing an exploratory case study methodology including focus groups and campus observations, this research examines the following questions: What are the experiences of Emerson's LGBTQ+ students? How do Emerson's LGBTQ+ programs and policies meet the needs of LGBTQ+ students on campus? In what ways do Emerson's efforts enhance LGBTQ+ students' feelings of belonging? This study found that many organizations and campus spaces operate as queer by default due to the orientation of their members, shaping the way that students experience campus culture. As such, other motivators such as race, ethnicity, and background prior to coming to college influence the connections students seek on campus moreso than their LGBTQ+ identity. This study also found that LGBTQ+ students experienced belonging in both LGBTQ+ campus activities and non-LGBTQ+ campus activities, although students do feel a need for more specific LGBTQ+ programming reflective of community struggles. Lastly, findings indicated that students felt that administration and faculty have a major impact on the sense of belonging present on campus as well as the LGBTQ+ offerings of the college, and there is a need for both groups to better their efforts as students feel they are earnest but misguided. The findings of this study revealed multiple implications for practice. Most of all, sense of belonging on campus for LGBTQ+ students encompasses many components, all directly related to their base need for connection. This means their sense of community cannot be pinpointed on any one item being present, but rather on multiple factors that create genuine relationships with others. LGBTQ+ students on Emerson's campus experience that definition in unique ways unique to Emerson's campus environment – perhaps most significantly, their sense of belonging being influenced greatly by being in the majority and attending a campus where they are able to interact with other LGBTQ+ students in a variety of settings, not just in specific organizations that cater to that population.

FILENAME: King_fsu_0071E_18200.pdf

TITLE: Improving Clinical Risk Models through Integration of Polygenic Risk Scores and Omics

AUTHOR: King, Austin T.

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Huang, Chao

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Wu, Chong

MEMBER (university representative): He, Zhe

MEMBER (committee member): Bradley, Jonathan R.

MEMBER (committee member): Slate, Elizabeth H.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Statistics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (172 pages)

ABSTRACT: Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) have significantly contributed to the identification of genetic variants by leveraging thousands of loci associated with complex traits and diseases, leading to breakthroughs in human genetics research. However, interpretation of these results is often difficult as the GWAS-identified variants (single-nucleotide polymorphisms [SNPs]) often have small effect estimates on target traits, limiting their direct application to disease research. Methods such as polygenic risk score analysis have been presented to enhance disease risk prediction, however, the clinical utility of these methods are controversial. Similarly, the identification of genes associated with likely causal SNPs is unclear as identified SNPs explain only a small portion of heritability. Genetic regulations of GWAS findings are often characterized using statistical methods such as transcriptome-wide association studies (TWAS), but these methods tend to ignore functional mechanisms that play critical roles in gene-regulatory pathways, resulting in loss of predictive power.In this essay we present three integrative methodologies for improving disease risk prediction as well as identifying likely causal genes through incorporation of omics level data and GWAS results for complex traits. First, we propose an integrated PRS method that leverages multiple PRS methods, as well as multiple GWAS datasets, to improve coronary artery disease (CAD) risk prediction over clinically used prediction models (PCE). Our results indicate that our proposed method improves model discrimination for incident CAD cases over the PCE model while also improving risk reclassification in European populations. Second, we propose a Cauchy integrative model that aggregates gene expression levels, DNA methylation, and splicing event information to increase identification of likely causal genes in 24 GWAS complex trait datasets. Additionally, we extend our method to identify causal genes for lung adenocarcinoma risk. Finally, we implement our Cauchy integrative model to identify likely causal omics biomarkers for CAD and propose a penalized regression framework integrative PRS model to improve risk prediction in an African population when limited to a European GWAS and reference panel.

TITLE: Investigation of Crashes Involving Vulnerable Roadway Users Utilizing Geographical Information Systems-Driven Spatio-Temporal Statistical Techniques

AUTHOR: Koloushani, Mohammadreza

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Ozguven, Eren Erman

MEMBER (university representative): Horner, Mark W.

MEMBER (committee member): Moses, Ren

MEMBER (committee member): Sobanjo, John Olusegun, 1958-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (159 pages)

ABSTRACT: Over the last three decades, traffic crashes have been one of the leading causes of fatalities and economic losses in the world. Since vulnerable road users have specific characteristics, they are perceived to have a higher risk of being involved in fatal road crashes. Therefore, it is essential to focus on mitigating the vulnerabilities of roadway users as well as investigating the key causes of crashes in order to achieve the desired level of roadway safety. It is imperative that we understand the specific needs of vulnerable roadway users and their involvement in crashes in order to address their unique challenges, determine the underlying factors contributing to their vulnerability, and develop targeted interventions and policies that can contribute to improving their safety. The level of vulnerability among roadway users depends on a variety of factors, including their age, level of protection, surrounding characteristics, situational conditions, and the presence of extreme events such as disasters. The majority of vulnerabilities cannot be attributed to the negligence of roadway users, since they are primarily determined by an individual's intrinsic physical characteristics and the conditions imposed by particular circumstances. Therefore, this dissertation provided comprehensive insights into helping vulnerable roadway users by examining them from four distinct perspectives: (a) exploring young-driver-involved crashes to understand vulnerability based on age, (b) investigating pedestrian vulnerability due to their lack of protection, (c) examining the challenges faced by drivers experiencing daytime sun glare-induced temporary visual impairment to assess vulnerability in relation to surrounding circumstances, and (d) analyzing the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on the entire society to comprehend vulnerability in the context of a disaster situation.The purpose of the dissertation is to examine the spatial patterns of vulnerable-involved crashes in order to identify those locations that pose high risk to them. Furthermore, we develop several robust statistical models according to the type of dependent variables for each group of vulnerable road users. Based on an in-depth regression analysis, we are able to predict crash likelihood and provide clear guidelines for the development of plans, policies, and effective safety countermeasures. In order to accomplish the objective of the study, we introduce a Geographic Information System (GIS)-based methodology to analyze the spatial crash patterns associated with each crash type in terms of focused vulnerability. This is followed by a more detailed examination of selected counties of Florida using both planar Euclidean Distance (ED) and Roadway Network Distance (RND)-based Kernel Density Estimation (KDE). According to the GIS maps developed in this dissertation, there are differences in spatial patterns between vulnerable roadway users involved in crashes. In conclusion, this dissertation proposes a number of novel methodological approaches in order to address the following objectives: • An investigation of contributing factors influencing crashes caused by vulnerable youth drivers (aged 16-24) and assessment of the correlation between intersection presence near university campuses and likelihood of these crashes, • An assessment of the spatial correlation and impact of the network-based distance between locations of vulnerable pedestrian-involved crashes and the centroid of associated land use of various types, • An assessment of the adverse effects of daytime sun glare on driving performance and evaluation of the potential actions taken by vulnerable drivers under the direct influence of temporary blindness caused by sun glare, • A spatial-temporal investigation of the crash density pattern during the COVID-19 pandemic, assuming all individuals to be vulnerable roadway users, in accordance with the specific socio-demographic features of the study area. Findings clearly show that intersections near university areas pose a significant problem for youth drivers. Moreover, the part of this study focusing on pedestrians as another vulnerable roadway user reveal that pedestrian-involved crashes were more likely to occur near retail stores and nightclubs. Additionally, daylight has an effect regardless of the type of surrounding land use on the severity of pedestrian-related crashes. This dissertation also investigates the temporary visual impairment caused by sun glare during the daytime as well as the likelihood of potential actions performed by drivers experiencing this adverse circumstance. Furthermore, the results obtained from the investigation of crashes caused by vulnerable drivers exposed to daytime sun glare indicate that the majority of observed actions, particularly on local roadways, involve in the violation of stop signs and red lights. In addition, drivers tend to follow too closely in high-traffic areas when their vision is impaired by sun glare. Moreover, a non-parametric method (Kruskal-Wallis) confirms that there is a significant difference in crash densities during the COVID-19 pandemic compared to the pre-pandemic period in different counties irrespective of their sociodemographic differences. Finally, the findings indicate that the presence of young populations (e.g., college students) in Leon County is highly correlated with the decline in the number of crashes during COVID-19. In summary, the results of this dissertation can be utilized by transportation agencies to pinpoint high-risk locations which have a higher likelihood of vulnerable population-involved crashes and to develop more reliable plans targeting the vulnerable population and their special needs. The implementation of safety countermeasures is essential to improving the safety of vulnerable road users. Education campaigns emphasizing defensive driving skills and risk awareness, for example, may be effective in preventing young drivers from engaging in risky driving. Additionally, implementing cutting-edge Intelligent Transportation System (ITS) technologies and offering alternative routes to avoid sun glare may improve driving performance and reduce the number of crashes caused by drivers experiencing daytime sun glare. A pedestrian-friendly environment, which includes crosswalks, adequate lighting, clear signage, and well-maintained sidewalks, also contributes to pedestrian safety. Lastly, promoting alternative remote options for E-learning, e-shopping, teleconsultations, and teleconferencing can reduce the number of trips generated during the COVID-19 pandemic and reduce the risk associated with increased vulnerability while maintaining road safety for all users in the region affected by the pandemic. In this dissertation, material has been incorporated from three papers written by the author (1)–(4). Chapter 2 uses material from References (1), coauthored with Mahyar Ghorbanzadeh, Mehmet Baran Ulak, Eren Erman Ozguven, Mark W. Horner, and Omer Arda Vanli. Meanwhile, Chapter 3 is based on Reference (2), coauthored with Alican Karaer, , Eren Erman Ozguven, Thobias Sando, Maxim A. Dulebenets, and Ren Moses. Meanwhile, Chapter 3 is based on Reference (3), coauthored with Mehmet Burak Kaya, Alican Karaer, and Eren Erman Ozguven. Finally, Chapter 4 is based on Reference (4), coauthored with Mahyar Ghorbanzadeh, Eren Erman Ozguven, and Mehmet Baran Ulak. Some material from each of these papers has also been incorporated into this introductory Chapter.

FILENAME: Krishnan_fsu_0071E_17937.pdf

TITLE: Examining Dynamics of Student Disciplinary Engagement in Science

AUTHOR: Krishnan, Harini

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Jaber, Lama

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Southerland, Sherry A., 1962-

MEMBER (university representative): Winn, Alice A.

MEMBER (committee member): Khurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (committee member): Kurshid, Ayesha

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: School of Teacher Education

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (203 pages)

ABSTRACT: The recent reforms in science education envision engaging students in authentic practices of science and habits of mind (NRC, 2012); in other words, engaging students in doing science. Science is a multidimensional endeavor (Davidson, Jaber, & Southerland, 2020; Pickering, 1995). The work of the scientists include various aspects-- conceptual (kinds of knowledge such as facts, laws, theories), epistemological (ways of thinking and understanding such as how to construct and evaluate scientific knowledge), social (social norms and collaborations), and affective (emotional experiences- the joy of a successful experiment or frustration over a failed one). With science being a multidimensional endeavor, there is a need to view and understand students' disciplinary engagement in science as a multidimensional endeavor as well. Using a qualitative, naturalistic, case study research design, this dissertation generates an in-depth, multi-faceted understanding of the dynamics of students' disciplinary engagement in science classrooms by focusing on a single instance of disciplinary engagement of a group of four students in a middle school science classroom, examined from three different lenses. The main data sources for the three investigations in this dissertation are the audio and video recordings of classroom engagement and student interviews from a two-day long lesson–Mechanisms of Evolution–in a middle school science classroom. Additional data sources include student artifacts such as lab reports and claim-evidence-reasoning posters. The main analytical tool used throughout this study was multimodal discourse analysis that allowed for a focus both on the verbal and non-verbal cues to make inferences about the conceptual, epistemological, social, and affective engagement of students in small groups. In the first investigation, we examine the entanglement of the conceptual, epistemological, social, and affective dynamics that emerge in a small group as students encounter conceptual uncertainties arising from examining ambiguous data in science. Our findings from the first investigation demonstrated the ways in which students engaged in the epistemic work of science–analyzing data, generating claims, evaluating alternative claims, and challenging each other in service of developing a mechanistic reasoning for the scientific phenomenon. However, these findings also portray how overwhelming social and affective experiences along with persistent conceptual and epistemological conflicts have the potential to undermine the rich epistemic work of students. While the first investigation examines the dynamics of engagement of the whole group, the second investigation in this dissertation explores the shifts in discourse moves of a single student in that group with evolving argumentation goals and the influence of the shifting discourse moves on shaping opportunities for disciplinary sensemaking in a small group. Our findings from the second investigation demonstrated that as the local task goals (i.e., students' understanding of what is required or what needs to be done at a particular moment) evolve, similarly phrased discourse moves can have different effects on students' sensemaking opportunities. In other words, depending on the local task goals, the same phrase can be used dialogically or rhetorically, by the same student, resulting in opening up or closing off spaces for sensemaking. Complementing the first two investigations that examine the student engagement from the researchers' perspective, the final investigation in this dissertation centers student voices of their experiences in the lesson. Our findings from the third investigation highlight the differential experiences of students working in the same group when engaging with uncertainty and demonstrate how these four students experienced the same episode in different ways. Too, their perspectives allowed us to understand how their past experiences with one another in the classroom influenced the ways in which they experienced this episode. The differential experiences highlighted in the student reflections provide further insights into students' disciplinary engagement in science. Our findings from the three investigations considered together suggests that students' disciplinary engagement in science is not simple and straightforward. Rather, it is "messy" and multidimensional, with students managing both the epistemic and relational (i.e., pertaining to the collaborative work) aspects of science. The case analyzed in this dissertation presents a unique view of how students engaged in rich disciplinary work of science can become overwhelmed with the entanglement of dynamics along the multiple dimensions eventually undermining the epistemic work of the students. This study contributes to the growing body of literature examining the multidimensional nature of students' disciplinary engagement, students' negotiations of conflicts and tensions that arise during that engagement, and influential discursive moves that support and sustain disciplinary engagement.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the School of Teacher Education in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): July 14, 2023.

TITLE: Molecular Composition and Physiographic Controls of Dissolved Organic Matter across North American Lakes and Wetlands

AUTHOR: Kurek, Martin Roman

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Spencer, Robert G. M.

MEMBER (university representative): Marshall, Alan G. (Alan George), 1944-

MEMBER (committee member): Chanton, Jeffrey P.

MEMBER (committee member): Mason, Olivia Underwood

MEMBER (committee member): Wickland, Kimberly P.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (226 pages)

ABSTRACT: Inland aquatic systems such as lakes, rivers, and wetlands are pivotal in cycling carbon between the landscape and the atmosphere. However, as global air temperatures increase and precipitation patterns continue to change, their roles as net carbon sources or sinks will become uncertain. New carbon sources will become available to aquatic systems in regions such as the permafrost zone in the northern high latitudes or in temperate forested wetlands where increased precipitation connects waterbodies to upland catchments. In dryer regions, the water residence time of aquatic systems will increase, restricting the inputs of organic carbon from the surrounding landscape, but also amplifying its internal production and degradation. This dissertation aims to investigate the sources and molecular properties of dissolved organic matter (DOM) across northern high-latitude lakes and temperate North American wetlands and to consider its potential role in the carbon cycle as these regions continue to experience changes in temperature and precipitation. Using a combined approach of Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometry (FT-ICR MS), optical and fluorescence spectroscopy, and mediated electrochemical oxidation and reduction, molecular-level DOM composition was revealed and related to large-scale climate and physiographic variables. Specifically, the goals of this dissertation were to characterize DOM in lakes spanning the Western North American Arctic with respect to differences in seasonality and climate (Chapter 2) as well as hydrology and landscape characteristics (Chapter 3). Using these findings, a quantitative relationship between molecular level-composition and bulk electrochemical DOM properties was also assessed (Chapter 4). Finally, DOM properties were surveyed across various wetland types across temperate North American regions and further examined between surface waters and porewaters as well as during different annual hydroperiods (Chapter 5). DOM composition and dissolved organic carbon (DOC) concentrations varied seasonally across Alaskan Tundra lakes. DOC concentrations were significantly higher in the winter months than in the summer due to ice exclusion concentrating solutes while DOM contained unique signatures indicative of extensive microbial processing. DOM properties also varied spatially in this region with shallower lakes and lakes closer to the northern coast generally containing more aromatic DOM. Expanding this study region further south across boreal ecosystems revealed that DOM aromaticity increased northward as forests transitioned into shrublands and permafrost coverage became continuous. Many lakes across the Western North American Arctic were primarily composed of autochthonous, or internally produced, DOM rather than DOM originating from the landscape. These differences were mainly driven by landscape connectivity where more hydrologically isolated lakes had higher DOC concentrations but less terrestrial DOM than lakes that were hydrologically connected to the landscape. In contrast, DOM from the hydrologically connected lakes had greater electron accepting and donating capacity, likely originating from the surrounding continuous permafrost soils. Furthermore, DOM electrochemical properties correlated positively with bulk aromaticity and negatively with protein-like fluorescence and aliphaticity, allowing for the development of the Reducing Index which quantified DOM electrochemical properties using FT-ICR MS parameters. Finally, temperate North American wetlands had higher DOC concentrations and greater DOM aromaticity than other inland waters such as lakes and rivers. However, these compositional differences were primarily driven by geographical sampling region rather than sampling depth or hydroperiod and possibly related to soil content and vegetation. Using FT-ICR MS, 3,489 molecular formulae were found across all sites and persisted in both wet and dry hydroperiods, representing the signature of wetland DOM. Many of these molecular signatures were also found in the world's largest arctic rivers, highlighting the role of wetlands in transporting terrestrial organic matter to coastal systems. These studies demonstrate the diversity of aquatic DOM composition and DOC concentrations across expansive regions as related to hydrology and physiographic properties and allows for future work to draw comparisons to similar regions and assess their role in a changing carbon cycle.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Earth Ocean and Atmospheric Sciences in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): July 7, 2023.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Robert G.M Spencer, Professor Directing Dissertation; Alan Marshall, University Representative; Jeffery Chanton, Committee Member; Olivia Mason, Committee Member; Kimberly Wickland, Committee Member.

TITLE: Constructing Identity in Exile: Stories of Tibetan Refugees in Nepal Seeking to Become Educated

AUTHOR: Leyava, Emily

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Khurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Kurshid, Ayesha

MEMBER (university representative): Cuevas, Bryan J., 1967-

MEMBER (committee member): Milligan, Jeffrey Ayala

MEMBER (committee member): Beatty, Cameron C.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Leadership and Policy Studies

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (251 pages)

ABSTRACT: In the spring of 1959, thousands of Tibetans fled China, crossing the border into Nepal. They were following the Dalai Lama into exile after years of living under an oppressive regime in Chinese-occupied Tibet. In the decades that followed, tens of thousands of Tibetans would leave their homeland, searching for a better life abroad. As Tibetans found new homes around the world, many stayed close to their homeland, seeking refuge and new opportunities in Nepal. One of the opportunities they were seeking was access to quality education. A generation later, Tibetans born in exile are still seeking the opportunity to become educated. Through in-depth interviews, participant observations, and an examination of artifacts, this study aims to explore how Tibetan refugees in Nepal construct their identities as educated persons through their experiences with differing systems of education, including formalized secular, monastic, and a hybrid of formal and monastic education. Additionally, it seeks to investigate how Tibetans perform their roles as educated persons within the refugee community in Kathmandu. By analyzing their experiences and perspectives, I seek to understand how Tibetan refugees have formulated their identities through their educational experiences, sociocultural contexts, and historical events, as well as how they perform and make sense of their identities as educated persons in the refugee community in Kathmandu.

ABSTRACT: Health and wellness are the cornerstones of life. Unfortunately, even with the COVID-19 pandemic still fresh in our minds people are not consistently pursuing health activities that can bolster health and wellness. In our study, we concentrate on utilizing the health and wellness mobile technology (HWMT) to help people establish healthy lifestyle habits. Using integrative preventive medicine as a backdrop, we contextualized Hull's (1943) stimulus-response-reinforcement (SRR) theoretical framework to explore the habit formation mechanism. Results of an empirical online survey (n = 696) validated our hypotheses. The stimulus (i.e., health and wellness self-improvement) positively influences the physical health goal. In turn, the physical health goal influences the two-stage response (i.e., stickiness and engagement). Engagement brings individuals positive feelings as the reinforcer (i.e., subjective vitality and sense of accomplishment) that lead to HWMT exploitation and health and wellness related habit formation. The theoretical and practical implications of the study are provided.

TITLE: Investigating Speech Sound Acquisition in School-Based Speech Sound Therapy Sessions for Children with SSD in Isolation and SSD and IDD

AUTHOR: Lovell, Paige

CORPORATE NAME: College of Communication and Information

CORPORATE NAME: School of Communication Science and Disorders

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (47 pages)

ABSTRACT: Speech- language pathologists (SLPs) require up-to-date, evidence-based research to inform their treatment decisions. Current literature on clinical recommendations lacks ecological validity, meaning they do not reflect the realistic environment in which speech sound disorders are treated. This discrepancy impacts the validity of treatment practices in speech sound disorders (SSDs) for both children with SSD in isolation as well as children with intellectual and developmental disabilities (IDD). Using the experience sampling method, we queried school-based speech language pathologists in two data collection periods for both populations (n=106, n=50) three times per day for five days regarding the dynamics of their speech sound therapy sessions. This investigation, specifically, examined target selection for both students with SSD in isolation and IDD populations. Our results indicate that /ɹ/ was the most commonly targeted speech sound in the SSD in isolation population, and /s/ was the most commonly targeted speech sound in the IDD and SSD population.

TITLE: The 𝐿𝑝-Fisher-Rao Metric and Information Geometry

AUTHOR: Lu, Yuxiu

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Bauer, Martin

MEMBER (university representative): Palmer, James Allen

MEMBER (committee member): Bowers, Philip L., 1956-

MEMBER (committee member): Farhat, Aseel

MEMBER (committee member): Farhat, Aseel

MEMBER (committee member): Klassen, E. (Eric), 1958-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mathematics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (117 pages)

ABSTRACT: In this thesis, we will provide a Finslerian point of view on several objects of classical informationgeometry. Therefore we will generalize the Fisher-Rao metric to a family of Finsler metrics which we denote by ??-Fisher-Rao metrics. Generalizing a construction of Khesin et al. we construct a simplifying transformations, that allows us to derive an explicit formula for geodesics on Dens(? ) and that reduces the geodesic problem on Prob(? ) to finding geodesics on an ??-sphere. We then show that the Amari-Chentsov connection on the space of all positive densities can be interpreted as the Chern connection of the ??-Fisher-Rao metric and we also show that this equivalence does not hold on the space of probability densities. For the space of densities we can use this correspondence to calculate the flag curvatures of the ??-Fisher-Rao metric and show that they are identically zero. Next if we restrict ourselves to the case of manifolds of dimension one, we can provide a new geometric interpretation of the non-periodic Proudman–Johnson equations as geodesic equations of the right invariant homogeneous ? 1,?-Finsler metrics on the diffeomorphism group. We then show that in the non-periodic case two families of equations, the generalized inviscid Proudman– Johnson equation, and the ?-Hunter–Saxton equation (recently introduced by Cotter et al.) coincide for a certain range of parameters. Generalizing a construction of Lenells for the Hunter–Saxton equation [57], we analyze these equations using an isometry from the diffeomorphism group to an appropriate subset of real-valued functions. Thereby we show that the periodic case of the ?-Hunter-Saxton equations is equivalent to the geodesic equations on the ??-sphere in the space of functions, and the non-periodic case for both the ?-Hunter-Saxton and the inviscid Proudman– Johnson equations is equivalent to a geodesic flow on a flat space. This allows us to give explicit solutions to these equations in the non-periodic case, and answer several questions of Cotter et al. regarding their limiting behavior. Finally we derive the geodesic equation of a right invariant Orlicz norm on the diffeomorphism group Diff(?1).

TITLE: The Politics of Climate Change: on the Interplay of Parties and Public Attitudes on the Climate

AUTHOR: Mackie, Kenneth R.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Jackson, Robert A., 1966-

MEMBER (university representative): Tang, Tian

MEMBER (committee member): Atkeson, Lonna Rae, 1965-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Social Sciences and Public Policy

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Political Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (143 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation seeks to make a valuable contribution to the fields of public policy and American politics by introducing novel theoretical and empirical insights via the study of the politics of climate change. Climate change represents a daunting challenge for societies across the world, but in no other major country are political parties more polarized on this issue than in the United States. This dissertation takes a dynamic approach to study the interplay between public attitudes on climate change and positions the parties adopt. This dissertation's primary goal is to provide a more theoretically motivated and comprehensive look at the endogenous relationship between public opinion and party agendas. Recent work in political science and other social sciences researching climate change has primarily used either cross-sectional data to study climate sorting or experiments on top-down forms of opinion change according to which elite cues impact opinions and then inferring the causes of sorting. Yet not enough work looks at the role of bottom-up processes such as how a party's climate change policies impact voter support for the party and its candidates, let alone empirically compare the contributions of both processes to overall rates of sorting. This dissertation addresses these limitations in prior literature by utilizing a wealth of cross-sectional and panel survey data to understand climate change and environment opinion over time, as well a novel survey experiment to understand whether and how voters hold parties accountable for not supporting climate change action. The contributions described above result in a richer and more complete scientific foundation for studying essential policy considerations in the modern world. This dissertation offers the first direct examination of the interplay between public attitudes and political parties and contributes to a clearer yet more dynamic understanding of climate politics.

TITLE: Development of UHPC with Limestone Calcined Clay Cement (LC3) Binder: A Feasibility Study

AUTHOR: Mank, Emily

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Zhang, Qian

MEMBER (committee member): Elwardany, Michael

MEMBER (committee member): Spainhour, Lisa

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (58 pages)

ABSTRACT: Ultra-high-performance concrete (UHPC) is a special type of concrete with high compressive and tensile strength, high durability, and a dense microstructure that results in improved mechanical and durability properties. However, due to the high cement content typically used in UHPC, the carbon footprint of UHPC is generally very high. On the other hand, limestone calcined clay cement (LC3) is a more environmentally friendly alternative to ordinary Portland cement (OPC) with lower carbon emissions during production. Previous research has explored LC3 replacing up to 50% of OPC content in normal strength concrete, which contributes to significant reduction of carbon footprint. The use of LC3 binder in UHPC material though has not been widely explored. This thesis research presents a feasibility study on the development of UHPC with sustainable LC3 binders. Up to 30% of OPC replacement with LC3 binder in non-proprietary UHPC mixtures was investigated; the workability, compressive and tensile properties of the resultant UHPC mixtures were experimentally characterized to determine the influence of LC3 on UHPC.

TITLE: Addressing the Continuation of the Allatoona Fault: The Youngest Thrust in the Appalachian Blue Ridge Kinematic Sequence

AUTHOR: McMahan, Ericka Lynn

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Tull, James F.

MEMBER (committee member): Mookherjee, Mainak

MEMBER (committee member): Stewart, Emily

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (122 pages)

ABSTRACT: The Allatoona fault is an internal, out-of-sequence thrust fault in the southernmost Appalachian hinterland, extending >280 km. Along the fault's nearly linear trace it cuts obliquely through Blue Ridge tectonostratigraphy, metamorphic isograds, earlier thrusts, and Pennsylvanian regional cross antiforms; making it the youngest fault in the kinematic sequence of events along the west flank of the Appalachian orogen. In the central segment of the fault, between Hightower, Alabama and Dahlonega, Georgia, the Allatoona fault marks the western/eastern Blue Ridge province boundary, and south of Hightower the Allatoona fault becomes an internal eastern Blue Ridge structure. Just north of Buchannon, Georgia, the Mulberry Rock window (a ~20 km-long breached eyelid window) allows a 3-D view into the structural architecture, kinematics, and trajectories of the regional thrusts. From here, northeast to Dawsonville, Georgia, it carries the Dahlonega Gold belt in its immediate hanging wall, with older faults (Burnt Hickory Ridge and Chattahoochee) carried passively piggyback above the gold belt. The extension of this fault northeast of Dawsonville has inspired controversy for years. However, recent mapping around the complex triple junction between the western, central, and eastern Blue Ridge provinces west of Dahlonega, Georgia has revealed new evidence supporting the continuation of the Allatoona fault northeast of this intersection. For instance, between Dawsonville and Dahlonega, internal Dahlonega Gold belt stratigraphy maintains its northeast-trend, and the Allatoona fault cuts both the structurally underlying "ancestral Allatoona" fault carrying rocks correlated with the Otto Formation, and the Etowah River fault at the base of the Sally Free Mafic Complex. Both the "ancestral Allatoona" fault and the Etowah River fault are folded by the overturned NW-SE Sally Free synform, and this fold in turn is decapitated by the Allatoona fault. Although previous studies suggested that the Hayesville-Soque River fault to the northwest postdated the Allatoona fault, the regional Jasper antiform folds the Great Smoky thrust, the Murphy synclinorium, the "ancestral Allatoona" fault, and the Hayesville-Soque River fault, but is decapitated by the Allatoona fault north of Dawsonville. Although the Canton and Univeter Formations of the Dahlonega Gold belt were displaced 10's of km northwest along the Allatoona fault and extend >110 km from type sections near Canton to at least Lake Burton, Georgia, previous interpretations have placed the Dahlonega Gold belt in the immediate footwall of the northwest-dipping Hayesville-Soque River fault, with the Allatoona fault apparently being cut by this fault approximately 12 km north of Dawsonville. Mapping efforts for this study, around the complex junction between the western, central, and eastern Blue Ridge provinces, have revealed new evidence that supports the continuation of the Allatoona fault north of this intersection.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.

NOTE (Date of Defense): July 6, 2023.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): James F. Tull, Professor Directing Thesis; Mainak Mookherjee, Committee Member; Emily Stewart, Committee Member.

FILENAME: Meza_fsu_0071E_18222.pdf

TITLE: Investigation of NADPH Oxidase as a Link between Vascular and Metabolic Dysfunction

AUTHOR: Meza, Cesar Arturo

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Hickner, Robert C., 1962-

MEMBER (university representative): Pinto, Jose R. (Jose Renato)

MEMBER (committee member): La Favor, Justin

MEMBER (committee member): Berryman, Claire E. (Elizabeth)

MEMBER (committee member): Machin, Daniel

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Health and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Nutrition and Integrative Physiology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (87 pages)

ABSTRACT: INTRODUCTION: Obesity is associated with increased cardiometabolic disease risk, although the vascular and metabolic features of obesity are often studied independently. Resistance to both insulin-mediated suppression of lipolysis and increases in microvascular blood flow are important risk factors for cardiometabolic diseases. Emerging evidence points to heightened NADPH oxidase (Nox) activity as a critical feature of reduced vascular and metabolic function. Overproduction of Nox-derived reactive oxygen species (ROS) is a major source of microvascular dysfunction in obesity and increased adipose tissue Nox activity is a main determinant of insulin resistance. In addition, Nox-derived ROS is an important component of increased lipolysis; however, the mechanisms by which Nox regulates lipolysis are unknown. In addition, the mechanistic basis for Nox in the intricate relationship between insulin control of vascular and metabolic responses is not well described. PURPOSE: The overall objective of this study was to investigate whether increased Nox-derived ROS production impairs blood glucose profiles by reducing insulin-mediated suppression of lipolysis. METHODS: Sixteen sedentary, non-obese, otherwise healthy males and females (males = 1, females = 15; age: 21.7 ± 5 years; body mass index: 22.7 ± 4 kg/m2) participated in this study. Participants completed three study visits, each after a ten-hour overnight fast. During the first study visit, anthropometric assessments were completed, as well as measurement of fasting blood glucose and blood pressure. During the second study visit, assessments of body composition (via dual-energy x-ray absorptiometry, DXA) and maximal aerobic capacity (VO2peak) were completed. The final study visit was the main experimental visit, where participants underwent microdialysis and hyperinsulinemic-euglycemic procedures to monitor local adipose tissue (total and Nox-dependent) ROS production and lipolysis (measured as dialysate glycerol) under basal as well as hyperinsulinemic conditions. Total dialysate H2O2 concentrations, including dismutated superoxide, were detected via perfusion of Amplex UltraRed reagent, horseradish peroxidase and superoxide dismutase through microdialysis probes. Further, microdialysis probes were perfused with either isoproterenol (β-adrenergic agonist) or atrial natriuretic peptide (ANP) to stimulate lipolysis through independent signaling pathways, then additionally perfused with apocynin (Nox inhibitor) to determine the contributions of Nox to lipolysis. RESULTS: Upon perfusion of apocynin, the dialysate concentrations of H2O2 decreased in the control (without apocynin: 1.17 ± 0.5 M, with apocynin: 0.66 ± 0.2 M; p = 0.003) and isoproterenol probes (without apocynin: 1.09 ± 0.6 M, with apocynin: 0.68 ± 0.3 M; p = 0.03). Isoproterenol and ANP perfusion significantly increased dialysate glycerol concentrations compared to the control probe (control: 56.0 ± 21.9, isoproterenol: 125.6 ± 59.8, ANP: 130.9 ± 47.7 mol/L; p < 0.0001). However, apocynin perfusion had no effect on dialysate glycerol concentrations in the control (p = 0.99), isoproterenol (p = 0.99) or ANP (p = 0.59) probes in the basal state. During the clamp, apocynin perfusion decreased dialysate H2O2 concentrations in control (without apocynin: 1.3 ± 0.6 M, with apocynin: 0.79 ± 0.3 M; p = 0.046), isoproterenol (without apocynin: 1.58 ± 0.8 M, with apocynin: 0.83 ± 0.3 M; p = 0.02) and ANP (without apocynin: 1.60 ± 0.60 M, with apocynin: 0.95 ± 0.3 M; p = 0.04) probes. Hyperinsulinemia decreased dialysate glycerol concentrations compared to the basal state (basal: 56.0  21.9 mol/L, clamp: 32.8  20.2 mol/L; p = 0.02). In addition, dialysate glycerol concentrations decreased in the isoproterenol probe following apocynin perfusion during the clamp procedure (without apocynin: 126.1  38 mol/L, with apocynin: 91.9  25.7 mol/L; p = 0.002). Further, there was a correlation between basal adipose tissue lipolytic rates and Nox contributions to basal adipose tissue lipolysis (r = -0.66, p = 0.005), and individuals with lower insulin sensitivity (glucose disposal rate) tended to have high basal Nox-mediated ROS production (r = 0.56, p = 0.04). CONCLUSIONS: The novel findings of this study are that Nox is a stimulus of adipose tissue ROS production in healthy individuals, and this effect contributes to increases in adipose tissue lipolysis during hyperinsulinemic conditions. The mechanism by which Nox increases lipolysis involves β-adrenergic signaling and is independent of the ANP pathway. These data have important implications for individuals with insulin resistance and excess adiposity, as basal adipose tissue Nox activity was highest in individuals with lower insulin sensitivity and higher basal lipolytic rates, which may impair blood glucose regulation and vascular function. Overall, these study findings provide in vivo evidence of a novel regulator of adipose tissue lipolysis.

TITLE: Gender Differences in Pain Gender Differences in Pain: Assessing Explainations for the Association Assessing Explanations for the Association

AUTHOR: Michael, Cherish

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Barrett, Anne E., 1971-

MEMBER (university representative): Martorella, Geraldine

MEMBER (committee member): Padavic, Irene

MEMBER (committee member): Ueno, Koji

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Social Sciences and Public Policy

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Sociology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (82 pages)

ABSTRACT: Physical pain is a gendered experience: Women report higher levels of it than do men. This pattern may stem from differences in experiences of the body. Women are socialized to be attentive to its functioning, appearance, and sensations, while men are discouraged from paying much attention to their bodies. Little is known, however, about the precise social and economic pathways leading to gender differences in pain, especially in middle and later life when pain is most prevalent. I examine this issue using data from two waves of Midlife in the United States (2004-2006 and 2013-2014). I consider four possible explanations for gender differences in reports of pain: economic security, health, relationship strain, and stress exposure. Results indicated that women are more likely than men to report experiencing chronic pain and that three out of four explanations contributed to explaining this gender difference. Two of the explanations, however, played more substantial roles than the others. These conclusions held in both the cross-sectional and panel analyses. Results indicated that women's worse physical and mental health and their lower economic security played the largest roles in accounting for the association between gender and pain. Women's greater relationship strain, particularly in their partner and family relationships, also contributed to the explanation, but its role was more limited. Stress exposure was the only potential mediator that failed to contribute to explaining the association between gender and pain. This result derived from the observation that men, rather than women, experienced greater exposure to stressful events. This research responds to the call for more sociological research on chronic pain (Wood and Bourke 2020). More specifically, it adds to the literature on gender and pain by clarifying the processes underlying this well-documented association. The results of this study point to the role of macro-level social factors, especially socioeconomic inequality, in generating women's greater experience of chronic pain. They also reveal the central role that is played by women's worse physical and mental health, which can be viewed as another consequence of socioeconomic inequality. These results have important implications not only for research on pain but also for interventions aimed at reducing gender disparities in pain. The processes revealed in this study could be further clarified by research that uses multiple waves of data to examine changes in pain as well as potential mediators over time.

TITLE: College Career Courses and Vocational Identity Achievment College Career Courses and Vocational Identity Achievement: An Investigation of Mediators and Moderators An Investigation of Mediators and Moderators

AUTHOR: Morgan, Michael J., Jr.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Osborn, Debra S., 1968-

MEMBER (university representative): Charness, Neil

MEMBER (committee member): Jenkins, Lyndsay Nicole

MEMBER (committee member): Ebener, Deborah J.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Educational Psychology and Learning Systems

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2022

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (232 pages)

ABSTRACT: The development of a clear vocational identity is a critical task for emerging adult undergraduates (Arnett, 2014). Ego psychology theorists (e.g., Marcia, 1993) argue that exploration contributes to the development of career commitment, and career commitment in the presence of career exploration constitutes one's vocational identity. Career courses are an evidence-based intervention provided at many colleges for the purpose of career development through structured career exploration (Reardon & Fiore, 2014); however, no study of career courses has investigated whether career exploration mediates the effects of career course participation on career commitment. This dissertation addressed gaps in the literature and solidified connections between theories by comparing students enrolled in a manualized, theory-based college career course and a non-equivalent control group with multilevel modeling and autoregressive path analyses on measures of career exploration, career commitment, and metacognition to observe mediation and moderation effects. Participation in the career course was associated with significant growth in career exploration and career commitment relative to the control group. Career exploration was observed as a partial mediator of treatment effects. Negative career thoughts and career outcome metacognitions differentially moderated the direct and indirect effects of the treatment on career commitment. These findings are discussed at length, followed by review of study limitations and implications for theory, practice, and research.

FILENAME: Mullings_fsu_0071N_18164.pdf

TITLE: Optimization of Electric Field Enhancement of Helium Gas Cooled High Temperature Superconducting Power Cables for Transportation Applications

AUTHOR: Mullings, Alexia

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Cheetham, Peter

MEMBER (committee member): Pamidi, Sastry V.

MEMBER (committee member): Bernadin, Shonda

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: FAMU-FSU College of Engineering

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (68 pages)

ABSTRACT: The need for efficient, reliable, and environmentally friendly transportation is increasing rapidly as countries set target dates for achieving net zero carbon emissions. High Temperature Superconducting (HTS) cables have current densities up to 100 A/mm2, approximately ten times greater than conventional copper cables. This increases the power density of electrical systems that utilize HTS cables and can result in substantial size and weight savings, making them an attractive solution for all-electric aircraft and ships with power system ratings ranging from 20 MW to 100 MW. Gaseous helium (GHe) is the preferred cryogen for (HTS) devices for transportation applications due to its wider operating temperature range and reduced risk of asphyxiation compared to liquid nitrogen (LN2). However, its lower dielectric strength compared to LN2 poses design challenges. A previous study found that GHe mixed with small mole percentages of hydrogen (H2) results in significant improvement of dielectric breakdown strength. The same level of improvement was not seen when measuring the partial discharge inception voltage (PDIV) of lapped tape insulated cables in the helium-hydrogen gas mixtures. A greater understanding on the electric field enhancement within the electrical insulation of the HTS cable was required to develop materials and approaches to increase the partial discharge rating of the cables. Partial discharge is one of the limiting factors when determining the voltage rating of a cable. The research presented in this thesis focuses on five prototype cables using cryogenic rated epoxies as electrical insulation. These cables were characterized at 77 K in both pure GHe and GHe mixed with small mol percentages of H2. The electric field of the cables were varied through the addition of stress cones, techniques used to apply the ground layer application, and the type of cryogenic epoxy used as electrical insulation. A summary of the conclusions drawn from this research is as follows: • The addition of 4 mol% of H2 to GHe led to an average increase in PDIV values of about 57% compared to PDIV measurements in pure GHe for pressure levels ranging from 0.5-2.0 MPa at 77 K. This improvement is a similar ratio to what has been observed with the intrinsic breakdown strength of GHe and He/H2 gas mixtures at cryogenic temperatures. • The addition of stress cones to an EP37 insulated cable resulted in an average increase in PDIV of 45% in pure GHe and 54% improvement in the 96% GHe 4% H2 mixture compared to an EP37 insulated cable without stress cones. Confirming that the addition of stress cones will limit field enhancement and improve PDIV results. • The use of conductive epoxy to form a direct ground connection on an EP37 insulated cable resulted in 64% improvement in pure GHe at 2 MPa compared to an EP 37 cable with a ground layer formed using semiconductive paper and copper tape. This indicated that the use of conductive epoxy instead of semiconductive paper limits the formation of butt gaps between the insulation and ground layers. • The EP29 insulated cable experienced PDIV values 47% and 45% higher than the corresponding EP37 insulated cable in 2MPa pure GHe and in 2 MPa GHe with 4 mol% H2 respectively. EP29 has a relative permittivity of 3.95 compared to that of EP 37 which is 4.4. EP29 has a closer relative permittivity value to GHe (εr =1) which reduces the electric field enhancement at the triple point of the epoxy insulation, GHe, and ground layer.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Thesis submitted to the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Master of Science.

NOTE (Date of Defense): July 3, 2023.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Peter Cheetham, Professor Directing Thesis; Sastry Pamidi, Committee Member; Shonda Bernadin, Committee Member.
