FILENAME: Simon_fsu_0071E_18052.pdf

TITLE: Impact of Effort and Expectancy on the P300

AUTHOR: Simon, Jessica R.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Proudfit, Greg Hajcak

MEMBER (university representative): Becker, Martin Swanbrow

MEMBER (committee member): Eckel, Lisa A.

MEMBER (committee member): Schmidt, Norman B.

MEMBER (committee member): Kabbaj, Mohamed

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Psychology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (100 pages)

ABSTRACT: Motivationally significant stimuli activate motivational systems to support perception and action. Rewards are naturally occurring motivationally salient stimuli that activate approach behaviors, for example, effort for a reward. Two theories have been proposed regarding the impact of effort on subsequent reward salience. Effort discounting theories suggest that effort is costly and makes the outcome less salient. Comparatively, effort justification theories posit that the reward is more salient after exerting effort. Existing literature has supported both theories; however, the methods used (e.g., fMRI, behavior) were not temporally precise, so we extend this work by using electroencephalogram (EEG) to better understand the sequential effects of effort on reward processing. The P300 event-related potential has been used as a measure of motivational significance and is related to reward processing. The P300 is also associated with task relevance (experimentally manipulated significance) and stimulus expectations. Literature shows that P300 amplitude to reward feedback is increased following high compared to low amounts of effort, supporting effort justification theories or increased salience of the feedback after effort completion. Critically, however, these studies have failed to control for subjective stimulus expectations known to influence P300 amplitude. It may be that outcome feedback is more unexpected when more effort is required. When less effort is required, there may be no differences between expected and unexpected stimuli because participants can predict relatively well when the cue may be presented. To investigate the influence of both effort and expectancy on P300 amplitude to reward feedback we created a monetary reward task that varied effort and waiting, high and low amounts (duration) of effort (waiting), and expectancy. Expectancy was manipulated by having some trials countdown the number of presses left (countdown) as subjects exerted effort or waited, so participants know when the reward was coming. Alternatively, some trials stayed static (no countdown) and gave no information about upcoming reward presentation. From this task we also investigated mean differences in behavioral response rate, reaction time, and trial duration for effortful trials, and related the P300 amplitude to the behavioral measures. The initial study focused on these within subject differences, but it is known that effort for reward is disrupted in various psychological and neurological disorders, especially depression where anhedonia is a symptom that reflects problematic consummation and motivation for rewards. Indeed, P300 amplitude is consistently decreased in people with depression or anhedonia and may be a good biomarker of motivational salience deficits in people with anhedonia symptomology. Thus, we investigated relationships between P300 amplitude and self-reported anhedonia symptoms. We demonstrated that the amount of effort or waiting required influenced P300 amplitude—high effort amounts or waiting durations had larger P300 amplitudes than low effort or waiting, which varied by expectations. When subjects knew when to expect reward presentation (countdown), there was no difference between high and low amounts of either effort or waiting. Comparatively, when expectations were violated (no countdown), there was a significant difference between high and low amounts (durations) of effort (waiting). Additionally, effort for reward processing seems to be distinct from reward processing following waiting as P300 amplitudes were larger following effort conditions. The present study also demonstrated task effects on behavioral reaction times; when more effort was required, participants were quicker to start the trial, and participants that were faster at pressing across the task (shorter trial durations) had lower P300 amplitudes. Finally, individuals with lower experiences of pleasure or heightened anhedonia symptoms had blunted P300 amplitudes following effort compared to waiting conditions. These results provide evidence for effort justification theories and are interpreted within the motivational significance framework, which suggests salient stimuli in the form of surprising, unexpected, and task relevant reward stimuli may enhance attention and/or facilitate subsequent action by eliciting a larger P300 amplitude waveform. Moreover, the P300 was attenuated to reward feedback during effort conditions in individuals experiencing anhedonia symptomology suggesting disrupted processing of motivationally salient reward stimuli. Our results call for future investigation of expectations on reward processing in addition to task relevance.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Psychology in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): June 13, 2023.

NOTE (Keywords): Effort, Expectation, Motivational Signficance, P300, salience, Surprise

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Greg Hajcak, Professor Directing Dissertation; Martin Swanbrow Becker, University Representative; Lisa Eckel, Committee Member; N. Brad Schmidt, Committee Member; Mohamed Kabbaj, Committee Member.

FILENAME: Smith_fsu_0071E_18070.pdf

TITLE: Virtuous Knowers: A Virtue-Theoretic Analysis of the Intersection of Doxastic Agency, Doxastic Obligations, and Doxastic Justification

AUTHOR: Smith, Joseph Emmanuel

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Hinchman, Edward

MEMBER (university representative): Kelsay, John, 1953-

MEMBER (committee member): Kearns, Stephen, 1979-

MEMBER (committee member): Ward, Zina

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Philosophy

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (96 pages)

ABSTRACT: In this dissertation, I argue for a virtue-epistemological take on doxastic agency, doxastic reasons, doxastic obligations, and doxastic justification. After a brief introduction, in chapter 2 I argue in favor of doxastic involuntarism. I argue that, though the work of theoretical reason is to produce true beliefs, it does not do so in a way similar to how practical reason produces actions. I support this claim by focusing on the debate between doxastic voluntarists and involuntarists. I reframe this debate and then argue in favor of doxastic involuntarism, which has significant implications for theoretical reason. Many proponents of doxastic involuntarism characterize their view as one that denies that we can form beliefs at will. A sometimes-implicit assumption is that the formation of a belief is something that could, in principle, be an action. Their reason for why we cannot form beliefs at will is that there are various obstacles that impede us performing such an action. In contrast, I characterize the dispute between doxastic voluntarists and involuntarists as a dispute over whether the formation of a belief is an action, not over whether it is an action we can perform. I present an understanding of the nature of belief that implies that the formation of a belief is never an action. I use this characterization of the nature of belief in an argument in favor of doxastic involuntarism. In chapter 3, I argue for a new understanding of reasons for belief and doxastic obligations. I argue that, if doxastic involuntarism is true, then we should reconceive what are traditionally called reasons for belief. The truth of doxastic involuntarism would rule out a certain understanding of reasons for belief according to which they are necessary conditions for doxastic obligations. Thus, reconceiving reasons for belief would require reconceiving doxastic obligations. I argue that, in fact, a re-conception of reasons for belief warrants abandoning the notion of doxastic obligations, understood as obligations to form, alter, or relinquish doxastic states. Instead, the only sorts of obligations we would have that concern our doxastic states would be aretaic or practical. In chapters 4 and 5, I apply the arguments from chapters 2 and 3 to testimonial beliefs and doxastic justification, respectively. In chapter 4, I argue that a general feature of human psychology provides strong reason to modify or reject anti-reductionism about the epistemology of testimony. Because of the work of what I call 'the background' (which is a collection of all of an individual's synthetizations, summarizations, memories of experiences, beliefs, etc.) we cannot help but form testimonial beliefs on the basis of a testifier's say so along with additional evidence, concepts, beliefs, etc. Given that we arrive at testimonial beliefs through the work of the background, to be justified in holding a testimonial belief, we must not only have a rational speaker's say so, but we must also form such beliefs in the right way. If this is right, then, contrary to typical anti-reductionism, justified testimonial beliefs require more than just a trustworthy testifier's say so—another requirement is that they are formed in the right way. In chapter 5, I argue that what it takes for an agent to be justified in holding a belief is that the agent formed the belief in the right sort of way, which should be understood in terms of virtue epistemology. That is, in contrast to the predominant way of understanding doxastic justification—a deontological view according to which you are justified in holding a belief if and only if it is permissible for you to hold the belief—we should understand doxastic justification aretaically: you are justified in holding a belief if and only if your belief is the result of the operation of virtue. I argue that the aretaic account of justification is superior to the deontological one.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A dissertation submitted to the Department of Philosophy in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): June 16, 2023.

TITLE: Robert Marcellus: Clarinet Teaching from the Cleveland Institute of Music and Northwestern University

AUTHOR: Spengler, Colby

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

CORPORATE NAME: College of Music

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

ABSTRACT: Robert Marcellus was one of the most respected clarinetists and teachers in the twentieth century. He was a performer in the Cleveland Orchestra and taught at both the Cleveland Institute of Music and Northwestern University. His students occupied positions in major orchestras and universities. The purpose of this research was to collect and compare pedagogical information from the experiences of Robert Marcellus's students from both the Cleveland Institute of Music and Northwestern University. Interviews were conducted with J. David Harris, Diane Barger, David Bell, Steve Cohen, Kathy Jones, Lee Morgan, Michele Gingras, and John Weigand. A similar set of questions were asked to each interviewee. Questions pertained to participants' time frame in studying with Mr. Marcellus, their experiences in private lessons, Mr. Marcellus's communication skills, his personality, the studio environment, pedagogy, and syllabus of study. After all the interviews were completed, the results were analyzed to provide insight into his teaching. The information was categorized into six groupings: inspiration, communication, personality, Mr. Marcellus's studio, pedagogy, and syllabus of study. The groupings were examined based on criteria for the interviewees: location of study, specific years in school, and length of study. Along with the analysis of the interviews, a full transcript of each interview is included. The experiences of his students are valuable in describing the teachings of Robert Marcellus.

TITLE: Cloud Feedbacks and Convective Self-Aggregation in the Radiative-Convective Equilibrium Model Intercomparison Project

AUTHOR: Stauffer, Catherine Lynn

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Wing, Allison

MEMBER (university representative): Chicken, Eric, 1963-

MEMBER (committee member): Atwood, Alyssa Regine

MEMBER (committee member): Bourassa, Mark Allan

MEMBER (committee member): Liu, Guosheng, (Professor of meteorology)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (219 pages)

ABSTRACT: Changes in cloud properties in response to surface warming have been consistently identified as the feedback contributing the largest uncertainty in the overall climate feedback parameter, which describes changes in top of atmosphere radiation balance in response to warming surface temperatures. The primary concern regarding clouds are twofold: (i) Clouds have competing influences on the climate. Their high albedo reflects solar insolation, cooling the climate system while simultaneously absorbing and re-emitting the radiation emitted by the Earth, a warming effect on the climate system. (ii) Clouds are inherently a subgrid-scale process for most climate change studies (such as those using global climate models), necessitating the use of a parameterization scheme. Here, an ensemble of models of many types in an idealized configuration of the tropical climate is leveraged to investigate how and why deep-convecting clouds change the way they do, what the resultant cloud feedbacks are from these changes, and how organized convection affects these changes and cloud feedbacks. Deep-convecting anvils, independent of how cloud fraction is defined, increase in height, increase slightly in temperature, and (generally) decrease in cloud fraction with warming sea surface temperature while mid-level cloud fraction robustly decreases with warming. The response of tropical clouds to warming found in this work follows previously established physical reasoning, confirming this reasoning across a much larger ensemble of models that explicitly simulate convection than previously considered. The cloud feedbacks associated with these changes generally align with results using comprehensive global climate models and observations, especially for cloud feedbacks associated with tropical high clouds. However, when convection organizes, different cloud regimes become more important. There is an established understanding that organized convection alters the mean climate state. If convective organization is absent, the cloud feedbacks have a smaller magnitude. Amongst domains that have convective organization, if a domain is strongly organized, the cloud feedbacks are weaker and sometimes switch sign. This is primarily due to the impact of changes in cloud optical depth in the shortwave, specifically high clouds thickening (as opposed to thinning) with warming in strongly organized domains, as well as more strongly organized domains having more low clouds to begin with. The shortwave cloud optical depth feedback also plays an important role in causing the tropical anvil cloud area feedback to be positive which is directly opposed to the expected negative cloud feedback found in prior work. This calls into question the expectation for and assumptions regarding a negative tropical anvil cloud area feedback, particularly the role of changes in cloud optical depth with warming, especially given these simulations more accurately resolve convection.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Earth, Ocean and Atmospheric Science in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): June 20, 2023.

NOTE (Keywords): climate sensitivity, cloud feedbacks, idealized modeling, organized convection, radiative-convective equilibrium, tropical convection

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

TITLE: Urban-Rural Disparities in Access to Covid-19 Testing Sites: The Impact of Funding Cuts in the Capital Region of Florida

AUTHOR: Steele, Quinn

MEMBER (professor co-directing thesis): Mukherjee, Tathagata

MEMBER (professor co-directing thesis): Wong, Sandy

MEMBER (professor co-directing thesis): Uejio, Christopher K.

MEMBER (committee member): Horner, Mark W.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Social Sciences and Public Policy

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Geography

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (76 pages)

ABSTRACT: In this study I analyzed the relationship between access to COVID-19 testing sites and neighborhood characteristics before and after federal funding cuts to determine if socially vulnerable communities were more likely to be affected by testing site closures. This was studied across eight counties in Florida's panhandle: Leon, Wakulla, Taylor, Madison, Jefferson, Gulf, Gadsden, and Franklin. For the purpose of this study, the study area will be referred to as the Capital Region (as it includes Leon County, which hosts the capital of Florida, and all of Leon County's neighboring counties). This project has three objectives: (1) To create a Social Vulnerability Index (SoVI) that summarizes the social determinants of health in the region, (2) To investigate how levels of access to COVID-19 testing sites changed over time as a result of testing site closures, and (3) Lastly, to analyze access before and after federal funding cuts, and the change in access, in relation to social vulnerability factors. The geographic scale for these analyses is at the census tract level. To accomplish these objectives, I (1) generated SoVI to measure social vulnerability, (2) calculated the drive-times from the population-weighted centroids of each census tract to the closest, two closest, and five closest testing facilities to measure access; and calculated the difference in drive times before and after federal funding cuts, and (3) utilized Generalized Additive Models (GAMs) to analyze the relationship between drive times and social vulnerability. From the results, I detected which census tracts had the lowest access to COVID-19 testing sites and which were the most affected by testing site closures. I found that SoVI did not have a statistically significant relationship to access to testing facilities when accounting for spatial autocorrelation, which was counter to expectations. However, I found that there was a consistently significant relationship between rural census tracts and high drive times to COVID-19 testing facilities. Rural status was the only significant indicator of an increase in drive time as well. These findings highlight the need for more comprehensive strategies to address healthcare access disparities in rural areas. This study enriches the argument for the essentiality of public health federal funding and provides important insights on how federal funding cuts for COVID-19 mitigation efforts affect at-risk communities, specifically rural ones. The purpose of this research is to analyze how geographic accessibility changed as a result of closures to state-funded testing sites and to identify which communities are the most affected. These findings have important implications for policy makers and local planners because they can inform decisions related to the allocation of resources for public health services. Additionally, evaluating how changes in funding affect geographic access to testing can help guide future decisions regarding public health funding and resource allocation. The intellectual merit of this research lies in its assessment of urban-rural disparities in access to testing sites and social vulnerability at a finer geographic scale than the extant research. Whereas most COVID-19 studies analyze accessibility and vulnerability at the scale of county-level units (e.g., Tao, et. al, 2020; Kim, et. al, 2021; CDC, n.d.), I measured these variables at the scale of census tracts. The application of SoVI will provide local governments with an evidence-based understanding of relative vulnerability across census tracts in the Capital Region and their capacities to prepare for, respond to, and recover from COVID-19. Because there is no standard for the number of testing facilities to consider in the drive-time analysis, I compared the findings from the closest, two closest, and five closest testing facilities and analyzed how the results changed. Furthermore, there are very few studies that examine the relationship between access to testing sites and social vulnerability. One relevant study conducted by Mullachery and colleagues (2022) analyzed vulnerability and access in 30 US cities, but none were in Florida or in rural communities. My project contributes empirical findings on unstudied regions impacted by COVID-19. The broader impacts of my project are to demonstrate how critical COVID-19 federal funding is for disadvantaged communities. The findings of this study may help policymakers and healthcare providers better understand the needs of rural communities and develop targeted interventions to improve access to testing. The lack of a statistically significant relationship between access to COVID testing sites and SoVI suggests that other factors, such as rurality, may be more important in determining access to healthcare services, particularly for North Florida.

TITLE: Evaluation of a Screening Battery for Developmental Language Disorder

AUTHOR: Summy, Sarah Rebecca Adams

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Catts, Hugh W. (Hugh William), 1949-

MEMBER (university representative): Terry, Nicole Patton

MEMBER (committee member): Farquharson, Kelly

MEMBER (committee member): Wood, Carla, (Speech-Language Pathology Professor)

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Communication and Information

CORPORATE NAME: School of Communication Science and Disorders

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (73 pages)

ABSTRACT: Students with developmental language disorder (DLD) have difficulty understanding and using oral language, and these difficulties negatively impact academic achievement. DLD has a prevalence of 7-8% of school-age students, yet research has shown that less than half of those students are receiving services. Implementation of a screening tool in early elementary school has the potential to improve identification challenges of DLD in schools. The purpose of this study was to evaluate a comprehensive language screening battery that included seven language measures. The study aimed to identify what language measures were most predictive of overall language ability and determine what language measures resulted in the highest diagnostic accuracy for DLD. One hundred and twenty-six students were administered a screening battery that included sentence repetition, nonword repetition, listening comprehension, expressive vocabulary, receptive vocabulary, synonyms, and paired associate learning. All students were then administered the Core Language subtests from the Clinical Evaluation of Language Fundamentals-5th Edition (CELF-5). The CELF-5 served as the reference standard to evaluate the screening battery. A dominance analysis was performed to determine the relative importance of all measures as well as determine what models explained the most variance in the outcome. A series of logistic regressions were then used to determine what measures predicted DLD. Predicted probabilities from the logistic regressions were entered into ROC curve analyses to analyze diagnostic accuracy of various models. Results of the dominance analysis revealed that sentence repetition was the most dominant predictor of language ability. Adding additional measures to sentence repetition slightly increased the amount of variance explained, but the changes in R2 were not significant. Results of the logistic regression revealed that sentence repetition was the only consistent predictor of DLD. Preliminary results indicate that including additional measures with a sentence repetition task increases diagnostic accuracy. However, results related to diagnostic accuracy should be interpreted cautiously due to the small sample size of students with DLD (n=17).

TITLE: Stochastic Optimal Control through Gradient Projection Method and Backward Action Learning

AUTHOR: Sun, Hui

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Bao, Feng

MEMBER (university representative): Liu, Xiuwen, 1966-

MEMBER (committee member): Ökten, Giray

MEMBER (committee member): Zhu, Lingjiong

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mathematics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (138 pages)

ABSTRACT: The aim of this work is to carry out convergence analysis and algorithm implementation of a novel sample-wise backpropagation method for training a class of stochastic neural networks (SNNs). The structure of the SNN is formulated as a discretization of a stochastic differential equation (SDE). A stochastic optimal control framework is introduced to model the training procedure, and a sample-wise approximation scheme for the adjoint backward SDE is applied to improve the eﬀiciency of the stochastic optimal control solver, which is equivalent to the back-propagation for training the SNN. The convergence analysis is derived by introducing a novel joint conditional expectation for the gradient process. Under the convexity assumption, our result indicates that the number of SNN training steps should be proportional to the square of the number of layers in the convex optimization case. In the implementation of the sample-based SNN algorithm with the benchmark MNIST data set, we adopt the convolution neural network (CNN) architecture and demonstrated that our SNN is more robust than the conventional CNN. To further demonstrate that our algorithm can be adopted to solve an array of problems (including high dimensional ones), we present the result of learning noisy functions of using SNN and demonstrate that SNN can capture complex noise level of the function very well. We also present results of solving the high dimensional HJB/Linear Quadratic Control Problems, by casting the problem in the control framework hence the SNN formulation.

ABSTRACT: After the discovery of carbon nanotubes, boron nitride nanotubes were first theoretically predicted and successfully synthesized in 1995 by an arc-discharge method. TITLE: A Multidimensional Study on Articulation Deficits in Parkinson's Disease

AUTHOR: Thompson, Austin R.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Kim, Yunjung

MEMBER (university representative): Kaschak, Michael P.

MEMBER (committee member): Lansford, Katlin L.

MEMBER (committee member): Morris, Richard Jack, 1950-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: School of Communication Science and Disorders

CORPORATE NAME: School of Communication Science and Disorders

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (144 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation encompasses a series of studies aimed at characterizing the articulatory speech characteristics of individuals with Parkinson's disease (PD) and healthy control (HC) speakers using perceptual, acoustic, and kinematic measures. The first study investigated group differences in perceptual, acoustic, and kinematic measures, while the second study explored changes in these measures during conversational, less clear, and more clear speaking conditions. The third study examined the predictive power of acoustic and kinematic measures for perceptual outcomes of intelligibility and articulatory precision. Forty speakers, including 22 with PD and 18 HC speakers, participated in the study. Acoustic and kinematic speech data were collected simultaneously using the Wave System, an electromagnetic articulography device. Participants read the phrases "Buy Bobby a puppy," "Tess told Dan to stay fit," and "Carl got a croaking frog," using three speaking conditions, including conversational, less clear, and more clear speech. Acoustic and kinematic measures were derived from corner vowel tokens and the /aɪ/ diphthong. Perceptual ratings of intelligibility and articulatory precision were obtained from 368 listeners through crowdsourcing. Linear mixed-effects models were employed to analyze group effects (Study 1), speaking condition effects (Study 2), and the predictive relationship between acoustic and kinematic measures and perceptual outcomes (Study 3). Study 1 revealed that speakers with PD exhibited lower intelligibility and articulatory precision ratings, as well as compressed acoustic vowel space areas (VSAs) compared to HC speakers. Study 2 demonstrated that perceptual measures aligned with expectations (i.e., less clear < conversational < more clear), while some acoustic and kinematic measures followed the predicted trend (i.e., acoustic and kinematic distance), and others did not (i.e., kinematic VSA, F2 slope). Study 3 identified acoustic VSA and kinematic distance as strong predictors of intelligibility and articulatory precision, with a stronger association with articulatory precision. In summary, these findings provide valuable insights into the effects of speech clarity cues on perceptual, acoustic, and kinematic measures of articulation in speakers with PD. By utilizing a multidimensional framework, a more comprehensive understanding of dysarthria's effects on speech articulation in individuals with PD emerges. Methodological considerations, including speech stimuli, measurement techniques, and speaker dialect, are discussed in relation to the study outcomes.

NOTE (Date of Defense): June 26, 2023.

FILENAME: Thompson_fsu_0071N_18260.pdf

TITLE: Associations between Objectively Measured Habitual Physical and Sedentary Activity, the P300 and Depression in Older Adults

AUTHOR: Thompson, Brittney

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Proudfit, Greg Hajcak

MEMBER (committee member): Patrick, Christopher J.

MEMBER (committee member): Charness, Neil

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Psychology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (58 pages)

ABSTRACT: Deficits in cognitive processing, as measured by P300 activity, have been noted in older adults struggling with depressive symptoms, thus understanding factors that may influence cognitive processing are an important area of interest in the search to improve quality of life during older adulthood. Activity levels, such as physical activity (PA) and sedentary behavior, is one such factor. Although literature pertaining to the associations between PA levels, sedentary behavior and depression in older adults appear abundant, much of the recent work investigates the relationship between interventions, such as bouts of exercise throughout a week, workout types, and fitness levels. There is an evident gap in knowledge on the influence habitual activity levels (day-to-day activity) plays on the cognitive aspects of depression in older adults. The goal of our study was to utilize neurophysiological measures collected during a Go/No-Go task, in addition to accelerometers, which collect continuous data on habitual activity levels and self-report measures to investigate the relationship cross-sectional relationship between P300 amplitude and latency, depression symptoms and objectively measured habitual PA in a sample of older adults (n=75). Although no association was found between P300 activity and depression symptoms, heighten depressive symptoms were found to have a significant relationship with longer periods of prolonged sedentary behavior (sedentary bouts, SBs), but not overall sedentary activity. Furthermore, increased No-Go P300 amplitude was associated with higher levels of Daily Lifestyle Activity (e.g. slow walking, grocery shopping) as well as, higher daily incidences of prolonged periods of sedentary and moderate-vigorous activity (MVPA). Moreover, Go-Infrequent latency was shorter among participants who had longer periods of MVPA. Age was found to be associated with increased P300 latency as well as, habitual activity levels, such that older members of the sample engaged in lighter habitual activity and less MVPA. Exploratory analysis revealed subjective reports of time spent walking and in MVPA per day were associated with objectively measured Daily MVPA and prolonged periods of MVPA. In contrast, subjective reports of sitting per day were not associated with objectively measured sedentary activity, showing a potential limitation of subjective measures. Taken together, the current project demonstrates the negative influence prolonged periods of sedentary activity has both on depressive symptoms and cognitive processing as measured through P300 activity, while exploratory analysis illuminated the importance of objectively measured habitual activity over subjective reports as a potential tool to better understand the elements of day-to-day life that impact cognitive and psychological functioning of older adults.

TITLE: Examining Multiple Methods for Nonparametric Multivariate Profile Monitoring

AUTHOR: Timme, Daniel

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Chicken, Eric, 1963-

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Barrientos, Andrés Felipe

MEMBER (university representative): Liu, Guosheng, (Professor of meteorology)

MEMBER (committee member): Sinha, Debajyoti

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Statistics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (211 pages)

ABSTRACT: Statistical Process Control (SPC) tools are popular for monitoring system performance. SPC tools usually monitor the changes of the behavior of a sequence of noisy observations, called profiles, to validate whether the process of interest is operating under desired conditions over time. The challenges of a good SPC tool include quick detection of out-of-control (OOC) process and minimizing the probability of false alarms when the process is in-control (IC). The task of a change-point detection (CPD) tool, often used in conjunction with an SPC, is to identify the time-point when the process becomes OOC for the first time. We propose multiple nonparametric methods, including regression trees and random forests, to model the functional relationship of the observed profile with possibly multiple predictors/explanatory variables. We use a Kolmogorov-Smirnov (KS) statistic of the residuals at current and past time-points as the monitoring statistic. In addition to the first KS based test, we present a method where we smooth this KS statistic with Bayesian Bootstrap. To obtain our third SPC tool, we apply Universal Residuals along with Bayesian hypothesis testing ideas. In the latter SPC tool, we are able to perform a post-hoc analysis and develop credible intervals of the change-point time. We perform extensive simulation studies to assess the performance of our proposed methodologies and compare them among themselves and with other existing methods. For these comparisons, we use two logical performance metrics: average run length (ARL) and false alarm rate (FAR). We also compare these competing methods in terms of their computational costs. We conclude with a summary of their potential applications, advantages, and limitations of our methods. Our plans for future research include improving the Bayesian Bootstrap method using an informative prior, improving the post-hoc analysis of our Universal Residuals method, and further residual based SPC tools using Kullback-Leibler divergence and the Beta Distribution.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Statistics in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

TITLE: Dissecting the Regulators of DNA Replication Timing

AUTHOR: Vouzas, Athanasios

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Bass, Hank W.

MEMBER (university representative): Lemmon, Alan R.

MEMBER (committee member): Dennis, Jonathan Hancock

MEMBER (committee member): Fraser, Peter H.

MEMBER (committee member): McGinnis, Karen M.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Biological Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (106 pages)

ABSTRACT: During S-phase, the mammalian genome replicates in a defined temporal order called the DNA Replication Timing (RT) program. This program is developmentally regulated and is perturbed in diseased cell states, such as cancers and progeria. In recent years, the field has uncovered multiple layers of regulation of the RT program. These layers of regulation range from genome wide (Rif1), to chromosome wide (ASARs) and domain wide (ERCEs). Transcription is a process in the nucleus that tightly correlates with RT and has been suggested to be yet another way the cell regulates its RT program. Here I used a systematic approach to investigate how ectopic insertions of a series of transcription units in a late replicating domain influences the RT of that domain. Through this work, I show that transcription of a small gene is not sufficient to induce a RT advance. Since the only difference between the transcription units used in this study is the promoter itself, I posit that the local epigenetic environment built around the inserted promoter is critical for the ability of the promoter to induce a RT advance. Additionally, I present evidence that transcriptional activation using an inducible promoter can lead to a controlled RT advance. We also identified and characterized chromosome wide regulators of DNA RT, Asynchronous Replication and Autosomal RNAs (ASARs), across human autosomes. Utilizing the known features of ASARs, we identified 68 transcribed loci across human autosomes as candidate ARARs with allelic expression imbalance and asynchronous RT. Indeed, we discovered that five of these 68 transcribed loci share the characteristics and functionality of ASARs and classified them as novel ASARs. We further decoupled the RT of any particular ASAR allele from the RTs of the other allele, other ASARs on the same chromosome, and RT genome wide. Importantly, we showed that the RT of an ASAR allele was independent of the expression profile of the allele, which indicates that transcription is neither necessary nor sufficient to induce early DNA replication of the ASAR.

FILENAME: Waldman_fsu_0071E_18058.pdf

TITLE: Penance and Penitential Intent within Religious Themed Works of Chaucer

AUTHOR: Waldman, Peter

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Fumo, Jamie

MEMBER (university representative): Cairns, Francis

MEMBER (committee member): Johnson, David F. (David Frame), 1956-

MEMBER (committee member): Boehrer, Bruce Thomas

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of English

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (145 pages)

ABSTRACT: The evolution of the concept of penance during the Middle Ages in England reflects the influence of many geopolitical sources, as well as the expanding influence/maturation of the Roman Catholic Church and the development of sacramental rituals during this period. One of these sacraments was codified as a result of the Fourth Lateran Council, which evolved the concept of penitence from an evocation of one's personal relationship with God into a sacrament presenting the Church as the ultimate authority on the Christian afterlife. Prior to the advent of the Council and its doctrine, penitential writings such as the Soul and Body poems and the dream poetry of the time established penance as largely a personal matter, and the writings were more intended to convince the faithful to take reckoning of their own connections with the divine rather than to enforce penitential doctrine vis-à-vis the Church specifically. As medieval England accepted the Lateran Council's doctrine and the Christian community began to place more emphasis on concepts such as mandatory Church-based confession and Purgatory, the religious perspective on the afterlife became more nuanced. In adopting a broader perspective on the afterlife, the Church was able to attract more parishioners, which in turn helped to spread the Church's influence. Given this perceived rise in the importance of penance following the Council, it naturally becomes a topic to be explored in the literature of the period. Perhaps because of his use of the vernacular as well as his placement of classical pagan characters into some texts, Chaucer's writings are not considered as openly religious as those written by some of his contemporaries; nonetheless, there exists an undercurrent of piety throughout several of his works that merits analysis. The most prominent of these works include Troilus and Criseyde, the Prologue to the Legend of Good Women, and the Canterbury Tales told by the Friar, Pardoner, and Parson. All of these draw attention to the importance of penitence despite their emphasis on classical mythology and then-current social themes. This thread culminates in the Retraction to his Canterbury Tales, which he presents as an apology for the faults found in his complete body of works and as a personal plea for the grace of both God and his audience. Through his use of the Retraction and apologies, Chaucer brought religious and penitential themes to the attention of his largely secular court audience. In turn, because he wrote for the courtiers and not for the Church or a specifically religious patronage, he was provided a forum from which to point out the flaws he found apparent in aspects of the Church and its representatives while still incorporating Christian penitential messages in his writings.Coinciding with his discussions of penance, also notable within Chaucer's works is the fact that he presents personal intent or "entente" as a theme within his writings. This concept appears within several of the Canterbury Tales, most notably those told by the Pardoner and Friar, but is also referenced in Troilus's prayers to the God of Love and in Chaucer's defense of his writings in the prologue to the Legend of Good Women. Given the myriad interpretations of his works, his use of these concepts invites the question of his regard for the import of penitential intent and contrition. This becomes especially important in that it reflects on the Retraction to his Canterbury Tales, wherein he rescinds nearly all of his most famous literary works ostensibly in the name of repentance for having created them. It is possible to interpret the Retraction in multiple different ways as well, from a genuine plea for forgiveness in the face of death to a way to promote himself or escape criticism by the Church. This is indicative of the larger issue surrounding the interplay between Chaucer's notions of intent and his treatment of penance. When viewed in this light, the Retraction becomes a tool used to draw focus to Chaucer's true intent in constructing his texts. The goal of this examination is to consider Chaucer's use and discussion of penitential concepts to argue that he presents a thematic progression regarding representations of penance between Troilus and Criseyde, the Prologue to the Legend of Good Women, and the Canterbury Tales, moving from what may be described as a more personal, albeit playful, take on the concept in Troilus to more institutionalized interpretations in the Legend's Prologue, the Canterbury Tales, and its accompanying Retraction. This exploration of penitential history resembles the evolution of penitential concepts across the whole of the medieval period.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of English in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): June 8, 2023.

NOTE (Keywords): Canterbury Tales, Chaucer, Criseyde, Penance, Troilus

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Jamie Fumo, Professor Directing Dissertation; Francis J. Cairns, University Representative; David F. Johnson, Committee Member; Bruce T. Boehrer, Committee Member.

TITLE: Reducing Stress in Leisure Travelers through the Use of Biophilic Design Elements to Enhance the Sense of Arrival in Hotel Lobby Interior Design

AUTHOR: Walker, Virginia H.

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Ransdell, Marlo E.

CORPORATE NAME: College of Fine Arts

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Interior Architecture and Design

ABSTRACT: The objective of this study was to gain knowledge as to the impact of the use of light, materiality, and access to nature in reducing stress in hotel lobbies. This topic rose to importance with the rise of the pandemic of 2020 as safety precautions began to change and people stopped traveling completely. In order for hotels to regain business, they would have to rethink their design to accommodate people's stress levels, as they have become hyper aware of their interior surroundings having been stuck in their homes for long period of time. With little research president on this topic area, this study sought to gain knowledge from a review of literature and original research on which biophilic design elements are most effective in reducing stress levels of parents traveling with young children to child friendly, resort style hotels. After using a snowball sampling technique to reach a sample size of fifty participants, the researcher came to the conclusion that of the three biophilic design elements, access to nature was most effective in reducing feelings of anxiety in high traffic zones of resort style hotel lobbies. A virtual survey helped the researcher come to these conclusions as well as hotel lobby observations and cataloging images and behaviors.

FILENAME: Wang_fsu_0071E_18088.pdf

TITLE: The Effect of Shared Book Reading and Video Viewing on Preschool Children's Vocabulary and Knowledge Acquisition in Informational Text

AUTHOR: Wang, Sen

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Cabell, Sonia Q.

MEMBER (university representative): Schatschneider, Christopher

MEMBER (committee member): Terry, Nicole Patton

MEMBER (committee member): Phillips, Beth M.

MEMBER (committee member): Mukherjee, Tathagata

MEMBER (committee member): Wong, Sandy

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Education, Health, and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: School of Teacher Education

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (168 pages)

ABSTRACT: An experimental study was conducted to examine the effects of shared book reading and video viewing on preschoolers' vocabulary and knowledge acquisition in informational text. The study included 60 preschool children who were randomly assigned to three experimental groups —shared book reading group, video viewing group, and shared book reading plus video viewing group. The content in the book and the video clip was equivalent, since the book was an exact transcript of the video, meaning children received the same information content and similar visual images in both media. What was varied was that the images in the print version were static while in the video were animated with music, which represented the distinct differences between the two media. Baseline vocabulary and knowledge measures about the content of the book/video were administered to all children prior to the experiment. After the pretests, children in the shared book reading group were read aloud the book twice, children in the video viewing group watched the video clip twice, and children in the shared book reading plus video viewing group were read aloud the book once and then watched the video once. Thereafter, children's vocabulary and knowledge acquisition were assessed. The Simple Slopes Analysis revealed statistically significant differences between the groups on the dependent variables of vocabulary and knowledge, controlling for the pretest scores, TOPEL, age, gender, race, and socioeconomic status (SES). In terms of vocabulary acquisition, the results demonstrated that there were significant differences between the shared book reading and two-media groups, and between the shared book reading group and the video viewing group when children's scores were one standard deviation below the mean, with better outcomes for children in the two-media and video viewing groups. Also, there was a significant difference between the shared book reading group and video viewing group when children's pretest scores were at the mean, with better outcomes for children in the video viewing group. As for knowledge acquisition, there were significant differences between the shared book reading group and video viewing group, as well as between the two-media group and the video viewing group when children's pretest scores were one standard deviation above the mean, with better outcomes for children in the video viewing group. Cross-classified generalized random-effects (CCGRE) models were used to explore the extent to which the repetition frequencies and difficulty levels of the words influenced vocabulary acquisition. After controlling the pretest scores, both word repetition frequency and difficulty level explained the variance on vocabulary acquisition, with difficulty level explaining more variance than repetition frequency. The discussion of the findings and null findings is followed by limitations and suggestions for future research.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the School of Teacher Education in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): June 20, 2023.

TITLE: Ecological Assemblages: Christian Animism, Indigenous Ingenuity, and Moral Bricolage

AUTHOR: Waters, James W.

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Kelsay, John, 1953-

MEMBER (university representative): Frank, Andrew, 1970-

MEMBER (committee member): Cecil, Elizabeth A.

MEMBER (committee member): Kalbian, Aline H., 1954-

MEMBER (committee member): Kavka, Martin

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Religion

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (226 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation aims to present a more compelling and transformative religious-moral framework for environmental behavior. It specifically seeks to offer alternatives to prevalent Anglo-European, Christian approaches such as dominion, stewardship, and theocentric models, which view nonhuman nature primarily as resources to be controlled, conquered, or utilized for the benefit of humanity's material or spiritual well-being. These frameworks fall short in fostering a truly transformative shift in our relationship with the environment. To achieve this, it a new religious-moral framework that recognizes the intrinsic value of nature and considers nonhumans as ends in themselves is required.One promising approach that comes close to such a model is known as "Christian animism." Christian animism endeavors to establish a fundamental connection or compatibility between Christianity and Animism, aiming to guide Christians towards more environmentally conscious behavior and worldviews. However, existing scholarly work on Christian animism primarily focuses on constructing theological justifications for adopting this framework, often overlooking the longstanding incorporation of Christian and Animist worldviews among various indigenous groups in North America. To address this oversight, my manuscript examines how American Indian movements have merged their traditional Animist cosmologies with Christian worldviews as a means of adapting to changing socio-political contexts during the era of colonization. Emphasizing the ecological implications of this adaptive strategy, I align decolonization efforts with the creation of new frameworks for environmental conduct in a time of escalating climate crises. By recognizing the historically marginalized indigenous teachings, practices, and ecological wisdom as legitimate and potentially superior, this research challenges the colonizing "rational" Anglo-European understandings of nature that have arguably contributed to significant global environmental damage. Employing historical, ethnographic, and textual research methods, I demonstrate how the religious and ecological assemblages of American Indians can enrich and inform the development of Christian animism. In return, I argue that when appropriately contextualized and guided by decolonial methods and objectives, Christian animism can reciprocally contribute to the spiritual and political aspirations of contemporary American Indian environmentalism.

TITLE: Isotopic Niche Overlap among Foraging Marine Turtle Species in the Gulf of Mexico

AUTHOR: Weber, Savannah M.

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Fuentes, Mariana

MEMBER (committee member): Grubbs, R. Dean

MEMBER (committee member): Ceriani, Simona A.

MEMBER (committee member): Chanton, Jeffrey P.

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Earth, Ocean, and Atmospheric Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (39 pages)

ABSTRACT: Sympatric species may overlap in their use of spatial and trophic resources, which can increase the risk of competition. Comparing the ecological niches and quantifying the degree of niche overlap among these species can provide insights into the extent of resource overlap. This information can be used to guide multispecies management approaches tailored to protect priority habitats that offer the most resources for species. Stable isotope analysis is a valuable tool used to investigate spatial and trophic niches, though few studies have employed this method for comparisons among sympatric marine turtle species. For this study, δ13C, δ15N, and δ34S values from epidermis tissue were used to quantify overlap and compare isotopic niches in loggerhead (Caretta caretta), green (Chelonia mydas), and Kemp's ridley (Lepidochelys kempii) turtles sampled from a shared foraging area located offshore of Crystal River, Florida, USA. Overall, the results revealed high degrees of isotopic overlap (>68%) among species, particularly between loggerhead and Kemp's ridley turtles (85 to 91%), which indicates there may be interspecific competition for resources. Samples from green turtles had the widest range of isotopic values, indicating they exhibit higher variability in diet and habitat type. Samples from loggerhead turtles had the most enriched mean δ34S, suggesting they may forage in slightly different micro-environments compared to the other species. Finally, samples from Kemp's ridley turtles exhibited the smallest niche size, which is indicative of a more specialized diet. This is one of the first studies to investigate resource use in a multispecies foraging aggregation of marine turtles using three isotopic tracers. These findings provide a foundation for future research into the foraging ecology of sympatric marine turtle species and can be used to inform effective multispecies management efforts.

TITLE: Solving Clustering Problems Using Riemannian Optimization

AUTHOR: Wei, Meng

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Gallivan, Kyle A., 1958-

MEMBER (professor co-directing dissertation): Huang, Wenrui, 1961-

MEMBER (university representative): Erlebacher, Gordon, 1957-

MEMBER (committee member): Ökten, Giray

MEMBER (committee member): Sussman, Mark

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mathematics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (163 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation considers the optimization problems that are in the form of minX∈Fv f(x)+λ∥X∥1, where f is smooth, Fv = {X ∈ Rn×q : XTX = Iq,v ∈ span(X)}, and v is a given positive vector. Clustering analysis is a fundamental machine learning problem with broad-ranging applications. Its aim is to group unlabelled data objects into clusters according to a certain similarity measure such that objects within each cluster are more similar to each other than to objects of another cluster. Several clustering problems can be formulated as such optimization problems, such as community detection, k-means clustering, discriminative k-means clustering, and normalized cuts. In this dissertation, three Riemannian optimization approaches for the clustering problems in terms of assignment matrix are proposed, which are ARPPG, AManPG, and Inexact_AManPG. It is proven that the domain Fv forms a compact embedded submanifold of Rn×q and optimization-related tools are derived. Global convergence analysis for Inexact_AManPG is then established. Numerical experiments on clustering problems including community detection, k-means, discriminative k- means, and normalized cut for image segmentation are used to demonstrate the performance of the proposed optimization approaches. ARPPG, AManPG, and Inexact_AManPG algorithms as with many other projection and dimension reduction methods, can have difficulties with time and space complexity when the number of clusters is not reliably known or too large. To address this limitation, we also propose a recursive version of Inexact_AManPG algorithm.

NOTE (Date of Defense): July 5, 2023.

TITLE: Intergenerational Perfectionism: Mechanisms and Treatment

AUTHOR: Wissemann, Karl Lawrence

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Schmidt, Norman B.

MEMBER (university representative): Becker, Martin Swanbrow

MEMBER (committee member): Meyer, Alexandria

MEMBER (committee member): Cougle, Jesse R. (Jesse Ray), 1975-

MEMBER (committee member): Schatschneider, Christopher

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Psychology

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (139 pages)

ABSTRACT: Internalizing disorders are a broad category of psychopathology in children characterized by children's reactions to stress that occur within the self, such as emotional distress related to feelings of anxiety and depression. Perfectionism, which is defined as high standards of performance which are accompanied by tendencies for overly critical evaluation of one's own behavior, is a well-defined risk factor for internalizing psychopathology in children and across the lifespan. Despite this risk, there is currently a lack of efficacious treatment options targeting perfectionism in children. Therefore, more research is needed to both a) understand maintaining mechanisms of perfectionism in children, and b) continue the development and investigation of treatments targeting those factors. Chapter 2 describes the development and evaluation of a measure of a novel construct hypothesized to be relevant to the development of perfectionism in children, parent sensitivity to children's errors, described as the extent to which parents are distressed by their children's mistakes. Exploratory factor analysis revealed a stable 3-factor structure consisting of Checking Behaviors, Evaluative Worry, and Emotional Investment. Total and individual factor scores demonstrated good internal reliability and associations with relevant constructs. Mediation models demonstrated that parent sensitivity to child errors predicted overprotective parenting behaviors, which in turn predicted child anxiety symptoms. These data demonstrate that parent sensitivity to child errors may be one important factor that can contribute to parenting behaviors that increase risk for perfectionism and associated psychopathology in children. In Chapter 3, I developed and evaluated the efficacy of a novel intervention targeting perfectionism in children. This intervention consisted of a single, virtual study visit in which both parents and children were encouraged to decrease certain behaviors related to perfectionism in children. There were no group differences on primary outcomes of perfectionism or related internalizing symptoms. However, post-hoc analyses suggested that parents and children in the control group decreased perfectionism-related behaviors, and that these behavior reductions predicted decreases in perfectionism and internalizing symptoms regardless of group assignment. Overall, these data suggest that parents and children are able to decrease perfectionism-related behaviors following a single study visit, and that reductions in these behaviors can be an effective approach for treating perfectionism and related internalizing symptoms.

TITLE: Ethnic Identity, Self-Efficacy, Academic Adjustment, and Anxiety Symptoms in Latinx Undergraduates

AUTHOR: Zambrano Gonzalez, Samuel

MEMBER (professor directing thesis): Parker, Michele

MEMBER (committee member): Gonzales Backen, Melinda Airr

MEMBER (committee member): Rudaz, Myriam

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Health and Human Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Human Development and Family Science

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (40 pages)

ABSTRACT: Objectives: The Latinx population is one of the fastest growing minority groups in the United States, with a current population of around 60 million people, they make up roughly 18% of the US population. The current study examined the relationship between ethnic identity, self-efficacy, academic adjustment, and anxiety symptoms in Latinx undergraduates. Methods: Sample consisted of 155 participants (Mage = 20.4, SD = 1.67; 72.7% female). Ethical approval was granted by Florida State University Institutional Review Board (IRB) (Study ID: STUDY00003509). Participants completed an online Qualtrics questionnaire available to eligible students using FSU's secure network (Qualtrics Software, 2021). Completion of the survey questionnaire took approximately 35-40 minutes. Results: No domains of ethnic identity (exploration, resolution, affirmation) were correlated with symptoms of general anxiety (r = .010, p > .05; r = .036, p > .05; r = -.135, p > .05) respectively. Results found college self-efficacy significantly mediates the effect of ethnic identity-exploration on academic adjustment with an estimated standardized indirect effect ab = 0.11, 95th percentile bootstrap CI [.05, .11]; p<.01, and standardized direct effect c = .125 , 95th percentile bootstrap CI [-.04; .281]; p>.05). Conclusion: As the Latinx college population continues to increase, researchers in this area of development must pay close attention to all aspects of the college environment that may influence Latinx outcomes. Ethnic identity, college self-efficacy, and academic adjustment were all shown to positively correlate with one another, emphasizing the need to continue research on how higher levels of ethnic identity may promote successful academic adjustment

FILENAME: Zhang_fsu_0071E_18152.pdf

TITLE: Novel Methods in Transcriptome-Wide Association Study

AUTHOR: Zhang, Zichen

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Bradley, Jonathan R.

MEMBER (university representative): Nowakowski, Richard S.

MEMBER (committee member): Cao, Hongyuan

MEMBER (committee member): Niu, Xufeng, 1954-

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Statistics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (61 pages)

ABSTRACT: Genes with moderate to low expression heritability may explain a large proportion of complex trait etiology, but such genes cannot be sufficiently captured in conventional transcriptome-wide association studies (TWASs), partly due to the relatively small available reference datasets for developing expression genetic prediction models to capture the moderate to low genetically regulated components of gene expression. In the first chapter, we introduce a method, the Summary-level Unified Method for Modeling Integrated Transcriptome (SUMMIT), to improve the expression prediction model accuracy and the power of TWAS by using a large expression quantitative trait loci (eQTL) summary-level dataset. We apply SUMMIT to the eQTL summary-level data provided by the eQTLGen consortium. Through simulation studies and analyses of genome-wide association study summary statistics for 24 complex traits, we show that SUMMIT improves the accuracy of expression prediction in blood, successfully builds expression prediction models for genes with low expression heritability, and achieves higher statistical power than several benchmark methods. Finally, we conduct a case study of COVID-19 severity with SUMMIT and identify 11 likely causal genes associated with COVID-19 severity. In the second chapter, we introduce a method, Comprehensive omics-phenotype association estimation using \textit{Cis-} and \textit{Trans-}regulated elements (ComPACT), to integrate genetic information from \textit{trans-}loci into classic association studies, by iteratively detect potential outlying locus. Like SUMMIT, ComPACT is also capable of utilizing summary-level data to construct imputation models. However, as an extension of SUMMIT, ComPACT do not require individual-level genotype data to do model tuning. We apply ComPACT to the deCODE summary-level data and construct 233\% more imputation models than the existing method. In addition, we verify that the selected models were statistically robust by validation using an external dataset, INTERVAL, and show that our pipeline had achieved similar prediction accuracy to using individual-level data. Finally, we conduct a case study of Alzheimer's disease and identify 207 likely causal proteins, whereas competing method identify 19 likely causal proteins.

NOTE (Date of Defense): July 17, 2023.

NOTE (Keywords): Statistical Genetics, Transcriptome-wide association studies

FILENAME: Zhang_fsu_0071E_18168.pdf

TITLE: Mathematical Study on the Expressive Power of Machine Learning and Applications in Optimal Filtering Problems

AUTHOR: Zhang, Zezhong

MEMBER (professor directing dissertation): Bao, Feng

MEMBER (university representative): Liu, Xiuwen, 1966-

MEMBER (committee member): Farhat, Aseel

MEMBER (committee member): Farhat, Aseel

MEMBER (committee member): Ökten, Giray

MEMBER (committee member): Zhu, Lingjiong

CORPORATE NAME: Florida State University

CORPORATE NAME: College of Arts and Sciences

CORPORATE NAME: Department of Mathematics

PUBLICATION: Tallahassee, Florida: Florida State University, 2023

PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 1 online resource (143 pages)

ABSTRACT: This dissertation investigates the practical expressive power of machine learning models as general function approximators and their practical applications in optimal filtering problems. The practical expressive power of these models depends on the choice of \textit{model structure} (deep or shallow), which sets the upper limit of expressive power, and the \textit{trainability} of the model, which enables the realization of the expressive power in practical applications, such as regression and classification. Our primary objective is to enhance the practical expressive power and overall performance of neural networks (NNs) by improving their trainability. In addition to traditional machine learning tasks, we specifically focus on the optimal filtering problem, which holds significant importance in science and engineering. When addressing the representation of filtering density in optimal filtering problems, we adopt a similar rationale for practical expressive power by considering the \textit{model structure}, which determines the theoretical capacity for storing probability distributions, and the \textit{trainability}, which determines the optimization cost for utilizing the expressive power of the model to approximate the filtering density. By carefully balancing these two factors, our aim is to enhance the overall performance of optimal filtering problems. The first part of the dissertation focuses on enhancing the practical expressive power of neural networks by improving their trainability. To achieve this, we first introduce the concept of the general activation transform (GAT) as a generalization of the traditional elementwise activation function in the function space. The GAT can be derived from the general deep neural networks (GDNNs) framework, in which the affine transformations in traditional deep neural networks (DNNs) are replaced with integral transforms, with a finite-rank parameterization of the weight integral kernels. The GAT maps the input vector into the function space by treating the input vector as coefficients of the input basis function, performing activation on the state function, and generating the output through integration with the output basis function. We specifically focus on GAT-ReLU, a variant of GAT with ReLU activation, which exhibits enriched activation patterns and smoother solutions compared to traditional ReLU activation. By selecting proper basis functions (continuous and high-variation), GAT-ReLU enhances the practical expressive power of the model, which is demonstrated by many numerical experiments. Apart from GAT, we introduce transferable neural networks (TransNet) for solving partial differential equations (PDEs) by reducing the optimization difficulty through the idea of transfer learning. The construction of transferable neural feature spaces involves re-parameterization of hidden neurons and auxiliary functions. Theoretical analysis validates the high quality of the resulting feature space, characterized by uniformly distributed neurons. Extensive numerical experiments demonstrate the effectiveness and improved transferability of our proposed method across different PDEs. The second part of this dissertation concentrates on addressing the optimal filtering problem by different choices of representations for filtering density. This involves considering the model's theoretical capacity for representing probability distributions and the associated optimization cost for approximating the distributions. By carefully balancing these factors, we aim to develop effective approaches for solving the optimal filtering problem. We first introduce an adaptive kernel method that utilizes a Gaussian mixture model (GMM) to represent the probability density function (PDF) within the Bayesian framework. The state dynamics are formulated using the Fokker-Planck equation, and the PDE operator is decomposed into linear and nonlinear parts. The linear part is analytically incorporated into the GMM model, while the nonlinear part is approximated using an adaptive kernel algorithm. Bayesian inference is applied to each Gaussian component in the GMM to incorporate observational data. We also provide many numerical examples to validate the performance of the GMM representation in solving nonlinear filtering problem. In addition, We also explore the use of score-based models for solving optimal filtering problems, where the score function (gradient of the logarithm of the PDF) plays a central role in representing the filtering density. We train score-based generative models to approximate samples from the prior distribution, and by combining the learned score functions of the prior and likelihood, we can directly generate samples from the posterior distribution. Score-based models leverage the high capacity of deep neural networks (DNNs) to effectively capture non-Gaussian and high-dimensional distributions. Our numerical experiments demonstrate the effectiveness of this approach, showcasing its ability to handle high-dimensional (up to 100 dimensions) and highly nonlinear filtering problems effectively.

NOTE (Submitted Note): A Dissertation submitted to the Department of Mathematics in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of Doctor of Philosophy.

NOTE (Date of Defense): July 12, 2023.

NOTE (Bibliography Note): Includes bibliographical references.

NOTE (Advisory Committee): Feng Bao, Professor Directing Dissertation; Xiuwen Liu, University Representative; Aseel Farhat, Committee Member; Giray Ökten, Committee Member; Lingjiong Zhu, Committee Member.
